<DIV1 TYPE="text"><PB REF="00000228.tif" N="CCXXVI">

<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="1">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN Saynt Bede bokes writen er stories olde.</L>
<L>Sex hundreth &amp; four score &amp; nien &yogh;ere mo er tolde</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;at Jhesu Criste of Mary was born,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e kyng Cadwaladre &thorn;is lond had alle lorn</L>
<L>For Englis &amp; Sessons he went to lesse Bretayn,</L>
<L>To speke with his cosyne, his name was kyng Alayn.</L>
<L>&amp; fro &thorn;ien he went vnto &thorn;e courte of Rome,</L>
<L>For to tak his penance &amp; of his synnes dome.</L>
<L>Whan he was asoyled of &thorn;e pape Sergie,</L>
<L>He died &amp; was biried in Rome solemplie.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e &yogh;ere after nou&thorn;er lesse ne more</L>
<L>Kom his &amp; his kosyn Ini &amp; Iuore,</L>
<L>In schip out of Irelond, in Wales gan &thorn;ei vpryue,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh out Chestreschire werre gan &thorn;ei dryue.</L>
<L>Had &thorn;ei no styntyng, bot &thorn;orgh alle &thorn;ei ran,</L>
<L>Unto Wynchestre, alle &thorn;e loud &thorn;ei wan.
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="2"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN Westsex was &thorn;an a kyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, his name was.</NOTE> his was Sir Ine.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Rege de Westsexe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan he wist of &thorn;e Bretons, of werre ne wild he fine.</L>
<L>Messengers he sent &thorn;orghout Inglond</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e Inglis kynges, &thorn;at had it in &thorn;er hond,</L>
<L>&amp; teld how &thorn;e Bretons, men of mykelle myght,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lond wild wynne ageyn &thorn;orh force &amp; fyght.</L>
<L>Hastisly ilkone &thorn;e kynges com fulle suythe,</L>
<L>Bolde men &amp; stoute, &thorn;er hardinesse to ki&thorn;e.</L>
<L>In a grete Daneis felde &thorn;er &thorn;ei samned alle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer si&thorn;en hiderward Kampedene men kalle.</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;o Inglis kynges, &thorn;at &thorn;an comen wore,</L>
<L>Sigbert, kyng of Estsex, in elde was he more.</L>
<L>He bigan to speke tille alle &thorn;e chiualrie:</L>
<L>"We be comen alle of kynde of Germenie,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at chaced has &thorn;e Bretons here of &thorn;er kythe.</L>
<L>"Now ere &thorn;ei comen to clayme it, &amp; mykelle force &thorn;am with.</L>
<L>"Oi&thorn;er bihoues vs defend it, or &yogh;elde vp our<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> right.</NOTE> righ.</L>
<L>"I rede we chese a hede, &thorn;at vs to werre kan dight,</L>
<L>"&amp; to &thorn;at ilk hede I rede we vs bynde.</L>
<L>"For werre withouten hede is not wele, we fynde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons &yogh;ede to conseile, &amp; teld it si&thorn;en on hie,</L>
<L>Ine kyng `kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Redundat.</NOTE> of Westsex was a knyght wor&thorn;ic,</L>
<L>Forto gye vs alle, &thorn;at now er comen here.</L>
<L>Ine toke &thorn;e feaute, displayed his banere,</L>
<L>&amp; went to &thorn;e bataile in a fulle faire grene,</L>
<L>&thorn;at is vnder Kampedene, a medew I wene.</L>
<L>Iuor &amp; Ini were disconfite &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Iris &amp; &thorn;e Wals with &thorn;am fled away.
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="3"></L>
<L>Alle were &thorn;ei nere slayn, &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;er left<NOTE PLACE="marg">Iuor &amp; Ini fugiunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fled vnto Wales vnto &thorn;er schippes eft.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ise Bretons tuo were fled out of &thorn;is lond,</L>
<L>Ine toke his feaute of alle &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> helde lond.</NOTE> lond helde.</L>
<L>At the fiftend day &thorn;ei samned at Southamptone,</L>
<L>With joy alle at ons &thorn;ei went tille Snawdone</L>
<L>On Iuor &amp; Ini, &thorn;at tapised by &thorn;at side,</L>
<L>To purueie &thorn;am a skulkyng, on &thorn;e Englis eft to ride.</L>
<L>Bot Ine had &thorn;e Inglis euerilkon at wille,</L>
<L>Bot Segbert of Estsex at home left stille.</L>
<L>He was of grete elde, &amp; myght not trauaile,</L>
<L>Bot Iuor &amp; Ini &thorn;e Englis gan &thorn;am assaile.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Englis were bolde, &amp; drofe &thorn;am to &thorn;e sand.</L>
<L>&thorn;e fled out of Wales away tilleI reland.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE Englis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>See pag. 12, 13. of a most rare Book, be|ing Mr. Thomas Ellis's imper|fect Edition (with great Im|provements) of Dr. Powell's History, to which is prefix'd</I> Sir John Prise's Description of Wales. <I>Oxon.</I> 1653. 4<I>to. I call it imperfect, because it was never near compleated by Mr. Ellis, as will appear from the following Remark, which I have written at the beginning of my Copy that I happen'd to purchase in the Year 1722. "The following Description of Wales was published by Mr. Thomas Ellis, A. M. and Fellow of Jesus Coll. Oxon. but 'tis much altered from the Edition which Dr. Powell set out, with the His|tory of Cambria, now call|ed Wales, at Lond. in</I> 1584. 4<I>to. The said Mr. Thomas Ellis was a learned Man, and a very great Antiquary. He began also to reprint the said History of Cambria, which was grown (and is now) very scarce. In order to which that great Antiquary, Rob. Vaughan of Hengwort in Merionethshire, Esq. (who was diverted by other Business from publishing this Work, as he otherwise designed) com|municated to him his Correc|tions and Additions. But Mr. Ellis finding, that a paul|try, illitterate Author, called Percie Enderbie, had been be|fore hand with him, and some way or other had got Mr. Vaughan's Notes also, and was so bold, as, without Mr. Vaughan's leave, to print them in his Book (which is but a poor thing) in Folio call'd</I>, Cambria Triumphans: or, an|cient and modern British and Welsh Histories, <I>he laid by his Design, and so no more was printed than</I> 128. <I>Pages, all which are here. After he had desisted (for which all curious and learned Men were very sorry, he being so very capa|ble of doing great Matters) the Copies, all but a very few, were sold for wast Paper. upon which account the Book is now a wonderfull Rarity, and highly valuable. Dr. Powell's Additions are marked thus <GAP>. Mr. Vaughan's thus &para;. This Book belong'd to the Revd. Mr. Josiah Pullen, M. A. and Vice-Principal of Magd. Hall Oxon." What I have here observ'd about Mr. Ellis &amp; Percie Enderbie is con|firm'd by Mr. Wood, Ath. Oxon. Vol. II. col.</I> 248, 249. <I>But the chief reason of my referring here to Mr. Ellis's imperfect Ed. of Dr. Powell's Hist. of Cambria is upon account of a Passage that is there published, (as 'tis also in Dr. Powell's own genuine Ed.) out of John Castoreus or Bever, which will very much illustrate this Place of Langtoft.</I></NOTE> kynges turned, &thorn;ei mot do nomore,</L>
<L>Bot soiorned &thorn;am a while in rest a Bangore,
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>&thorn;at ilk a kyng of reame suld mak him alle redie.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e Paske after &thorn;e kyng Ine<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> gan. <I>Quod si</I> gart <I>reti|neas, tum idem erit quod</I> pre|pared.</NOTE> gart<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> crie.</NOTE> trie,</L>
<L>Home forto wend to childe &amp; to wife,</L>
<L>To visitte &thorn;er londes, to solace &thorn;er life.</L>
<L>Ine kyng of Westsex for his<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ethel|burga,</NOTE> wife sent</L>
<L>Vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Id est, Manchester, in agro Lancastrensi, quod</I> Ma|mecestre <I>appellat Hovedenus</I>, Mamerceaster <I>Florentius</I>, Ma|nige-ceaster <I>Chron. Sax. Fu|tilem autem eorum conjecturam esse arbitror, nec ulla confuta|tione egere, qui vocem</I> Mani|ge ceaster (<I>in Chronico Saxo|nico</I>) <I>non de unica duntaxat urbe, sed de multis civitatibus esse intelligendam putant. Sed en tibi ipsa verba &egrave; Chronico, sub anno</I> DCCCCXXIII. <I>ubi de Edmundo Seniore agens, docu|it, ipsum eodem illo anno, mox post &aelig;statem, ad</I> Th&aelig;lw&aelig;le [<I>i. e.</I> Thelwel, <I>sive</I> Thelwall, <I>viculum ad ripam fluminis Mer|sey in agro Cestrensi, notante cl. Gibsono, p.</I> 45. <I>Explicat. No|minum Locor. in Chr. Sax.</I>] <I>cum exercitu profectum, primum jus|sisse eam urbem construi, &amp; fir|mari, pr&aelig;sidioque muniri; de|inde jussisse etiam alium exer|citum, dum ibi commoraretur, de Merciorum terra, adire</I> Ma|nigeceaster <I>in Northymbria, ac eam resarcire, pr&aelig;sidioque mu|nire.</I> Her on &thorn;yssum geare. For Eadweard cyning mid syrde on ufan h&aelig;rfest to D&aelig;lw&aelig;le. &amp; het gewyrcan &thorn;a burh. &amp; gesettan. &amp; gemannian. And het o&eth;re fyrd eac of Myrcna &thorn;eode. &thorn;a hwile &thorn;e he &thorn;&aelig;r s&aelig;t gefaren Manige|ceaster on Nor&eth;-hymbran. &amp; hie gebetan &amp; gemannian. <I>Pro</I>on ufan h&aelig;rfest,<I>autum|nali tempore habet Florentius Wigorniensis. Sic enim ille sub A.D.</I> 920. <I>(quo anno, non, ut Chr. Sax.</I> 923. <I>rem gestam fuisse retulit.)</I> Autumnali tem|pore rex invictissimus Eadwardus ad Tealweale profectus est, ibid|emque urbem construxit, &amp; ad ejus pr&aelig;sidium quosque fortissi|mos de exercitu suo reliquit. Mi|sit etiam in Northimbriam Mer|ciorum exercitum, ut urbem Ma|merceastram restaurarent, &amp; in ea fortes milites collocarent. <I>Ne|que hac in re quid discrepat ex|emplar pr&aelig;stantissimum editio|nis Florentii Wigorniensis in</I>4<I>to. Londini</I> 1592. <I>quod, doctissimi Langbainii notis quamplurimis MSS. (maxim a ex parte &egrave; duobus Mariani Scoti, &egrave; quo pleraq; sua surripuit Florentius, sicut in Lelando nostro, Col. Vol. III. p.</I> 277. <I>monui, Codicibus exi|miis, calamo exaratis, petitis) adornatum, &egrave; Mus&eacute;o Arthuri Charletti, nuper defuncti, rede|mi, idem nimirum illud exem|plar, quod ad pag.</I> 212. <I>editionis nostr&aelig; vit&aelig; &AElig;lfredi Magni Spelmannian&aelig; commemoravi.</I></NOTE> Malmcestre, &thorn;e quene tille him went.
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>Ine &thorn;e kyng had a sonne, his name Adellus.</L>
<L>Dede him toke &amp; he died, als it salle do vs.</L>
<L>Sorow &amp; site he made, &thorn;er was non o&thorn;er rede,</L>
<L>For his sonne &amp; heyre, &thorn;at so sone was dede.
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="6"></L>
<L>Ine was kyng of Westsex sex &amp; &thorn;ritty &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Fulle wele he &yogh;emed &thorn;e lond fro wo &amp; fro wehere.</L>
<L>Iuor &amp; Ini ost did he &thorn;am chace.</L>
<L>In his tyme to rise had &thorn;ei neuer grace.</L>
<L>Tuenty grete batailes Ine ouerkam,</L>
<L>&thorn;e quene withouten childe non heyre of hir nam.</L>
<L>Ine went to Rome als in pilgremage,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ine per|rexit Ro|mam, &amp; ibi sepultus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Adelard his cosyn he gaf his heritage.</L>
<L>The pape him asoyled in treuth stedfast,</L>
<L>Whan he had don his penance, he &yogh;ald to God &thorn;e gaste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ADELARD of Westsex was kyng of &thorn;e empire,</L>
<L>Of Noreis &amp; Surreis, guyour of ilk schire.</L>
<L>He ne suffred neuere wrath to be aboue</L>
<L>Bituex kyng baron, &thorn;at ne he mad ay loue.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e Bretons he ouercome, &thorn;at wild him assaile,</L>
<L>&amp; in his &thorn;irtende &yogh;ere force gan him faile.</L>
<L>Tille Uttred his kosyn, a stiffe knyght in stoure,</L>
<L>He gaf his kyngdom, &amp; died in langoure.</L>
<L>He ligges at Bathe, for &thorn;ider was he born.</L>
<L>&thorn;e holy man Saynt Bede died a &yogh;ere beforn.</L>
<L>&para; Henry of Huntyngton sen &thorn;at day &amp; &thorn;at &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de Henrico Huntyng|tone.</NOTE></L>
<L>To write Inglis gestes fond he non his pere.</L>
<L>A bisshop of Lincolne, Alisandre he hight,</L>
<L>Praied him to write &thorn;e gestes &thorn;at were right.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor &thorn;is Henry is cald a compiloure.</L>
<L>He wrote &thorn;e Englis gestes whilom of honoure.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;us wrote to &thorn;e bisshop Henry &thorn;e same,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Alex|andro epi|scopo Lin|colni&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>He sais, &thorn;is lond hight Bretayn, &thorn;at now has o&thorn;er name.
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>Inglond now is cald, for Inglis men we fynd</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk &thorn;at is &thorn;erin, it is of diuers kynd.</L>
<L>He sais &thorn;is lond has suffred so many tyme wo,</L>
<L>Fiue sorowes he writes withouten o&thorn;er mo.</L>
<L>&thorn;o ilk fiue sorowes he calles fiue woundes,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ere not &yogh;it haled, ne salle be many stoundes.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles &thorn;e clerk Merlyn sais certeyn,</L>
<L>That Bretons at &thorn;e last salle haf &thorn;is lond agayn,</L>
<L>Whan Cadwaldre salle calle with him &thorn;e kyng Konan,</L>
<L>What tyme it salle falle, &yogh;it wote no man.</L>
<L>Now of fiue sorowes, &thorn;at &yogh;it not endid are,</L>
<L>Henry in his writyng telles what &thorn;ei ware.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE first of &thorn;ise fiue was &thorn;orgh Romeyns,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Quinque plagarum terr&aelig; pri|ma plaga fuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>That wan it of Casbalan in to &thorn;er demeyns.</L>
<L>Grete treuage &thorn;ei toke of &thorn;is lond here.</L>
<L>&thorn;re &thorn;ousand pounde of gold to paye ilk a &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>&amp; four hundred &yogh;ere lastid &thorn;at ilk wo,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei mad &thorn;e lond fulle pouere, &thorn;e folk ded &thorn;ei slo.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e to&thorn;er sorow of &thorn;is lond mykelle gan it greue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Secunda plaga.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottes &amp; &thorn;e Peihtes togider gan &thorn;ei cheue,</L>
<L>To waste alle Northumberland, &thorn;e godes away &thorn;ei ledde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at men with &thorn;e bestes in feldes &thorn;ei &thorn;am fedde.</L>
<L>&para; The &thorn;rid sorow of &thorn;is lond com &thorn;orgh &thorn;e Sessons,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Tercia pla|ga.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at ten si&thorn;es aryued vppon &thorn;e Bretons,</L>
<L>&amp; si&thorn;en were chaced ageyn aw with maistrie,</L>
<L>&amp; eft aryued on &thorn;am here &thorn;orgh quantise of spie.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last &thorn;ei chaced out &thorn;e Bretons so clene,</L>
<L>Away vnto Wales &thorn;er kynd is I wene.
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>&thorn;e Englis of &thorn;is lond &thorn;e lordschip &thorn;ei toke,</L>
<L>&amp; haf it &yogh;it in &thorn;er hond, &thorn;e Bretons forsoke.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e ferthe sorow of &thorn;is lond com &thorn;orgh &thorn;e Danes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Quarta plaga.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e folk of the North slouh, destroied &thorn;er wanes.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en wan &thorn;ei alle &thorn;e South, maistrie &thorn;ei schewed,</L>
<L>&amp; laid &thorn;er Dangilde on lered &amp; lewed,</L>
<L>&amp; left &thorn;e Inglis &thorn;e lond on a forward dere,</L>
<L>To pay ilk a hede a peny to &thorn;am bi &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>&para; The fift sorow &thorn;er after com, whan William conqueroure,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Quinta plaga.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at aryued on &thorn;is lond, Harald he slouh in stoure,</L>
<L>&amp; barons o&thorn;er inouh, &thorn;at died in &thorn;e feld,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lond lese &thorn;e armes, changed is &thorn;e scheld.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he &amp; his haf had &thorn;e lond in heritage,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e Inglis haf so lad, &thorn;at &thorn;ei lyue in seruage,</L>
<L>He sette &thorn;e Inglis to be &thorn;ralle, &thorn;at or was so fre.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at bigan it alle in &thorn;e geste may &yogh;e se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HENRY of Huntyngton testimons &thorn;is title.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Henricus dicit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyngdom of Westsex, he sais, it was not litelle,</L>
<L>Whan Adelard died &thorn;erfro, &amp; Uttred &thorn;erto went.</L>
<L>Uttred in his first &yogh;ere messengers he sent<NOTE PLACE="marg">Uttredus regnavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>For kynges &amp; barons vntille his parlement,</L>
<L>In stede &thorn;er he it sette, &thorn;ei wist what it ment.</L>
<L>Bot Eadbald it withsaid, kyng of Lyndesay,</L>
<L>He was of &thorn;e Bretons kynde, he stode of him non eye.</L>
<L>Uttred wrathed him &thorn;erfore, &amp; ran on him fulle tite,</L>
<L>&amp; tuys &thorn;orgh batale in felde was Eadbald disconfite.</L>
<L>&yogh;it wild he not be war &thorn;er bi, so proude he was in herte,</L>
<L>Tille he was wonded &thorn;e &thorn;rid tyme, &amp; died also smerte.
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>Biried he is at Repyndon, &amp; in &thorn;e kirke he lis.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at wille not bowe in skille, I hold him vnwis.</L>
<L>Many tymes on Uttred Bretons bataile souht:</L>
<L>Uttred was so valiant, he gaf of &thorn;am right nouht.</L>
<L>He regned fiftene &yogh;ere, &amp; died alle to rathe.</L>
<L>He ligges biried als a kyng in the toun of Bathe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER Uttred regned Sibriht, his kosyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sibriht regnavit.</NOTE></L>
<L>He luffed wele &thorn;e Bretons, &thorn;at com tille ille fyn.</L>
<L>He bare him so tille his barons, &thorn;at noi&thorn;er &yogh;ong ne olde</L>
<L>Wald vnto him bowe, ne bli&thorn;eli of him holde.</L>
<L>What did &thorn;e barons alle with &thorn;is fole Sibriht?</L>
<L>Chaced him fro his reame, &amp; chese a no&thorn;er knyght,</L>
<L>Kynewolf, of &thorn;e kynred of Adelarde's blode,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Kynewolf c&oelig;pit re|gnare.</NOTE></L>
<L>A while lufed &thorn;e Inglis, &amp; wele with &thorn;am stode.</L>
<L>Sibriht &thorn;at schrew as a lordan gan lusk,</L>
<L>A suynhird smote he to dede vnder a thorn busk.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>KYNEWOLF toke &thorn;e kyngdom (for better mot not falle)<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex Kyne|wolf.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; si&thorn;en toke &thorn;e feaute of &thorn;e kynges alle,</L>
<L>As his ancestres had it befor hand,</L>
<L>Bot of Kent &amp; Lyndesay &amp; Northumberland.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise &thorn;re kynges geynsaid it hym,</L>
<L>&amp; Kynwolf to &thorn;o &thorn;re bare him so brym,</L>
<L>So wis he was in dede, of body so valiant,</L>
<L>With dynt of suerd &amp; drede he mad &thorn;am recreant.</L>
<L>Kyng was Kynwolf sex &amp; tuenty &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>He was neuer wedded, to woman's daungere.
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>No childe had he neuer, his heritage myght to wende,</L>
<L>Bot welth inou to welde, vntille his lyue's ende.</L>
<L>At Wynchestre he lis, &thorn;ider men him bare.</L>
<L>Fulle frely he lyued here, his soule with God it fare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN &thorn;e kyng Kynwolf had don his endyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex Brit|trik.</NOTE></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> Brittrik.</NOTE>Brittrk his kosyn &thorn;ei lift him to kyng.</L>
<L>Offa, kyng of Lyndsay, a faire douhter had,</L>
<L>Brittrik hir wedded, &amp; quene home hir lad.</L>
<L>Whan he had regned foure &yogh;ere, one ryued vpon his right,</L>
<L>A duke of Danmark, Kebriht he hight.</L>
<L>Britrik had a stiward, his name was Herman:</L>
<L>Kebriht he kept at Humber, &amp; on him he ran.</L>
<L>Hard was &thorn;e bataile, als &thorn;ei togider stynt</L>
<L>Herman was &thorn;er slayn, &thorn;e duke gaf &thorn;e dynt.</L>
<L>Ageyn to Danmark Kebriht gan schake,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> Brittrik.</NOTE> Kebriht ne myght him ouertake.</L>
<L>He mot not venge Herman of Kebriht &thorn;at him slouh.</L>
<L>He did his ost turne agayn, &amp; had sorow inouh.</L>
<L>In his elleuent &yogh;ere com folk, &thorn;at misleued,</L>
<L>Aryued on Brittrik, &amp; sore &thorn;ei him greued.</L>
<L>&thorn;ore Brittrik bare him so in &thorn;at ilk bataile,</L>
<L>&thorn;e dede &yogh;ede Danes to, &thorn;e Noreis gan him vaile.</L>
<L>Edburgh hight &thorn;e quene, &thorn;at I ore of ment,</L>
<L>Scho purueied a poyson to &thorn;e kyng sonne of Kent.</L>
<L>Hatred before was, S. Bede herd I say,</L>
<L>Biten &thorn;e kyng of Kent, &amp; &thorn;e kyng of Lyndsay.
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="11"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Malim</I>, Eilred (<I>vel, at alii Cantii regem vocant</I>, Alric) of Kent alle Lyndesay he wast|ed.</NOTE>Eilred of Lyndesay alle Kent he wasted.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng after, I say, to hate often he tasted</L>
<L>&thorn;e was of Lyndesay, als I ore told.</L>
<L>Scho<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>The Author hath here an eye upon the History of Ead|burg, (or, as he just above writes her, Edburgh) King Brictrick's Queen, who was Daughter of Offa, K. of Mercia; but, as he hath represented it, it is very obscure and imperfect; and whereas he tells us, that Bri|ctrick was buried at Tewksbury, others assure us, that it was at Warhame, Whence the Saxon Annals. An.</I> DCCLXXXIV. Her Cyneheard of-sloh Cy|newulf cyning. &amp; he &thorn;&aelig;r we|ar&eth; of-flegen. &amp; LXXXIV. monna mid him. And &thorn;a on|feng Byrhtric West-Seaxna rices. &amp; he ricsode XVI. gear. and his f&aelig;deren-cyn ge&eth; to Cerdice. <I>The story of Eadburg is given at large by several Writers. She was a most beau|tifull Lady, and had gained the Affections of the King her Hus|band (a good natured mild Prince) so much, that he was governed and directed more by her, than was consistent with his Royal Dignity. She was of a very haughty, proud temper, and could not brook, that the King should have any favourites, but such as she approved of. So that if she saw, or knew of, any, that, without her special con|sent and approbation, were countenanced, and particularly respected by him, she contrived methods to make such away. There happened to be a very delicate, fine young Gentleman (Son, it seems, as Langtoft in|forms us, to the King of Kent) that the King shew'd a more than ordinary kindness to, both upon account of his exquisite beauty, and the excellency of his understanding. The youth was perfectly innocent, and the King (notwithstanding an Usurper, as being not of the right line</I> [<I>See Dr. Brady's History of the Succes|sion, p. 359.</I>]) <I>of too virtuous a nature to cause any just grounds of suspicion, that there was any immorality in the case. The Queen, however, thought otherwise. She look'd upon the youth as the King's minion, and her jealousy wrought her to such a pitch of madness, that she pre|par'd a potion for him (an or|dinary practise with her, when she had a mind to vent her spleen) that prov'd fatal not only to the lovely youth, but even to the King himself, who had the misfortune (tho' quite contrary to her design) to tast first of the cup. This raised the indignation of the King's Sub|jects to such a degree, that she was forced, for security, to fly beyond Sea, and the West-Sax|ons thereupon resolv'd, that, for the future, no Queen should sit on the throne with the King, nor be stil'd his Queen, but only</I> the King's wife. <I>But this custom being look'd upon as barbarous and very dishonourable, it was soon after broke by King Ethel|wolf</I> (<I>father to &AElig;lfred the Great</I>) <I>notwithstanding in the times of some of his successors there was often a respect had unto it, as I have shew'd in my Notes upon Sir John Spelman's Life of K. &AElig;lfred, p.</I> 24. <I>to which place I shall refer the Reader, and, upon this occa|sion, will only beg leave to in|sert, what is said about King Brictrick in the prose additions to the MS. of Robert of Glou|cester, that belongs to the He|ralds Office.</I> After him [<I>Kyne|wulfe</I>] Brightrik regned. xvi. yere, more studious a boute pees thanne bataille. This toke to wyfe Edburge, kyng Offes doughter of Merchene|riche. Whiche Edburge stu|ried her lorde a yenst gilt|lese men, notwithstandyng that him self was meoke and benynge. And yf she ne myght nat come to here purpose by counseille to ouercome thoo that here liked by werre, sheo dude hem be slayne by poy|son. This was preued in a yonglyng of the kynges whiche he muche loued, which heo with her poysen sloughe. And after that the kyng deyde &thorn;orgh a drenche, whiche vnwytyng the quene he dranke, of hure makyng. and whenne the tythinge here of was sprong oute, thulke wikked quene by the comminalte was driue oute of the countre, and a statute i made a mong the West|Saxones, that no quene af|terwarde shulde sitte by the kynge atte mete, ne be clepud quene, for the malice of Ed|burge forsaiden. And sheo &thorn;en wendyng to kyng</P><P>Charles the gret Charles of Fraunce, bi the grete. happe on a tyme, as she was essheked of him, whether sheo hadde lyuer haue him, than his sone that stode ther by, into housbond, sheo chees his sone. Thenne Charles, of he answere a|meved, saide thus. Yf thow haddest chose me, thow shuld|est haue hadde my sone; but for thow castest me a way, and chese my sone, nother him ne me shalt &thorn;ow haue. And then he putte her in a abbey, where she was wor|shipfulliche I founde. but af|ter sheo was founde gylty in lecherie, wherefore she was putte oute ther of. Kyng Bryghtryc had take these to wyue as for the mightyest kynge's doughter of En|glisshemen, that thourgh the affinite of hure he myghte haue his regne atte his wille, and putte of his Enmys the lightloker, and a gaste the rebelle to him. By the helpe of this kyng Offe he droff in to Fraunce Egbright, of the kynge's kynrede alone a lyf, and whiche he most dradde to be a yenst hym and contrarie to his profytes. For this Brightric, and other kynges fram Ine to him, were oute of the right lyne of kynges, as of Certikes kyn. Whanne Egbright thus was exiled, to Brightric a newe gre|uance yut sprong. For a folke of hethen Danes, y vsed to lyue by see robbery, pryuy|lich in iii. shippes shende the pes of Westsex. Whiche ship|pes aspied the plenteuous|nesse of the londe and the ver|tues of the men ther inne dwellyng, and they thenne wendyng home a ye, brought more peple, and assaide to stroye the contre, so that they toke the kyngus toune that was neighe and robbed hit. but anon, for drede of the peple rennyng therto, they flow to her shippus, lesyng her praye. And whenne Brigheric [<I>sic</I>] was dede, as aboue is saide, by poyson happeliche I dronke, atte Warham his body was take to buriels.</P></NOTE> purueid &thorn;at poyson &thorn;orgh hatered of old.
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="12">
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="13"></L>
<L>Brittrik hir lord, &thorn;at scho nouht wiste,</L>
<L>Unwarned drank &thorn;erof a drauht als him liste.</L>
<L>He lyued bot a moneth, &thorn;er of gan he die.</L>
<L>At Teukesbiri in toumbe his body did lie.
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="14"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIBRIHT, &thorn;at I of told, &thorn;at &thorn;e lond had lorn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Egbriht Rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at a suynhird slouh vnder a busk of thorn,</L>
<L>Had a kosyn, hight Egbriht, whilom exiled was</L>
<L>&thorn;orh &thorn;e kyng Brihtrik, I ne wote for what trispas.</L>
<L>&thorn;is ilk Egbriht was norised at Paris</L>
<L>In Charlemayn courte, sire of Saynt Dinys.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Male. Nam pater Egberti fuit Alcmundus sive Ealmundus. Vide Sax. Chron. p. 76.</NOTE>Ailrik was his fader, a duke of faire fame,</L>
<L>Lord of Wicombe, of Redynges, &amp; of Tame.</L>
<L>His moder was Sibriht sister, &thorn;at was a fole kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;at Brittrik was dede him com ti&thorn;ing.</L>
<L>He toke leue at Charles, &amp; com tille &thorn;is lond,</L>
<L>Among his riche kynde gode frendes he fond.</L>
<L>What &thorn;orgh lowe of lond, &amp; olde auncestrie,</L>
<L>Wan he &thorn;e regne of Westsex alle pleynerlie.</L>
<L>Whan he pleynere seysyn in &thorn;at his eam had lorn,</L>
<L>&thorn;at his fiue ancestres had holden beforn,</L>
<L>&thorn;orghout &thorn;e South to &thorn;e North he had for grete nyth,</L>
<L>If any Breton were fonden holdand lond or lyth,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he suld voide &thorn;e lond, if he his life wild saue.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Berne|wolf rege.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many fled to Lynday, socour forto haue,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng Bernewolf, &thorn;at was Breton,</L>
<L>&amp; he withsaid his feaute, &thorn;at he suld haf don.</L>
<L>Bituex &thorn;ise tuo kynges a werre bigan,</L>
<L>Slayn was Bernewolf, &amp; with him many man.</L>
<L>Under Elendoune &thorn;e bataile was smyten.</L>
<L>Men syng in &thorn;at cuntre (fele &yogh;it it witen)
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>"Elendoune, Elendoune, &thorn;i lond is fulle rede</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;e blode of Bernewolf, &thorn;er he toke his dede.</L>
<L>After &thorn;at bataile Egbriht, &thorn;us herd I say,</L>
<L>Seised Kent &amp; Estsex, Southsex &amp; Surray,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e grete lond, fro Douer to Grymsby.</L>
<L>Wilaf, Bernewolf sonne, &thorn;erwith had envy.</L>
<L>He wild haf venged his fadere, if he had haued myght.</L>
<L>Bot he fond no force agayn &thorn;e kyng Egbriht.</L>
<L>If he wild ouht haue, after `after<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dele.</NOTE> his fader decesse,</L>
<L>Nedly him bihoued com tille Egbriht pes.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last he com, &amp; mad &thorn;e kyng homage,</L>
<L>Egbriht for his curteisie gaf him his heritage.</L>
<L>&para; Egbriht of alle &thorn;e lond had &thorn;e regante,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De homa|gio Walli&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro Douere vnto Tuede, alle was his fee.</L>
<L>Wilaf with him he led, Wales forto se.</L>
<L>Bangore with force, &thorn;ei toke &thorn;at cite.</L>
<L>The Walsch men it sauh, it mot no better be,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei com befor Egbriht, &amp; mad him feaute,</L>
<L>&para; Sone after &thorn;e wyntere, whan &thorn;e somer bigan,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &amp; his meyne went to burgh Konan.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Konynges|burghe.</NOTE></L>
<L>It was on Witsonday, in tyme of slepyng,</L>
<L>Kom messengers of &thorn;e North, &amp; teld Egbriht &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh Frithbald a lord of &thorn;e Northende,</L>
<L>&amp; said, "Sir Egbriht, our chefe kyng to tille lende,</L>
<L>"Suffre not Sir Frethebald long to lede &thorn;is pyne.</L>
<L>"His folk beside Tuede es slayn &amp; kast &thorn;er ine,</L>
<L>"He is now in poynt his regne forto tyne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Frethe|baldo.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;orgh &thorn;am of Danmark &thorn;is lond wille &thorn;ei wyne,
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="16"></L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;ei Sir Frethebald haf now ouer comen,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e to &thorn;ere remenant of &thorn;e North son salle &thorn;ei nomen.</L>
<L>"Sir, for &thorn;is hie feste, &amp; for &thorn;e Trinite,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Bellum a|pud Kar|ham, &amp; rex fugam cepit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Suffre vs nouht to lese, for defeaute of &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAT did kyng Egbriht? Withouten any somons,</L>
<L>&amp; withouten askyng of Erles or barons,</L>
<L>He hied him &thorn;ider suyth, &amp;, whan he com to Tuede,</L>
<L>He sauh suylk oste of paiens, &thorn;at alle he was in drede.</L>
<L>Neuer&thorn;eles at Karham was the bataile gyuen,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng was narow holden, his folk alle to dryuen.</L>
<L>Tuo dukes &amp; tuo bisshopes for euer toke &thorn;er leue,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng was alle affraied, &thorn;er dede gan him greue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's folk was litelle, it had no dure.</L>
<L>On the nyght he fled away, &thorn;at non suld him se.</L>
<L>Myght he neuer noure fynd a restyng place.</L>
<L>Right vnto Donkastre &thorn;e Danes gan him chace.</L>
<L>Whan he wend haf passed &thorn;o &thorn;at gan him dryue,</L>
<L>&thorn;an were aryued in Humber &thorn;ritty schippes &amp; fyue.</L>
<L>Ilkone with folk inouh, redy to bataile,</L>
<L>"God wate," said &thorn;e kyng, "now comes me trauaile.</L>
<L>&para; Dardan hight &thorn;e cheftayn of &thorn;at company,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Dar|dano filio regis Da|ci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sadok sonne of Danmark kyng Danesry.</L>
<L>&thorn;er pauillons had &thorn;ei sette beside &thorn;e water of Done,</L>
<L>Egbriht gadred partie, &amp; &yogh;ared him fulle sone.</L>
<L>Listen now, how Jhesu Criste, for his mykelle mercy,</L>
<L>Agayn &thorn;e fals paiens &thorn;e Cristen stode he by.
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="17"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIBRIHT duke of Brailes, Egbriht sister sonne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De militia Anglorum, &amp; nomini|bus eorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>He com his eam to socour fro fer &thorn;er he gan wonne.</L>
<L>Syward &thorn;e gode westreis, Edald &thorn;e vavasoure,</L>
<L>Wilaf kyng of Merce, he com to &thorn;at stoure.</L>
<L>Harald of Donsmore his lord &thorn;ider led</L>
<L>Berald of &thorn;e Marche, of strength non he dred.</L>
<L>Haldayn of Donkastre was chosen &thorn;at ilk day,</L>
<L>To bere &thorn;e kynge's banere ageyn &thorn;e paien lay.</L>
<L>Bot Hakon, Hernebald sonne, of best he bare &thorn;e voice,</L>
<L>In stede of kynge's banere he did him bere &thorn;e croice,</L>
<L>In wirschip of Jhesu, &amp; of his passion,</L>
<L>&thorn;e paiens were so ferd, &thorn;ei myght haf no foyson.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e fer&thorn; day of Septembre, in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> heuest tide,<NOTE PLACE="marg">IIII<SUP>o</SUP>, die Septembris fuit bellum apud Don|kastre inter regem<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> Eg|briht &amp; Danos.</NOTE></L>
<L>At Donkastre mot men se manyon to batale ride.</L>
<L>&thorn;at to &thorn;e kyng Egbriht alle were &thorn;ei gyuen,</L>
<L>For &thorn;er heritage &thorn;er to die or lyuen.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei hewe on &thorn;e paiens, as men of wille gode.</L>
<L>&thorn;e paiens ageyn &thorn;am fulle stifely &thorn;ei stode.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei fauht alle &thorn;at day, ne left &thorn;ei not &thorn;e nyght,</L>
<L>Wilaf &thorn;e kyng of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> Merce.</NOTE> Merte was slayn in that fight,</L>
<L>&amp; Berald of &thorn;e Marche, &amp; &thorn;e duke Uttre</L>
<L>Lord of Cirencestre, &thorn;at nyght slayn was he.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at nyght &thorn;e kynge's folk fulle ille were &thorn;ei led,</L>
<L>Many on was slayn, &amp; wonded hard bisted.</L>
<L>Right in &thorn;e mornyng in aldermost nede</L>
<L>Com &thorn;e kynge's sonnes tuo, als Criste wild it rede,</L>
<L>Out of Germinie with folk inouh of myght,</L>
<L>Adelwolf &amp; Ethelbert, knyghtes bo&thorn;e fulle wyght.
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="18"></L>
<L>Was neuer in alle his lyue &thorn;er fadere ore so glad,</L>
<L>Als whan he sauh his sons tuo, &thorn;e paiens force to sprad.</L>
<L>Adelwolf his fader saued at &thorn;at ilk iorne,</L>
<L>&amp; Ethelbert in the felde his fader lete he se,</L>
<L>How Dardan for his lance doun to &thorn;e erth went,</L>
<L>&amp; smote his hede of, his fader to present.</L>
<L>&para; Harald of Donesmore vppon Done him mette</L>
<L>Vibrand, Dardane's bro&thorn;er, with suerd so him grette,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;orghout his armes Wibrand alle to hewe.</L>
<L>Sone with &thorn;e Danes gamned &thorn;am no glewe.</L>
<L>&thorn;at perceyued Haldayn, &thorn;at bare &thorn;e croice on hie,</L>
<L>Sex &amp; &thorn;ritty paiens enbussed priuelie.</L>
<L>He tok his suerd in hand, &thorn;e croyce lete he falle,</L>
<L>&amp; medeled him in &thorn;e pres, among &thorn;e barons alle.</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e kyng &amp; his sons he rincthed &thorn;am &thorn;e way,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de probitate Haldayn, qui porta|vit crucem pro vexillo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Many wer &thorn;e paiens &thorn;at Haldayn did slouh &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>Bituex vnderon &amp; noen was &thorn;e feld alle wonnen.</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at wild abide were ouer riden &amp; ronnen.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng with &thorn;e maistrie went in to &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pris he had wonnen, in vertew of Criste's passioun.</L>
<L>&para; Whan he had done &thorn;ere alle &thorn;at he suld do,</L>
<L>He went vnto Wynchestre, his conseile gaf him so.</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e somerestide &thorn;er gan he lende,</L>
<L>Fyue &amp; &thorn;ritty batailes had he brouht tille ende.</L>
<L>He felt him heuy &amp; ferly seke, his body wex alle seere,</L>
<L>His childre he wild auance, tille he o lyue were.</L>
<L>Tille Adelwolf gaf he Westsex, hede of alle &thorn;e thede,</L>
<L>Lordschip ouer alle &thorn;e londes bituex Douer &amp; Tuede.
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="19"></L>
<L>Ethelbert held Estsex, Southsex &amp; Kent,</L>
<L>For homage &amp; feaute tille Adelwolf it went.</L>
<L>Whan Egbriht had feffed his sons in londes seere,</L>
<L>Now in his last ende of fyue &amp; &thorn;ritty &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>At Wynchestre he died, &amp; &thorn;er his body is laid.</L>
<L>Was neuer &thorn;e lond so &yogh;emed, &thorn;e folk so &thorn;an said.</L>
<L>Fyue childir he had, knyghtes douhty of handes,</L>
<L>&amp; alle were &thorn;ei kynges in diuers landes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ADELWOLF of Westsex, after his fadere dede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Adelwolf rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>At Chestre sette his parlement, his tenantz &thorn;erto bede.</L>
<L>He sent for alle &thorn;e kynges, fro Berwik vnto Kent,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ei with fulle gode wille alle vnto him went,</L>
<L>&amp; mad tille him feaute, withouten any chest,</L>
<L>&amp; cleymed him for &thorn;er chefe of West &amp; of Est,</L>
<L>Of North &amp; of South in length &amp; in brede,</L>
<L>Fro Kent vntille Berwik, als lastes alle &thorn;at thede.</L>
<L>&para; He was first of Inglond, &thorn;at gaf God his ti&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>He was also so great a Friend to the University of Oxford, that he had thoughts of rebuilding it, after it had been destroyed by barbarous Enemies. Whence 'tis that some Historians say, that he was the Founder of that Uni|versity, which, however, is more truly asserted of his Son K.Al|fred, who certainly did raise it up again after the Destruction brought upon it by the Danes. Among others that ascribe this Act to K. &AElig;thelwolf is John Rastell, or Rastall, in his Chro|nicle, a wonderfull scarceprint|ed Book, lent me by my very worthy Friend, the ingenious Mr. John Murray of London.</I> &para; Ethelwolphus (<I>says Ra|stell</I>) son to Egbert began his reyn ouer the westsaxons the yere of cryst. viii. c. xxxii. &verbar; some say that this Ethelwold [<I>l.</I> Ethelwolf] foundyd furst the vnyuersyte of Oxonford. <I>Where the word</I> furst <I>is to be understood of the</I> first found|ing <I>it after it had been destroy|ed, not that there had been no University here before. See my Preface to Thomas Sprot's Chronicle</I>, &sect;. 15.</NOTE>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Primus rex, qui dedit decimas ec|clesi&aelig; in Anglia.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Isshue of bestes, of londes or of li&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he went to Rome, as man of holy wille,</L>
<L>His sonne &amp; he alle &thorn;at &yogh;ere with &thorn;e pape duelled stille.</L>
<L>&thorn;e to&thorn;er &yogh;ere next, after his duellyng,</L>
<L>He went home bi France, &amp; spak with &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng him his douhter, hir name was Juwet,</L>
<L>Fulle wele on Sir Adelwolf was &thorn;at maiden sett.</L>
<L>He brouht hir Inglond, &amp; si&thorn;en lyued tuo &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>He lies at Wynchestre beside an autere.</L>
<L>&thorn;re &thorn;ousand marke he gaf with testament fulle right</L>
<L>To Petir &amp; Paule of Rome, to susteyn &thorn;er light.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER Adelwolf, his sonne hight Edbalde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Edbaldus rex fatuus.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &yogh;ere &amp; a half &thorn;e regne gan he halde.</L>
<L>Of him in holy kirke men said euelle sawe,</L>
<L>His stepmoder Juwet he weddid agayn &thorn;e lawe.</L>
<L>Of his body was no force, non for him wild murne.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;us I fond in my boke, he lies at Schirburne.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date of Criste to neuen &thorn;us fele were gon,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno Do|mini.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Repone</I>, DCCC.LXI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> D CCCC. LXI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Auht hundreth euen, &amp; sexti &amp; on.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER Edbalde com Ethelbert his eam,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ethelbertus rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>Adelwolfe's bro&thorn;er, of Egbrihte's team.</L>
<L>He did him coroune kyng, he was a noble man,</L>
<L>&amp; in his first &yogh;ere paiens on him ran
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>Right at Wynchestre, ageyn &thorn;am gan he stand,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &thorn;am bataile, &amp; did &thorn;am fle &thorn;e land.</L>
<L>In werryng &amp; in wo he regned fyue &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Men biried him at Schireburn, Edbald fulle nere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date of Jhesu Criste was written in &thorn;is lyue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno Domini. DCCC<SUP>mo</SUP>. LX.V<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Auht hundreth wynter sexti &amp; fyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER Ethelbert com Elfrith his bro&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Elfridus rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at was Egbrihte's sonne, &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;er was a no&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Elfride &thorn;orgh heritage toke him &thorn;e coroune,</L>
<L>&amp; gaf Alfride his bro&thorn;er Surray to warisoune.</L>
<L>Tille Elfride oure kyng com ti&thorn;inges starke,</L>
<L>&thorn;at fyue kynges &amp; fyue erles wer comen of Danmarke,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wild on him renne, &amp; reue him &thorn;e coroune,</L>
<L>With alle &thorn;er grete folk, &thorn;ei lay in Aluertoune.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &amp; his bro&thorn;er, &thorn;at hight Alfrede,</L>
<L>Gadred folk togider, als men &thorn;at had nede,</L>
<L>&amp; com to &thorn;e bataile with fulle egre herte.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Danes stode &thorn;am ageyn with bataile fulle smerte.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e passion tyme was &thorn;e first bataile,</L>
<L>Nene was &thorn;at ilk &yogh;ere, grete was &thorn;er trauaile.</L>
<L>&thorn;e to&thorn;er &yogh;ere, &thorn;e &thorn;rid day after Halwethurs tide,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Danes, &thorn;orgh Gode's grace, were on &thorn;e wers side.</L>
<L>For slayn were &thorn;ei alle, erle &amp; baron.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng did mak at &yogh;ork a faire procession,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;anked Jhesu Criste with herte fulle mylde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ageyn &thorn;e paiens his lond myght schilde.
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="22"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ELFRIDE had a kosyn, &thorn;at kyng was of schelde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Sancto Edmundo martire, &amp; de morte ejus per to|tum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Northfolk &amp; Southfolk of Elfride he helde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was Saynt Edmunde, &thorn;e croune &thorn;at tyme bare.</L>
<L>A duke of Danmark, his name was Inguare,</L>
<L>Ubbe an erle of Huneis with &thorn;at Inguar kam,</L>
<L>Uppon Saynt Edmunde Northfolk he nam.</L>
<L>Edmunde sent his messengers, of pes &thorn;am bisouht.</L>
<L>Inguar sent bode ageyn, &thorn;at pes wild he nouht,</L>
<L>Bot if he &yogh;ald him &thorn;e lond, &thorn;an he suld haf pes.</L>
<L>&thorn;at wild not Saynt Edmunde, &thorn;e bataile he ches.</L>
<L>He atired him to bataile with folk &thorn;at he had.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is cursed Danes so grete oste ay lad,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Edmunde was taken, and slayn at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>Fulle fer fro &thorn;e body lay was &thorn;e hede kast.</L>
<L>&thorn;e body son &thorn;ei fonde, &thorn;e hade was in doute.</L>
<L>Up &amp; doune in &thorn;e felde &thorn;ei souht it aboute,</L>
<L>To haf knowyng &thorn;erof, alle &thorn;ei were in were,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce mira|culum de capite San|cti Edmun|di.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tille &thorn;e hede him self said, <I>here, here, here.</I></L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;ei fond &thorn;e hede is now a faire chapelle,</L>
<L>Oxen hate &thorn;e toun, &thorn;er &thorn;e body felle.</L>
<L>&thorn;er where he was schotte a no&thorn;er chapelle standes,</L>
<L>&amp; somwhat of &thorn;at tre, &thorn;ei bond vntille his handes.</L>
<L>&thorn;e tone is fro &thorn;e to&thorn;er moten a grete myle,</L>
<L>So fer bare a woulfe &thorn;e hede, &amp; kept it a grete while,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e hede said, <I>here</I>, als I befor said.</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e woulf &thorn;ei it toke, vnto &thorn;e body it laid.</L>
<L>Men sais, &thorn;er he ligges &thorn;e flesch samen &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e token of &thorn;e wonde als a rede threde.
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>Now lies he in schryne in golde &thorn;at is rede.</L>
<L>Seuen &yogh;ere was he kyng &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at he was dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e &yogh;ere after, right in &thorn;e tyme of May,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Oseth, rex Daci&aelig;, ar|ripuit por|tum in Ber|wik super regem El|fridum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Oseth, &thorn;e Danes kyng, com Inglond to affray.</L>
<L>He aryued at Berwik, in &thorn;e water of Tuede.</L>
<L>Priue help of &thorn;e Scottes he had at his nede,</L>
<L>&amp; com fast toward &thorn;e South, grete powere he led.</L>
<L>Elfride &amp; his bro&thorn;ere out of &yogh;ork fled.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei praied God specially, &thorn;at he wild &thorn;am saue,</L>
<L>&amp; ageyn &thorn;e Danes help inouh to haue.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;e bataile, displayed his banere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &yogh;ede to &thorn;e kirke, his messe forto here.</L>
<L>Bot Alfride his bro&thorn;er &yogh;ede to &thorn;e bataile.</L>
<L>He was ouer hardy, &thorn;e Danes he gan assaile.</L>
<L>Discomfite was Alfride within a litelle throwe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng herd &thorn;at telle, &thorn;at his side &yogh;ede lowe.</L>
<L>He dight him to &thorn;e bataile, his folk to socoure.</L>
<L>God did faire miracle for Elfride &thorn;at houre.</L>
<L>For non of &thorn;e Danes askaped with &thorn;e life.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e Scottes kyng, &thorn;at mayntend &thorn;at strife,</L>
<L>Opon Elfride ran, als traytoure inferd.</L>
<L>Elfride he wonded with dynt of a suerd.</L>
<L>Sex &yogh;ere was he kyng, with werre weldid &thorn;e scheld.</L>
<L>Fulle gode was his endyng, he ligges at Driffeld.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;of alle &thorn;at he werred in wo &amp; in strife,</L>
<L>&thorn;e foure &amp; tuenty houres he spended in holy life.</L>
<L>&thorn;e ferst. viii. houres in praier alderbest,</L>
<L>&thorn;e to&thorn;er. viii. houres in slepe &amp; in rest.
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;rid. viii. houres he studied, how he myght</L>
<L>Mayntene &thorn;e lond with lawe, his folk hald to right.</L>
<L>Haluendele his godes he gaf to Gode's werkes,</L>
<L>Sustened abbeis, norised pouer clerkes,</L>
<L>Did reise vp kirkes, &thorn;at were fallen doun,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;at him serued he brouht to warisoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;ere of Criste's birth was auht hundreth euen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno. D CCCo. LXXIo.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;us many mo, sexty &amp; elleuen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ALFRIDE his bro&thorn;er, a gode clerk was he one,</L>
<L>Of body so douhty in Inglond was none.</L>
<L>He resceyued &thorn;e coroune, after his bro&thorn;er dede,</L>
<L>Strong were &thorn;e batailes &thorn;e Danes on him bede.</L>
<L>Tuo &amp; tuenty batailes he wanne &thorn;e first &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Danes so many tymes aryued on him here.</L>
<L>&thorn;at he so many slouh a duke had envie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Rollo pagano ba|ptizato, cui nomen erat Robertus, &amp; hic con|quisivit to|tam Nor|manniam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; eft aryued on &thorn;is lond with fulle grete nauie.</L>
<L>Rollo was his name, a knyght fulle douhty,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Alfride wend wele, haf lorn &thorn;e seignory.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei com to bataile, ilk o&thorn;er gan askie,</L>
<L>Alfride vnto Rollo sone gan him alie.</L>
<L>So many douhty dyntes was bituex &thorn;am tueye,</L>
<L>Wele &thorn;ei did togidere, better may no man seye.</L>
<L>God, &thorn;orgh his grace, &thorn;at day so wele sped,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Rollo asked Cristendom at &thorn;e kyng Alfred.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;at Cristendom, &thorn;o, &thorn;at were so wro&thorn;e,</L>
<L>At haly kirke's fayth alle on were bo&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Rollo was kald Roberd, whan he was baptized,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e kyng Alfride, als he had deuised.
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>Now is Roberd Cristen, he dightes his nauie,</L>
<L>&amp; ferde ouer &thorn;e see, &amp; conquerd Normundie.</L>
<L>Duke &thorn;an was he cald, &thorn;orgh conquest of hond,</L>
<L>Alfrid he left stille here in Inglond.</L>
<L>&para; &yogh;it a no&thorn;er Danes kyng in &thorn;e Nor&thorn; gan aryue.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Gun|tero patre Hanelok, sicut dicit Petrus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alfrid it herd, &thorn;idere gan he dryue.</L>
<L>Hanelok fader he was, Gunter was his name.</L>
<L>He brent citees &amp; tounes, ouer alle did he schame.</L>
<L>Saynt Cutberte's clerkes &thorn;o Danes &thorn;ei dred.</L>
<L>&thorn;e toke &thorn;e holy bones, about &thorn;ei &thorn;am led.</L>
<L>Seuen &yogh;ere &thorn;orgh &thorn;e land wer &thorn;ei born aboute,</L>
<L>It comforted &thorn;e kyng mykelle, whan he was in doute.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Alfrid &amp; Gunter had werred long in ille,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e grace of God, Gunter turned his wille.</L>
<L>Cristend wild he be, &thorn;e kyng of fonte him lift,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ritty of his knyghtes turnes, &thorn;orgh Gode's gift.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at first were foos, &amp; com of paien lay,</L>
<L>Of Cristen men haf los, &amp; so &thorn;ei wend away.</L>
<L>&para; Bot I haf grete ferly, &thorn;at I fynd no man,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Hane|lok.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at has writen in story, how Hanelok &thorn;is lond wan.</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er Gildas, no Bede, no Henry of Huntynton,</L>
<L>No William of Malmesbiri, ne Pers of Bridlynton,</L>
<L>Writes not in &thorn;er bokes of no kyng Athelwold,</L>
<L>Ne Goldeburgh his douhtere, ne Hanelok not of told,</L>
<L>Whilk tyme &thorn;e were kynges, long or now late</L>
<L>&thorn;ei mak no menyng whan, no in what date.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at &thorn;ise lowed men vpon Inglish tellis,</L>
<L>Right story can me not ken, &thorn;e certeynte what spellis.
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="26"></L>
<L>Men sais in Lyncoln castelle ligges &yogh;it a stone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Hanelok kast wele forbi euer ilkone.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;it &thorn;e chapelle standes, &thorn;er he weddid his wife,</L>
<L>Goldeburgh &thorn;e kynge's douhter, &thorn;at saw is &yogh;it rife.</L>
<L>&amp; of Gryme a fisshere, men redes &yogh;it in ryme,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he bigged Grymesby Gryme &thorn;at ilk tyme.</L>
<L>Of alle stories of honoure, &thorn;at I haf &thorn;orgh souht,</L>
<L>I fynd, &thorn;at no compiloure of him tellis ouht.</L>
<L>Sen I fynd non redy, &thorn;at tellis of Hanelok kynde,</L>
<L>Turne we to &thorn;at story, &thorn;at we writen fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SON after com an erle, Alfden hight &thorn;at hunde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De comiti|bus Daci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aryued vp with Inguar, &thorn;at slouh S. Edmunde.</L>
<L>Upon &thorn;e kyng Alfrid werre son began,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;or&yogh;h &thorn;e gode Northeren slayn wer ilkaman.</L>
<L>Sex &amp; fifty batailes Alfrid ouercam,</L>
<L>After nyen &amp; tuenty &yogh;ere &thorn;e dede him hi&thorn;en nam,</L>
<L>&amp; sex monethes mo, &thorn;us &thorn;e story said.</L>
<L>At Wynchestre in toumbe in &thorn;e abbay is he laid.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date &thorn;at certeyn es in boke writen here,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er more no lesse, &thorn;an nien hundreth &yogh;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER &thorn;is Alfride kom Edward &thorn;e olde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Edwardus ICX.</NOTE></L>
<L>Faire man he was &amp; wis, stalworth &amp; bolde.</L>
<L>At London, at Saynt Poule's, toke he &thorn;e croune,</L>
<L>&amp; purueied his parlement of erle &amp; baroune.</L>
<L>He seid vnto &thorn;am alle, &thorn;at purueied suld it be,</L>
<L>&thorn;at in alle &thorn;e lond suld be no kyng bot he.
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>&thorn;e smale kynges of &thorn;e lond all were &thorn;ei comen,</L>
<L>Of Scotland, of Wales, of Kombirlond, &thorn;ei nomen</L>
<L>Inglis &amp; Danes, &amp; &thorn;e gode Norreis,</L>
<L>Duke, erle &amp; baron, &amp; o&thorn;er knyghtes curteis,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei said in &thorn;at parlement, &thorn;orgh conseile of alle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Edward felle best be chefe, o&thorn;er suld non falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Edward chosen kyng at &thorn;er parlement,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e lordschip of &thorn;e lond alle tille him went.</L>
<L>Fourtene childre he gate opon tuo wifes,</L>
<L>Sex sonnes &amp; auht douhtres, &thorn;o were faire lyues.</L>
<L>Athelstan, Edwyn, Edgar, Edmond, Edred, Edwy:</L>
<L>Hilde was his douhter, was kald Hilden lady,</L>
<L>Elfled &amp; saynt Eadburgh &thorn;at lyued holy life,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ferth Octouian Mary &thorn;at Emperoure's wife.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei passed of &thorn;is world, whan &thorn;ei were right &yogh;onge,</L>
<L>What &thorn;er names were I kan telle no tonge.</L>
<L>&para; In Edwarde's tend &yogh;ere aryued vp in Kent</L>
<L>&thorn;re kynges &amp; sex dukes, &thorn;at out of Danmark went.</L>
<L>In to Lyndsay brouht &thorn;ei him tiyng,</L>
<L>&amp; purueied oste &amp; dight him als a douhty kyng.</L>
<L>At Teteford in Northfolk his baner was displaied,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;re kynges were slayn, &thorn;e to&thorn;er were affraied,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei went to &thorn;er schippes, so hard he sette his chace,</L>
<L>Edward had &thorn;e maistri, &amp; &thorn;anked God his grace.</L>
<L>He com neuer to bataile, &thorn;at he ne had &thorn;e maistrie.</L>
<L>Foure &amp; tuenty &yogh;ere was he kyng, &amp; &thorn;orgh no folie</L>
<L>Neuer in his lyue a fote of lond he les.</L>
<L>Scotland &amp; Cumberland &amp; Wales he had in pes,
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>Cornwalle, Lyndsay &amp; Kent, Dorsette &amp; Surreie.</L>
<L>He ligges at Wynchestre, &thorn;e soth it is to seie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date of God nien hundreth, &amp; four &amp; tuenti mo,</L>
<L>Whan dede his lyfe sundred, &thorn;e folk for him was wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER Edward &thorn;e olde regned Athelstan,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Adelsta|nus rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at was his eldest sonne, &amp; a noble man.</L>
<L>&thorn;e baronage &amp; &thorn;e cler&yogh;ie were somond to Kyngeston,</L>
<L>&thorn;er wes his fest holden, &amp; gyuen him &thorn;e croune.</L>
<L>&thorn;e next &yogh;ere &thorn;ere after his coronment,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Tributo Walli&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Walsh men, &thorn;at luf no pes, on him ran &amp; brent.</L>
<L>Bot Athelstan &thorn;e maistrie wan, &amp; did &thorn;am mercie crie,</L>
<L>&amp; alle Northwales he set to treuage hie.</L>
<L>Tuenti pounde of gold be &yogh;ere, &thorn;re hundreth of siluer clere,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er to fyue hundreth kie ilk &yogh;ere to his lardere.</L>
<L>Siluer for Southwales not a fer&thorn;ing noke</L>
<L>O&thorn;er treuage he sette, a &thorn;ousand kie he toke.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ist&icirc; sunt qui moverunt guerram super A|thelstanum regem.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e ferth &yogh;ere of &thorn;e regne Owald a werreoure,</L>
<L>Constantyn of Scotland kyng was &amp; traitoure,</L>
<L>Ouwer kyng of Wentland, &thorn;ese &thorn;re with &thorn;er powere</L>
<L>Werred on Athelstan with oste fulle austere.</L>
<L>Bot Athelstan, &thorn;orgh Gode's graee, so with &thorn;am fore,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei were fayn to ask pes, &amp; feaute &thorn;ei him suore.</L>
<L>&thorn;e tend &yogh;ere of his regne sen he was crouned kyng,</L>
<L>Of Edwyn his bro&thorn;er bifelle suilk a &thorn;yng.</L>
<L>At London in his courte with wiknes men him fond,</L>
<L>Athelstan did him bynd both fote &amp; hond,</L>
<L>&amp; kast him in tille Temse, whan it was most brym,</L>
<L>To chastise alle o&thorn;er he tok vengeance on him.
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>At myn vnderstandyng he wild tak no mede</L>
<L>&thorn;at was ateynt of wikkednes, his bro&thorn;er to dede &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&para; Constantyn of Scotlond, &thorn;at I are of spak,</L>
<L>Brak his feaute sone, of treson it is lak,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De falsitate regis Sco|torum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; alle folk of Danmark with Constantyn held,</L>
<L>&amp; slouh our Inglish men, wasted toun &amp; feld.</L>
<L>Athelstan herd say, he went to Beuerlay,</L>
<L>&amp; praied to &thorn;e bisshop Jon in fertre &thorn;er he lay,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wild bede his bone, vntille &thorn;e Trinite,</L>
<L>&amp; he suld gyue his kirke franchise &amp; fe,</L>
<L>To haf &amp; to holde als he was kyng leale.</L>
<L>Of him haf &thorn;ei chartre seled with his seale.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he went to Durham, &amp; gaf Saynt Cutbert</L>
<L>Londes &amp; li&thorn;es, with chartir aperte.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of his gift holdes his fe,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he went to bataile, Constantyn to fle.</L>
<L>Constantyn he reymed, &amp; did vnto stresse,</L>
<L>&amp; wan &thorn;e lond ilk dele, &amp; wasted alle Cathenesse,</L>
<L>&amp; his son &yogh;olden vnto his ostage.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he turned to London, &amp; his baronage.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Misio rex Karolus re|gi Athel|stano pro sorore sua Hilda. lege per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Athelstan in Scotland a selcouth ded he one,</L>
<L>He smote depe at Donbarre, an elne in &thorn;e stone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT &thorn;e feste of our lady &thorn;e Assumpcion,</L>
<L>Went &thorn;e kyng fro London toward Abindon.</L>
<L>&thorn;ider out of France fro Charles kyng of fame</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Princeps hujus legationis fuit Adulphus, filius Balde|wini Comitis Flandri&aelig;, ex filia regis Edwardi Ethel|switha</I> Guil. Malmsb. de gestis regum Anglorum, p. 28.</NOTE>Com &thorn;e of Boloyn, Adulphus was his name,
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e duke of Burgoyn, Edmunde sonne, Reynere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e brouht kyng Athelston present withouten pere,</L>
<L>Fro Charles kyng sanz faile thei brouht a gonfaynoun</L>
<L>&thorn;at Saynt Morice in bataile befor &thorn;e legioun,</L>
<L>&amp; scharp lance &thorn;at thrilled Ihesu side;</L>
<L>&amp; a suerd of gold, in &thorn;e hilte did men hide</L>
<L>Tuo of &thorn;o nayles, &thorn;at war &thorn;orh Ihesu fete</L>
<L>Tached on &thorn;e croyce, &thorn;e blode &thorn;ei out lete,</L>
<L>&amp; som of &thorn;e thornes &thorn;at don were on his heued,</L>
<L>&amp; a fair pece &thorn;at of &thorn;e croyce leued,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Saynt Heleyn sonne at &thorn;e bataile wan</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Soudan of Askalone, his name was Madan.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an blewe &thorn;e trumpes fulle loud &amp; fulle schille,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng com in to &thorn;e halle, &thorn;at hardy was of wille.</L>
<L>&thorn;an spak Reyner, Edmunde sonne, (for he was messengere)</L>
<L>"Athelstan, my lord &thorn;e gretes, Charles &thorn;at has no pere.</L>
<L>"He sendes &thorn;e &thorn;is present, &amp; sais, he wille him bynde</L>
<L>"To &thorn;e &thorn;orh Ilde &thorn;i sistere, &amp; tille alle &thorn;i kynde.</L>
<L>Befor &thorn;e messengers was &thorn;e maiden brouht,</L>
<L>Of body so gentille was non in erth wrouht.</L>
<L>No non so faire of face, of spech so lufly,</L>
<L>Scho granted befor &thorn;am alle to Charles hir body,</L>
<L>&amp; so did &thorn;e kyng, &amp; alle &thorn;e baronage.</L>
<L>Mykelle was &thorn;e richesse, &thorn;ei purueied hir passage,</L>
<L>&amp; led hir vnto France, spoused forto be,</L>
<L>Athelstan leues stille, &amp; passed not &thorn;e se.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Iterum de perjura|tione regis Scottorum, &amp; de bello Dacorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e &yogh;ere after &thorn;at Ilde wedded was,</L>
<L>Constantyn of Scotlond did &yogh;it more trispas.
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>He brouht &thorn;e kyng Anlaf aryued vp in Humbere,</L>
<L>Seuen hundreth schippes &amp; fiftene, so fele were &thorn;e numbere.</L>
<L>Athelstan herd say of &thorn;er mykelle oste,</L>
<L>He &amp; Edmunde his bro&thorn;er dight &thorn;am to &thorn;at coste.</L>
<L>At Brunesburgh on Humber &thorn;ei gan &thorn;am assaile,</L>
<L>Fro morn vnto euen lastell &thorn;at bataile.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last to &thorn;er schippes &thorn;e kyng gan &thorn;am chace,</L>
<L>Alle away &thorn;ei fled, &thorn;at was of Gode's grace.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e most partie algate was slayn,</L>
<L>&thorn;at with life fled I trowe &thorn;ei were fulle fayn.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e kyng Anlaf sauh his folk lorn,</L>
<L>He fled vnto Danmark &thorn;er pere he was born.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e Pask after he ryued in &thorn;e South,</L>
<L>At a hauen of Sandwich, in &thorn;e portis mouth.</L>
<L>Whan he was aryued, &thorn;e folk was affray,</L>
<L>&amp; com unto Wynchestre &thorn;er &thorn;e kyng lay.</L>
<L>He brouht with him a deuelle, a hogge Geant,</L>
<L>Wele haf &yogh;e herd telle, he hight Colibrant.</L>
<L>Anlaf sent messengers vnto Athelstan,</L>
<L>&amp; bad him &yogh;eld &thorn;e lond, or fynd a no&thorn;er man</L>
<L>To fight with Colibrant, &thorn;at was his champion;</L>
<L>Who felle to haf &thorn;e lond, on &thorn;am it suld be don.</L>
<L>Athelstan tok a day, a parlement did make,</L>
<L>If any ageyn Colibrant &thorn;e bataile durst take.</L>
<L>He fond no man &thorn;at durst, for non had myght,</L>
<L>With Colibrant alone in bataile to fight.</L>
<L>&thorn;an praied Athelstan to Criste &amp; sore wepe,</L>
<L>&amp; God sent him tokenyng on nyght als he slepe,
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="32"></L>
<L>&thorn;at he suld fynd a palmere orly at morn,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e South &yogh;ate, alone as he was born,</L>
<L>&amp; if he wild praie him, for Jhesu Criste's loue,</L>
<L>He wild do &thorn;e bataile, &amp; &thorn;ei suld be aboue.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de bello inter Guydonem de Werwyk &amp; Coli|brant.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at was Guy of Werwik, as &thorn;e boke sais.</L>
<L>&thorn;er he slouh Colibrant with hache Daneis.</L>
<L>Anlaf turned agayn, I trowe him was wo,</L>
<L>He &amp; alle his to schippe gan &thorn;ei go.</L>
<L>God delyuerde Athelstan of many hard affaies,</L>
<L>Sextene &yogh;ere was he kyng &amp; seuentene daies,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en at Gloucestre dede euelle him toke.</L>
<L>Bot quik he out went, so sais my boke.</L>
<L>Pers can not say where he lies,</L>
<L>Bot as I herd telle I say myn auys.</L>
<L>Men say he was fonden in &thorn;e North cuntre<NOTE PLACE="marg">De fine Athelstani regis.</NOTE></L>
<L>At Hexham now late, I wene soth it be.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date whan he died of God men tellis by<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno Domini DCCCC<SUP>mo.</SUP> XL<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nien hundreth wynter &amp; fulle fourty.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER Athelstan &thorn;e kyng was Edmunde his bro&thorn;er,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Edmundus Rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e northren did him desceit, &amp; ches &thorn;am a no&thorn;er.</L>
<L>One Anlaf &thorn;ei ches, &amp; crouned him for kyng.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e North ende was in his kepyng,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e South ende tille Edmunde &thorn;ei drouh.</L>
<L>Upon &thorn;e fals Norreis Edmunde wan inouh.</L>
<L>Fyue cites he wan, &thorn;at &thorn;ei held for &thorn;ers,</L>
<L>&thorn;at whilom was ancestres, fro heires vnto heires,
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>Lycoln &amp; Derby, &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Snotingaham (<I>vel</I> Notinge|ham) <I>aliis. Neque aliter qui|dem tam apud Florentium quam &amp; Chron. Saxon.</I> Stafford <I>pro</I> Stamford <I>habet Speedus, secus atque auctores vett.</I></NOTE> Southampton,</L>
<L>Leycestre &amp; Stamford, &thorn;ise fyue wan Edmon,</L>
<L>&amp; yit &thorn;e kyng Anlaf so hard gan he chace,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he asked Cristendom opon Gode's grace.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e he &amp; Reynald was Guthefride's sonne,</L>
<L>He exilde &thorn;am out of &thorn;e North, &thorn;er &thorn;ei wild wonne.</L>
<L>&amp; gaf to Malcolme, kyng of Scotlande,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he suld be him leale, bi se &amp; bi lande.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE fifte &yogh;ere of his regne he went to Canterbiri,</L>
<L>&thorn;e feste of S. Austine, to hold it fulle myri.</L>
<L>A thefe of his courte was outlawed late,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng knew him fulle wele, he mette him in &thorn;e gate.</L>
<L>Whilom he serued in his panterie,</L>
<L>&amp; was outlawed for a felonie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng tok &thorn;is pantelere, &amp; strangled him right &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>&amp; he wonded &thorn;e kyng dedely fulle sore.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De mirabili morte regis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seuen &yogh;ere was he kyng, &amp; seuen monethis mo.</L>
<L>At Gloucestre is he laid, &thorn;e pantelere did him slo.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date was nien hundreth four&thorn;ty &amp; seuen.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno Domini DCCCC<SUP>mo</SUP> XLVII.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is was &thorn;e selcouthest cas, &thorn;at haf herd neuen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EDRED after Edmunde had &thorn;e coroune,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Edredus rex, frater Edmuudi.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e Pask day, at London toune.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en of all his barons he tok feaute,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e Northeren men held him no leaute.
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="34"></L>
<L>Eylrike of Danmark for kyng &thorn;ei him ches,</L>
<L>&amp; forsoke Edrede, &thorn;er were &thorn;ei les.</L>
<L>Edrede with powere vntille &thorn;e North went,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e toun of Ripon he wasted &amp; brent.</L>
<L>Northumberland was in affray for Edred comyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei did doun Eylrik &thorn;e Danes kyng,</L>
<L>&amp; went out of &thorn;e lond with his rascaile,</L>
<L>Was he not so hardy at stand to bataile.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;o Norreis, &thorn;at had bien so fikelle,</L>
<L>Pes forto haue &thorn;ei glosed him fulle mykelle.</L>
<L>&thorn;er londes &amp; &thorn;er rentes were at his wille,</L>
<L>He gaf S. Cutbert &thorn;erof, &yogh;it &thorn;ei hold it stille.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e regne holy was &thorn;at tyme in his hand,</L>
<L>&amp; erles &amp; barons &thorn;at wer in &thorn;e land,</L>
<L>So wele were &thorn;ei chastised, alle com tille his grith,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e pes of &thorn;e lond &thorn;e sikered him alle with.</L>
<L>Auht &yogh;ere was he kyng, his daies alle filled.</L>
<L>At Wynchestre he lies, so himself willed.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date nien hundreth fifty &amp; fyue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno Domini. DCCCC<SUP>mo</SUP>. LV<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at kyng Edred passed of &thorn;is lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER Sir Edred was his bro&thorn;er Edwy,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Edgarus rex homo sanctus, pa|ter Sancti Edwardi martyris.</NOTE></L>
<L>He resceyued &thorn;e croune of &thorn;e seignory.</L>
<L>So foole a man of his life non was seene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e hie men of &thorn;e lond conseild &thorn;am bituene,</L>
<L>To do doun Edwy at a parlement,</L>
<L>&amp; tille his bro&thorn;er Edgare gyf &thorn;e tenement.
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>S. Donstan &thorn;e bisshop was at his<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> coronyng.</NOTE> coronment,</L>
<L>&amp; of alle his ancestres was neuer better kyng.</L>
<L>He was bo&thorn;e gode &amp; wys in alle his dedis,</L>
<L>&amp; right vnderstandyng, to help at alle nedis.</L>
<L>Mikille he wirschiped God, &amp; serued our Lady,</L>
<L>&thorn;e abbey of Rumeye he feffed richely,</L>
<L>With rentes fulle gode &amp; kirkes of pris,</L>
<L>He did &thorn;er in of Nunnes a hundreth ladies.</L>
<L>&para; Edgare forto fle lichery of lyfe,</L>
<L>His barons gaf him conseile for to take a wyfe</L>
<L>Elfled &thorn;e faire, &thorn;e duke's douhter Ormere.</L>
<L>He gate of hir S. Edward, &thorn;at is &thorn;e martere.</L>
<L>Dame Elfled died sone, &yogh;it wild he luf mare,</L>
<L>He tok bittere Estrild, duke's douhter Orgare.</L>
<L>Of hir lord Edgar had scho sonnes tueye,</L>
<L>Edmunde, &thorn;at in his tende &yogh;ere at Peterburgh gan deie.</L>
<L>Eylred was the &yogh;ongest, &amp; Estrild fulle dere.</L>
<L>Wo was in his tyme, as &yogh;e may after here.</L>
<L>Edgar &thorn;er fader had alle Ingland,</L>
<L>He went to Kerlion, &thorn;e Walsch men he band</L>
<L>With homage &amp; feaute, in right &amp; in lawe.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Omnes isti fecerunt homaginum regi Ed|garo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kymak kyng of Scotland, he com for fyne awe,</L>
<L>&amp; Malcolme of Combirland was at his wille,</L>
<L>Maccum kyng of &thorn;e Iles, Dufnald fitz Omere,</L>
<L>Sifreth &amp; Huwalle, Jacob &amp; Juthille,</L>
<L>He did &thorn;am mak feaute, als right was &amp; skille.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he went aboute, kirkes vp to raise,</L>
<L>Abbayes forto help, were fallen in miseyse.
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="36"></L>
<L>He gaf to Crouland, in &thorn;e Abbot tyme Gounterc,</L>
<L>&thorn;re myle of seignorie, about his autere.</L>
<L>Auhten &yogh;ere Edgar regned kyng &amp; sire,</L>
<L>He lies in tombe in &thorn;e abbey of Glastenbire.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OF Edgar &thorn;e kyng &thorn;us fond I writen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de mi|raculo San|cti Edgari.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pers telles &thorn;e same &thorn;ing, at his boke may &yogh;e witen.</L>
<L>Sen four &amp; tuenti &yogh;ere, &thorn;at he in erth was laid,</L>
<L>An abbot of Glastebiri, Edward his name is said,</L>
<L>He did mak a toumbe, Edgar in to lay,</L>
<L>Bot it was ouer litelle, in alle maner way.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei brak in tuo his schankes, to mak &thorn;e toumbe mete,</L>
<L>&thorn;e blode was bo&thorn;e warme &amp; fresh, &thorn;at of &thorn;e schankes lete.</L>
<L>&thorn;e abbot wex alle blynd, &thorn;at did his bones breke.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop Owald herd of &thorn;at miracle speke,</L>
<L>Renst at at &thorn;e toumbe, he tok vp &thorn;e bones,</L>
<L>In a fertre &thorn;am laid a riche for &thorn;e nones.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date was nien hundreth sexti &amp; &thorn;rittene,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno DCCCC<SUP>mo</SUP>. LXXIII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was a holy man &thorn;orgh miracle was sene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER Edgare was Edward his sonne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Sancto Edwardo martire.</NOTE></L>
<L>Regnand in alle &thorn;e lond, als his fader was wonne.</L>
<L>S. Dunstan corouned him bifor &thorn;e baronage</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er bisshopes inouh, fulle &yogh;on&yogh;e he was of age.</L>
<L>A gode man he was, &amp; stalworth knyght als stele.</L>
<L>In Ingland neuer before was kyng lufed so wele,</L>
<L>Ne of &thorn;e folk strange non honourd so mykelle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e right lawes did he loke for fals men &amp; fikelle.
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e riche &amp; pouere he &yogh;emed in euenhede,</L>
<L>Non suld do o&thorn;er wrong for couetise no drede.</L>
<L>Estrild his stepmoder scho &thorn;ouht on felonie.</L>
<L>Tille wikked men scho spak, Edward to aspie.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei did als scho &thorn;am bad, &amp; wrouht &thorn;am seluen wouh,</L>
<L>At Koruesgate &thorn;orgh desceit Edward kyng &thorn;ei slouh.</L>
<L>&thorn;re &yogh;ere was he kyng, &thorn;e story &thorn;us me said,</L>
<L>His body at Westmynstere in fertre is it laid.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de morte ejus anno. DCCCC<SUP>mo</SUP> LXXVI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e date was nien hundreth sexti &amp; sextene,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was alle forwondred, for his dede com tene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>UNTO Kyngeston &thorn;e first wouke of May<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce ea qu&aelig; Sanc|tus Dun|stanus pro|misit Re|gi Eilredo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Com S. Dunstan, opon a Sonenday,</L>
<L>&amp; of alle &thorn;e lond erle &amp; baroun,</L>
<L>To Eilred, Edgar sonne, bitauht him &thorn;e coroun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eilredus coronatus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>S. Dunstane hette him wele, in sorow his life to lede,</L>
<L>In alle his life ilk dele, of suerd he mot him drede.</L>
<L>S. Dunstan tille him spak wrothfulle wordes of eye,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ei of his mouth brak, listen, I salle &yogh;ow seye.</L>
<L>"Eilred," said Dunstan, "&thorn;i bro&thorn;er Edward was slayn</L>
<L>"&thorn;orgh &thorn;i moder Estrid, &thorn;er of scho was fulle fayn.</L>
<L>"For slauhter of &thorn;i bro&thorn;er has &thorn;ou &thorn;e coroune,</L>
<L>"Wele weld it salle &thorn;ou neuer, &thorn;ou has it &thorn;orh tresoune.</L>
<L>"&thorn;of alle Edgar &thorn;e gate, Estrild &thorn;i moder ware,</L>
<L>"To &thorn;e reame has &thorn;ou no right, bot &thorn;orgh slauhter care.</L>
<L>"For &thorn;e luf of &thorn;e &thorn;i bro&thorn;er did scho slo,</L>
<L>"&thorn;erfor &thorn;ou &amp; &thorn;ine salle weld it with wo.</L>
<L>"&amp; sone after &thorn;i daies &thorn;e reame salle men se</L>
<L>"Gouerned &thorn;orgh aliens kynde, &amp; euermore fro &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>&para; Whan Dunstan had thus said, bifor alle &thorn;at were &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>&amp; taken had his leue of barons lesse &amp; more,</L>
<L>Eilred &thorn;e &yogh;onge kyng toward London &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>A rede cloude in &thorn;e skie about Ingland gan sprede,</L>
<L>So mykelle blode it rayned, &thorn;e erth wex alle rede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk was affaied, &amp; alle heuy als lede.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e to&thorn;er &yogh;ere next of his coronment,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce pri|mum tor|mentum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Danes vp aryued, Souhamptone &thorn;ei brent,</L>
<L>&amp; robbed Cornwaile, &thorn;e folk were alle anoyed,</L>
<L>&thorn;at with Norwais Kerlion was destroied.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei com to London, &amp; brent &thorn;e cite.</L>
<L>Eilred &amp; &thorn;e barons, &thorn;at were of his meyne,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e erle of Herford held contek &amp; fight,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er heritage defend &thorn;ei ne myght.</L>
<L>Als alle &thorn;is sorow &amp; wo was in &thorn;e gynnyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eccesecun|dum tor|mentum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Died S. Dunstan, men herd &thorn;e angels syng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>JUSTYN &amp; Godemunde, of Danmark dukes riche,</L>
<L>Aryued in Southfolk &amp; brent Ipsewiche,</L>
<L>Men &amp; women slouh, &amp; robbed &thorn;orgh &thorn;e lond,</L>
<L>Tille &thorn;ei com to Mideweie, cuntre non &thorn;ei fond.</L>
<L>With &thorn;e erle of Kent &thorn;ei countred at Medeweie,</L>
<L>&thorn;e maistrie of him &thorn;ei wan, &thorn;ei did his folk alle deie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lerid &amp; &thorn;e lewid, &thorn;at wonned in &thorn;e South,</L>
<L>Sauh werre on ilk a side, &thorn;ei wer in &thorn;e woulfe's mouth.</L>
<L>Ten pounde of gold bi &yogh;ere for &thorn;e pes &thorn;ei gaf</L>
<L>To Justy &amp; Gudmund, &thorn;ei tok alle riffe &amp; raf.</L>
<L>To schip &thorn;ei turned &amp; went, &amp; charged &thorn;am fulle wele,</L>
<L>Aryued in Danmark with robberie ilk a dele.
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN to Wales &thorn;at coste went Eilred pitously,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Tercium tormentum.</NOTE></L>
<L>For to gadre him oste, if he mot haf maistrie.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at ilk tyme, as he to Wales went,</L>
<L>Tuo outlandes kynges on &thorn;is lond hauens hent.</L>
<L>Anlaf of Norway, of Danmark kyng Suane,</L>
<L>Aryued in &thorn;is lond, to many wer &thorn;ei bane.</L>
<L>&thorn;er ostes bo&thorn;e at ons vnto London nam,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei toun was warned wele, &amp; wist &thorn;at &thorn;ei cam.</L>
<L>Folk inouh redy was gadred, to &thorn;e cite</L>
<L>&thorn;ei went egrely, &amp; did &thorn;o kynges fle.</L>
<L>Fro London &thorn;ei were dryuen, &amp; com to Southampton.</L>
<L>Man &amp; beste &thorn;ei slouh, destroied &thorn;e cuntre doun.</L>
<L>Eilred myght nouht to stand &thorn;am ageyn,</L>
<L>For pes he &thorn;am bisouht, to gyf &thorn;am a certeyn.</L>
<L>&para; Fyue &thorn;ousand pound of siluer &thorn;e Danes kyng toke.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Summa.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Quartum tormentum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e went to &thorn;er schippes, &amp; to Danmark schoke.</L>
<L>&amp; many of &thorn;o Danes priuely were left,</L>
<L>&amp; busked Westward, forto robbe eft.</L>
<L>Wilton had &thorn;ei taken, Southampton also,</L>
<L>Cornwaile &amp; Wales bouwed &thorn;am vnto.</L>
<L>&thorn;e cuntre of Dorseth, lond &amp; tenement,</L>
<L>Alle had &thorn;ei wasted, fro Seuerne vnto Kent.</L>
<L>Eilred on a stound &thorn;e told of &thorn;at wo,</L>
<L>Four &amp; tuenti &thorn;ousand ponde he gaf away to go,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Summa.</NOTE></L>
<L>To haf pes in his lyue, &thorn;e lond no more schende.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Danes tok &thorn;e siluer, to Danmark gan wende.
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOUR &amp; tuenti wynter lasted &thorn;is sorow,</L>
<L>If he had pes at euen, he had non at morow.</L>
<L>For so hette S. Dunstan, he suld alle his lyue</L>
<L>With werre his lond welde, &amp; with his suerd stryue.</L>
<L>Now has Eilred nede of help &amp; socoure,</L>
<L>For boldenes he wild him bynd to som berde in boure.</L>
<L>Fulle so frendes he had, &amp; fele foos inowe,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e duke of Normundie he went for to wouwe.</L>
<L>He wedded &thorn;e duke's douhter, faire Emme &thorn;e blaunche,</L>
<L>&thorn;re bouwes of &thorn;am spronge, &thorn;e ton es holy braunche.</L>
<L>Edmunde Irenside was eldest of &thorn;o &thorn;re,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De filiis Eilredi re|gis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e to high Edward, &thorn;e &thorn;rid Alfrid hight he.</L>
<L>&para; <NOTE PLACE="foot">Id est, <I>through aid of.</I></NOTE>&thorn;orgh of Sir Richard, duke of Normundie,</L>
<L>Eilred &yogh;ede &thorn;orgh his lond, priuely to spie</L>
<L>Euerilkon &thorn;e Danes, &amp; smertly bounde</L>
<L>Or smyte of &thorn;er hedes, ay as men &thorn;am founde.</L>
<L>&thorn;us had Eilred &thorn;e lond at his wille,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e duke died sone, &amp; &thorn;at felle him fulle.</L>
<L>&thorn;an was Eilred socoure sone away went.</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;ing com to Danmark, &thorn;at he &thorn;e Danes schent.</L>
<L>Suane &thorn;e Danes kyng &thorn;erwith had enuy.</L>
<L>To aryue on Hingland he dight his nauy.</L>
<L>Whan he was aryued, he sent fulle baldely</L>
<L>Messengers to Eilred, als tille his cnmy.</L>
<L>&thorn;is was his message, his Danes wild he venge</L>
<L>Ageyn him in bataile, to renne &amp; to renge.</L>
<L>Eilred our kyng his help had he lorn</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e duke of Normundie, &thorn;at dede was beforn.
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>Suane, &thorn;e Danes kyng, was of so grete strength,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he destroied &thorn;is lond in brede &amp; in length.</L>
<L>Fyue wynter holy lasted &thorn;at werre,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer Eilred our kyng durst negh him nerre.</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er bi Nor&thorn; no bi South com him neuer help.</L>
<L>Wo was alle his comforth, of sorow mot he &yogh;elp.</L>
<L>&thorn;ritty &thorn;ousand pounde vnto Suane he sent,</L>
<L>Pes to haf his lyue, &amp; &thorn;ei to Danmark went.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is kyng Suane went tille his cuntre,</L>
<L>Eilred sent for Edrik to be his owen priue.</L>
<L>So fals a traytour in erth was non as he,</L>
<L>Of Lincolne he gaf him &thorn;at cuntre schire.</L>
<L>&thorn;e duke said vnto &thorn;e kyng, "Sir, I salle &yogh;ow say,</L>
<L>"For to saue &yogh;our lond wele, a fulle siker way.</L>
<L>"Do mak &thorn;re hundreth schippes opon &thorn;e sees koste,</L>
<L>"To kepe &thorn;am of Norweie &amp; &thorn;e Danes oste.</L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;e folk &thorn;erin be trewe vnto &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"Doute &thorn;e of non enmys, &thorn;at comes vp on &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e sent to seke many a schip wright</L>
<L>To &thorn;e toun of Sandwiche, &thorn;e nauie forto dight.</L>
<L>Whan Edrik it wist, &thorn;at &thorn;e schippes wer redy.</L>
<L>He sent to Norweie his lettres priuely,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e kyng Anlaf, tille Inglond to com.</L>
<L>Anlaf &amp; Sir Thurkille aryued vp in &thorn;ei nom.</L>
<L>Anlaf &amp; Thurkille aryued vp in Kent,</L>
<L>Alle about &thorn;ei robbed, &amp; tok &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot hent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk of &thorn;e cuntre to &thorn;is conseile &thorn;ei ches,</L>
<L>To gyf &thorn;am four hundreth pounde, forto lyue in pes.
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>&thorn;e Danes tok &thorn;at siluer, &amp; turned eft ageyn,</L>
<L>&amp; voided &thorn;e cuntre, &thorn;e folk was fulle feyn.</L>
<L>&para; Bot in &thorn;e &yogh;ere after, obowen Grimsby</L>
<L>Eft &thorn;ei gan aryue &thorn;orgh sonde priuely,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh fals Edrike, &thorn;at &thorn;am &thorn;ider hasted.</L>
<L>Lincolne &amp; Lyndeseie &thorn;ei stroied &amp; wasted.</L>
<L>Fals Edrike went, pes with &thorn;am to make.</L>
<L>Fourti &thorn;ousand pounde he did &thorn;am take,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non in alle &thorn;e cuntre more suld be piled.</L>
<L>Bot euer was Eilred fouly begiled.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e kyng wende, haf pes in his lyue,</L>
<L>Suane of Danmark at Sandwyche gan aryue,</L>
<L>&amp; brouht hider with him his sonne, &thorn;at hight Knoute.</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk vntille Humber to Suane gan &thorn;ei loute.</L>
<L>Alle was &thorn;orgh Edrik, &thorn;at mykelle was to blame.</L>
<L>He was &thorn;e kynge's conseiloure, &amp; did him mykelle schame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ANE erle in &thorn;e North, Uctred men kalde,</L>
<L>He com vnto Gaynesburgh, of Suane forto halde,</L>
<L>Forto lyue in pes, &amp; werre forto fle,</L>
<L>He com vnto Suane, &amp; mad him feaute.</L>
<L>Of the North Suane had a partie, &thorn;e South he desired,</L>
<L>Ostes tille him his sonne fast &thorn;ei atired.</L>
<L>Knoute went to &thorn;e North, Suane in to &thorn;e South,</L>
<L>&thorn;an was Eilred in &thorn;e wolfe's mouth.</L>
<L>Suane toward Oxenford went fulle smertly,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;at ilk toun did he krie a krie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;at him serued, &amp; of his meyne ware,</L>
<L>Man, woman &amp; childe, suld &thorn;ei alle forfare.
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>Kastels suld &thorn;ei bete doun, kirkes suld &thorn;ei brenne,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e citez &amp; tounes, &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot se or ken.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e toun of Wynehestre feaute had he at wille,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he went to London, &thorn;at hated he fulle ille.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bode com to &thorn;e kyng, &thorn;at soiorned &thorn;er in,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng Suane &thorn;e toun wild he wyn.</L>
<L>A Danes erle, <NOTE PLACE="foot">Vulgo vocant <I>Turkillum.</I></NOTE>with &thorn;e Kurkille he hight,</L>
<L>He halp our kyng defend &thorn;e toun at his myght.</L>
<L>Kyng Suane gaf assaut, &thorn;e walles to assaile,</L>
<L>Mykelle folk he les, &amp; tynt his trauaile.</L>
<L>Four &amp; tuenti &thorn;ousand in Temse alle at ones</L>
<L>Wer dronkled of Danes, &thorn;e Deuelle haf &thorn;er bones.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SUANE turned fro London, alle &thorn;orgh felonie,</L>
<L>&amp; went to Wallyngford, to mak his maistrie.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he &yogh;ede to Bathe, &amp; sette &thorn;e toun on fire.</L>
<L>Achelmare tille him felle, an Erle of Deuenschire.</L>
<L>Achelmare with feaute to Suane he him bonde,</L>
<L>Fro Wellis vnto London alle felle to his honde.</L>
<L>Suane toward Denmark sped him fulle fast,</L>
<L>&amp; ostage of London he had at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>Ilk cried on o&thorn;er, now is Suane kyng</L>
<L>Ouer alle Inglond, &amp; Eilred has no &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&para; Eilred is so reymed of his tresorie,</L>
<L>His wife &amp; his childre he sent to Normundie.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eilredus trausfreta|vit versus Norman|niam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Londone he hight Sir Alphanie</L>
<L>Led Edward &amp; Alfride, &amp; Emme &thorn;at was ladie.
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e wynter after Eilred went ouer &thorn;e se</L>
<L>Unto<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> Nomundie, with his wife to be.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e duke herd say, &thorn;at Eilred &thorn;ider cam,</L>
<L>With mykelle nobley ageyn Eilred he nam.</L>
<L>Rcsceyued him curtasly, &amp; said, "lefe &amp; dere,</L>
<L>"My lond is at &thorn;i wille, tille &thorn;e socoure is here."</L>
<L>&thorn;e date a &thorn;ousand was, &amp; mo bi fourty &yogh;ere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno Domini. Mo. XL<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at Eilred &amp; his childre soiorned with duke Richere.</L>
<L>&para; Now comes Suane eft ageyn with Criste's malison,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lond leid to taliage so mykclle on ilk a toun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at noi&thorn;er erle no baron of alle &thorn;er heritage</L>
<L>Myght not lyue &thorn;er on, to gif &thorn;er taliage.</L>
<L>Treuage als he asked of S. Edmunde &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;e corsaynt &amp; &thorn;e kirke he thrette for to brennyng,</L>
<L>&amp; bot he had his askyng, &thorn;e lond he suld destroye.</L>
<L>To Gaynesburgh he kald &thorn;e barons forto noye.</L>
<L>He said befor &thorn;am alle, of S. Edmunde's lond</L>
<L>He wild haf treuage, or brenne alle &thorn;at he fond.</L>
<L>&para; Alle was wele, tille euen after &thorn;e soupere</L>
<L>He &yogh;ede about, &amp; plaied with &thorn;o &thorn;at were him nere.</L>
<L>He sauh out of &thorn;e firmament an armed knyght com doun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was S. Edmunde, cruelle als a leon,</L>
<L>Suerd girded &amp; lance in hand, &thorn;an gan Suane to crie,</L>
<L>Non sauh bot he one, he said, "now salle I die,</L>
<L>"Help knyghtes, if &yogh;e may, I may no ferrer go.</L>
<L>"I se Edmunde with me wro&thorn;e, I wote he wille me slo.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at word he felle doun dede as any stone,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Suane.</NOTE></L>
<L>Life &amp; saule to Helle, &amp; flesh, blode &amp; bone.
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="45"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Suane dede, &amp; wonnes with Sathanas,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Danes ches Knoute to kyng of Danmark &thorn;at he was,</L>
<L>&amp; Inglond he seised for his fader conquest,</L>
<L>Grete taliage laid he &thorn;eron bi Esten &amp; bi West.</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk wild not suffre to be treuwageres,</L>
<L>Bot sent after Eilred bi certeyn messengeres,</L>
<L>&amp; praied him to com home, &thorn;e croune &yogh;eme &amp; take,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lordschip of Knoute kyng wild &thorn;ei alle forsake.</L>
<L>&para; Eilred sent tille Inglond Sir Edward his sonne</L>
<L>With his letter sealed, &amp; &thorn;anke wild he &thorn;am conne,</L>
<L>&amp; bli&thorn;ely tille Inglond wild he com agayn,</L>
<L>If he myght on &thorn;am troste, &thorn;at &thorn;ei were certayn.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e comons of &thorn;e lond with letter &thorn;am bond,</L>
<L>&amp; ilkon sette his seale &thorn;erto with his own hond,</L>
<L>&thorn;at if he wild com ageyn, &thorn;e lond forto were,</L>
<L>Neuer more to Danes kyng fai&thorn;e suld &thorn;ei bere.</L>
<L>Whan he wist &thorn;er wille, he hied hider suythe,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei resceyued him fulle faire, &amp; were of him blythe.</L>
<L>With him alle, &thorn;ei said, &thorn;ei wild lyue &amp; deie</L>
<L>Alle holy &thorn;e lond, bot &thorn;ei of Lyndseie</L>
<L>Eilred &thorn;er lege lord him &thorn;ei alle forsoke,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eilredus fugavit Knoutum regem, &amp; iterum re|gnum cepit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er hede kyng Knout &thorn;ei &thorn;an toke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW rises Eilred, &amp; gadres oste stark,</L>
<L>&amp; chaces kyng Knoute in tille Danmark.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e Danes were out, &thorn;at timbred him his tene,</L>
<L>Lyndeseie he destroied quite alle bidene.</L>
<L>It was &thorn;am self to wite, &thorn;ei lete of him so lite.</L>
<L>e wrong was alle &thorn;airs, &thorn;e kyng did bot right.
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e kyng wende, &thorn;at pes suld for&thorn;e go,</L>
<L>&thorn;e fals Erle Edrik bigan eft a wo.</L>
<L>Tuo old gentille men Edrik did forfare,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ton hight Sigiferd, &thorn;e to&thorn;er Sir Morgare,</L>
<L>For couetise of &thorn;er londes, &amp; seignorie &thorn;at &thorn;ei helde,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;ei were a partie smyten in to elde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e fals Edrik did lede Sigiferde's wife</L>
<L>Unto Malmcestre, hir name was Aldife.</L>
<L>Edmunde Irenside, Eilrede's sonne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer in &thorn;is lond stille wild he wonne,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is ilk treson he herd oft speke,</L>
<L>&amp; of fals Edrik fayn wild he him wreke.</L>
<L>He toke Sigiferde's wife, withouten his fader leue,</L>
<L>&amp; wedded hir at &thorn;e kirke, Edrik forto greue.</L>
<L>Whan he had hir wedded, he went also quik,</L>
<L>&amp; oute of alle &thorn;o londes he kast &thorn;e erle Edrik,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at tenement, &thorn;at bo&thorn;e &thorn;e brethres ware,</L>
<L>&thorn;at longed to Sigiferd, &amp; to Sir Morkare.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Edmun|do Irenside.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Eilred our kyng fallen in sekenes,</L>
<L>He lies at Euesham, his abbay it es.</L>
<L>His eldest sonne Edmunde knyghtes gode he sekes,</L>
<L>Fro Douere vnto Wales &thorn;e folk tille him mekes.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e erle Edrik he gadred mykelle pride,</L>
<L>Knyghtes &amp; serganz on Lyndesay side.</L>
<L>Forto slo Edmunde &thorn;orgh tricherie,</L>
<L>Bot Edmunde es wele warned of his felonie.</L>
<L>Edmunde bi messengers &thorn;e erle he diffies,</L>
<L>Edrik in tille Danmark to Knoute sent spies,
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>For to com tille Inglond sone suld he assay,</L>
<L>Aryued &thorn;at he ware of &yogh;ole &thorn;e tuelft day.</L>
<L>Knoute bi his sonde Edrik ageyn grette,</L>
<L>To aryue he suld fonde &thorn;e day &thorn;at he him sette.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>COMEN is Knoute to cuntre, to ride he him hastis,</L>
<L>Man &amp; woman to slo, he robbes &amp; wastis.</L>
<L>A gode erle of Warwik was don to &thorn;e suerd,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;at fals Edrik, als he did Sigiferd.</L>
<L>Eilred was led to London, &amp; seke gan &thorn;er lie.</L>
<L>Edmunde praied him of help priuely bi spie.</L>
<L>Londreies inow com tille Edmunde,</L>
<L>&amp; wastid alle &amp; brent Leicestre alle doun.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e fals Edrik did his quaintise,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Edmund with Knoute mette in non wyse.</L>
<L>&para; Knoute &amp; Edrik &thorn;ei seised &thorn;orgh tresone<NOTE PLACE="marg">De tradi|tione Edrik.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bokyngham &amp; Bedford, &thorn;e toun of Huntyngtone,</L>
<L>Lincolne &amp; Notyngham, &thorn;e toure of Northampton.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en went to Donkastre &amp; vntille Aluerton,</L>
<L>&amp; alle Northumberland it was at &thorn;er wille.</L>
<L>Edmunde &amp; &thorn;e erle Uctred &thorn;at tyme held &thorn;am stille.</L>
<L>To London vnto Eilred hasted &thorn;ei &thorn;er weie,</L>
<L>For bodword men brouh, &thorn;e kyng suld sone deie.</L>
<L>Whan Edrik wist Edmond to London was gone,</L>
<L>His londes &amp; his rentes he seised eft ilkone.</L>
<L>Eilred at London endid his life,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mortuus est Eilred's rex anno Domini millessime. XVI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Auht &amp; &thorn;ritty wynter he regned with strife.</L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme he died in peyn &amp; in wo,</L>
<L>&thorn;e date was a &thorn;ousand &amp; sextene mo.
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="48"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Eilred biried, &thorn;at mykelle wo bade.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Knoutus rex Daci&aelig; factus est rex An|gli&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e clergie &amp; &thorn;e baronage samned at a reade,</L>
<L>&amp; com to Southampton, &amp; corouned Sir Knoute.</L>
<L>&thorn;e burgeis of London were wro&thorn;e &amp; stoute,</L>
<L>&amp; said &thorn;ei suld fond to felle Knoute's pride.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei corouned for enuy Edmunde Irenside.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Edmundus Irenside co|ronatus a|pud Lon|done.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;erof were &thorn;ei paied alle &thorn;e North cuntre,</L>
<L>&thorn;e com alle to London to mak him feaute.</L>
<L>Knoute gadred him an oste, on Edmunde he ran,</L>
<L>&amp; Edmunde on him ageyn, as a douhty man,</L>
<L>&amp; trauailed sore Knoute, neuer he blanne,</L>
<L>Whan wend haf left, Edmunde biganne.</L>
<L>Tuo &yogh;ere &thorn;ei werred with many trauailes,</L>
<L>In &thorn;o tuo &yogh;eres were sex grete batailes.</L>
<L>In the sex batailes was many a man slayn.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last &thorn;ei acorded, &thorn;e lond was fulle fayn.</L>
<L>Edmunde of &thorn;e lond had &thorn;e haluendele,</L>
<L>He regned bot tuo &yogh;ere, no more his tyme felle.</L>
<L>He lies at Glastenbire toumbed, as I wene,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mortuus est Edmundus Irenside Anno. M<SUP>o</SUP>. XVIII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e date of Criste a &thorn;ousand &amp; mo bi auhtene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN God had don his wille of Edmunde Irenside,</L>
<L>Knoute vnto London com with grete pride.</L>
<L>He asked &thorn;e barons in &thorn;at parlement,</L>
<L>If he schewed a &thorn;ing, o&thorn;erwaies he ment:</L>
<L>If Edmunde &thorn;e kyng, whan to acorde went,</L>
<L>If he saued to his heyers oi&thorn;er lond or tenement.</L>
<L>Ilkon said, &thorn;at Edmunde &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>Spak no word &thorn;er of, at &thorn;er sauhtillyng.
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="49"></L>
<L>Wharfor &thorn;e barons granted him ilkone,</L>
<L>Knoute to be corouned, &amp; haf it alone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN Knoute had resceyued bo&thorn;e &thorn;e seignories,</L>
<L>He parted &thorn;e lond in foure parties.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Knoutus regnavit per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e West cuntre him seluen he held,</L>
<L>Fals Edrik gaf he Lyndeseie of Lyncolne &thorn;e scheld.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e erle Thurkille he gaf Estangle,</L>
<L>Northfolk &amp; Southfolk, ficacie men Iangle.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e erle Uctred Northumberland he toke,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pes to mayntene &thorn;e suore alle on &thorn;e boke.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an tok kyng Knoute alle his homages,</L>
<L>&thorn;at cleymed to hold of him &thorn;er heritages.</L>
<L>Edmunde had a sonne, &amp; childre no mo.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh Edrike's conseile Knoute did him slo,</L>
<L>&amp; tok quene Emme &amp; wedded hir to wife,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh Edrike's conseile, scho scorted his life.</L>
<L>&para; Knoute on a day bi his wife satte,</L>
<L>Of Edrike's treson scho warned him of &thorn;at.</L>
<L>"Listen me, lord Knoute, if it be &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>"How he betraied my lord, &amp; my sonne fulle ille.</L>
<L>"Whilom Eilred my lord he him bitraist to &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>"&amp; my sonne Edmunde &thorn;orgh treson he slouh,</L>
<L>"&amp; if he regne long he salle haf &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>"He was neuer with no man, &thorn;at he ne did him schame.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng one on &thorn;e morn went to London,</L>
<L>His &yogh;ole forto hold was his encheson.</L>
<L>Knoute &thorn;ouht on &thorn;at tale, &thorn;at his wife him told,</L>
<L>&amp; si&thorn;en ateyned Edrik &thorn;orgh treson of old.
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="50"></L>
<L>&thorn;e fer &thorn;e day of &thorn;e fest, no lenger it was,</L>
<L>Edrik was hanged on &thorn;e toure, for his trispas.</L>
<L>&thorn;an said &thorn;e quene, "&thorn;at Edrik &thorn;e Giloure</L>
<L>"Had not fully dome, &thorn;at felle to traytoure.</L>
<L>"Traytours with runties suld men first drawe,</L>
<L>"&yogh;a dame," said &thorn;e kyng, "bot he salle haf &thorn;e law,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at his body salle hang in colde &amp; in hote,</L>
<L>"Schame tille alle his kynd, &thorn;at it sees &amp; wote.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>KNOUTE of his body gate sonnes &thorn;re,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Knoutus divisit re|gnum filiis suis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tuo bi tuo wifes, &thorn;e &thorn;rid in jolifte.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e first had he Suane, he was eldest bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Bi Emme, &thorn;e second wife, Hardeknoute ano&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Harald he had geten on his playeng,</L>
<L>Knoute lufed him best, he was his derlyng.</L>
<L>Olaf in Norweie regned fulle stoute,</L>
<L>&amp; bare him ouer strange to &thorn;e kyng Knoute.</L>
<L>Knoute com with his kythe, &thorn;at kant was &amp; kene,</L>
<L>&amp; chaced him out of Norweie quyte &amp; clene.</L>
<L>&thorn;an was he kyng of Danmark, Inglond &amp; Norweie,</L>
<L>Danmark was his heritage, he conquered &thorn;e to&thorn;er tueie.</L>
<L>Malcolme, &thorn;e Scottis kyng, &thorn;at tyme died he,</L>
<L>Mathithade his bro&thorn;er resceyued &thorn;e regante.</L>
<L>Knoute as for his chefe he tok his homage,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kyngdom of Inglond he had &thorn;e heritage.</L>
<L>Knoute vnderstode wele, he mot not long lyue,</L>
<L>His sonnes in his lyue his londes wild he gyue.</L>
<L>Suane gaf he Norweie, (Olaf he chaced oute)</L>
<L>Danmark his heritage he gaf tille Hardeknoute.
<PB REF="00000279.tif" N="51"></L>
<L>He assigned Harald to Inglond, to had it in fee.</L>
<L>&thorn;us he gaf his londis tille his sonnes &thorn;re.</L>
<L>Seuentene &yogh;ere was he kyng &thorn;orgh conquest &amp; desceit,</L>
<L>At Westmynstere he ligges in a toumbe purtreit.</L>
<L>A thousand was &thorn;e date &amp; sex &amp; &thorn;ritty,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno. M<SUP>o</SUP>. XXXVI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan Knoute kyng died, so sais &thorn;e story.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HARALD was curteys &amp; strong, of body auenant,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Haraldus rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>To be &thorn;er kyng &amp; hede &thorn;e lond was wele ogrant.</L>
<L>Hardknoute of Danmark payd not withalle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he suld bere &thorn;e coroune, for he was born thralle,</L>
<L>He gadred of Danes folk right inouh,</L>
<L>&amp; did him toward &thorn;e se, &amp; tille &thorn;is lond drouh.</L>
<L>Whan he was aryued, he sent to Harald,</L>
<L>&amp; said, &thorn;at a bastard no kyngdom suld hald,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;at he it wan with suerd or with lance</L>
<L>Of tirant or of Sarazin, &thorn;orgh douhtynes of chance.</L>
<L>&amp; if he wille &thorn;e lond &yogh;eld, &amp; to &thorn;e pes chese,</L>
<L>For he is my bro&thorn;er, he salle not alle lese;</L>
<L>&amp; if he wille &thorn;orgh bataile, &thorn;er to wille I stand,</L>
<L>&amp; bataile bituene vs wille not be semand.</L>
<L>Harald was fulle, a lone day he toke,</L>
<L>To here what &thorn;e barons &thorn;am bo&thorn;e wild loke.</L>
<L>&para; Vnder Southamptone was &thorn;er assemble,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Parliamen|tum suum est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Harald &amp; Hardknoute, what suld bituex &thorn;am be.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei were bre&thorn;er, &thorn;e luf was more sene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons portiond &thorn;e lond euen &thorn;am bituene,</L>
<L>Harald tille his parte suld haf alle &thorn;e Northende,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e Southside tille Harknout suld wende.
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="52"></L>
<L>To &thorn;at ilk lokyng bo&thorn;e &thorn;ei consent,</L>
<L>In luf &thorn;ei departed, Hardknout home went.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;at tyme, &thorn;at Harald &amp; Hardknout held partie,</L>
<L>Died &thorn;e duke Roberd, &thorn;at regned in Normundie.</L>
<L>William was his heire, resceyued &thorn;e heritage,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we kalle &thorn;e bastard, &thorn;at sette vs in seruage.</L>
<L>Richard was Roberd fader, &thorn;e duke &thorn;at died beforn,</L>
<L>Emme &thorn;e quene his douhter, of &thorn;e whilk was born</L>
<L>Alfred &amp; Edward, Hardknoute &thorn;e &thorn;rid,</L>
<L>&thorn;e tuo first of Eilred, of Knoute Hardknoute tid.</L>
<L>Alfred &amp; Edward, &thorn;am of Eilred kam,</L>
<L>Wer with duke Roberd, now ere &thorn;ei with William.</L>
<L>&thorn;o childre tok to rede, to com vnto &thorn;is lond,</L>
<L>To speke with &thorn;er moder, at Wynchester &thorn;ei hir fond.</L>
<L>Alfrede was eldest, non mot his wille withhald,</L>
<L>To London he wild alle gate, to speke with kyng Harald.</L>
<L>Godwyn, an erle of Kent, met with Alfred,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De obceca|cione Al|fredi fratris Edwardi, &amp; morte ejus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him &amp; alle his feres vntille prison &thorn;am led.</L>
<L>Of som smote of &thorn;er hedes, of som put out &thorn;er i&yogh;ene,</L>
<L>Sex hundreth at Gildford did Godwyn slo &amp; pyne.</L>
<L>Alfred he was led to &thorn;e abbay of Elyng,</L>
<L>Bifor Godwyn himseluen &thorn;ei did his i&yogh;ene out &thorn;ring.</L>
<L>He lyued bot &thorn;re daies, &amp; &yogh;ald to God &thorn;e gaste,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bode com to his moder, scho did Edward in haste</L>
<L>Wende to Normundie, for drede of Alfred pyne,</L>
<L>To William, hir bro&thorn;er sonne, was Edwarde's kosyne.</L>
<L>Edward told William of Alfred alle &thorn;e case,</L>
<L>&amp; praied him of help, for he dred harder pase,
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>&amp; if he myght conquere Inglond, &thorn;at was his speyre,</L>
<L>Edward sikerd him wele, to mak William his heyre,</L>
<L>&amp; bond him with skrite, his seale hyngand &thorn;erbi,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De ingrati|tudine &amp; malicia Haraldi.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; William hette him wele, to help him sikerly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW duelles Harald &thorn;e kyng among his baronage,</L>
<L>Tille Emme, Hardknoute's moder, he did a grete outrage,</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er a foule despite, him self vileyn skandre.</L>
<L>He chaced hir out of &thorn;e lond, &amp; scho went vnto Flandres.</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e erle Baldwyn, for scho was of his kynde.</L>
<L>He resceyued hir fulle faire inouh, he did hir fynde</L>
<L>To brige in to Danmark, &thorn;er Hardknout was kyng.</L>
<L>Of Inglond &amp; of Flandres brouht men him ti&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>How kyng Harald chaced his moder of lond.</L>
<L>What skille he had &amp; whi Herdknout &yogh;erned to fond.</L>
<L>Now<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> Hardwnout toward Flandres dightes him day bi day.</L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme at Westmynstir Harald sore seke lay,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mortuus est Haraldus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Died &amp; was &thorn;er laid, als my boke me told.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Harde|knoutus ob|tinuit re|gnum anno <NOTE PLACE="foot">L. M<SUP>o</SUP>. XL<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE>M<SUP>o</SUP> L. VI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fyue &yogh;ere was he kyng, &amp; sex &amp; fifty old.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date of Criste &thorn;an was a &thorn;ousand &amp; fourti,</L>
<L>Harald for his trespas &yogh;it felle a vilany.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is kyng Harald dede, &thorn;at whilom was so stoute,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons sent Flandres vnto Hardeknoute,</L>
<L>&amp; praied him com to lond, &thorn;e coroune if he wild take,</L>
<L>If he wild vnderstond, non o&thorn;er kyng wild &thorn;ei make.
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="54"></L>
<L>Whan he wist &thorn;er wille, he hasted him &thorn;ider sui&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei gaf him &thorn;e coroune, &amp; were of him fulle bli&thorn;e.</L>
<L>He studied, how he myght venge his moder despite,</L>
<L>He did Harald body do drawe vp also tite,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;orgh &thorn;e podels it drouh, &thorn;at foule were &amp; deppest,</L>
<L>&amp; si&thorn;en in to Temse his body did he kest.</L>
<L>&thorn;at fischid in Temse on &thorn;e nyght, whan &thorn;ei &thorn;er nettes vp wond,</L>
<L>&thorn;e body of Harald in a nette &thorn;ei fond.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei durst it not forth schewe, for &thorn;e kyng wer &thorn;ei ferd.</L>
<L>Som frendes he had, &thorn;at biried it in kirke &yogh;erd.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HARDEKNOUT did charge &thorn;e lond in suilk treuwage,</L>
<L>&thorn;at noi&thorn;er erle no barone myght lyue for taliage.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at alle &thorn;e comonalte had him ageyn herte,</L>
<L>&thorn;at were to him so fre, for&thorn;ouht it sore &amp; smerte.</L>
<L>Hardknoute wex fulle wroth toward Godwyn of Kent</L>
<L>For his bro&thorn;er Alfred, &thorn;at he slouh &amp; schent,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e bisshop Alfrik, &thorn;at was his conseilere.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei dred &thorn;e kyng folle sore, for he was fulle austere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle had frendes, to acorde &thorn;ei gaf him &thorn;e weie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle was fulle quaynte, did mak a riche galeie</L>
<L>With fourscore armed knyghtes, in suilk apparaille dight,</L>
<L>&thorn;at so riche armes was neuer sene with sight.</L>
<L>&amp; ilk knyght bare on his arme, be redy acounte,</L>
<L>Also mykelle brent gold, as sextene vnce amounte.</L>
<L>Withouten alle &thorn;is a hundreth knyghtes he toke.</L>
<L>Befor &thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;e barons he suore on &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer Alfred his bro&thorn;er &thorn;orgh him was dede,</L>
<L>No blynfeld no slayn, bot &thorn;orgh Haralde's rede.
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei said he did inouh, &thorn;e erle alle vplift,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng forgaf his wra&thorn;e, resceyued his gift.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Narratio de vita Sancti Ed|wardi, de comiteGod|wino quali|ter strangu|latus fuit propter fal|sum jura|mentum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; In Saynt Edwarde's life it sais, he was forsuorn.</L>
<L>Bifor Edward himself he strangled &amp; was lorn.</L>
<L>&amp; I salle telle &thorn;at tale, or I ferrer go,</L>
<L>How falsnes brewes bale with him, and many mo.</L>
<L>In S. Edward tyme &thorn;e erle suld with him ete,</L>
<L>A seruitour &thorn;er was, &thorn;at serued at &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>He stombled at a chance, &amp; felle on his kne,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e to&thorn;er schank he ros, &amp; serued in his degre.</L>
<L>"A ha!" said &thorn;e erle, "had &thorn;at schank ne bien,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou had liggen &thorn;er stille, &thorn;e risen suld non haf sene.</L>
<L>"God wote, said &thorn;e king, so is it with me nouh,</L>
<L>"&amp; I had my bro&thorn;er Alfred, &thorn;at &thorn;ou slouh,</L>
<L>"&thorn;of I had stombled &thorn;orgh myn vnmayn,</L>
<L>"He suld haf bien my schank, &amp; reised me agayn.</L>
<L>"&thorn;an hopes &thorn;ou," said &thorn;e erle, "&thorn;at for me was he dede.</L>
<L>"I praye God if it wer so I strangle of &thorn;is brede.</L>
<L>&amp; putte a morselle in his mouth with &thorn;at ilk worde,</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;am alle he strangled at &thorn;e borde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng biheld him a stound, &amp; sauh no repentance,</L>
<L>He bad drawe away &thorn;at hound, God has taken vengeance.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN Harknout &amp; &thorn;e erle wer at an assent,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh alle his lond &thorn;e kyng his sonde sent,</L>
<L>Forto reise &thorn;e treuage, &thorn;at on &thorn;e lond was sette,</L>
<L>Pader &amp; Thurston to &thorn;at office were fette.</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk of Wircestre ageyn &thorn;e treuage spak,</L>
<L>Bituex &thorn;am &amp; &thorn;e messengers bro&thorn;efulle wordes brak.
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>Pader &amp; Thurston &thorn;er hedes &thorn;er &thorn;ei left.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Alii</I> Thurum <I>vocant. Vide Flor. Wig. pag.</I> 403. <I>ed.</I> 4to.</NOTE> Burd send o&thorn;er to ask treuage eft.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng sone herd say, his messengers were slayn,</L>
<L>Toward Wircestre he com with myght &amp; mayn,</L>
<L>&amp; comanded all &thorn;o, &thorn;at euer lufed him wele,</L>
<L>Alle Wirecestreschire spare it neuer a dele,</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er man no beste, no manere no no toun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e cite of Wircestre &thorn;ei brent euen doun.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ei wasted quitely, &amp; slouh &thorn;e folk fulle &yogh;erne,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;o &thorn;at fled with &thorn;er godes to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Civium vero multitudo in quandam modicam insulam, in medio Sabrin&aelig; fluminis sitam, qu&aelig; Beuerege nuncupatur, confugerant: <I>&amp;c. Flor. Wig.</I></NOTE> ilde of Seuerne,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at wer in &thorn;e ilde duelled &thorn;er for drede,</L>
<L>Untille &thorn;e kyng turned, &amp; his wrath ouer &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&para; Right als Hardeknout had left alle &thorn;at folie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Hic venit Edwardus ad curiam Hard|knouti.</NOTE></L>
<L>Com Edward, Eilred sonne, out of Normundie,</L>
<L>&amp; Hardeknoute's bro&thorn;er on his moder side,</L>
<L>Right heyre of &thorn;e lond, &thorn;orgh grace &thorn;at may betide.</L>
<L>Edward was welcom tille Hardeknoute &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>He bad his wille suld be, als his in alle &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Here now of Hardeknoute, how he endid his life.</L>
<L>Tille a duke of Danes he gaf his douhter to wife.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bridale was holden at &thorn;e maner of Lambithe.</L>
<L>After mete in &thorn;e haule &thorn;e kyng mad alle blithe.</L>
<L>In alle his joy makyng, among &thorn;am ilkone,</L>
<L>He felle dede doun colde as any stone.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei bare him to Wynchester, &amp; biried him &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>Tuo &yogh;ere &amp; a half he regned, &amp; no more.
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand was &thorn;e date, &amp; tuo &amp; fourty.</L>
<L>I trowe it was for vengeance, he died so sodenly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ALLE &thorn;e baronage at Pask afterward,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Coronacio Sancti Ed|wardi.</NOTE></L>
<L>Com to Wynchester to coroune kyng Edward,</L>
<L>Als he &thorn;at had gode right vnto &thorn;e regalte,</L>
<L>In Inglond was non so right heyre as he.</L>
<L>Whan he had regned fyue, &amp; wele was aboue,</L>
<L>Suane &thorn;e kyng of Danmark sent to him for loue,</L>
<L>&amp; praied him for his nauy to help him with summ,</L>
<L>Bataile was gyuen in &thorn;e se, ageyn &thorn;e kyng Magnum,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was kyng of Norweie, with wrong gan him trauaile.</L>
<L>Edward sent him fifty schippes, to help at his bataile.</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;e help &thorn;at he had, Magnus on him so ran,</L>
<L>&amp; chaced away Suane, &amp; Danmark on him wan.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is ilk Magnus lyued &thorn;er no longe.</L>
<L>Eft Suane, &thorn;e Danes kyng, &thorn;is lond did vnderfonge,</L>
<L>&amp; eft vntille Edward Suane sent ageyn,</L>
<L>&amp; praied him bituex &thorn;am &thorn;e pes wer certeyn.</L>
<L>Edward him granted, opon suilk a wise,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer &thorn;e Dangilde for ne non of hise,</L>
<L>Suld be chaleuged for man of Danes lond,</L>
<L>&amp; Suane, kyng of Danmark, to &thorn;at conant him bond.</L>
<L>&thorn;us was &thorn;e pes granted with skrite on bo&thorn;e sides,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e Danes gilde forgyuen, &thorn;at neuer eft bitides.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;is Edwarde's tyme a riche erle &thorn;an was,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De comite Godwino &amp; Haraldo filio ejus.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at hight Godwyn of Kent, I red him ore in pas.
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="58"></L>
<L>He had a sonne Harald, heyre of his tenement.</L>
<L>Engle his wife he drofe away, &amp; held in peyrment.</L>
<L>Egyne, &thorn;at was an abbes, out of hir hous had</L>
<L>Maugre hire wille in hordom his life with hir lad.</L>
<L>Ageyn the kyng Edward, &amp; of his to wynne,</L>
<L>Godwyn &thorn;e Erle to werre wild bigynne.</L>
<L>Harald &amp; Lofwyn, &thorn;ise were his sonnes tueye,</L>
<L>Douhty knyghtes &thorn;ei were, after salle we seye.</L>
<L>Godwyn sent for frendes, knyghtes he had inowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng was at Gloucestre, &amp; &thorn;iderward &thorn;ei drowe.</L>
<L>Whan Edward perceyued, his hcrte was in studie,</L>
<L>How &thorn;at werre bigan on him so sodanly.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &yogh;ared his folk, on haste alle &thorn;at he myght.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle in his askyng had no maner right.</L>
<L>Wherfor &thorn;e erle of Ba did Gowyn understand,</L>
<L>To leue alle his werre, &amp; take &thorn;e lawe of land.</L>
<L>"At London at &thorn;e benke schewe &thorn;er &thorn;in askyng,</L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;at lawe wille, &thorn;ou wynnes it of &thorn;e kyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE kyng com to London, with lawe to mote in benke,</L>
<L>Men sauh on &thorn;e kynge's side &thorn;er was no gile, no wrenke;</L>
<L>&amp; for he had &thorn;e treuth, on his side were &thorn;e mo,</L>
<L>&amp; Godwyn perceyued wele, on his side were bot fo.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor Godwyn &amp; his fro London went away,</L>
<L>He stode vntille no more, defaute he mad &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor was &thorn;e dome gyuen &thorn;orgh &thorn;e Justise,</L>
<L>To exile &thorn;e erle Godwyn, his sonnes &amp; alle hise.
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>Godwyn went to Flandres, vnto &thorn;e erle Baldwyn.</L>
<L>At Bristow in tille Ireland schipped Harald &amp; Lofwyn.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e erle was exiled, his sonnes tille Irland ouer,<NOTE PLACE="marg">WilleImus, dux Nor|manni&aelig;, ve|nit in An|gliam ad Sanctum Edwardum Regem.</NOTE></L>
<L>William &thorn;e Normant aryued vp at Douer,</L>
<L>In luf &amp; in pes to speke with Sir Edward.</L>
<L>He had bien in his courte, whan his happe was more hard.</L>
<L>He resceyued him with joy, &amp; with herte fulle glad.</L>
<L>To se &thorn;e lond about &thorn;e duke with him he lad.</L>
<L>Whan he had soiorned long, &amp; was in wille to go,</L>
<L>Gode giftes he him gaf, or &thorn;at he went him fro.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at alle of his were paied of &thorn;er parte.</L>
<L>With joy alle ageyn &thorn;ei went to Normundie.</L>
<L>&para; Thus Harald &amp; Lofwyn, &thorn;at out of lond were dryuen,</L>
<L>With grete oste of Ireland at Chestre vp aryuen.</L>
<L>Dorseth &amp; Somerseth &thorn;ei robbed &amp; did wo,</L>
<L>Of knyghtes &amp; serganz &thorn;ei slouh &thorn;ritty &amp; tuo.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei had so robbed, &thorn;at &thorn;am &thorn;ouht inouh,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei went ageyn to schip, &amp; saile vp drouh.</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e South side turned &thorn;ei &thorn;ar flete,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar fader &amp; &thorn;ei o chance togider gan mete.</L>
<L>Godwyn &amp; his sonnes at Sandwych hauen hent,</L>
<L>Lettres tille his frendes for help about sent,</L>
<L>Of socour &amp; conseile bisouht &thorn;am pitously,</L>
<L>Of many had he grante, to ask for him mercy.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e kyng wist, &thorn;at &thorn;ei had taken land,</L>
<L>For &thorn;o barons he sent &thorn;at were his wele willand.</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;e longe duellyng of barons in &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>Godwyn, &thorn;at non wist, aryued in Surray.
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="60"></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng also sui&thorn;e ta bataile mad him &yogh;are.</L>
<L>Godwyn he diffied, &amp; alle &thorn;at with him ware.</L>
<L>Grete wer &thorn;o parties, &thorn;at ferd in to &thorn;e felde.</L>
<L>Eldolf, bisshop of Bath, &thorn;e pes mayntend &amp; helde.</L>
<L>Eldolf, &thorn;e gode bisshop, com with his clergie,</L>
<L>&amp; said to kyng Edward, "Sire, we &thorn;e mercy cric</L>
<L>"For &thorn;e erle Godwyn, &thorn;at wille &yogh;eld him to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>"His sonnes er at &thorn;i wille, &amp; alle &thorn;at with &thorn;am be.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons said, "for &thorn;are sake, for &thorn;am &thorn;an praye we,</L>
<L>"&thorn;are trespas we vndertake opon alle our fee.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e erle com him self, mercy forto craue,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng, for his curteysie, granted &thorn;am pes to haue,</L>
<L>&amp; gaf him ageyn bo&thorn;e rent &amp; lond,</L>
<L>Harald &amp; Lofwyn to &thorn;e pes &thorn;am bond.</L>
<L>Bot Suane, &thorn;are bro&thorn;er, &thorn;at died in Lumbardie,</L>
<L>For he slouh his cosyn, he fled &thorn;orgh felonie.</L>
<L>He went to &thorn;e holy lond, to do &thorn;erfor penance,</L>
<L>&amp; died &thorn;er for colde in Lumbardie o chance.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE kyng wedded a wife, &thorn;at Godwyn douhter was.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Regina Edith.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scho soiorned at Romeneie, for hir fader trespas.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle bisouh &thorn;e kyng, to take hir home ageyn.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng granted &thorn;at &thorn;ing, to mak pes alle pleyn.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle vnto &thorn;e kyng bare him si&thorn;en so wele,</L>
<L>&amp; his sonnes bo&thorn;e tille him war trost als stele,</L>
<L>Sithen in alle his courte were non so wele him with,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei halp him at &thorn;are myght to maynten pes &amp; grith.
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="61"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON &thorn;e Wissonday at Burgh in Lyndeseie</L>
<L>Com bode to &thorn;e kyng, &amp; &thorn;us gan &thorn;ei seie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e duke Siward<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vide Johan. Forduni Sco|tichron. p.</I> 396.</NOTE> had taken in his balie</L>
<L>Machog, &thorn;e Scottes kyng, &thorn;at wild, &thorn;orgh traitourie,</L>
<L>Haf traised Edward &thorn;e kyng, &thorn;at in &thorn;e North was rife.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor Machog les &thorn;e reame &amp; his life.</L>
<L>He gaf it to Malcolme, &thorn;at was of Cumberland.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh gift of Edward he seised it in his hand.</L>
<L>Malcolme mad homage tille Edward our kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he &amp; alle his age of Ingland suld hold &thorn;at &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GRIFFYN, kyng of Wales, &thorn;at ilk self &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="marg">Griffynus de Wallia bellum mo|vit contra Edwardum Regem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was proued traitoure fals, &amp; &thorn;at bouht he fulle dere.</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e tuelft euen Griffyn his hede les,</L>
<L>To Gloucester was it brouht befor &thorn;e kyng at des.</L>
<L>Edward had a kosyn in preson at Hungarie,</L>
<L>Edmunde, his bro&thorn;er sonne, was &thorn;er &thorn;orgh tricherie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng sent to frendes for him alle aboute,</L>
<L>For praier at &thorn;e last &thorn;e childe was laten oute.</L>
<L>Home vnto Inglond &thorn;e childe tille Edward cam,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;at childe's luf forgeten was William.</L>
<L>&thorn;ouht he not of &thorn;e trouth, &thorn;at he to William plight,</L>
<L>For to mak him his heyre, if he &thorn;e lond haf myght.</L>
<L>Neuer&thorn;eles to William he &yogh;eld him wele his bone,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is no more to speke, &thorn;e childe died right sone.</L>
<L>Algar, an erle of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Others say, he was earl of Chester. See p.</I> 121. <I>of Mr. Thomas Ellis's Ed. of part of</I> Dr. Powell's History of Wales. <I>But it should be rather</I>, earl of Mercia. <I>See Dugdale's Baronage, Tom. I. p.</I> 10.</NOTE> Kent, &thorn;at tyme exiled was;</L>
<L>My boke sais with wrong, he did no trespas.
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>He went in to Wales to Griffyn, Griffyn sonne,</L>
<L>&thorn;ese tuo a werre als Walsch men er wonne.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Haraldus factus est dux turma|rum apud Walliam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Whan Edward hard say, he samned alle his oste.</L>
<L>Harald, Godwyn sonne, led &thorn;am bi &thorn;at coste.</L>
<L>At Herford in Wales &thorn;e ostes &thorn;er mette,</L>
<L>&amp; dight on bo&thorn;e parties in batailes to sette.</L>
<L>Harald &amp; his Inglis biheld &thorn;e erle Algare,</L>
<L>&thorn;am for&thorn;ouht fulle sore, &thorn;at he suld &thorn;ore misfare.</L>
<L>&thorn;is wald &thorn;e Inglis conseile, if &thorn;ei mot Algare saue,</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ei suld biseke, &thorn;e kynge's pes to haue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis com to &thorn;e kyng, &thorn;er he was in place,</L>
<L>&amp; specially Harald, he had &thorn;e kynge's grace.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e erle Algare had &thorn;e kyng mercie,</L>
<L>&amp; forgaf Sir Griffyn also for curteisie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN &thorn;at kyng Edward wend to lyue in pes,</L>
<L>Griffyn, kyng of Wales, eft he mad a res.</L>
<L>He com vnto Herford, &amp; slouh &thorn;e bisshop Ligere,</L>
<L>Spared noi&thorn;er preste no clerk, to dede alle &yogh;ede in fere.</L>
<L>Kirkes &amp; houses brent, nouht &thorn;an wild he spare.</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;e Inglis had bigged, he mad it wast &amp; bare.</L>
<L>&para; Malcolme of Scotland kyng &yogh;it on Inglond ran,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De rege Scotorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng had him auanced, he was an vnkynd man.</L>
<L>Northumberland he brent, &amp; wasted &thorn;at he fond.</L>
<L>Kirkes non wild he spare of S. Cutberte's lond.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop sent to &thorn;e kyng, for socour him bisouht.</L>
<L>Whan Malcolme herd it say, no more ska&thorn;e he wrouht.
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng did samen his men, to abate Griffyn's pride,</L>
<L>&amp; Harald &thorn;am bitauht ageyn &thorn;e Walsch to ride.</L>
<L>"Do him vnto &thorn;e suerd, withouten jugement,</L>
<L>"If &yogh;e may Griffyn take bityme at any went.</L>
<L>Harald went to Wales, his was fulle fre,</L>
<L>&amp; whan he com &thorn;er, Griffyn was passed &thorn;e se</L>
<L>Unto Irland, &thorn;an comandid Harald</L>
<L>&thorn;o londes to destroie, &thorn;at Griffyn &thorn;er gan hald.</L>
<L>His tounes forto brenne, &thorn;e houses doun to breke,</L>
<L>&amp; destroie &thorn;at kynde, &thorn;at ouht to him couth speke.</L>
<L>&para; Harald &thorn;e Walschmen did &thorn;am ilkon suere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at to kyng Edward faythe &thorn;ei suld alle bere.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en to Rotland he went, &amp; exiled Griffyn &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>Him &amp; alle his heyres for &thorn;at tyme euer more.</L>
<L>&para; Griffyn com ageyn, whan Harald home was went,</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk priuely of Wales mad &thorn;er a parlement.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei said, &thorn;at Sir Griffyn with right he was outlawed,</L>
<L>&amp; Edward of Inglond had &thorn;am so gate awed,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei said, "we wille no more, his vengeance is &yogh;it hote.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei toke &thorn;er Sir Griffyn, &amp; of his hede &thorn;ei smote,</L>
<L>&amp; sent it kyng Edward, &amp; presented him with &thorn;at</L>
<L>Right at Glastenbiri, at his mete &thorn;ore he sat.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GRIFFYN had tuo bre&thorn;er, Bleoth &amp; Ruthe Walan.</L>
<L>&thorn;o tuo were with &thorn;e kyng, whan he on Griffyn kan.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De fratri|bus Griflini &amp; filio ejus.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;erfor vnto &thorn;am tuo he gaf Griffyn's feez.</L>
<L>For South Wales holy &thorn;ei mad &thorn;e kyng feautez.
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>Harald to Wales went, vnto<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vulgo</I>, Port Skeweth. Por|tascith <I>autem Florentio, sub A. D.</I> 1065. <I>Neque discre|pantia ulla in eximio nostro Florentii Codice Langbai|niano.</I></NOTE> Portastiche.</L>
<L>Wrightes he did make, haules &amp; chambres riche,</L>
<L>Whan Harald or &thorn;e kyng wild com &thorn;ider eftsons</L>
<L>In &thorn;e tyme of gese, to tak &thorn;am venysons.</L>
<L>Karaduk, Griffyn sonne, he fordid &thorn;o wones.</L>
<L>He com &thorn;ider on nyght, &thorn;e wrightes slouh at ones,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;at he mot gete, he robbed &amp; reft,</L>
<L>Peny no penyworth, no &thorn;ing he no left.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De contu|melia Dun|stani, filii Agilet.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;at ilk tyme, &thorn;at &thorn;is was beten doun,</L>
<L>Harald tille his fader went to Southampton.</L>
<L>For Dunstan, Agilet sonne, wild greue Sir Godwyn,</L>
<L>For Gospatrik was slayn, &thorn;ei blamed him &thorn;er in.</L>
<L>My boke tellis nay, Godwyn did him no dere.</L>
<L>It sais &thorn;e quene Egyn, &thorn;e blame suld scho bere.</L>
<L>Scho did slo Gospatrik, withouten any skille,</L>
<L>Tostus of Cumbirland retted Godwyn &thorn;er tille.</L>
<L>Tostus of Cumbirland he was chefe Justise,</L>
<L>Ageyn &thorn;e erle Godwyn he gert sette assise.</L>
<L>Gospatrike's dede on Godwyn wild he venge,</L>
<L>Harald souht Tostus, to leue &thorn;at ilk chalenge.</L>
<L>He praied him for luf, in pes lat him be stille,</L>
<L>&amp; kisse &amp; be gode frende in luf &amp; in a wille.</L>
<L>Tostus wild not leue, bot held on his manace,</L>
<L>&amp; Harald tened withalle, of lond he did him chaee.
<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TOSTUS ouer &thorn;e se went to S. Omere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Tosto de Cumber|land.</NOTE></L>
<L>His wife &amp; his meyne, &amp; duelled &thorn;er &thorn;at &yogh;ere</L>
<L>With &thorn;e erle Baldwyn, &thorn;e wynter alle plenere.</L>
<L>His londes he were gyuen to Morkar fitz Richere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode kyng Edward to London turnes he,</L>
<L>&thorn;e feste of &yogh;ole to hold, with grete solempnite,</L>
<L>At Saynt Petir mynstere, &thorn;at he did sette &amp; wirke,</L>
<L>On Saynt Steuen day he did halow &thorn;at kirke.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng fro day to day he heuyed more &amp; more,</L>
<L>Nerhand his endyng, sekenes greued him sore,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De visione &amp; morte Sancti Ed|wardi.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e barons before him kald, &amp; said vnto &thorn;am alle,</L>
<L>"Tille Harald, Godwyn sonne, &thorn;e regne wille best falle.</L>
<L>Me meruailes of my boke, I trowe, he wrote not right,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he forgate Wiliam of forward &thorn;at he him hight.</L>
<L>Neuerles &thorn;e forward held what so was in his &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>I wote wele Criste it wild, &thorn;at Edwarde's wille wer wrouht,</L>
<L>Who so lokes his life, &amp; redis his vision,</L>
<L>What vengeance ordeynd was on Inglond to be don</L>
<L>Of princes of &thorn;e lond, it sais of &thorn;am &thorn;is sawe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei dred no &thorn;ing God, no &yogh;emed euenhed of lawe,</L>
<L>Bot felawes vnto &thorn;efes, to robbours of ilk cuntre,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar wilkednes was fulfilled, venged behoued it be.</L>
<L>Prelates ne no prestes, non of &thorn;am lyued wele,</L>
<L>&thorn;e did not Godde's hestes, bot brak &thorn;am ilk a dele.</L>
<L>Licheros lif &thorn;ei led, &amp; &thorn;ouht it in &thorn;ar breste,</L>
<L>Holynes did away, of &thorn;e kirke gaf &thorn;ei leste.</L>
<L>Edward God bisouht, &thorn;at it suld be forgyuen,</L>
<L>&amp; amendid with penance, &amp; &thorn;erof clene be scryuen
<PB REF="00000294.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ei had don, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;at suld betide</L>
<L>To warne &thorn;am &thorn;erfro, &amp; fle it on ilk side.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is was ansuere ageyn, "a day &thorn;er in salle falle,</L>
<L>"&thorn;are wiknes is fulfilled, &thorn;er in ere waxen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Deest forsan</I> alle.</NOTE> hard.</L>
<L>"God has sette &thorn;at &yogh;ere, a day &thorn;er in salle falle,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e Inglis salle go to suerd, to pyne &thorn;ar soules alle.</L>
<L>"Dede &amp; fire salle fede &thorn;e scheperdes &amp; &thorn;are schepe.</L>
<L>&thorn;is vision is &yogh;it to drede, &thorn;ink &amp; gif Gode kepe.</L>
<L>&para; I trowe it is ouergone &thorn;orgh William conqueroure,</L>
<L>He com &amp; slouh ilkone &thorn;o wikked men in stoure,</L>
<L>&amp; sette vs in seruage, of fredom felle &thorn;e floure.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis &thorn;orgh taliage lyue &yogh;it in sorow fulle soure.</L>
<L>Now is Edward dede, &thorn;e soner for &thorn;o affrayes.</L>
<L>&thorn;re &amp; tuenti &yogh;ere, sex mone&thorn;es &amp; seuenten dayes</L>
<L>He regned in &thorn;is lond, &thorn;e date of God &thorn;an wex</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand, I fond, sexti &yogh;ere &amp; sex.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER Saynt Edward, Harald kyng &thorn;ei ches,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Haraldus factus est Rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;orgh conseile of &thorn;am alle, &amp; he &thorn;e scheld les</L>
<L>Right &amp; in lawe, &thorn;e barons held him trewe.</L>
<L>Neuerles his falshed brouht vs sorowe alle newe.</L>
<L>Tostus, &thorn;at was exiled &thorn;orgh Harald ore I told,</L>
<L>He com out of Flandres, brouht an oste fulle bold.</L>
<L>Fro Sandwich to Lincolne Tostus ran,</L>
<L>Tresore alle &amp; bestes he robbed ilk a man.</L>
<L>&thorn;at herd Harald, fulle kene he was &amp; kof,</L>
<L>With folk out of &thorn;e South toward &thorn;e North drof.
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="67"></L>
<L>Tostus herd it say, &thorn;e best wild he do,</L>
<L>To Malcolme, &thorn;e Scottis kyng, Tostus alied to.</L>
<L>Tostus tok his leue, aryued in Norweie,</L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;e gamen &yogh;ede lithe I salle &yogh;ow seie.</L>
<L>In Norweie was a kyng, my boke tellis sua,</L>
<L>Saynt Onlaf bro&thorn;er, Harald Heruegra.</L>
<L>He aryued in Tyne, bot sone he went ageyn,</L>
<L>&amp; smote iu tille Humber, his flete alle pleyn</L>
<L>In an arme of Ouse vnder Ricalle lay,</L>
<L>On Saynt Mathew euen, on a Wednesday.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EDWYN &amp; Morkare, tuo lordes Kumberland,</L>
<L>To Harald &amp; Tostus &thorn;ei gaf bataile on hand.</L>
<L>Harald of Norweie had folk right inouh,</L>
<L>A hundreth &amp; fifty &thorn;e to&thorn;er side alle slouh.</L>
<L>Harald &amp; Tostus vndir Ricalle so sped,</L>
<L>A hundreth &amp; fifty to &yogh;ork ostage &thorn;ei led.</L>
<L>Nouht &thorn;ien fulle fer to &thorn;am com a ti&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Harald was comand, neuly was mad kyng.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at ilk ti&thorn;ing Tostus was affraied,</L>
<L>&amp; Harald Heruegra, I trow, was no &thorn;ing paied.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh a mede &thorn;ei passed vnto Staunford brigge,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar loges &amp; &thorn;are tentis vp &thorn;ei gan bigge.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Harald &thorn;ider cam, &amp; sauh alle &thorn;ar manere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Haraldus rex devicit bellum, oc|cidit<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> Ha|raldum Tos|tum apud Staynford brigge.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tille &thorn;am smertly he nam, displaied his banere.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e morning it was, he mette with his enmys,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e day &thorn;ei fauht, at euen he had &thorn;e pris.</L>
<L>Harald &amp; Tostus bo&thorn;e to dede &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh Harald &thorn;e &yogh;ong kyng, of wham I salle rede.
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>Listen &amp; I salle rede, why &thorn;e misauentoure</L>
<L>On Harald side gan sprede, &thorn;orgh William conqueroure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE duke of Normundie, William is his name,</L>
<L>Wolnoth, Haralde's bro&thorn;er, he had in prison at Kame,</L>
<L>&amp; his neuow Hakon in prison was him with,</L>
<L>I ne wote for what roson so fer out of &thorn;er kith.</L>
<L>Harald whan he was &yogh;onge, he went vnto France,</L>
<L>&thorn;e cuntre forto se, &amp; for to here of chance.</L>
<L>Alle his mishappyng felle, he com in to Pountif,</L>
<L>To Richere &thorn;at was erle, men told it fulle rif.</L>
<L>&thorn;is lord of Pountif Richer le fitz Izoun</L>
<L>He tok &thorn;is ilk Harald, &amp; did him in presoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bode of him sone kam to &thorn;e duke of Normundie,</L>
<L>&thorn;i duke went to Pountif, &amp; toke him with maistrie,</L>
<L>&amp; brouht Harald home, &amp; said, &thorn;orgh curteisie,</L>
<L>"Harald haf now &thorn;in eyse, in alle my seignorie.</L>
<L>Now has Harald his eyse at reson in alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;e meyne in alle &thorn;ing plesed him next &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&para;William &amp; Harald went &thorn;am forto<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, play.</NOTE> paly,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota de Conque|store, &amp; de causa con|questus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tales togider &thorn;ei tald, ilk on a gode palfray.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei had wele riden, &thorn;at &thorn;am &thorn;ought right lang,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei lighted &amp; abiden biside a water stank.</L>
<L>"Harald, "said William, "listen to my resoun,</L>
<L>"What right &thorn;at I haue of Inglond &thorn;e coroun</L>
<L>"After Edwarde's dede, if it so betide,</L>
<L>"That God haf ordeynd so I after him abide.</L>
<L>"Whan &thorn;at we were Edward &thorn;e king &amp; I,</L>
<L>"He was in my fader courte exiled, I ne wote whi,
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>"Out of Inglond, &thorn;an suore he to me,</L>
<L>"If he &thorn;e coroun mot wynne, his heyre suld I be.</L>
<L>"&thorn;erof he mad me skrite, his hote to mak leale,</L>
<L>"&amp; for to sikere his dede, set &thorn;er to his seale.</L>
<L>"Harald whan &thorn;ou ses tyme, do &thorn;i help &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>"I salle delyuer<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, &thorn;i.</NOTE> &thorn; bro&thorn;er, &amp; &thorn;i neuow also,</L>
<L>"&amp; Marie my douhter to wife I wille &thorn;e gyue,</L>
<L>"A man I salle &thorn;e make, richely forto lyue,</L>
<L>"Or my chefe Justise, &thorn;e lawes to mend &amp; right.</L>
<L>"&thorn;i sistere I salle gyue a rich prince of myght.</L>
<L>&para; "Sire," said Harald, "I salle, if &thorn;at I may,</L>
<L>"Help &thorn;e &thorn;e coroun to hald, &amp; euer I se &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>"My bro&thorn;er delyuer &thorn;ou me, my neuow &thorn;ou me grante,</L>
<L>"&amp; hold &thorn;i certeynte, &amp; salle hold couenante."</L>
<L>&thorn;e presons forth were fette tille Harald or he foore.</L>
<L>To hold &thorn;at he had hette, on &thorn;e boke he suore.</L>
<L>Now gos he home Harald, &amp; has ouercomen his tene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e o&thorn;e &thorn;at he suld hold, it is forgeten clene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EDWARD is dede, allas! messengers ouerwent</L>
<L>To William. Harald was, &thorn;orgh comon assent,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Redundat.</NOTE> Was" corouned nobly, &amp; for kyng &thorn;ei him helde,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e duke of Normundie to William felle &thorn;e schelde.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e duke wrote to &thorn;e kyng, in luf withouten loth,</L>
<L>Bisout him ouer alle &thorn;ing, &thorn;at he wild hold his oth,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;eld him &thorn;e coroun of Inglond ilkadele,</L>
<L>Or Marie to warisoun wed hir, &amp; joy it wele;</L>
<L>&amp; if he wild not so, he suld mak him oknowen,</L>
<L>He suld wynne it for do in right as for his owen.
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>Harald wrote ageyn, &amp; said he neuer &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Marie to wedde certeyn, &thorn;e lond hight him nouht.</L>
<L>&amp; if he wild it wynne with dynt, als duke hardie,</L>
<L>He suld fynd &thorn;erinne kyng Harald redie.</L>
<L>&para; &yogh;it is<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> Halald, I say, regnand in myght &amp; mayn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fece mira.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng of Norway in bataile has he slayn.</L>
<L>&thorn;e duke forgeten is he of &thorn;ing, &thorn;at Harald hette,</L>
<L>Now is he in &thorn;e see with saile on mast vpsette.</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;is lond &thorn;ei drouh, to auenture his chance,</L>
<L>With Normandes inouh, of Flandres &amp; of France.</L>
<L>He had redy sailyng, &thorn;at to &thorn;e lond him ledde,</L>
<L>&amp; at his riuyng &thorn;e lond non him forbedde.</L>
<L>His folk went vpto lond, him seluen was &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>To bank ouer &thorn;e sond, plankes &thorn;ei ouer kast.</L>
<L>Als William &thorn;er on suld go, he stombled at a nayle,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e waise &thorn;am fro he tombled top ouer taile.</L>
<L>His knyghtis vp him lyft, &amp; did him eft atire,</L>
<L>William was oglyft, his helm was fulle of myre,</L>
<L>William was not paied, &thorn;at falle mad him ofright,</L>
<L>He stode alle dismaied, &thorn;an said tille him a knyght,</L>
<L>"Discomfort no &thorn;ing &thorn;e, so faire happe neuer &thorn;ou fond,</L>
<L>"Stoupe &amp; &thorn;ou may se, &thorn;i helm has wonne lond.</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;e lond is &thorn;in, &thorn;i helm schewes it &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"Forsuorn is Haraldyn, he salle no dure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN William alle was dight &amp; to &thorn;e boun<NOTE PLACE="marg">Bellum in|ter Haral|dum &amp; Willelmum Conquesto|rem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Redy with him to fight, he forid Harald fulle sone.
<PB REF="00000299.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>He fond fulle wele &amp; sone, &thorn;at Harald nouht ne slepe,</L>
<L>To proue with dede to done fulle wakand on him lepe.</L>
<L>To bataile haf &thorn;ei mynt Harald &amp; William,</L>
<L>Bot non stode Harald dynt, &thorn;at bifor him kam.</L>
<L>&thorn;e rouht of &thorn;are rascaile he did it rere &amp; ryme,</L>
<L>Normanz &amp; Flemmyng taile he kutted many tyme.</L>
<L>To while &thorn;at he was fresch &thorn;ei fond him fulle austere,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei felt of his pruesse, als knyght did his deuere.</L>
<L>For he was ouer prest, &amp; egre to assaile,</L>
<L>He wild haf no rest, tille he myght trauaile.</L>
<L>Allas! for `for<NOTE PLACE="foot">Redundat.</NOTE> Sir Harald, for him was mikelle reuth,</L>
<L>Fulle wele his awen suld hald, if he had kept his treuth.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at he was forsuorn, mishappyng &thorn;erfor he fond,</L>
<L>Suld he neuer els haf lorn for William no lond,</L>
<L>Ne bien in &thorn;at bondage, &thorn;at brouht was ouer &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Now ere &thorn;ei in seruage fulle fele &thorn;at or was fre.</L>
<L>Our fredom &thorn;at day for euer toke &thorn;e leue,</L>
<L>For Harald it went away, his falshed did vs greue.</L>
<L>He was so fer in presse, so fele wer him about,</L>
<L>Him befor alle &thorn;ei ches, &thorn;at he suld not skape out.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Haraldus occisus est. regnavit novem menses &amp; tres dies.</NOTE></L>
<L>Normanz &amp; Burgolons, with lance, suerd &amp; mace,</L>
<L>Bare Sir Harald doun, allas! he had no grace.</L>
<L>So douhty knyght of dede was non of noi&thorn;er sides,</L>
<L>&thorn;ore to dede he &yogh;ede, als man forsuorn betides.</L>
<L>Nien monethes beforn kept Harald &thorn;e regalle</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at he was forsuorn, &thorn;erfor he lost alle.</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e stoure &thorn;at stode tuo men askaped ware</L>
<L>Of Sir Haralde's blode, Eadwyn &amp; Morkare.
<PB REF="00000300.tif" N="72"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei toke &thorn;e quene Edith, for doute of treson,</L>
<L>Was kyng Edwarde's wif, led hir to Kelion.</L>
<L>Wele was scho &thorn;er, to hold priue soiorne.</L>
<L>Eadwyn &amp; Morkare to London gan &thorn;ei turne,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Londreis &thorn;ei told, &thorn;at &thorn;ei had fonden an hayre,</L>
<L>Was Edmund kosyn &thorn;e kyng, &thorn;e Londreis wer in speyr,</L>
<L>Him for &thorn;ar kyng vplift, his name was kald Edgar.</L>
<L>For William &thorn;ei were oglift, &amp; said, "&thorn;at we ne dar.</L>
<L>"For slayn is kyng Harald, &amp; in lond may non be,</L>
<L>"Bot of William hald for homage &amp; feaute.</L>
<L>Morkar recleymed es, as es &thorn;e faukon fre,</L>
<L>&amp; Eadwyn com to pes, he mot no better se.</L>
<L>&thorn;e burgeis of London &thorn;ar conseile wild it nouht,</L>
<L>To gif Edgar &thorn;e coroun, &thorn;at for heyr &thorn;ei brouht.</L>
<L>William &thorn;e Conquerour to London has he &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;e bataile was stoure an abbay wild he haf wrouht.</L>
<L>&thorn;er he &amp; Harald mette, &thorn;er standes &thorn;e kirke,</L>
<L>For blode &thorn;at &thorn;er was gette, to praie &thorn;ei suld not irke.</L>
<L>To London com William, his &yogh;ole feste to hold,</L>
<L>His barons with him nam, knyghtes &thorn;at wer bold.</L>
<L>Wardeyns of tour &amp; toun, &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at ne wold</L>
<L>&thorn;er landes les alle doun, for tynt wer &thorn;ei told.</L>
<L>To Frankis &amp; Normanz, for &thorn;ar grete laboure,</L>
<L>To Flemmynges &amp; Pikardes, &thorn;at wer with him in stoure,</L>
<L>He gaf londes bityme, of whilk &thorn;er successoure</L>
<L>Hold &yogh;it &thorn;e seysyne, with fulle grete honoure.</L>
<L>Fair grace William fond, his chance fulle wele him satte,</L>
<L>&thorn;e reame of Inglond so graciously he gatte.
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>&thorn;e archbisshop Stigand, of Inglond primate,</L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme was suspended, &thorn;e pape reft him &thorn;e state.</L>
<L>&amp; abbot &amp; prioure, men of Religion,</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er men of honour, archdecane &amp; person,</L>
<L>Wer priued of &thorn;ar office, of woulfes had renoun.</L>
<L>For lichorie &thorn;at vice wer many als don doun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e archbisshope of &yogh;ork com with deuocioun,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh William praiere, com to London toun,</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e barons brouht, he gaf William &thorn;e coroun.</L>
<L>To chalange was he nouht, Sir Stigand was don doun.</L>
<L>Whan William was coruned kyng so solemply,</L>
<L>&amp; had taken homage of barons bi &amp; bi,</L>
<L>He turned ouer &thorn;e se vnto Normundi.</L>
<L>Dam<NOTE PLACE="foot">Matildin <I>appellant alii.</I></NOTE> Helienore quene was sche, scho bare him company.</L>
<L>Whan he had duelled &thorn;ore at Pask he com ageyn,</L>
<L>&amp; dam Helianore with many knyght &amp; sueyn.</L>
<L>To London alle &thorn;ei went &thorn;e courte holy alle pleyn,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e archbisshop &thorn;ei sent, messengers &yogh;ede tueyn.</L>
<L>Elred &thorn;e archbisshop of &yogh;ork had &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng him bisouht, als clerk of dignite,</L>
<L>To coroune Helianore, &thorn;at biseke I &thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Helianora regina<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> coronata.</NOTE> co|ronate est.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop corouned hir &thorn;ore, bifor &thorn;at faire semble.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e folk had bien at &thorn;e coronment ilk dele,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;e quene &thorn;e barons paied wele.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;e clergie ordeynd &thorn;at ilk seele,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pes to &yogh;eme &amp; gyue with lawes trewe als stele.</L>
<L>Edmunde &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Godwyn <I>aliis.</I></NOTE> Edwyn, Harald sonnes of Kent,</L>
<L>Alle Somersetschire &thorn;ei wasted &amp; brent,
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>Sir Adinoth &thorn;ei slouh, &amp; alle &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot hent.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei had frauh inouh, ageyn tille Ireland went.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle Robert Comyn, &thorn;e West had to welde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non vnto William for no &thorn;ing suld &thorn;am &yogh;elde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN &thorn;at kyng William &thorn;o ti&thorn;inges herd say,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mult&aelig; ad|versitates.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e toun of Durham fulle fast he toke &thorn;e way.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop to him said, <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Vide Dugdalii Baronag. Tom. I. p. 54. Lelandi Coll. vol. II. p.</I> 380. <I>aliosque etiam Historicos nostros, qui secus atque noster rem narr&acirc;runt.</I></NOTE>&amp; told to him fulle tite,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e Norreis purueied, to do him a despite.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ilk tale, &thorn;at &thorn;e bisshop told,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Komyn had his bale, his lif was lightly sold.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lond of S. Cutbert he did serch &thorn;at nyght,</L>
<L>William alle apert his oste redy he dyght.</L>
<L>At &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot fynd, to suerd alle &thorn;ei &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&amp; or Roberd wist, or &thorn;ouht on suilk a dede,</L>
<L>Ore was his hous on fire, &thorn;er Sir Robert lay,</L>
<L>&amp; brent Roberd to dede, bi &thorn;at it was day.</L>
<L>Now is &thorn;e Komyn dede, his haires has alle lorn,</L>
<L>William &thorn;am it forbede, &thorn;at held his londes beforn.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce Da|nachi.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW William has soiorned, &amp; slayn alle his enmys,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e South is turned, als kyng &thorn;at wan &thorn;e pris.</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;ynges com him fulle stoute, &thorn;at a grete oste &amp; stark,</L>
<L>With Harald &amp; with Knoute, &thorn;e kyng sonnes of Danmark,</L>
<L>Were aryued in Humbere, &amp; an erle Turkille,</L>
<L>With folk withouten nombere, &thorn;e Norreis felle &thorn;am tille.
<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>Comen is &thorn;e erle Edgar with alle &thorn;o of his kynde,</L>
<L>Sir Wolnoth he is &thorn;ar, &thorn;o with &thorn;at he mot fynde.</L>
<L>Marlesuayn Turkille sonne, &amp; Suane a douhty knyght,</L>
<L>Of Scotland Gospatrik, with &thorn;am at alle his myght.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Normans in &thorn;e South wer in so grete affray,</L>
<L>Of kastels &amp; of touns &thorn;ei com out alle day,</L>
<L>To &yogh;ork ran ilk a man, to rescet in &thorn;at toun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at no Danes man &thorn;e walles to breke doun.</L>
<L>Sir William Malet was wardeyn of &thorn;e cuntres,</L>
<L>Sibrigh &thorn;e Gaunt was set with him to kepe &thorn;e fees.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise tuo brouht tiyng, &thorn;e wer comen bi &thorn;at coste,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor William &thorn;e kyng did turne ageyn his oste,</L>
<L>&amp; suore a grete othe, &thorn;at he suld neuer spare</L>
<L>Noi&thorn;er lefe no lothe northeren, what so &thorn;ei ware.</L>
<L>&para; William turned ageyn, &amp; held &thorn;at he had suorn,</L>
<L>Alle mad he wasteyn, pastur, medow &amp; korn,</L>
<L>&amp; slouh bo&thorn;e fader &amp; sonne, women lete &thorn;ei gon,</L>
<L>Hors &amp; hondes &thorn;ei etc, vnne&thorn;is skaped non.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e Danes herd, &thorn;at William held his oth,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he with &thorn;e Norreis so ferd, spared lefe no loth,</L>
<L>Fulle quaintly &thorn;ei sent to William messengers,</L>
<L>Of pes &thorn;ei mad present, to turne ilkon &thorn;er pers</L>
<L>Ageyn to Danmark go with his wille &amp; his leue,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he suld no mo slo, ne &thorn;ei suld him not greue.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce Da|nachi.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW duellis William eft, fulle bare mas many wone,</L>
<L>Of gode men er non left, bot slayn er ilkone.</L>
<L>Clerkes vnne&thorn;is &thorn;ei lete, to kirke o lyue to go,</L>
<L>Horses &amp; hondes &thorn;ei ete for hunger &amp; for wo.
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>Grete synne did William, &thorn;at suilk wo did wirke,</L>
<L>So grete vengeance he nam of men of holy kirke,</L>
<L>&thorn;at not did no wem, tille him ne no trespas,</L>
<L>Fro &yogh;ork vnto Durhem no wonyng stede was.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Id quod etiam notat Jo|annes Rastellus, sive Rastal|lus, in Chronico suo, supra &agrave; me commemorato, libro sane rarissimo, mihi vero (pro more suo) perquam humani|ter mutuo dato ab amicissimo nostro Murraio, cujus cum alibi, tum jam supra etiam mentionem feci. Sic autem Rastellus:</I> &para; Also about the.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sege at Yorke.</NOTE> iii. yere of his [<I>Wyllyam Conquerour's</I>] rayne &verbar; Har|rolde &amp; Cauntus [<I>Sic</I>] sonnes to Suanus kyng of Denmarke enteryd into the North coun|trey &verbar; and with the helpe of some of the people of the contrey and of some of the cytezyns of yorke enteryd the citye &verbar; and slewe mo than. iii. M. Normans. But sone after kyng Wyllyam chasyd them out &verbar; and droue them to theyr schyppes and toke suche displeasure with the inhabytans of that prouynce &verbar; that he distroyed the lande from yorke to Durham &verbar; that. ix. yere after it lay vnlaboryd and vntylled &verbar; and the peo|ple there were kept so harde by the warre of the kynge &verbar; &amp; in suche famyne that they ete rattes &verbar; cattes &verbar; dogges &verbar; and other vermyne.</NOTE>Nien &yogh;ere, sais my buke, lasted so grete sorowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop clerkes tuke, &thorn;ar lyues forto borowe.</L>
<L>Seynt Cutberte's bones of fertre toke &thorn;ei out,</L>
<L>With &thorn;am &thorn;ei fled at ons in sere stedes about,</L>
<L>&thorn;at vengeance burd be don, als tellis S. Edward,</L>
<L>He sauh in a vision, &thorn;at vengeance suld falle hard</L>
<L>Of prestes &amp; of clerkes, of princes of &thorn;e lond,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Reli|quiis Sancti Cuthberti.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of God ne of his werkes &thorn;ei dred not &thorn;at &thorn;ei fond.
<PB REF="00000305.tif" N="77"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SAYNT Cutberte's clerkes in hidnes euer &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>At Geruans <NOTE PLACE="foot">Vide Sim. Dunelm. p. 199. &amp; Leland. Coll. Vol. II. p. 380.</NOTE> set &thorn;er merkes, a hous &thorn;e gan vpspede.</L>
<L>&yogh;it Northermore &thorn;ei &yogh;ed vntille Bethlyngton,</L>
<L>At Toghalle was &thorn;e &thorn;rid, &amp; &thorn;er restid &thorn;am doun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e ferth was holy Eland, &thorn;er &thorn;e se it withdrouh,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei &yogh;ede on &thorn;e sand, to &thorn;at Ilde wele inouh.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei wer &thorn;erinne, of non had &thorn;ei doute,</L>
<L>&thorn;e flode bigan to gynne, &amp; klosed it aboute.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en dred &thorn;ei no &thorn;ing, of &thorn;efe ne of feloun</L>
<L>&thorn;at were with &thorn;e kyng, Norman no Burgoloun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kirke of Geruans &thorn;at ilk tyme was brent,</L>
<L>Durham &thorn;e same sans, alle to fire went.</L>
<L>&thorn;e croice &amp; &thorn;e rode, right as Criste vs bouht,</L>
<L>Tille askes alle it &yogh;ode, &thorn;e fire spared nouht.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Normans did it alle in &thorn;e guyse of theft,</L>
<L>&thorn;e godes &thorn;erof stal, no &thorn;ing &thorn;ei ne left.</L>
<L>&para; Whan William vnderstode, how his men ferd with alle,</L>
<L>Of holy kirke &thorn;e gode his serganz robbed &amp; stal,</L>
<L>He comandid alle his, to mende &thorn;at trespas,</L>
<L>In alle maner wise, as it ore feffed was,</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;e same asise serued &amp; alowed</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e franchise, &thorn;at it are was dowed.</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;at wikkednes, &thorn;at men suld haf wroken,</L>
<L>Was noi&thorn;er more no lesse of &thorn;er penance spoken.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Reliqui&aelig; Sancti Cuthberti ad Durham ubi prius in feretro re|conduntur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop brouh the bones ageyn vnto &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Tille Durhame's wones, &thorn;er &thorn;ei were wont to be.
<PB REF="00000306.tif" N="78"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WILLIAM the Conquerour changis his wikked wille,</L>
<L>Out of his first errour, repentis of his ille,</L>
<L>&amp; of his crueltes he gynnes forto assuage,</L>
<L>&amp; gaf ageyn &thorn;o fees, of whilk he toke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> ostage.</NOTE> ostages.</L>
<L>Gospatrik com tille hand, &amp; left of his manage,</L>
<L>&amp; William Comberland gaf him in heritage.</L>
<L>Gospatrik &yogh;ed alle &thorn;orgh, his dedis forto praise,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kastelle of Bamborgh &thorn;e walles he did vpreise.</L>
<L>Malcolme, &thorn;e Scottes kyng, &thorn;erwith had envie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Gospatrik of suilk &thorn;ing bare his state so hie,</L>
<L>Dight him to Combirland, destroied about aywhare,</L>
<L>Ilkon he slouh at hand, &thorn;er godes away bare,</L>
<L>Many with him he led, &amp; did &thorn;am in seruage,</L>
<L>In Scottland was alle spred mykelle of &thorn;at lynage.</L>
<L>&para; On &thorn;is Gospatrik William gan affie,</L>
<L>He dight also quik, &amp; went Normundie.</L>
<L>Malcolme in Kumberland dos &thorn;at he may tille ille,</L>
<L>Gospatrik his willand lates him haf his wille.</L>
<L>&thorn;re &thorn;ousand pounde Malcolme sent tille Gospatrik tresorie,</L>
<L>To William comyng &thorn;at went suld suffre his folie.</L>
<L>Litelle wend William of his trecherie,</L>
<L>A message tille him nam vnto Normundie,</L>
<L>Teld William eueridele of Malcolme robberie,</L>
<L>For siluere &thorn;at he toke suffred &thorn;e folk to die,</L>
<L>Gospatrik did not wele, mayntend his partie.</L>
<L>William also sui&thorn;e dight him tille his nauie.
<PB REF="00000307.tif" N="79"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WILLIAM has hauen nomen, &amp; is at Southampton.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Willelmus applicuit apud Ham|ptoniam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at with him er komen, erle knyght &amp; baron,</L>
<L>Went tille Comberland fulle sui&thorn;e opon haste,</L>
<L>&thorn;e cuntre &thorn;at &thorn;ei fand alle was wilde &amp; waste.</L>
<L>Malcolme fled beforn in mountayns &amp; in playn,</L>
<L>He wend for neuer more William suld com agayn.</L>
<L>No more did Gospatrik, &thorn;at did him &thorn;at disceit,</L>
<L>Bot comen is William quik, &amp; sekes &thorn;am fulle streit.</L>
<L>Bi a side of Scotland Malcolme flies fer in,</L>
<L>Bot William Malcolme fand in &thorn;e toun of Abrenethyn.</L>
<L>&thorn;er is Malcolme taken, &amp; &yogh;olden to preson.</L>
<L>Siluer was not forsaken was giffen for his raunson.</L>
<L>To take he bed inouh, for at his wille he was.</L>
<L>William to do his prowe, forgaf alle his trespas.</L>
<L>Malcolme with skrite him bond, his heires of his lynage</L>
<L>To hold of Ingland for feaute &amp; homage.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e pes was siker, &thorn;e kyng turned fulle sui&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Gospatrik &thorn;at suffred biker, he reft bo&thorn;e lond &amp; li&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Cumberland him reft, his o&thorn;er londes als,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lif ouer mykelle him left, for he was traitour fals.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en to Durham went, &thorn;er he destroied &thorn;e see.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop he bisouht, S. Cutberte's bones to see,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop opned &thorn;e schryne, the bones &thorn;ei vp raised.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng wepte with his ine, that sight mykelle he praised,</L>
<L>&amp; siluer grete plente opon the altere laid,</L>
<L>&thorn;er franchise gaf &thorn;am fre, &thorn;e whilk &thorn;at &thorn;ei of said.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kastelle did he wirke of his tresore alle,</L>
<L>&amp; S. Cutberte's kirke closed with a walle.
<PB REF="00000308.tif" N="80"></L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he had &thorn;am turne to &yogh;ork, &amp; &thorn;er abide,</L>
<L>For &thorn;er he wild soiorne alle &thorn;e Whitsons tide.</L>
<L>&para; At &yogh;ork did he crie, his pes suld holden be,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non did felonie bi land no bi se.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he &yogh;ede to London, &thorn;at cite set to grith,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e lawe alle bondon ilk man in his kith.</L>
<L>Chefe justise he satte, &thorn;e sothe to atrie,</L>
<L>For lefe no loth to lette &thorn;e right lawe to guye.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wronges to amend, &amp; maynten &thorn;e right,</L>
<L>Ageyn &thorn;e fals defend, &thorn;orgh dome of Justise sight.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THAT tyme &thorn;at I of say of William &thorn;e kyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De tribus monachis de Lynd|say.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;re monkes of Lyndsay &yogh;ede to seke wonyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e first dan Aldwyn, &thorn;e to&thorn;er Elwyn hight he,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;rid hight Reynfride, &thorn;us told my boke to me.</L>
<L>Hughe le fitz Galdre, of &yogh;ork he was Schirue,</L>
<L>He resceyued alle &thorn;re, &amp; heberd &thorn;am bileue.</L>
<L>After &thorn;er soiornyng, whan &thorn;at &thorn;ei suld wende,</L>
<L>He praied &thorn;am of alle &thorn;ing, as gentille men &amp; hende,</L>
<L>To haf saf condite, vnto &thorn;e New Kastelle.</L>
<L>&amp; Hugh did as he hight, led &thorn;am sauely welle.</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e New Kastelle vnto Geruans &thorn;ei &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&thorn;er duelled &thorn;ei non seel, to Durham gan &thorn;am spede.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;ei to Durham com to &thorn;e bisshop Waltere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">&AElig;dificave|runt eccle|siam &amp; claustrum de Durham.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;ei bigan a home of religiouse manere.</L>
<L>A closter &thorn;ei bigan, &thorn;e bisshop &thorn;o &thorn;at wrought,</L>
<L>Hired ilk a man, &amp; alle paied &amp; bought.</L>
<L>Or it wer alle ent &thorn;e werke &thorn;at &thorn;ei did wirke,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei ordeynd a couent, to ministre in &thorn;at kirke.
<PB REF="00000309.tif" N="81"></L>
<L>"Help Lady," said Waltere, "of &thorn;e &thorn;an is &thorn;is house</L>
<L>"&thorn;at are was prouendere, now is religiouse.<NOTE PLACE="marg">&AElig;dificatur abbatia beat&aelig; Ma|ri&aelig; apud Eboracum.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &yogh;orke &thorn;e com a&yogh;eyn, &amp; wrouht &thorn;er worschiply</L>
<L>Cloistre with couent pleyn a kirk of our Lady.</L>
<L>&para; Whan it was wrouht tille ende, &thorn;e monkes alle &thorn;re<NOTE PLACE="marg">&AElig;dificave|runt clau|strum de Whiteby.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Whitby gan wende, &thorn;at standis on &thorn;e see.</L>
<L>&thorn;er wirke &thorn;ei wild an abbeye wele to preise</L>
<L>In wirschip of Saynt Hilde, a kirke &thorn;ei did vp reise.</L>
<L>&thorn;us wrouht &thorn;ise monke &thorn;re, &thorn;orh &thorn;e holy goste,</L>
<L>Abbayes in sere cuntre, &thorn;at wikked men did waste,</L>
<L>&amp; many a gode man to holy lif did calle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;orgh &thorn;e lawe paien men left &amp; lete doun falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT London is William, at Lundreis takes leue,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e parlement he nam at Paris to Lowis cheue.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex venit ad parlia|mentum a|pud Parys.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e duze pers of France were &thorn;at tyme at Parys,</L>
<L>To William felle &thorn;ar chance, he mad conquest of pris,</L>
<L>&thorn;e toun wan of Terwenne, the castelle of Malbis,</L>
<L>His auncestrie whilom when left it &thorn;orgh folis.</L>
<L>Whan William with &thorn;e lawe had seisen pleynerly,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he gan him drawe toward Normundy,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lond to visite, &amp; to comfort his frendes.</L>
<L>He restid bot a lite, a sonde &thorn;e Inglis him sendes.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Surrey sent Hacon Henry sonne,</L>
<L>He to William went, &amp; praied him &yogh;it eftsonne</L>
<L>To com tille Inglond, or els alle he lesis,</L>
<L>Ageyn him wille men stond, &amp; partie tille him chesis.</L>
<L>&para; William was in wehere, whan he herd &thorn;at ti&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>In his auhtend &yogh;ere, als he regned kyng,
<PB REF="00000310.tif" N="82"></L>
<L>At Wyncehestre he held his parlement ilk &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er men him teld, who was his aduersere,</L>
<L>Of Northfolk &thorn;e erle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>His name was Ralph. But his Confederate, the Earl of Hereford's Name was Roger. See Dugdale's Baronage, p. 67, 68. This Affair is thus touch'd upon by John Rastall, in his most rare Chronicle:</I> &para; About the. x. yere of his raygne &verbar; Roger erle of Har|forde &verbar; and Rafe erle of North|folke fledde &verbar; and were out|laude &verbar; &amp; the erle walreffe was behedyd.</NOTE> Roger, men said of him treson,</L>
<L>For praier or for pere &thorn;ei did him in prison.</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e Marche gan long an erle, Wolnot he hight,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng with mykelle wrong did him slo &thorn;at knyght.</L>
<L>Abowen Wynchestere was schewed tille alle &thorn;at &thorn;er ware,</L>
<L>To lewed men &amp; lerid, to kirke as &thorn;ei him bare,</L>
<L>Miracle faire &amp; myrie, whan &thorn;ei laid him in pitte.</L>
<L>William of Malmesbirie witnesse it in his writte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SITHEN in his &thorn;rid &yogh;ere he tellis &thorn;er of a chance,</L>
<L>Of Durham bisshop Waltere was smyten &thorn;orgh with a lance.</L>
<L>In Gatesheued it was, &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;at suld be schent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Quomodo Episcopus Dunelmi&aelig; interfectus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o did &thorn;at trepas, Sir Liolfe's kynde of Kent,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle Liolf was slayn, for &thorn;e bisshop dede.</L>
<L>My boke sais certayn, &thorn;at he gaf neuer &thorn;at rede.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor kyng William did fleme alle &thorn;at kynde,</L>
<L>&thorn;ar landes fro &thorn;am nam, &thorn;at men not knowe &amp; fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SITHEN in his fer&thorn;e &yogh;ere he went tille Aluerton,</L>
<L>No man wend in er&thorn;e drede of no felon.
<PB REF="00000311.tif" N="83"></L>
<L>On warned him of a &thorn;ing, &thorn;at Malcolme with poysoun,</L>
<L>Schuld begile &thorn;e kyng, with som &thorn;at lufed tresoun.</L>
<L>William sent his sond his eldest sonne Roberd,</L>
<L>If he mot vnderstond, or any suilk of herd.</L>
<L>Roberd about did spie, if Malcolme wild haf wrouht.</L>
<L>Bot alle it was a lie, &thorn;at &thorn;ing was neuer &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>In his auhtend &yogh;ere &thorn;at William was regnand,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Extendere fecit ter|ram, &amp; di|visit terras filiis suis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Extendours he sette forto extend &thorn;e land,</L>
<L>Erldam &amp; baronie how mykelle felle to &thorn;e schelde,</L>
<L>Knyght &amp; sergeancie als how mykelle &thorn;ei helde.</L>
<L>How mykelle lond &amp; rent holy kirke had to a prowe,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ei did extend to witte &thorn;e verrey valowe,</L>
<L>&amp; William wist of alle, what it suld amounte,</L>
<L>Of lordyng &amp; of thralle &thorn;e extente &thorn;orgh acounte.</L>
<L>&para; Roberd Courthose his sonne he gaf all Normundie,</L>
<L>To hold, as it was wonne, als heyre of ancestrie.</L>
<L>William passid &thorn;e se, &thorn;er of he mad &thorn;e skrite,</L>
<L>Of France to hold &thorn;at fe of o&thorn;er tenement alle quite.</L>
<L>&para; His o&thorn;er sonne William Inglond assigned he,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;at of him cam with chartre mad he fre.</L>
<L>His sonne Henry was sire of Wales with chartre streite,</L>
<L>Of alle Loncastre schire vntille Bromsthueite.</L>
<L>&para; Ade his douhter dere, he lufed hir als his life,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Plesance Steuene weddid hir to wife,</L>
<L>&amp; kyng Steuen on hir gate, &thorn;at withouten reson</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is lond had &thorn;e state, &amp; conquered &thorn;e coroun.</L>
<L>&para; His douhter Custance was wedded to Bretayn,</L>
<L>With William's ordenance, vnto &thorn;e erle Alayn.
<PB REF="00000312.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>Tuo &yogh;ere &amp; a half he duelled in Normundie,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;at lond self at Kame gan he die.</L>
<L>At Saynt Steuen's kirke &thorn;ei laid him with honoure,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sepultus est in Kame Anno Domini. M<SUP>o</SUP> LXXX. VIII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Himself did it wirke, he was &thorn;ar<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>This king, in remembrance of the great Victory he had ob|tain'd over Harold (by which he got Possession of England) founded the great Abbey of Battel in Sussex. But then that, for which I am chiefly obliged to make this Note, is, his founding the Cluniack Abbey of</I> Bermondsey <I>in Surrey, if we may give any credit to John Rastall's Chronicle, which is a most rare Book (as I have be|fore noted) and was written by a learned Man (tho' a Printer, for Printers then were Men of Learning) who had married E|lizabeth, the Sister of Sir Tho|mas More, which was of no small Advantage to him in the History of our English Affairs. The Words in Rastall are these.</I> &para; This wyllyam made the newe forest in Hampshyre and therfore cast downe dyuers churches by the space of. xxx. myles. In his tyme he kept the englysshemen so lowe &verbar; that fewe of them bare any offyce of honour or rule &verbar; but somwhat he fauored the citye of London. Also he buylded two abbayes in En|glande &verbar; that is to say the abbaye of Battell &verbar; where he wanne the fylde agaynst Ha|rolde and the abbay of Bar|meseye in Southwarke besyde London &verbar; and also he buyld|ed. ii. other abbayes in Nor|mandye. <I>Which Words will give some Confirmation to what is asserted by those, that tell us, that William the Conqueror built many abbyes of the order of Cluny, in relation to which there is this Note in a MS. in the Bodleian Library, as is observ'd by the learned Dr. Tanner. A Note (saith the Dr. Pref. to his</I> Not. Mon. <I>p.</I> 42.) annexed to an old MS. book of Ecclesiastical Constitutions in the <I>Bodleian</I> Library [Inter MSS. <I>Junian.</I> 121.] <I>desires us</I> to note the slyght of the Pope, that when he had causyd the Deuke of Norman|dy to Conquer <I>England;</I> under pretence of penance causyd him to give muche Lands to Abbyes, and that Deuke dyd bylde many of the Order of <I>Cluny</I>, because Pope <I>Gregory VI.</I> was a monk of <I>Cluny.</I> Tho' I cannot find (<I>continues the Dr.</I>) that ever he founded any of this Order, yet he built and endowed the great Abbies of <I>Battel</I> Com. <I>Suss.</I> and <I>Selby</I> in Com. <I>Ebor.</I> and the Priory of <I>Hitchinbroke</I> in Com. <I>Hunt.</I> and the Alien|Priories of <I>Frampton</I> in Com. <I>Dors. Paunsfeld</I> in Com. <I>Essex, Derehirst</I> in Com. <I>Gloc. Ando|ver</I> in Com. <I>Hants.</I> and <I>Stanyng</I> in Com. <I>Suss.</I></NOTE> fondoure.</L>
<L>Tuenty &yogh;ere had he &thorn;e land &amp; nien moneth streite,</L>
<L>&thorn;e date was a &thorn;ousand &amp; fourscore &amp; auhte.
<PB REF="00000313.tif" N="85"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE conquerour is laid at Kame dede in graue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Willelmus Rufus coro|natus est apud West|monaste|rium.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Courthose befor said Normundie salle haue.</L>
<L>To William &thorn;e rede kyng is gyuen &thorn;e coroun,</L>
<L>At Westmynstere tok he ryng in &thorn;e abbay of Londoun.</L>
<L>Whan he had alle plenerly seisyn of &thorn;e lond,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons &amp; &thorn;e clergy ageyns him he fond.</L>
<L>&thorn;is was &thorn;are comon sawe in burgh &amp; cite,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e Courthose with &thorn;e lawe suld &thorn;are lord be.</L>
<L>"He is bro&thorn;er eldest, &thorn;e coroun salle he bere.</L>
<L>"He is of body best, &thorn;e reame forto were.</L>
<L>What did &thorn;e grete lordynges, erles &amp; barounes?</L>
<L>Kastels &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;inges seised, maners &amp; tounes.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng had fulle grete &thorn;ouht, his reame ageyn him ros,</L>
<L>Frendes fast he souht, to venge him on his fos.</L>
<L>&thorn;is sorow &amp; &thorn;is drede lastid him &thorn;re &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Of pes ne myght he spede, bot euer in &thorn;er dangere.</L>
<L>His frendes gan him rede, to go to &thorn;e kyng of France,</L>
<L>To conseile him in &thorn;is nede, to abate &thorn;at distance.</L>
<L>For &thorn;is kyng William dight him vnto schip,</L>
<L>His frendis with him nam vnto kyng Philip.</L>
<L>&para; Vnto kyng Philip he schewed ilka dele,</L>
<L>How his barons gan kip ageyn him did not wele,
<PB REF="00000314.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>"&thorn;erfor I am comen, to wite at &yogh;ow our heued,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e londes &thorn;at we haf nomen, to whom &thorn;e salle be leued;</L>
<L>"&amp; at &yogh;our jugement I will stand &amp; do,</L>
<L>"With &thorn;i &thorn;at it be ent &thorn;e strif bituen vs tuo.</L>
<L>Philip said bli&thorn;ely, &amp; sent his messengers</L>
<L>Tille Inglond to &thorn;e clergy, erles, barons &thorn;er pers,</L>
<L>&amp; askid if &thorn;ei wild stand to &thorn;er lokyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e duke Roberd fulfilled, so did William &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons wrote ageyn, at his demyng &thorn;ei ches,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei held his dome certeyn, for he was prince of pes.</L>
<L>Philip was fulle wis, with scrite he bond &thorn;am bo&thorn;e.</L>
<L>He said &thorn;an his avis, "kisse &amp; be not wro&thorn;e.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e first &thorn;ei kiste, as frendes felle to be.</L>
<L>"Of &yogh;our fader biqueste, dome &thorn;an salle &yogh;e se.</L>
<L>Doun &thorn;ei sat on benke, among &thorn;e duze pers.</L>
<L>Philip gan him<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> thnke, &amp; said on &thorn;is maners.</L>
<L>&para; "William &thorn;e Conquerour his ancestres &amp; he<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce dis|cussio facta est coram Philippo inter Wil|lelmum Rufum &amp; Robertum fratrem e|jus, ducem Norman|ni&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Held with grete honour Normundie in fe</L>
<L>"Of alle kynges of France, &amp; so did he of me,</L>
<L>"For alle o&thorn;er distance, with homage &amp; feaute.</L>
<L>"Alle Inglond he wan &thorn;orgh his vassalage,</L>
<L>"&amp; Harald kyng ouer ran, &thorn;at did William outrage.</L>
<L>"&thorn;erto had he no right, no non of his linage.</L>
<L>"&thorn;at William wan with myght is told non heritage.</L>
<L>"We se alle day in place &thorn;ing &thorn;at a man wynnes,</L>
<L>"It is told purchace, whedir he it hold or tuynnes.</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;at comes of grace or of conquest bigynnes,</L>
<L>"He may, tille he has space, gif it withouten synnes.
<PB REF="00000315.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>"Heritage &thorn;at lyues &amp; leues to &thorn;e eldest sonne,</L>
<L>"Purchaced &thorn;ing men gyues, woman weddyng to mone,</L>
<L>"Or tille a man is strange for his seruise oftsone.</L>
<L>"Heritage salle men not change on purchace wise to wone.</L>
<L>"Roberd, &thorn;orgh our assent, &thorn;e heritage to &thorn;e lies,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;ou, William, salle hent &thorn;e purchace at our avis.</L>
<L>"&thorn;us &yogh;our fader &yogh;ow sette, als man of lawe was wis,</L>
<L>"His dede ne wille we lette, be &thorn;e martir Saynt Denys.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Roberd sauh &amp; wist, how &thorn;e conseile &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e holy land him list, &amp; &thorn;ider gan him spede.</L>
<L>Whan he com at Marsille, &amp; ouer &thorn;e se suld wend,</L>
<L>Philip sauh his wille, &amp; after him gan send.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bode was sent to ra&thorn;e, &thorn;e messenger com ouersone.</L>
<L>For soth it was gret skathe, his passage was fordone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE rede kyng William felle a faire chance,</L>
<L>To Saynt Poule's he cam, withouten greuance.</L>
<L>For erles &amp; barons bi sond he for sent,</L>
<L>&amp; alle at his somons to parlement went.</L>
<L>He schewed on &amp; o&thorn;er, &thorn;at bated was &thorn;e strife</L>
<L>Bituex him &amp; Roberd, &amp; were in luf of life,</L>
<L>With chartre wele wreten &amp; selid certeyn,</L>
<L>&amp; wele it was to witen no chalange ageyn,</L>
<L>Wherfor he &thorn;am hight, if &thorn;ei to luf wild drawe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e coroune at his myght to maynten with lawe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Robertus Courthose applicuit in Angliam cum amore, &amp; venit fratri suo Willelmo.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he so suld &thorn;e barons had affiance,</L>
<L>His kastels &thorn;ei him &yogh;olde, with alle &thorn;e purtenance.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e &yogh;ere folowand, at &thorn;e somere's tide,</L>
<L>Roberd com to &thorn;is land, at Douer gan vp ride.
<PB REF="00000316.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>Whan herd say with luf, tille him he sped,</L>
<L>&amp; with grete noblay tille London him led.</L>
<L>With in &thorn;o auht daies com William &thorn;is ti&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;e North had fele affraies, &thorn;orgh &thorn;e Scottis kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;e cuntre gan assaile, &thorn;e folk forto schende,</L>
<L>Roberd gaf him consaile, &thorn;ider samen to wende.</L>
<L>With &thorn;ider &thorn;ei ferd William &amp; Roberd.</L>
<L>Malcolme, whan be it herd, fled for ferd,</L>
<L>&amp; William toke him &thorn;ere, his folk slouh ilk man,</L>
<L>&amp; als &thorn;ei were fleand vnto Louthian,</L>
<L>So ferd thei him found, &thorn;ei obliged &thorn;am to gyue,</L>
<L>Fourti &thorn;ousand pound, at his pes to lyue.</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;at he suore, to hold of him his fe,</L>
<L>&amp; or William fore, tok homage &amp; feaute.</L>
<L>To London William turnes, &amp; had alle his wille,</L>
<L>&amp; Malcolme soiornes in Scotland with ille.</L>
<L>Whan he was at London, a haule<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Concerning which I find a very remarkable Passage in Rastall's Chronicle, together with a Note about the first coming of the Cistercian Monks into England, which others refer to the Reign of King Hen. I. The Book being, as I have before noted, extremely scarce, I shall give the Passage at large from Mr. Murray's Copy.</I> &para; The. iiii. yere of his rayne a great wynde was in London &verbar; that blewe downe. v. c. howses and the rofe of Bowe churche &verbar; &amp; dyd great hurte in wynchester and in dyuers other places. In this tyme also the welchemen re|bellyd &verbar; but they were sub|dued &amp; theyr duke or kyng called Ryse was slayne which was accompted the last kynge of wales. After that Malcolyn kyng of Scot|tes rebellyd and came into Englande with<NOTE PLACE="marg">The kyng of his Scottes slayn.</NOTE> retenewe &verbar; whome one Ro|bert erle of Northumberlande inconter|yd &verbar; &amp; there the kyng Mal|colyn was slayne &verbar; and by the ayde of kyng wyllyam Edgare his son was made kynge of Scotlande. &para; A|bout this tyme the order of Cysteaux was fyrst brought into Englande &verbar; by one wa|ter Espeke that founded the fyrst Abbey of that Religyon at Ryuall. &para; This kynge wyllyam was a very couetous man &verbar; a proude &amp; wylfull &verbar; and pylled bothe the spery|tualte &amp; temperalte &verbar; with sellynge of Bysshoprykes &verbar; Abbeys &verbar; &amp; benefyces &verbar; and leuyenge vnresonable taxes &amp; trybutes on the temperalte &verbar; specially by the onely coun|sell of one Ranulphe hys pro|curatour. whiche ryches the kynge dyd spende vpon the Towre of London &verbar; &amp; some say vpon the makynge of westmyster halle: but yf that sayenge be trewe of westmy|ster halle &verbar; it must be some olde halle there &verbar; &amp; nat the newe halle that is nowe. For the armes that appere in the halle that nowe is aswell in the stone worke as in the tymber worke &verbar; be the armes whiche kyng Rycharde the second gaue &verbar; which be. iii. Lyons with the flour delyce quarterly &verbar; &amp; the whyte hart for his badge. For there was neuer kyng of Englande that bare the armes of Fraunce &verbar; whiche be the flour delyce &verbar; before kyng Edwarde the thyrde &verbar; for in his tyme the armes of Fraunce was fyrst ioyned to the armes of Eng|lande. wherfore it shuld seme euydently that westmyster halle that is nowe &verbar; was nat bylde in the tyme of kynge wyllyam Rufus &verbar; except it were onely the foundacyon therof &verbar; or els it was the halle in westmyster aboue the steyres &verbar; which is nowe called the whyte halle. <I>Stowe tells us (in his Survey of Lon|don, p.</I> 521. <I>Ed. fol.</I> 1633.) <I>that this Hall was repaired by K. Rich. II. which will recon|cile what is observ'd by Rastall about the Arms.</I></NOTE> he did vp wright.</L>
<L>First &thorn;ouht &amp; founden, for chambre was it right.
<PB REF="00000317.tif" N="89"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ROBERD leue has taken, &amp; went to Normundie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Robertus applicuit in Nor|maniam.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Wales is William schaken, estres to spie.</L>
<L>It felle in tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere, at Saynt Brice feste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he had regned here nyen &yogh;ere at &thorn;e meste,
<PB REF="00000318.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>Ros in Northumberland suilk a sorow hard,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE>Malcolcolme &yogh;ede robband, &amp; his sonne Edward.</L>
<L>&thorn;at herd an erle Roberd, he &yogh;ared him to bataile</L>
<L>With Malcolme &amp; Edward, he gan &thorn;am assaile.</L>
<L>&thorn;at bataile was hard, fo men has no frith,</L>
<L>Slayn was &thorn;at coward, &amp; his sonne him with.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e folk that ascaped on Malcolme side,</L>
<L>To Scotland &thorn;am raped, &amp; puplised it fulle wide.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei mad parlement, &amp; toke &thorn;am to rede.</L>
<L>Malcolme to God was went, &amp; Edward his sonne dede,</L>
<L>&amp; corouned Dufoald, Sir Malcolme bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>His sonnes &thorn;ei ne wald, &thorn;e ton no &thorn;e to&thorn;er.</L>
<L>&para; Of Malcome &thorn;at man left tuo sonnes ware,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De contu|melia Scot|torum, &amp; de dominio &amp; potestate Angli&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e ton hight Dunkan, &thorn;e to&thorn;er Edgare.</L>
<L>Dunkan sauh his eam had his heritage,</L>
<L>&thorn;er he wist bote of beam, he went &thorn;at viage</L>
<L>To William &thorn;e rede kyng, &thorn;er he was in Wales.</L>
<L>What tid of &thorn;at &thorn;ing, he told him alle &thorn;e tales.</L>
<L>"Myn heritage I craue of &thorn;e, &thorn;at is my heued.</L>
<L>"Help me it to haue, &thorn;at Dufnald has me reued.</L>
<L>With scrite vnto William Sir Dunkan him bond,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e heirs &thorn;at of him cam, for &thorn;e coroune of Scotlond.</L>
<L>Inglis &amp; Normans &thorn;e kyng did somoune,</L>
<L>To wend with Sir Dunkan, &amp; do Dufnald doune,</L>
<L>&amp; seise Dunkan &thorn;er in, als heyr of heritage,</L>
<L>To hold &amp; alle his kyn of Inglond for homage.</L>
<L>Whan corouned was Dunkan, &amp; &thorn;e fest ent,</L>
<L>Inglis &amp; Norman to kyng William went.
<PB REF="00000319.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>Dufnald, &thorn;at is put oute, alle about wendes</L>
<L>In fele stedes aboute, &amp; gadres his frendes,</L>
<L>&amp; conseiled with &thorn;am &thorn;is cas, &thorn;at alle suld &thorn;ei go,</L>
<L>&amp; spie where &thorn;e kyng was, Dunkan if he mot slo.</L>
<L>Slayn haf &thorn;ei Dunkan, &amp; eft corouned Dufnald,</L>
<L>Of kyng William wild &thorn;ei no more hald.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng was in affray, he might not tent &thorn;erto</L>
<L>With Roberd &thorn;e Moubray, his coroune he wild for do.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Contumelia orta est in|ter Regem &amp; Rober|tum Mou|bray.</NOTE></L>
<L>Roberd wild haf reft William alle his right,</L>
<L>&thorn;e coroune his kosyn left, &amp; gif it him &thorn;orgh myght.</L>
<L>William is war of &thorn;is, &thorn;orgh for Roberd he &thorn;retis,</L>
<L>&amp; takes him maugre his, his kastelle doun betis.</L>
<L>Better were Roberd, in pes haf holden him stille,</L>
<L>&thorn;an layn in prison sperd, &amp; at his fomen wille.</L>
<L>In Wyndesouere is he leued, sorow &thorn;an is his pyne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wis ouer his heued, &thorn;e chip falles in his ine.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e next &yogh;ere &thorn;er bi William to Wales went,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Walsch men did foli, his lond robbed &amp; brent.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor William ne wold vnne&thorn;is leue on o lyue,</L>
<L>&thorn;at bo&thorn;e &yogh;ong &amp; old alle &yogh;ede to &thorn;e kryue.</L>
<L>Neuer bifor in Wales was don so grete greue,</L>
<L>Bi dounes &amp; bi dales, &thorn;ar folk at suilk mischeue.</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;is greuance hard, &thorn;e slauhter &amp; &thorn;e drede,</L>
<L>Fulle sone afterward &thorn;e kyng to &yogh;ork &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&thorn;ider com Edgar, was Malcolme sonne,</L>
<L>&amp; Sir Dunkan bro&thorn;er, &thorn;at slayn was &thorn;orgh tresonne,</L>
<L>&amp; schewed to William, &thorn;at heyre he was of kynde,</L>
<L>Of Malcolme he kam, righter salle non fynde.
<PB REF="00000320.tif" N="92"></L>
<L>"Wherfor I &yogh;ow biseke, help me &thorn;e lond to haue,</L>
<L>"&amp; I with wille fulle meke &yogh;our seruise salle I saue.</L>
<L>William vnderstode, &thorn;at he said reson,</L>
<L>&amp; was next of blode, &amp; Dufnald did treson.</L>
<L>He dight an oste fulle stoute with Edgar forto leue,</L>
<L>Dufnald to dryue oute, or his hede him reue.</L>
<L>Eustace of Ferers &thorn;at oste suld guye,</L>
<L>Of Scotland &thorn;ei him brouht, Dufdald forto spie,</L>
<L>&amp; seised Edgar in alle, as right was &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>To William for &thorn;e regalle he did &thorn;at he suld do.</L>
<L>Edgar &amp; his peres &thorn;e chaced day bi day,</L>
<L>Of Scotland &thorn;ei him brouht for euer, &amp; drof away.</L>
<L>Edgar was Malde's bro&thorn;er, men kald &thorn;e gode quene,</L>
<L>&yogh;it sais on &amp; o&thorn;er, so gode has here non bene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN William had his wille of Scotland &amp; of Wales,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Ingrati|tudine Wil|lelmi.</NOTE></L>
<L>To riche men was he grille, of pouer held no tales.</L>
<L>Clerkes of holy kirke he chargis greuosly,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei were bisie &amp; irke on &thorn;er rentes to lyue by.</L>
<L>Of alle his wikked werkes &thorn;ese me &thorn;ouht &thorn;e meste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at seuenten kirkes he mad tille his<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>This was the</I> new Forest near Winchester, <I>which was really made by his Father King Wil|liam the Conqueror, who de|stroyed many Churches for it, and his Son. William Rufus was only an Improver of it, by en|larging it, in which he com|mitted also much Sacrilege. But then others (and even Peter of Langtoft and Robert of Brunne themselves seem to have been of the same opinion) tell us, that this was not the</I> New Fo|rest near Winchester, <I>but the</I> New Forest of Windsor, <I>a|mong which is John Rastall, who writes thus:</I> This kynge wyllyam as is sayd &amp; wryt|ten of hym &verbar; had great plea|sure in huntynge &verbar; in so moche that he pulled downe &amp; di|stroyed dyuers houses of re|ligyon to inlarge the newe forest of wyndesore for wylde dere: but a knyght of his named water Tyrell by the glaunsyng of his arowe vpon a braunche whan he shot at an harte in the sayd forest &verbar; smote the kyng &amp; wounded hym to dethe wherof shortely he dyed. The fyrst day of August the yere of Chryst. M.C. without any yssue of his body. And he rayned. xii. yere. xi. monethes and. xii. dayes &verbar; and is buryed at westmyster. <I>In which Passage this is also remarkable, that he makes William Rufus to be buried at Westminster, as does also the Chronicle I now pub|lish, whereas it is well known, from our other Historians, that he was buried at Winches|ter. And indeed it is</I> Win|chester <I>in the French Original of Peter Langtoft.</I> Le cors a Wyncestre fet leuesque por|ter, et mettre le en toumbe, al monster seint Peer.</NOTE> foreste,
<PB REF="00000321.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer ere non was sen &thorn;e Cristendam.</L>
<L>He did grete trespas of holy kirke so nam.</L>
<L>Wele tuelue &yogh;ere kept he &thorn;is lond,</L>
<L>&amp; how he died here selcouthly I fond.</L>
<L>&amp; if &yogh;e wille lithe, I salle telle it &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>His dede com him suythe meruellosly, se how.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON a Thurday at nyght at euen he &yogh;ede to reste,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Willelmi Rufi, &amp; de visione ante mortem.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hunte &thorn;er he had tight in his new foreste.</L>
<L>On slepe sone he felle, &thorn;e sueuen bifor him ran,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;ouht in his chapelle he was withouten man,</L>
<L>Ne non he sauh no herd, &amp; he biheld aboute,</L>
<L>&thorn;e dures were so sperd, he myght in no stede oute.</L>
<L>So grete hunger him cam, &amp; mete had he none,</L>
<L>Ne he ne wist to wham, &thorn;at he mot mak his mone.
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>His hunger was so grete, he wend haf waxen wode,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e rode he schete, &amp; ete it als it stode.</L>
<L>Whan be had eten &thorn;at, &yogh;it him hungred eft,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Mariole &thorn;er scho sat, of hir no &thorn;ing he left.</L>
<L>Whan he was turned, &amp; went out of &thorn;at affray,</L>
<L>For a bisshop he sent at morn whan it was day,</L>
<L>Sir Ode of Wynchestere, so &thorn;at bisshop hight,</L>
<L>He told him of allc &thorn;e estere, &thorn;at him mette &thorn;at nyght.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop gan it rede, "God is &thorn;e turned grym,</L>
<L>"Ou&thorn;er in word or dede has &thorn;ou greued him.</L>
<L>"&thorn;erfor alle &thorn;at &thorn;ou may to penance take &thorn;ou space,</L>
<L>"&thorn;au neuer on Friday to wod &thorn;ou go to chace.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e riuer salle &thorn;ou forsake on Friday ilka dele.</L>
<L>"&thorn;at penance I &thorn;e take, Sir kyng, &thorn;ou kepe it wele.</L>
<L>Sir Ode &thorn;e bisshop es with leue went him fro,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng herd his messe, to gamen &thorn;an wild he go.</L>
<L>His penance was forgeten, he asked for his archere,</L>
<L>Walter Tirelle was haten, maister of &thorn;at mister.</L>
<L>To triste was he sette, forto waite &thorn;e chance,</L>
<L>With a herde &thorn;ei mette, a herte &thorn;erof gan lance.</L>
<L>Walter was redi, he wend haf schoten &thorn;e herte,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng stode ouer nehi, &thorn;e stroke he lauht so smerte.</L>
<L>&thorn;us died William &thorn;e kyng, on &thorn;is ilk manere.</L>
<L>Sir Ode herd &thorn;at ti&thorn;ing, fulle mournand was his chere.</L>
<L>At Westminstre is he laid, at Saynt Petir kirke,</L>
<L>In a toumbe purtraid, &thorn;e bisshop did it wirke.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date a &thorn;ousand was, &amp; a hundreth mo,</L>
<L>Forgif him his trespas, Jhesu, &thorn;at lete &thorn;e slo.
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="95"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;AT tyme in Scotland was a mayden &yogh;eng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Matil|da bona Regina.</NOTE></L>
<L>As I red biforhand, Malcolme douhter &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>Malde hight &thorn;at mayden, many of hir spak.</L>
<L>Fair scho was, &thorn;ei saiden, &amp; gode withouten lak.</L>
<L>A doughter had Saynt Margrete, &thorn;at in Scotland lis.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at douhter sute com Malde, &thorn;at was of pris,</L>
<L>&amp; Dunkan &amp; Edgar, &thorn;at I red biforn,</L>
<L>Malde's bre&thorn;er &thorn;ei war, of Margrete douhter born.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER William men cald &thorn;e rede kyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Henri|co primo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Henry &thorn;e coroun nam, his bro&thorn;er &thorn;at was &yogh;ing.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop Maurice Henry corouned he,</L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme he did &thorn;e office, of London kept &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>Roberd &thorn;e Courthose to &thorn;e holy lond was went.</L>
<L>A Breton (dayet his `his<NOTE PLACE="foot">F. delend.</NOTE> nose) for Roberd &thorn;ider sent.</L>
<L>A Breton sent &thorn;at sond, he did for treson,</L>
<L>&amp; Roberd com to lond, withouten o&thorn;er reson.</L>
<L>&thorn;at did Roberd trauaile for nouht, he was a file.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles &thorn;e erle of Cornwaile kept his wife &thorn;at while,</L>
<L>Charles douhter scho lord of Cezile,</L>
<L>Dame Edith bright as glas; Roberd &thorn;ouht no gile,</L>
<L>Bot com on gode manere tille his bro&thorn;er Henry.</L>
<L>He wife &thorn;at soiorned here, he led to Normundie.</L>
<L>&para; Henry wedded dame Molde, &thorn;at kyng was &amp; sire.</L>
<L>Saynt Anselme men tolde corouned him &amp; hire.</L>
<L>&thorn;e corounyng of Henry, &amp; of Malde &thorn;at may,</L>
<L>At London was solemply on S. Martyn's day.
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="96"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE bisshop of Durham,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> Randolf.</NOTE> Kandolf he hight,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De falsitate episcopi Dunelmen|sis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of falshede to mak a gleam, &thorn;e wrong vnto &thorn;e right.</L>
<L>For he &amp; o&thorn;er fele sent vnto Roberd,</L>
<L>&thorn;at stound suld he not spele, sen he &thorn;at tiyng herd.</L>
<L>Roberd purueid him stille, &amp; com whan he wild.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e folk is alle in wille, &thorn;e lond &thorn;e to &yogh;eld.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh messengers fals Roberd gadred oste.</L>
<L>Henry was warned als, &amp; did kepe &thorn;e coste.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e fiue portes he sent, &amp; het &thorn;am in couenant,</L>
<L>&thorn;at aliens suld non hent hauen of Normant.</L>
<L>&thorn;er sikernes was fast of &thorn;e fiue portes, &amp; &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>Henry dight him on haste to &thorn;e toun of Hastyng.</L>
<L>A kastelle did vp sette, his oste longe &thorn;er lay.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei wend Roberde's flette suld haf comen bi &thorn;at way.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e bisshop &thorn;ouht treson, for warned was Henry.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De tradi|tione Epi|scopi.</NOTE></L>
<L>He went to Southampton, with him alle his clergy.</L>
<L>&thorn;e maistres of &thorn;e portes for gyftes tille him toke,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &amp; his force for Roberd &thorn;ei forsoke.</L>
<L>A hundreth schippes &amp; fiftene went to Normundie,</L>
<L>To help &amp; to mayntene &thorn;e duke Roberde's partie.</L>
<L>Roberd mad him alle preste, &thorn;e wynde gan him dryue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e first day of herueste at Portesmouth gan he ryue.</L>
<L>Toward Wynchestre &thorn;am dight, his folk forto eyse,</L>
<L>In token &thorn;at he had myght, a kastelle he did reyse.</L>
<L>To erles &amp; barons lettres he sent aboute.</L>
<L>For riche rewardons to Roberd gan loute.</L>
<L>Fulle fele suilk he fond, &thorn;at with Roberd held,</L>
<L>Of Inglis of &thorn;is lond agayn Henry bare scheld.
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="97"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ROBERD bi his letter his bro&thorn;er gan diffie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Ro|berto Courthose duce Nor|manni&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Him &thorn;ouht his partie better, of him to haf maistrie.</L>
<L>Bot gode Anselme, &thorn;at kept of Canterbirie &thorn;e see,</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e barons lept, kried, pes per charite.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh conseile of Anselme, &thorn;at wild &thorn;e comon prowe,</L>
<L>Ilk auailed his helme, &amp; to conseile drowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e parties were fulle stark, neuerlesse &thorn;orgh praiere,</L>
<L>Henry &thorn;re &thorn;ousand mark gaf to Roberd bi &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;us gate was &thorn;at werre pesed, withouten lore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at noi&thorn;er partie com nerre, I blisse Anselme &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L>In couenant of pes, men may wele witen,</L>
<L>Bituex &thorn;am no&thorn;eles a skrite enselid &amp; writen.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De pace facta per Ansel|mum, archi|episcopum Cantuari&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Als Anselme &thorn;e strif gan pes, of &thorn;e duke &amp; &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>Com Roberd de Beleyse, &thorn;orgh his ouerwenyng,</L>
<L>&amp; passed hider ouer &thorn;e se, &amp; in to Wales went,</L>
<L>He gadred grete mayne of alle &thorn;at he mot hent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Frankis tille him felle, &amp; alle &thorn;e Walsch fulle fikelle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kastelle Arondelle he seised, &amp; als of Tikelle.</L>
<L>Cites, burghes &amp; tounes ageyn kyng Henry</L>
<L>At Burgh in Schrobschire to werre mad him redy.</L>
<L>Alle Schobschire held with Roberd de Beleyse,</L>
<L>Henry lift vp scheld, his kastels did he sayse.</L>
<L>&thorn;e walles did doun felle, &thorn;e tours bette he doun.</L>
<L>In &thorn;ritty daies to telle, Roberd was taken in toun.</L>
<L>Within dayes &thorn;ritty taken he was &thorn;orgh spie,</L>
<L>&amp; led to kyng Henry, don had he felonie,</L>
<L>&amp; his bro&thorn;er Arnald, (for with Roberd he fore,)</L>
<L>As for traytours bald &thorn;e lond bo&thorn;e forsuore.
<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="98"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Henry venged of his traytours,</L>
<L>&amp; lord of mykelle &thorn;ing, &amp; riche man of tresours.</L>
<L>Mald &thorn;e gode quene gaf him in conseile,</L>
<L>To luf his folk bituene, &amp; leue alle his tirpeile,</L>
<L>Bere him tille his barons, &thorn;at held of him &thorn;er fees,</L>
<L>&amp; to lordes of tounes, tille burgeis of Citees.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh counseile of dame Malde, a kynde woman &amp; trewe,</L>
<L>&thorn;er ore was hatred alde, now gynnes luf alle newe.</L>
<L>Now luf &thorn;ei fulle wele &thorn;e barons &amp; &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng dos ilk a dele in skille alle &thorn;er biddyng.</L>
<L>&para; Bot Henry &thorn;ink it stark, &thorn;at he is charged so,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de Henrico.</NOTE></L>
<L>To gyue &thorn;re &thorn;ousand mark, &amp; bonden be &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh conseile of his barons, he sent to duke Roberd.</L>
<L>What was his respons writen, I ne sauh no herd.</L>
<L>Tuo gentille men of blode, &thorn;e best of Normundie,</L>
<L>Henry gaf gyftes gode, to hold on his partie.</L>
<L>Whan Henry wist &thorn;er wille, bi messengers priue,</L>
<L>An oste he purueid stille, &amp; passed ouer &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>He &thorn;ouht to compas ille &thorn;e same tille him did he.</L>
<L>Now salle Roberd fulfille, &thorn;at he tok in his cuntre.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Henry was ryued &thorn;er, &thorn;er he wild ame,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh power did he dryue Roberd out of Kame,</L>
<L>Bayone rent &amp; fe sone had he lorn,</L>
<L>&thorn;e best of &thorn;at cuntre tille &thorn;e kyng wer suorn.</L>
<L>Roberd fele si&thorn;es at &thorn;at comyng les</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e londes &amp; li&thorn;es, or he mot haf &thorn;e pes.</L>
<L>If he ne were &thorn;orgh help of William de Martayn,</L>
<L>&amp; Roberd de Beleyse halp him with myght &amp; mayn.
<PB REF="00000327.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>&thorn;ise tuo went to France, &amp; fonden at Parys,</L>
<L>Als it was &thorn;ar gode chance, Sir Philip sonne Lowys.</L>
<L>For Roberd &thorn;ei bisouht of socour &amp; mercie,</L>
<L>Sir Lowys failed nouht, his help was him redie.</L>
<L>Lowys wrote his letter vnto &thorn;e kyng Henry,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei acorded better, for his luf specially.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Parys &thorn;e pes &thorn;an formed he,</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ei at his auys bo&thorn;e wild paied be,</L>
<L>"Roberd salle cleyme all quite to Henry bifor vs here,</L>
<L>"&thorn;re &thorn;ousand mark be skrite &thorn;e Henry gaf bi &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at Roberd, ne non of hise, salle ask Henry &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>"&thorn;is dette on non wise, peny no fer&thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN &thorn;is barette was ent, &thorn;e bisshop tok his leue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Recessit de Norman|nia.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; Henry home went, to no mo wild he greue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e londes wild he nouht &yogh;eld, &thorn;at he of Roberd wan,</L>
<L>Bot haf &thorn;am he wilde, &amp; hold for any man.</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;at Henry was gone, Roberd went to France</L>
<L>To Sir Lowys on one, &amp; told him &thorn;at greuance:</L>
<L>&amp; Sir Lowys &thorn;erfore bad him tille Ingland go,</L>
<L>To praye Henry restore &thorn;o tounes he tok him fro.</L>
<L>Roberd tille Ingland kam, &amp; bisouht &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>&thorn;o fees he fro him nam, restore ageyn &thorn;at &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Henry ansuerd nay, &thorn;erto were him lothe.</L>
<L>&amp; Roberd went<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> away.</NOTE> awith, with William was he wrothe.</L>
<L>Whan he sauh, &thorn;at Roberd for wroth turned so sone,</L>
<L>&amp; no &thorn;ing ansuerd, bot to wend was alle bone,</L>
<L>Henry mad him &yogh;are, &amp; after him fulle sui&thorn;e</L>
<L>To Normundie to fare, &amp; se what he wild ki&thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000328.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>&amp; duelled &thorn;er a &yogh;ere biside Roberd his bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&thorn;at noi&thorn;er werre wo did &thorn;e ton to &thorn;e to&thorn;er.</L>
<L>&para; In alle &thorn;is ilk chek of Roberd &amp; Henry,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Iterum re|versus est in Nor|manniam.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bituex &thorn;am wex contek, &thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;e clergy.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng in &thorn;e courte of &thorn;e lay &thorn;e clerkes wild justise.</L>
<L>Saynt Anselm said him nay, he wild on no wise.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng on gan hald, to haf &thorn;am at his dome.</L>
<L>S. Anselm &thorn;erfor appeld vnto &thorn;e courte of Rome.</L>
<L>&para; Whan he had sped his nedis, &amp; fro &thorn;e courte comen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Dicta An|selmi pro clero.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng for o&thorn;er dedis to Normundie was nomen.</L>
<L>Anselm duelled nouht, bot sone ouer &thorn;e se</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng ti&thorn;ing brouht, what &thorn;erof suld be.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop schewed him skille, &thorn;at he mayntend &thorn;e ille.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng consented &thorn;er tille, &amp; gaf Anselm his wille.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh Anselm maytenyng was &thorn;e contek ent.</L>
<L>He tok leue at &thorn;e kyng, &amp; home to Inglond went.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng his retenanz alle tille him he drouh</L>
<L>Of Inglis &amp; Normanz, &amp; gadred folk inouh.</L>
<L>Whan he had samned his oste of folk fer &amp; nere,</L>
<L>He seged bi &thorn;at coste &thorn;e kastelle of Tenkere.</L>
<L>Whilom Wiliam Mortayn &thorn;erof lord was,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Courthose is vnfayn, him &thorn;enk it a trespas.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor &thorn;e duke him dight, as man of grete value,</L>
<L>Roberd Beleyse with myght, &thorn;e sege &thorn;ei wend remue.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De cap|cione Roberti Courthose fratris Hen|rici, &amp; de fine ejus|dem Ro|berti vide per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Mortayn befor spoken, with his nevow Reynere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e sege &thorn;e wend haf broken, &thorn;ei com with &thorn;er powere.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng sauh &thorn;at &thorn;ei kam, his trompes did he blowe,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bataile he nam, Roberd side &yogh;ede lowe.
<PB REF="00000329.tif" N="101"></L>
<L>Roberd side &yogh;ede doun, for he bitrayed was.</L>
<L>His owen men did treson, &thorn;e kyng him tok, allas!</L>
<L>Now taken is Roberd, &amp; brouht vnto prison,</L>
<L>At Corue his kastelle sperd depe in a dongeon.</L>
<L>William &thorn;e Mortayn he skapes with no gile,</L>
<L>Fettered he is certayn Roberd of Stoteuile.</L>
<L>&amp; Sir William Crispyn with &thorn;e duke was led,</L>
<L>Togider prisoned in &yogh;eres &amp; dayes &thorn;am fed</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &thorn;am &thorn;er in mete &amp; cloth inouh,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer &thorn;ei were o twynne, vntille ded &thorn;am slouh.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OFTEN I haf herd told of &thorn;is duke Roberd,</L>
<L>So gode knyght no so bold was non in alle &thorn;e werld,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyn &thorn;e Sarazins in bataile forto go,</L>
<L>Now he ligges in pynes, sorow wille him slo.</L>
<L>Why felle him suilk chance, &amp; &thorn;is ilk mishap?</L>
<L>For of Gode's ordinance he forsoke &thorn;e schap.</L>
<L>Gode's grace he forsoke for &yogh;ernyng of &thorn;is lond.</L>
<L>Vengeance &thorn;erfor he tok at his endyng he fond.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> Corue. <I>Others say Caer|diff in South_Wales. See what is said about his death in p.</I> 426, 443. <I>of Rob. of Glouc. To which may be here added, that as nei|ther Robert of Gloucester, nor the Chronicle of Peter Lantoft</I> (<I>that I now publish</I>) <I>say, that Robert Duke of Normandy's Eyes were pulled out, so neither does John Rastall say any thing of that matter, as well knowing</I> (<I>and Sir Tho. More too had told him the truth of that part of our History</I>) <I>that the Story was not vouch'd by such Historians, as came nearest to Duke Ro|bert's time. But I shall put down the Words of Rastall at large, because they will give some light to the Reader as he is perusing this work of Peter Langtoft.</I> &para; In the seconde yere of his [<I>Hen. the First's</I>] reygne Robert Courteyse his brother duke of Normandye &verbar; whiche had ben longe tyme oc|cupyed in warre agaynst Chrys|tes enemyes hauynge worde of the dethe of his brother wyl|lyam Rufus &verbar; and that his brother henry had takyn vp|on hym to be kynge of Eng|lande &verbar; made preparacyon in Normandye and came ouer into Englande with a great hoost to chalenge the crowne. But by mediacyon of the lordes &verbar; it was agreed that Robert shulde haue euery yere durynge his life. iii. M. markes &verbar; as was promysed hym before by kynge wyl|lyam his brother. And who so euer lyued longest to be others heyre. And sone after that &verbar; this Robert departed agayne into Normandye. This Robert by his man|hode &verbar; dyd many notable actes &verbar; and specially at the wynnynge of the citye of A|con vpon the myscreantes &amp; Turkes &verbar; and was chosyn kynge of Jerusalem &verbar; whiche he refused to take vpon him. In this tyme began great warre in Normandye be|twene kyng Henry &amp; kynge Philyp of Fraunce &verbar; but kyng Philyp sone after dyed. &para; About the. iiii. yere of this kyng &verbar; Robert Curteyse came into England agayne &verbar; to his brother henry whiche made hym great chere that before that Robert departed &verbar; he released to his brother the forenamed trybute of. iii. M. markes &verbar; &amp; departed agayne into Normandye. After this a great varyaunce fell be|twene this Robert and his lordes in Normandye that they sent vnto kyng henry his brother wyllynge for to come into Normandye &verbar; &amp; they wolde delyuer hym the contrey. And also by the intyssement of yll tale tellers &verbar; a great va|ryaunce fell betwene kynge henry &amp; his<NOTE PLACE="marg">battel in Norman|dye.</NOTE> brother Robert &verbar; that the kynge with a great armye sayled into Normandye &verbar; &amp; with the helpe of the lordes there &verbar; chased his brother Ro|bert from place to place &verbar; and wanne from hym Roan &verbar; Cane &verbar; Faloys &verbar; and all the good townes &amp; many castels. But at the last this Robert gaue battell to kynge hen|ry &verbar; in the whiche battell this Ro|bert<NOTE PLACE="marg">duke Ro|bert taken prisoner.</NOTE> was takyn and sent ouer into Englande &verbar; and kept in prison in the ca|stell of Cardiffe in walys &verbar; by the space of. xxviii. yere where he after dyed without yssue of his body &verbar; and was buryed at Gloucester. And when this Robert was tak|yn &verbar; the kynge Henry seasyd alle Normandye into his owne handes.</NOTE> Coue is Roberd dede, &thorn;e maner of his endyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce, heu! dicta God|fridi de Bo|lyon de Ro|berto Cour|those.</NOTE></L>
<L>My boke it me forbede to telle &thorn;erof no &thorn;ing.
<PB REF="00000330.tif" N="102">
<PB REF="00000331.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>A hardy knyght was he, ouer all bare &thorn;e pris,</L>
<L>At Jerusalem Cite, opon Gode's enmys.</L>
<L>Godferay Bolion said, that many man it herd,</L>
<L>"More my triste is laid on &thorn;e duke Roberd,</L>
<L>"&amp; I had grete nede ageyn &thorn;e Sarazines to go,</L>
<L>"&amp; better suld he spede &thorn;an a hundreth mo.</L>
<L>"Take him &thorn;e kepyng &thorn;e coroun of Jerusalem,</L>
<L>"For seke is the kyng, of him is no bote of beem.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e &thorn;rid day of Aduent, bifor Criste's messe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce quo|modo Ro|bertus de|spexit gra|ciam &amp; e|lectionem Dei.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng a seknes hent, &thorn;e dede him tok alle fresse.</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk of &thorn;at Cite to God mad orisoun,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e temple <I>domin&aelig;</I> with gode deuocioun,</L>
<L>Who &thorn;an were wor&thorn;i &thorn;e coroune forto haue,</L>
<L>Ageyn &thorn;e paemy &thorn;e Cristendam to saue,</L>
<L>Godfrey &amp; Roberd, &amp; lered men &amp; lewed,</L>
<L>&amp; God &thorn;er praieres herd, &amp; to &thorn;am alle schewed.</L>
<L>A brightnesse com fro heuen, &amp; on Roberd light,</L>
<L>&thorn;re tymes alle euen, &thorn;at alle sauh it with sight.</L>
<L>&thorn;ris &thorn;at alle mot se &thorn;e light on Roberd toke,</L>
<L>Vngracious man was he, &thorn;ris he it forsoke.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh conseile of som of hise, refused he &thorn;at present,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei said, on o&thorn;er wise he salle haf auancement.
<PB REF="00000332.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>Godfrey was oglift, to Roberd spak fulle tite,</L>
<L>"Withouten any essoyne, vengeance salle falle &thorn;e not lite.</L>
<L>"Forsakes &thorn;ou Gode's gyft, &thorn;ou dos him grete despite.</L>
<L>&thorn;us sayd Godfrey of Bolyon, his hert was fulle of site.</L>
<L>Forsoth vengeance he fond, of Criste &thorn;e grace he les.</L>
<L>For couetise of &thorn;is lond, his mischene he ches.</L>
<L>Of Roberd is no speyre to mak of parlement.</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er Henry is heyre of alle his tenement,</L>
<L>Of alle Normundie, withouten geynsayng,</L>
<L>Als heyr of ancestrie, Henry seysed &thorn;at &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SONE &thorn;an was it told vnto &thorn;e kyng of France,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Roberd lif was sold &thorn;orgh treson &amp; mischance.</L>
<L>Whan Lowys herd &thorn;at sawe, &thorn;at Roberd was so dede,</L>
<L>Ageyn right &amp; lawe, tille Henry he misbede.</L>
<L>For traytours of men Inglis to Lowys &thorn;am bond,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei hight him forto wisse, how he mot haf &thorn;is lond.</L>
<L>He trowed to &thorn;er conseile, at Douere he gan vp ryue,</L>
<L>It had bien wro&thorn;erheile, if he ne had went belyue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's kosyn Thebaut, &amp; Randolf Gobion,</L>
<L>To gyf Lowys assaut, samned at Chilyngton.</L>
<L>Of Wales &thorn;ei had inowe, &thorn;at Sir Lowys gan chace,</L>
<L>&amp; of his men &thorn;am slowe, to rest &thorn;ei had no space.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e se side chaced &thorn;ei Sir Lowys,</L>
<L>He durst not abide, no turne Thebald his vis.</L>
<L>To schip ilkon &thorn;ei went, fulle on lond leued.</L>
<L>Mot &thorn;ei Lowys hent, he suld haf lorn his heued.
<PB REF="00000333.tif" N="105"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN Henry herd telle &thorn;is of &thorn;at gode cheuysance,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Matild filia Hen|rici regis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of `of<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dele.</NOTE> &thorn;e to&thorn;er Inglis, &thorn;at conseild Lowys of France,</L>
<L>&thorn;at suld haf bien his owen, &amp; mad &thorn;e chance ouer grim,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ei wer fulle wele knowen, &thorn;at wild haf tresond him,</L>
<L>How Gobion was certeyn, Thebaut his neuow stoute,</L>
<L>Turned Lowys ageyn, of lond &thorn;ei chaced him oute,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en with grete nobley, &amp; with mykelle honoure,</L>
<L>Henry toke his way toward &thorn;e Emperoure,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Emperour of Almayn his douhter to gyue.</L>
<L>Malde hight &thorn;at mayden, a fayrer mot non lyue.</L>
<L>&thorn;at mayden moder hight Mald &thorn;e gode quene,</L>
<L>Lady to maynten right sen sho was has non bene.</L>
<L>Now has kyng Henry, &thorn;orgh &thorn;is weddyng,</L>
<L>Grete power &amp; party ageyns a lordyng.</L>
<L>&para; Now Henry kyng leue nam at &thorn;e Emperour Henry,</L>
<L>&amp; his sonne William, &amp; went to Normundy.</L>
<L>He gaf William his sonne with skrite &amp; `f<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic. Sed</I> f. <I>delend. est.</I></NOTE> seele fulle fre</L>
<L>To hold, als it was wonne, alle Normundie in fe.</L>
<L>To Thebaud of Plesance left with him of his meyne,</L>
<L>&amp; vntille Inglond eft he turned ouer &thorn;e se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN his seuentend &yogh;ere &thorn;at he regned kyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Matildis Regin&aelig; bon&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Malde &thorn;e quene his pere in God scho did endyng.</L>
<L>At London at Saynt Poule's in toumbe is scho laid,</L>
<L>Criste &thorn;an haf hir soule meusk of hir men said.</L>
<L>If any man wille witen, &amp; se of hir storie,</L>
<L>At Westmynster written er &thorn;ei redilie.
<PB REF="00000334.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>&para; Now es &thorn;e kyng sory, hir dede dos him fulle gram,</L>
<L>He gos to Normundy to his sonne William.</L>
<L>Tuo &yogh;ere he wonnes, &amp; faire courte &thorn;er held,</L>
<L>Untille bo&thorn;e his sonnes &thorn;er moder dede he teld.</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e &thorn;rid &yogh;ere &thorn;e kyng to Inglond went,</L>
<L>His sonnes &amp; &thorn;er powere a no&thorn;er tide &thorn;ei hent.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei toke a no&thorn;er tide, allas! it was ouer hard,</L>
<L>&amp; dronkled bi &thorn;e se side bo&thorn;e William &amp; Richard.</L>
<L>Tuo erles &amp; &thorn;er wyues with &thorn;am dronkled were,</L>
<L>&amp; many o&thorn;er lyues in &thorn;e se left &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>William Bigot &thorn;er felle, Roberd Maudut &thorn;at hight,</L>
<L>&amp; Sir Geffrey Ridelle, &amp; Othes &thorn;at was his knyght.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise men were of Gode, &thorn;at dronkled alle in fere.</L>
<L>To lyue non ne &yogh;ode, but on was marinere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bodies with &thorn;er godes wer costen vp on &thorn;e sond,</L>
<L>After an ebbe of &thorn;e flode, euer ilkon &thorn;ei fond.</L>
<L>Tuo sonnes were our kyng born, &thorn;at his heires suld be,</L>
<L>&amp; bo&thorn;e ere &thorn;ei lorn, for soth &thorn;at is pite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO lond com &thorn;e kyng, after &thorn;at passage,</L>
<L>With many grete lordyng of his baronage.</L>
<L>Godefrey of Louayn, &thorn;e duke &thorn;at was douhty,</L>
<L>Bi messengers tuayn sent to kyng Henry,</L>
<L>For his douhter Adelayn, &thorn;at wele was &thorn;an of age.</L>
<L>Sir Henry mad &thorn;e fyne, &amp; mad &thorn;e mariage.</L>
<L>&thorn;e may withouten vice, his weddyng was wele dight,</L>
<L>&amp; Malde &thorn;e Emperice is heyre of Henry right.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">Matild im|peratrix vidua.</NOTE>&para; &thorn;e Emperour Henry, &thorn;at Mald has to wyue,</L>
<L>Scho had no child him by Mald in alle his lyue.
<PB REF="00000335.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>&thorn;an died &thorn;e Emperour, Henry for Mald sent</L>
<L>As Emperice with honour, Mald tille Inglond went.</L>
<L>Henry was alle glad of his douhter comyng,</L>
<L>Nouht long si&thorn;en scho had praier for weddyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode erle of Aniowe of Mald herd he say</L>
<L>Fulle richely to trowe, tille tok his way.</L>
<L>He ryued vp at Douere, &amp; dight him eft alle bone,</L>
<L>Whan alle were wele ouere, to London com he sone.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle so wele sped tille our kyng Henry,</L>
<L>&thorn;at his sonne suld wed, &amp; Mald was alle redy.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Emperice was dight, as lady felle to be.</L>
<L>With hir went many a knyght tille Aniowe &thorn;at cuntre.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle &thorn;is lady gent gaf Henry<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>The Author here (as he does also in many other Places) strangely differeth from other Historians, in making Maud the Empress to be married to Henry Son of the Earl of An|jou, when she was really mar|ried (after the Death of the Emperour Henry IV. who was her first husband) to Geffrey Plantagenet Earl of Anjou, son of Foulk King of Jeru|salem. Hence John Rastall (in his most scarce Chronicle) writes thus:</I> &para; About the. xxi. yere [<I>of Hen. I.</I>) there was a great counsell called in Lon|don &verbar; for the correccyon of the vicyous lyuynge of preestes to be done by the kynges offycers. Sone after this Henry the Emperour dyed &verbar; &amp; Maude the empresse came to her father kynge henry &verbar; whiche caused Dauyd the kynge of Scotlande and the more parte of the lordes of Englande to do othe and fealte to the Empresse &verbar; and to kepe the lande to her if the kynge dyed without issue male.</P><P>&para; Also about the, xxviii. yere &verbar; one Geffrey Plantage|net erle of Angeo maryed the sayd Maude and after by her had issue Henry &verbar; whiche henry after kynge Steuyn was kynge of Englande.</P></NOTE> his sonne,</L>
<L>Alle his tenement, &thorn;at his eldres was wonne.
<PB REF="00000336.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e fader had ent alle at his auys,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e holy lond he went, &amp; died on Gode's enmys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HENRY his sonne &amp; Molde, &thorn;at held &thorn;e seignorie,</L>
<L>A sonne &thorn;ei had fulle bolde, &amp; his name Henrie.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en had &thorn;ei a no&thorn;er, &thorn;at &thorn;ei cald William,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was Henry bro&thorn;er, bo&thorn;e of Mald cam.</L>
<L>Hir fader &thorn;e kyng loued &thorn;o childre so,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wild for no &thorn;ing &thorn;e sight of &thorn;am forgo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E kyng went at the last vnto Normundie,</L>
<L>&amp; praied his douhter fast, to bere him companie;</L>
<L>&amp; hir sonnes bo&thorn;e, Henry &amp; William,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei were him nere bo&thorn;e, gladly with him &thorn;ei nam.</L>
<L>Henry regned here &thorn;ritty &yogh;ere &amp; fiue,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;re mone&thorn;es sere, in &thorn;is feble lyue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e dede euele him toke, he died at his day,</L>
<L>&thorn;e body did &thorn;ei loke, &thorn;at long abouen er&thorn;e lay.</L>
<L>On bere lay kyng Henry, on bere bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non wist certeynly, who his heyr suld be.</L>
<L>Of Mald som had &thorn;e speyre, &thorn;e erle wif of Aniowe,</L>
<L>Hir sone Henry &amp; heyre of him was maste to trowe.</L>
<L>So long he lay on bere, for doute of his lynage,</L>
<L>Tille men &thorn;e soth mot here, who suld haf &thorn;e heritage.</L>
<L>Els I ne wote for wham, his biriyng suld men schonne,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Henrici primi per totum.</NOTE>Tille Steuen of Plesance cam, &thorn;at was his sister sonne.</L>
<L>Steuen com for &thorn;e nons, &thorn;is lond to haf he &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>After were Henry bones to Redynge's abbay brouht.
<PB REF="00000337.tif" N="109"></L>
<L>His bones did he lay in a toumbe of honour,</L>
<L>It was his owen abbay, &thorn;erof he was <NOTE PLACE="foot">&para; This kynge henry the fyrst &verbar; buylded the Abbey of Redynge &verbar; &amp; released the En|glysshemen the Dane gelt. Also this kynge henry beynge in Normandye in the xxxv. yere of his reyne &verbar; the se|conde day of December in the yere of Chryst. M.C.xxxv. dyed. Some say he dyed of a surfet &verbar; and some wryters say that it was by a fall of a horse &verbar; and his body was brought into Englande &verbar; and is buryed in the Abbay of Re|dynge. <I>J. Rastall in his Chr.</I></NOTE> foundour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HENRY is at his reste, his soule at Criste's wille,<NOTE PLACE="marg">DeHenrico comite An|degavi&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; Steuen wille do his beste, in Inglond Ieues he stille.</L>
<L>Thebaud, Steuen bro&thorn;er, as erle in his cuntre,</L>
<L>Of o side ne of o&thorn;er no &thorn;ing deles he.</L>
<L>Henry of Aniowe takes conseile at frendes,</L>
<L>With Malde, &thorn;at is so trowe, to Saynt Denys he wendes,</L>
<L>&amp; his sonne Henry, &thorn;at men helde of grete pris,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei gaf him Normundie bifor &thorn;e kyng Lowys,</L>
<L>&amp; tille his heyres for ay, to hold of &thorn;e kyng of France.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e to&thorn;er day men teld him of a chance,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Gerard of Peiters &thorn;e erle Marchis had fet,</L>
<L>Aniowe with &thorn;er souders was alle biseged &amp; set.</L>
<L>Whan Henry herd telle, he tok leue at Lowys,</L>
<L>Bot Mald scho gan duelle at &thorn;e castelle Sir Amys,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was duke of Gaynes, Henry cosyn &thorn;orgh right.</L>
<L>To suffre Henry paynes he hette him alle his myght.</L>
<L>Also &thorn;e duke Henry with his fadere &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>With help of Normundie, &thorn;e better mot he spede.
<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>Bot William, Henry bro&thorn;er, died, &amp; &thorn;an was wo,</L>
<L>&thorn;e werre with alle &thorn;e to&thorn;er lasted fiue &yogh;ere &amp; mo.</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;is ilk tirpelle wex Steuen a fulle wise man,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh quaintise &amp; conseile &thorn;e coroune of Inglond wan,</L>
<L>&thorn;e date of Jhesu pundred, &thorn;at men tellis bi,</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; a hundred &amp; sex &amp; &thorn;ritti.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON Saynt Steuen day, withouten any conquest,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De corona|cione Sle|phani.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e barons on gode aray at London mad &thorn;ei feste,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh conseile of ilkon, &thorn;ai gaf Steuen &thorn;e coroun,</L>
<L>Heyre was he non, no &thorn;ertille had resoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Emperice sonne Henry he had right &thorn;ertille,</L>
<L>Bot right &yogh;ede &thorn;er forby, &thorn;e barons did no skille.</L>
<L>&para; Bot sen his corounyng tille Oxenford he fore,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De jura|mento Re|gis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er Steuen &thorn;e kyng bifor &thorn;e clergie suore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at if a bisshopriche vacant wer &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng, no non of his, suld chalange &thorn;at of fe,</L>
<L>With wrong no with right, of non &thorn;at fro him cam,</L>
<L>So help him God alle myght, &amp; &thorn;at halidam.</L>
<L>&para; A no&thorn;er oth not lefte, &thorn;e clergie did him karke,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wodes ne foreste, withouten palaised parke,</L>
<L>&thorn;e comon folk suld queme on &amp; o&thorn;er in fere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng no man suld deme in courte for wilde dere,</L>
<L>Clerk ne lewed man for no wilde beste,</L>
<L>For comon &thorn;e folk it wan wod open &amp; forest.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e &thorn;rid poynt &thorn;ei wild, to suere he was dryuen,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e Danegelde for euer suld be forgyuen,</L>
<L>&amp; of <NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> of ilk a hide tuo schillynges &thorn;at he toke</L>
<L>Suld neuer eft betide, he suore &thorn;at on &thorn;e boke,
<PB REF="00000339.tif" N="111"></L>
<L>Ne costom no seruise of &thorn;ing &thorn;at he forgaf,</L>
<L>&thorn;at noi&thorn;er he no hise suld chalange rif no raf.</L>
<L>Of som poyntes he spak, &amp; suore vnto &thorn;e clergie.</L>
<L>&thorn;at ilk &yogh;ere he it brak &thorn;e kyng in som partie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN wrathed Steuen with Dauid of Scotland,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wild not tille him cheuen, no bowe vnto his hand.</L>
<L>Dauid vnto Mald had mad his homage,</L>
<L>Steuen was in defaut, to Dauid did outrage.</L>
<L>Bot Henry Dauid sonne, &thorn;at his heyr suld be,</L>
<L>Contek for to schonne, to Steuen mad feaute.</L>
<L>Steuen sauh his skille, &thorn;at Henry did resoun,</L>
<L>With alle &thorn;at longed &thorn;er tille he gaf him Huntyngtoun.</L>
<L>Henry of Huntyngton he wrote &thorn;e gestes olde,</L>
<L>&amp; sais in his sermon &thorn;at newe ere now tolde.</L>
<L>A bisshop of Lyncoln, Alisaundre he hight,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non suld be forholn, he praied him if he myght.</L>
<L>In Alisaundre tyme kam, &amp; Henrie's &thorn;e compilour</L>
<L>Ros &thorn;e ordre of Sempyngham &thorn;orgh Gilbert &thorn;e confessour.</L>
<L>Saynt Margrete story sais Dauid of hir kam,</L>
<L>Of Dauid kyng Henry, of Henry com William,</L>
<L>Of William Alisandre, &amp; Alisandre of him,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wedded kyng Edward sistir, &thorn;at was &thorn;e Scottis grim.</L>
<L>&thorn;is is &thorn;e Genelogie fro S. Margarete &thorn;e quene</L>
<L>Of kynges bi &amp; bi in kynde &thorn;at has bene.</L>
<L>Now of Steuen to speke turne we eft ageyn,</L>
<L>Our tale wille we no breke, bot telle forth &thorn;e certeyn.
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="112"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Pask in London &thorn;e kyng his feste held,</L>
<L>With erle &amp; baron, with knyght &thorn;at was of scheld.</L>
<L>Was non &thorn;at &thorn;ider &yogh;ode, &thorn;at holden was of pris,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne had gyftes gode of Steuen &thorn;at was wys.</L>
<L>After &thorn;is fest praised Steuen with alle his here,</L>
<L>&thorn;e castellis he seised, &thorn;at he hat neuer ere.</L>
<L>&amp; Baudewyn of Beduere he flemed fro toun &amp; felde,</L>
<L>A kestelle with powere ageyn &thorn;e kyng held,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kastelle tille him toke, Baudwyn had it lorn.</L>
<L>Here how &thorn;e kyng forsoke his oth &thorn;at he had suorn.</L>
<L>&para; In Huntyngtonschire &thorn;e kyng in &thorn;at forest<NOTE PLACE="marg">Perjuratus est Rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>A moneth lay, to spire for wod &amp; wilde beste.</L>
<L>Forsters did somoun, enquered vp &amp; doun,</L>
<L>Whilk men of toun had taken his venysoun,</L>
<L>&amp; who &thorn;at was gilty &thorn;orgh &thorn;e foresters sawe,</L>
<L>Mercied was fulle hi, &amp; don <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> in fulle.</NOTE>&amp; fulle grete awe.</L>
<L>&thorn;us he brak his avowe, &thorn;at he to God had suorn,</L>
<L>For a buske or a bowe &thorn;at he forgaf beforn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OPON &thorn;is ilk syn to Normundie he went.</L>
<L>&thorn;o serganz he fond &thorn;erin, he exiled &thorn;am &amp; schent,</L>
<L>&thorn;at had kept &thorn;e land &thorn;orgh Mald &thorn;e Emperice,</L>
<L>&thorn;at were hir wele willand were putt out of office.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he went to Fraunce, &amp; com vnto Parys,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er acordance bituex him &amp; Lowys,</L>
<L>&amp; gaf it Eustace his sonne alle Normundie in fe,</L>
<L>To hold, as it was wonne, of Lowys for feaute.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng for his seruise confermed his gyft,</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;is ilk wise Eustace to duke was lift.
<PB REF="00000341.tif" N="113"></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e &thorn;rid &yogh;ere of his regne he com to Ingland,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De obsidie|ne Bedfor|di&aelig;, &amp; cap|cione ejus|dem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bedford he beseged, &amp; wan it to his hand.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en dight him to Scotland, &amp; mykelle folk him wit,</L>
<L>&amp; slouh alle &thorn;at he fand for luf of kyng Dauid.</L>
<L>For he mot neuer drawe Dauid tille homage.</L>
<L>Dauid did bot lawe, Mald had his seruage.</L>
<L>Tille Mald with alle his myght for lefe or for loth,</L>
<L>For scho was heyre &thorn;orgh right, to hir he held his oth.</L>
<L>He sauh he myght not spede, &amp; Dauid com no nerre,</L>
<L>To Wales sui&thorn;e he &yogh;ede, and on &thorn;am gan werre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>STEUEN stoutly deles, in stedes &thorn;or he kennes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Misit Gan|nok in Her|fordia.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at ageyn him holdes kasteles on &thorn;am ra&thorn;ely rennes.</L>
<L>In Herford fulle stoutely his gannok has vp set.</L>
<L>With Roberd fitz Henry Steuen so with him met,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Bristow kastelle &amp; toun, whedir he wild or non,</L>
<L>&amp; slede with alle &thorn;e honour, &amp; o&thorn;er sex ilkon,</L>
<L>Carro, Lodelow toun, Schrobesbiri &amp; Warwik,</L>
<L>Dunford &amp; Maltone, Steuen wan &thorn;am ilk a stik,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;e casteles kept, in penance &thorn;ei soiorned,</L>
<L>&thorn;at eft not on him lept, to Wynchestre he tourned.</L>
<L>At Wynchestre he spires, his frendes drawes tille him,</L>
<L>For folk of fele schires agen him turnes grim.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Dauid of Scotland herd &thorn;e soth sawe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Rege Scottorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at Steuen was duelland in &thorn;e South grete &thorn;rawe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk ferly mykelle ageyn him &thorn;ei ros,</L>
<L>&amp; Dauid herte gan tikelle, &thorn;at him wex fele fos.</L>
<L>Fulle son at Rokesburghe his parlement he helde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> folk.</NOTE>solk did somon &thorn;orgh of tuenty wynter elde.
<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>&amp; gaf &thorn;am sonde at wille in Inglond forto fare,</L>
<L>Man &amp; beste to spille, non ne suld &thorn;ei spare.</L>
<L>Southward &thorn;e Scottis hasted, bifor &thorn;am bare alle doun,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e cuntre wasted vnto Aluertoun.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e kyng Dauid Aluerton had sene,</L>
<L>&amp; wend wele at his grith alle Inglond had bene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Norreis so &thorn;am defendid ageyn &thorn;o &thorn;at he brouht,</L>
<L>Whan Dauid alle had spendid, of &thorn;am wan he nouht.</L>
<L>Liste how Dauid les his spente &amp; his trauaile,</L>
<L>&amp; whilk on him gan pres, to renne on his rascaile.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE archbisshop Thurstan, a gode clerk wele in age,</L>
<L>Herd &thorn;e Scottis com ilkan of Dauid baronage,</L>
<L>Forto destroie Inglond, &amp; set it in seruage,</L>
<L>Thurstan sent his sond, tille a bissh sauuage,</L>
<L>Rauf of Orkeney, noble of lynage,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he suld tak &thorn;ei wey, opon his kostage,</L>
<L>&amp; do &thorn;e Scottis deie, &amp; &thorn;er pride asuage.</L>
<L>Whan Rauf herd him so seie, he dight him to &thorn;at rage.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;ise were &thorn;o &thorn;at nam, als in &thorn;e geste it sais,</L>
<L>Of Almarle erle William, &amp; Walter de Gounteis;</L>
<L>Roberd de Brus &thorn;er cam, &amp; Gilbert de la Say,</L>
<L>&amp; his sonne Adam, &amp; Roger de Moubray.</L>
<L>Walter Spek was in&middot;&thorn;at stoure, gode knight at alle nedes,</L>
<L>&thorn;e boke tellis grete honoure of his douhty dedes,</L>
<L>Of monkes &amp; chanones he did mak abbeis,</L>
<L>Wis man in &thorn;e lawe knyght gode &amp; curteis.</L>
<L>William Peuerelle com als, he was of &thorn;e West,</L>
<L>Ageyn &thorn;e Scottis fals, a gode man with &thorn;e best.
<PB REF="00000343.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>&thorn;ise were &thorn;e barons, &thorn;at com of &thorn;e North ende,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Rauf mad somons ageyn Dauid to wende.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise men lift &thorn;er standard, &thorn;at stoute was &amp; grim,</L>
<L>Ageyn Dauid wandelard, &amp; disconfite him.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SAID Rauf tille ilkon, or &thorn;ei ta bataile went,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Radul|pho de Orkneye, qui ductor fuit de bello. Hii sunt qui fuerunt in pr&oelig;lio.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Of &thorn;e bisshop Thurston haf I comandment,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e clerkes forto tech, for &thorn;e londe's nede,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e lewed also to preche, &amp; comforte &thorn;am to dede.</L>
<L>&para; "&yogh;e wite wele a remenant, &amp; forsoth &yogh;e kenne,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at Inglis &amp; Normant be now ons men.</L>
<L>"&yogh;our ancestres conquered all France quitely,</L>
<L>"Were &thorn;ei neuer ferde of Frankis men hardy.</L>
<L>"Pople with alle &thorn;e recchesse, &amp; akres, als &thorn;ei wonnen,</L>
<L>"&thorn;orgh &thorn;er douhtinesse, &thorn;e lond &thorn;orgh &thorn;ei ronnen.</L>
<L>"Si&thorn;en wan &thorn;ei Inglond, &thorn;at is so plentynous,</L>
<L>"&amp; now er &thorn;ise bot mansbond, rascaile of refous.</L>
<L>"On &yogh;our fadres &thorn;ink, &thorn;at were staworth in stoure.</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ise ne salle &yogh;e blenk, bot hold vp &thorn;er honoure.</L>
<L>"Go we with gode wille, &amp; here I &yogh;ow assoyle,</L>
<L>"Of alle &yogh;our synnes ille granted of &thorn;e apostoyle,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &yogh;e haf said or &thorn;ouht, or don &thorn;at is schryuen,</L>
<L>"In Criste, &thorn;at vs alle bouht, be it &yogh;ow forgyuen.</L>
<L>"&thorn;erto my benyson tille alle &thorn;at go bli&thorn;ely,</L>
<L>"In &thorn;e name of &thorn;e fadere &amp; &thorn;e sonne &amp; sprit sancti.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>DAUID of Scotland hasted to &thorn;e bataile,</L>
<L>Walter Spek ros on hand, &thorn;e folk to forme &amp; taile.
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>He bad, &thorn;at non alone breke out of &thorn;e rengaile.</L>
<L>William of Almarle acordes to &thorn;at consaile.</L>
<L>To while &thorn;at &thorn;ise men bold with &thorn;er folk gan daile,</L>
<L>Sir Robert de Brus &thorn;e old to Dauid gan trauaile.</L>
<L>Here now of &thorn;e Brus, how he Dauid gan saile,</L>
<L>With word &thorn;at was Irus, if it mot out auaile.</L>
<L>&para; "Dauid my lordyng, land I hold of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"&amp; als of Steuen kyng, for hamage &amp; feaute.</L>
<L>"Leue alle &thorn;is foly, &thorn;at &thorn;ou here bigynnes,</L>
<L>"&thorn;in heyres salle it by, &amp; &thorn;ou no &thorn;yng wynnes.</L>
<L>"&amp; loke, &thorn;at &thorn;ou not lese of lond &thorn;is ilk day,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De consilio Roberti Brus.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;e best I rede &thorn;ou chese, &thorn;i lif saue if &thorn;ou may.</L>
<L>"For Inglis &amp; Normant er stalworth men in stoure,</L>
<L>"It is folk valiant, ouer alle &thorn;ei bere &thorn;e floure.</L>
<L>"For neuer mot &thorn;ou fynde Inglis kyng giloure.</L>
<L>"To &thorn;e &amp; to &thorn;i kynde haf &thorn;ei don honoure,</L>
<L>"Londes haf &thorn;ei gyuen to &thorn;in ancessoure.</L>
<L>"If trespas be misdryuen, &amp; do &thorn;in owen socoure,</L>
<L>"&amp; I wille mak amendes, tak a day of loue.</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ou ne wille, &thorn;ou spendes, &amp; we salle be aboue.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou may haf &thorn;i wille, if &thorn;ou to loue chese,</L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;ou turne tille ille, non wote who salle lese.</L>
<L>"Wherfor, my lord Dauid, do bi gode conseile,</L>
<L>"Tak &yogh;ow pes &amp; grith, &amp; late be &thorn;is tirpeile,</L>
<L>"&amp; late not now be spoken of &thorn;e mishap.</L>
<L>"For eft it wille be wroken with a hardere klap.
<PB REF="00000345.tif" N="117"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>DAVID listend Roberd, to pes fulle ech to drawe,</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;er was ansuerd, &amp; sturbled alle &thorn;er sawe,</L>
<L>William his neuen, a man of proude wille,</L>
<L>&amp; said, "Roberd &thorn;e bru, traytour hold &thorn;e stille.</L>
<L>Roberd said him nay, traytour was he non,</L>
<L>"Dauid haf gode day, myn homage now is gon.</L>
<L>He smote his hors with spors, &amp; fleih fro &thorn;at rascaile,</L>
<L>&amp; comandid his trompors, to blow vnto bataile.</L>
<L>&para; Rauf of Orkeney cried, "Inglis go now go,</L>
<L>"&amp; do &thorn;ise Scottis deie, &thorn;ei waken vs euer wo.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Normans were alle glad, &thorn;orgh schet &thorn;am als &thorn;e ro.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis did as he bad, bifor &thorn;am stode bot fo.</L>
<L>Almerle his banere sprad, &amp; o&thorn;er barons mo,</L>
<L>Mikelle blod &thorn;ei schad of folk &thorn;at &thorn;ei gon slo.</L>
<L>Dauid away fled, &thorn;at bigan alle &thorn;at &thorn;ro,</L>
<L>Here how a squier sped, sen Dauid fled &thorn;am fro.</L>
<L>&para; A hede &thorn;at was of smyten, &thorn;at &thorn;is squier fond,</L>
<L>Priue, &thorn;at non suld witen, in an orfreis it wond,</L>
<L>&amp; sette it on a spere, in an orfreis vnbiwened,</L>
<L>&amp; said, "lo! here I bere Dauid kyng heued,</L>
<L>"&thorn;is is &thorn;e hede &thorn;at was of Dauid &thorn;e Scottis kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis said, "allas! &thorn;is is a grete encumberyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis &thorn;at stode fer fro, &amp; &thorn;e hede biheld,</L>
<L>Fulle wightly gan &thorn;ei go, flehand out of &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>Wolgryn &amp; Dufnald for euer more &thorn;ei left,</L>
<L>Of knyght no squier bald on lyue non &thorn;ei left.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis whan &thorn;ei cam, bestes ouer alle &thorn;ei toke,</L>
<L>Hors &amp; nete alle samen bifor &thorn;er oste &thorn;ei schoke.
<PB REF="00000346.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei did it for a wile, &thorn;orgh &amp; &thorn;orgh toun,</L>
<L>To put bestes in perile, our folk to bere doun.</L>
<L>Our men herd it say, &thorn;ei were warned beforn,</L>
<L>In ilk strete &amp; way &thorn;ei ordeynd an er&thorn;e horn.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e com &thorn;am blewe, &thorn;e bestes ageyn fled,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis men doun thewe, for roryng wer &thorn;ei dred.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bestis &thorn;orgh &thorn;am &yogh;ede, &amp; ouer &thorn;er rascaile ran,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis after with dede, &amp; slouh &thorn;am ilk a man.</L>
<L>&thorn;is was at Kouton more, &thorn;at &thorn;e er&thorn;e hornes blewe.</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;e Scottis misfore, men telle &thorn;e tale &yogh;it newe.</L>
<L>Sir Henry, Dauid sonne, &thorn;e romance sais so &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>His dedis were more to mone, &thorn;an sex &thorn;e best &thorn;er were.</L>
<L>Our barons had &thorn;e pris, with &thorn;am held &thorn;e right,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis side doun lis, &thorn;ei &thorn;anked God all myght.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e moneth of heruest was Dauid disconfite,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De capci|one David, &amp; de Eus|tathio filio Stephani.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e next &yogh;ole alle preste Steuen dight him fulle tite,</L>
<L>&amp; tille Scotlond went, &amp; tok he kyng Dauid,</L>
<L>&amp; tille Inglond him sent, his sonne Henry him wit.</L>
<L>&para; A sonne had Steuen &thorn;e kyng, Eustace was his name,</L>
<L>In armes gode gynnyng, of pruesse had he fame,</L>
<L>Lowys douhter of France Eustace tok to wife,</L>
<L>Steuen for &thorn;at chance was more stouter in strife.</L>
<L>Alisander, &thorn;at was bisshop of Lyncoln schire,</L>
<L>I ne wote for what trespas, &thorn;e kyng tille him had ire.</L>
<L>Sleford &amp; Neuwerk &thorn;e kyng reft him &thorn;o tueyn,</L>
<L>At Wynchestere &thorn;orgh conseile he had &thorn;am bo&thorn;e ageyn.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;at ilk tyme so felle Mald &thorn;e Emperice com to lond,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matildis Imperatrix venit in Angliam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e castelle of Arondelle open ageyn hir fond.
<PB REF="00000347.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>Whan Steuen vnderstode Mald was in Arondelle,</L>
<L>With mykelle folk &amp; gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> bigeged &thorn;at kastelle.</L>
<L>Mald &thorn;ouht of &thorn;is stoure, scho bi&thorn;ouht hir straite,</L>
<L>&amp; douted dishonoure, &thorn;at mot com &thorn;orgh disceite.</L>
<L>Scho did hir to Bristow, &amp; duellid o&thorn;er half &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ider fro Anjowe com hire a messengere,</L>
<L>&amp; told to Mald here, &thorn;at scho fulle wele trod,</L>
<L>Hir lord lay on bere, his soule bitaken God,</L>
<L>&amp; Henry hire sonne had &thorn;e heritage,</L>
<L>To hold as it was wonne, don was his homage.</L>
<L>Mald in Bristow lettres fast sendes,</L>
<L>Bi messengers trowe, forto procore frendes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Misit baro|nibus pro auxilio.</NOTE></L>
<L>To burgeis &amp; citez (&thorn;e wardeyns alle scho freistes,)</L>
<L>&amp; to lordes of feez, &thorn;at scho on treistes.</L>
<L>Of help scho &thorn;am bisouht, in right &amp; leaute,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei failed hir nouht, for heyre &thorn;e wist hir be.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons said, scho had right in hire askyng.</L>
<L>Son was &thorn;e contek schad bituex &thorn;am &amp; &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>Ilkon on his side to bataile purueid him,</L>
<L>&thorn;at power had to bide most was stoute &amp; grim.</L>
<L>&para; Sir William of Almarle wex a stoute sire,</L>
<L>He &yogh;erned to haue alle Lyncolnschire,</L>
<L>Ageyn Gilbert &thorn;e Gaunt reised his banere.</L>
<L>Gilbert was valiaunt, ageyn him fulle austere.</L>
<L>Gilbert had &thorn;e erledam &thorn;at tyme of heritage.</L>
<L>Bituex him &amp; William was don many outrage.</L>
<L>Of Gilbert first to telle, to William did he wouh,</L>
<L>He did brenne Helwelle, &amp; William bro&thorn;er slouh.
<PB REF="00000348.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>&thorn;e castelle of Bitham to Gilbert &yogh;olden was.</L>
<L>It longed to William, &thorn;at tyme felle him &thorn;at cas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WILLIAM of Almarle &thorn;at tyme Northward rode,</L>
<L>. &thorn;e castelle of Hundmanby he cast doun alle o brode.</L>
<L>Sir Eustace le fitz Jon at &thorn;at dede was,</L>
<L>More him, &thorn;an ilkon, &thorn;e wited &thorn;at trespas.</L>
<L>Who so was wro&thorn;e, or o&thorn;er, biforn, for any chance,</L>
<L>His enmy &thorn;e to&thorn;ere toke &thorn;an his vengeance.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at lufed werryng mad parties ay bituen,</L>
<L>Som held with Steuen &thorn;e kyng, &amp; som with Mald &thorn;e quene.</L>
<L>For erles &amp; barons, &thorn;at were of Malde's kynde,</L>
<L>Souht citez &amp; touns, &thorn;e kyng if &thorn;ei mot fynde.</L>
<L>Hir frendes fulle fast waited aboute &amp; woke,</L>
<L>&amp; Mald at &thorn;e last kyng Steuen scho toke,</L>
<L>&amp; led him to Bristow, &amp; did him &thorn;er in hold,</L>
<L>In prison, I trowe, &thorn;orgh &thorn;e quene Mold.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Des riches &amp; des pouers de communalte Eft Malde leimperice dame rescen de gre. <I>Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;an &thorn;e riche &amp; pouere, &amp; alle comonly,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> fro.</NOTE>For Berwik to Douere held hir for lady.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e lond gan hir loute, &amp; alle was at hir wille,</L>
<L>&thorn;an bare scho hir ouer stoute, &amp; wild vnto no skille.</L>
<L>For or &thorn;at &yogh;ere was gon, scho bare hir so stoute,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e Lundreis ilkon of London drof hir oute.</L>
<L>Mald &thorn;orgh &thorn;e Lundreis fro London is katched,</L>
<L>With hors &amp; herneis Bristow has scho latched.
<PB REF="00000349.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>What for ire &amp; tene, &amp; alle in euelle wille,</L>
<L>Scho stokked kyng Steuen, &amp; &thorn;er did scho ille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW turnes eft Mold to Wyncester fulle stoute,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Matil|de Impera|trice.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; Steuen out of &thorn;at hold quaintly skaped oute.</L>
<L>Roberd went hir with, Malde's half bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e kyng Dauid of Scotland was &thorn;e to&thorn;er.</L>
<L>At Wynchester gan scho duelle, biseged &thorn;e castelle:</L>
<L>&thorn;e Londreis herd it telle, &amp; &yogh;ared &thorn;am fulle welle,</L>
<L>With gode aparaile of alle &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot gete.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sege &thorn;ei gan assaile, &amp; tok hir at &thorn;e mete.</L>
<L>Roberd &thorn;er was taken in to &thorn;e Londreis hand,</L>
<L>Bot Dauid was wele waken, he fled fast to Scotland,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;orgh Chestreschire, he fled to Louthian.</L>
<L>A preste was with hire, &thorn;at Mald fro &thorn;am wan.</L>
<L>Mald &amp; Roberd Louelle tille Oxenford &thorn;ei fled,</L>
<L>&amp; seised &thorn;e castelle, &amp; Steuen fast him sped,</L>
<L>&amp; gadred him an oste, &amp; went vnto Wilton,</L>
<L>&amp; did reise in &thorn;at coste a stalworth donjon.</L>
<L>Mald wist &thorn;at fulle wele, hir barons &thorn;ider sent,</L>
<L>&amp; Steuen left ilka dele, &amp; to Northampton went.</L>
<L>William Marschalle o chance was taken at &thorn;at turne:</L>
<L>He gaf for his delyuerance &thorn;e castelle of Schirburne.</L>
<L>Folk bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e se, &thorn;at were of Steuen's kynde,</L>
<L>Tille him com grete plente, &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot fyndc.</L>
<L>Steuen with his power tille Oxenford gan schake,</L>
<L>His sege he set plener, &thorn;e castelle forto take.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Emperice it held, was it &thorn;e wynter tide,</L>
<L>&thorn;e snowe lay in &thorn;e feld, &thorn;e water frese biside.
<PB REF="00000350.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>&thorn;e lady had defaute bo&thorn;e of mete &amp; drynk,</L>
<L>&amp; scho dred &thorn;er assaute, hunger was at &thorn;e brynk.</L>
<L>Scho asked hir conseile, what was &thorn;er of to rede.</L>
<L>"Steuen wille vs traueile, &amp; famen vs to dede.</L>
<L>Non ne couth ne wild conseile on no partie,</L>
<L>Bo &thorn;e castelle to &yogh;eld, &amp; ask &thorn;e kyng mercie.</L>
<L>&thorn;at ne wild scho nouht, hir herte was so stoute.</L>
<L>Bot here now how scho wrouht, &amp; how scho passed oute.</L>
<L>&para; A fulle selcouth rede tok at hir owen herte,</L>
<L>Scho left for life no dede, ne colde &thorn;at was so smerte.</L>
<L>Sone after mydnyght, &thorn;at crowe suld &thorn;e cok,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e snowe for syght scho &yogh;ede out in hir smok,</L>
<L>Ouere &thorn;e water of Temse, &thorn;at frosen was iys,</L>
<L>Withouten kirtelle or kemse, saue kouerchef alle bare vis.</L>
<L>To Walyngford scho wan, &amp; &thorn;er scho left a while,</L>
<L>&thorn;e way scho &yogh;ed &amp; ran, on length it is ten mile.</L>
<L>&amp; Steuen &thorn;e castelle wan of &thorn;am euer ilkon.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei gelded it ilk man, <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> whan.</NOTE>wham dam Mald was gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;is tyme had Steuen regned auht &yogh;ere in alle,</L>
<L>Lered &amp; lewed were euen, &amp; pere &amp; paringalle;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at knyght &amp; squiere, if &thorn;ei powere mot make,</L>
<L>Of holy kyrke pleynere tok &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot take.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape &thorn;an herd &thorn;e pleynt, he sent hider a legate.</L>
<L>At London &thorn;ei wer atteynt, decre was mad for &thorn;ate,</L>
<L>&yogh;if any lewed man laid hand opon clerk,</L>
<L>Or with ille on ran, &thorn;at of corun had merk,</L>
<L>He suld not escape, &thorn;orgh bisshop granted fre,</L>
<L>Of non bot of &thorn;e pape myght he assoyled be.
<PB REF="00000351.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng it was herd, &amp; chastised his meyne,</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er afterward left of &thorn;er nycete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THER after half a &yogh;ere &thorn;e clergie had gode pes,</L>
<L>&thorn;at noi&thorn;er wo no werre non on &thorn;am gan pres.</L>
<L>Bot Geffrey of Maundeuile &thorn;e kyng Steuen him reft</L>
<L>His baronie, &thorn;at while robberie with Job was left.</L>
<L>&thorn;e abbay of Rameseie bi nyght he robbed it,</L>
<L>&thorn;e tresore bare aweie with hand &thorn;ei myght on hit.</L>
<L>Abbote &amp; priour &amp; monke &thorn;ei did out chace,</L>
<L>Of holy kirke a toure to theft &thorn;ei mad it place.</L>
<L>Roberd &thorn;e Marmion &thorn;e same wayes did he,<NOTE PLACE="marg">DeRoberto Marmyon.</NOTE></L>
<L>He robbed &thorn;orgh treson &thorn;e kirke of Couentre.</L>
<L>Here now of &thorn;eir schame, what chance bifelle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e story sais &thorn;e same, soth as &thorn;e gospelle.</L>
<L>&para; Roberd &thorn;e Marmyon he lepe vp on his stede,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh Couentre &thorn;at toun vnto &thorn;e kirke he &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>He comandid his men, to dryue out &thorn;e couent,</L>
<L>&thorn;e godes him biken, &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot tak or hent.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei had inouh, als mykelle as &thorn;ei mot lede</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei of herneis drouh, to go &thorn;ei gan &thorn;am spede.</L>
<L>He turned his bridelle wi&thorn; querte, he wend away haf gone,</L>
<L>&thorn;e dede him smote to &thorn;e herte, word spak he neuer none.</L>
<L>&para; Geffrey of Maundeuile to fele wrouh he wouh,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De G. Maunde|uile.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e deuelle &yogh;ald him his while, with an arowe on him slouh.</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode bisshop of Chestre cursed &thorn;is ilk Geffray,</L>
<L>His lif out of &thorn;is estre in cursyng went away.</L>
<L>Arnulf his sonne was taken als thefe, &amp; brouht in bond,</L>
<L>Befor &thorn;e kyng forsaken, &amp; exiled out of &thorn;is lond.
<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>&thorn;e marschalle of &thorn;am alle, Helys of Saynt Omere,</L>
<L>To ded &thorn;an gon he falle doun of his destrere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e maistir of &thorn;er pedaile, &thorn;at kirkes brak &amp; brent,</L>
<L>&amp; abbeis gan assaile, monkes slouh &amp; schent,</L>
<L>Was born in Pikardie, &amp; his name Reyuere,</L>
<L>In suilk felonie gadred grete auere.</L>
<L>He had what he wild, &amp; was of wendyng &yogh;are,</L>
<L>&amp; had a schipe wele filled, ouer &thorn;e flode to fare.</L>
<L>&thorn;er in was wif &amp; childe, &amp; tresore wikly wonnen.</L>
<L>So com a tempest wilde, his schip had alle ouer ronnen.</L>
<L>&thorn;e maryner was ogast, &thorn;at schip &thorn;at wild not go.</L>
<L>Lotes did &thorn;ei kast, for whom &thorn;ei had &thorn;at wo.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lote felle on Reyuere, &amp; on his wif also.</L>
<L>&thorn;ris kast at tymes sere, selle it on &thorn;am tuo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E schip man wist wele, &thorn;e tempest &thorn;at &thorn;am smote,</L>
<L>For &thorn;am com ilk a dele, he did &thorn;an tak a bote,</L>
<L>&amp; did &thorn;am alle &thorn;erin, Reyuer &amp; his gode,</L>
<L>&amp; whan &thorn;ei were o tuyn, &thorn;er schip ferd on &thorn;e flode.</L>
<L>Reyuer &amp; his wif doun tille helle &thorn;ei sank,</L>
<L>For his wikked lif &thorn;e Deuelle gald him &thorn;at &thorn;ank.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN his tende &yogh;ere a hatrex wex alle hote,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng fulle austere ageyn Sir Hugh Bigote.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng did not wele, with &thorn;e wrong he wrouht;</L>
<L>Amendes he mad som dele, bot of &thorn;e most right nought.</L>
<L>&para; Rauf &thorn;e erle of Chestre, &amp; &thorn;e kyng were wroth,</L>
<L>In his elleuend &yogh;ere, &thorn;e wend haf acorded both
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="125"></L>
<L>In alle maner of &thorn;ing, &thorn;at Rauf felt him filed.</L>
<L>Bot here now how &thorn;e kyng Rauf &thorn;e erle begiled:</L>
<L>Unto Northampton Rauf to courte kam.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng, &thorn;orgh treson, Rauf &thorn;er he nam,</L>
<L>&amp; held him tille he &yogh;ald of Lyncolne &thorn;e castelle,</L>
<L>&amp; plenerly haf he wald &thorn;e rentis &thorn;at &thorn;erto felle.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e tuelft &yogh;ere of his regne at &yogh;ole he held his feste</L>
<L>At Lyncolne, as in signe, &thorn;at it was his conqueste.</L>
<L>Sone after &thorn;at feste, &thorn;at he &thorn;er seysen tok,</L>
<L>&thorn;e courte, moste &amp; leste, tille Arundelle &thorn;ei schoke.</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng was gone, Rauf herd sone say,</L>
<L>To Lyncoln forth on one Rauf &thorn;an tok his way,</L>
<L>&amp; reised a mangnel, to kast vnto &thorn;e toure.</L>
<L>&thorn;e burgeis were fulle felle, &thorn;ei &yogh;ald him hard stoure.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Gyour of his oste at &thorn;at saut was slayn,</L>
<L>&amp; Rauf, for alle his boste, fulle fast fled agayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE &yogh;ere next on hand &yogh;ede &thorn;e kyng of France<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce kou|wardise magnatum &amp; fuga eo|rum.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e holy land, with his purueiance.</L>
<L>&thorn;e emperour with &thorn;o kynges went withouten grace.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &amp; o&thorn;er lordynges mad &thorn;e grete manace,</L>
<L>Upon Gode's enmys forto tak vengeance.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei sauh &thorn;e payens of pris of so grete purueiance,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Cristen turned for drede withouten dynt of lance.</L>
<L>Bot here how &thorn;e poraile spede, God gaf &thorn;am fair chance.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e poraile &thorn;at went &thorn;ider, &thorn;at had no spendyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei suore &thorn;er oth togider, to lette for no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>To wend vnto Spayn, &amp; tuo Citez &thorn;ei wan.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins was &thorn;er wayn, &amp; slouh &thorn;am ilk a man.
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei &yogh;ede fro lond to lond, &amp; non ageyn &thorn;am stode.</L>
<L>&thorn;e better grace &thorn;ei fond, &thorn;e ferrer &thorn;at &thorn;ei &yogh;ode.</L>
<L>Hidere com &thorn;at ti&thorn;and tille o&thorn;er lordes manymo,</L>
<L>How mykelle grace &thorn;ei fand, &thorn;at durst &thorn;e Sarazins slo.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lordes mot haf schame, whan &thorn;ei herd it telle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at dred for Gode's name, at home &thorn;ei &yogh;ede to Helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN his sextend &yogh;ere Steuen &thorn;at &thorn;e lond auht,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Matildis Imperatri|cis, &amp; de forma scri|pti inter Stephanum &amp; Henri|cum filium Imperatri|cis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Mald scho died here, hir soule to God betauht.</L>
<L>&amp; hir sonne Henry to lond was he comen,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons &amp; &thorn;e clergy tille him alle &thorn;e nomen,</L>
<L>&amp; with &thorn;e kyng Steuen &thorn;ei held parlement,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Henry &amp; he euen acorded or &thorn;ei went.</L>
<L>With skrite was set &thorn;e pes, &amp; ordeynd &thorn;orgh baroun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Steuen tille his dises of Inglond suld bere coroun,</L>
<L>&amp; his gyft certeyn be holden stabilly.</L>
<L>To Normundie ageyn suld turne &thorn;e duke Henry,</L>
<L>&amp; Ingland alle holy after Steuen &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>Suld turne to &thorn;e same Henry, withouten geynsaiyng.</L>
<L>&amp; if &thorn;at Henry die, or Steuen mak his deses,</L>
<L>Henry heyr we seie salle haf &thorn;e lond in pes,</L>
<L>Coroun forto bere, as heyr &amp; eldest sonne,</L>
<L>His heritage to were in right, als it was wonne,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at Steuen &thorn;e kyng, no non of his heyres,</L>
<L>For heritage no &thorn;ing salle chalange for &thorn;eires.</L>
<L>&thorn;is dede was enseled bitauht &thorn;am of S. Poule's,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wrong were not deled for drede of lif &amp; soules.
<PB REF="00000355.tif" N="127"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW wendes duke Henry vnto Normundie,</L>
<L>Seysine has plenerly of alle his cheualrie,</L>
<L>&amp; Steuen leues here, Inglond is his balie.</L>
<L>After in his &thorn;rid &yogh;ere Steuen fulle seke gan lie,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;at grete languour endid he his life,</L>
<L>Ninetene &yogh;ere &thorn;e honour he kept in werre &amp; strife,</L>
<L>At Feuersham he lis, at a heuen in Kent,</L>
<L>In an abbey of pris he founded with lond &amp; rent.</L>
<L>&amp; Mald &thorn;e Emperice &thorn;er &thorn;an is scho laid,</L>
<L>&thorn;at serued &thorn;er office to me, so &thorn;ei said.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date a &thorn;ousand right a hundreth<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Obiit re vera Stephanus rex Oct.</I> 25. 1154. <I>Ipsius autem re|ginaMatildis defunct a est Maii</I> 3&deg;. 1152. <I>apud</I> Hedningham <I>ni|mirum sive</I> Hengham, <I>vulg&ograve;</I> Heningham, <I>elegans olim ca|strum (notante Camdeno) &amp; Oxoni&aelig; Comitum antiquam habitationem, in agro Essexi|ensi.</I></NOTE> &amp; fifty,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno. M&deg;. C&deg;. L&deg;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at Steuen to dede was dight, now comes &thorn;e secunde Henry.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Steuen dede, &amp; lies at Feuersham,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Henricus secundus factus est rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e barons &thorn;air red, &amp; after Henry nam.</L>
<L>To London &thorn;ei him brouht with grete solempnite.</L>
<L>&thorn;e popille him bisouht &thorn;er kyng forto be.</L>
<L>&thorn;e day of Saynt Liger<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Oct.</I> 2. <I>Sed de tem|pore Coronationis variant hi|storici.</I></NOTE> was Henry corouned kyng,</L>
<L>Thebald of Canterber gaf him &thorn;e coroune &amp; &thorn;e ryng.</L>
<L>&thorn;is Henry was Mald sonne, &thorn;e erle wif of Aniowe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Emp&egrave;rice was wonne, &amp; right heyre forto trowe.</L>
<L>For Henry douhter scho was, &amp; his heyre &thorn;orgh sight.</L>
<L>Now comes hir sonne in pas, Henry hir heyr &thorn;orgh right.
<PB REF="00000356.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Henry has four sonnes, &amp; douhters has he tuo,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e story mones, &thorn;ese ere &thorn;e names of &thorn;o:</L>
<L>Henry &amp; Richard, erle Geffrey &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">John.</NOTE> Jone,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Perperam. Nam tres duntaxat reges erant, Gal|fridus vero Britanni&aelig; tantum|modo Comes sive Dux, id quod mox ipse notat Auctor, qui pro|inde forsitan voluit, comitem h&iacute;c loci pro regulo accipi. haud enim aliud alibi etiam valet, sicut ex IIemingo nostro colligi potest.</I></NOTE>Ilkon afterward was kyng, &amp; quene<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Quin &amp; h&icirc;c etiam auctor secus atque alii, qui do|cent, tam Johannam quam &amp; Elianoram reginam fuisse. Ad|eo ut pro eorum sententia mox infra</I> quene of Cezile <I>pro</I> lady of Cezile <I>sit reponendum. id quod etiam liquet ex Petri de. Langtoft Codicibus Gallicis, in quibus</I>, Alyenore sa fylle fu Rayne de Espayne, Rayne de Secylle Johane la fylle darayne.</NOTE> bot on.</L>
<L>Geffrey was no more, bot erle of Bretayn:</L>
<L>&amp; dame Helianore scho we quen of Spayn.</L>
<L>Dame<NOTE PLACE="foot">Joane.</NOTE> Jon was &yogh;ongest, &amp; lady of Cezile.</L>
<L>&thorn;er fader kyng richest lyuand in alle his while.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is ilk Henry is told Henry &thorn;e scecunde,</L>
<L>So riche a prince in wold in &thorn;is lond si&thorn;en non funde.</L>
<L>Aniowe &amp; Normundie alle holy he held,</L>
<L>Of Gascoyne &thorn;e seignorie bowed vnto his scheld.</L>
<L>Ilk a knyght &amp; squiere, clerkes were to him suorn.</L>
<L>&thorn;an was his Chancelere Thomos of London born.</L>
<L>Saynt Thoma fader I fynd hight Thomas Beket,</L>
<L>In London of noble kynd, &amp; maste of alle was let.</L>
<L>A riche man he was, mot spend &thorn;re hundreth pound:</L>
<L>Ersdeken his sonne Thomas of Canterbiri &thorn;at stound,</L>
<L>In alle manere cause he sought &thorn;e right in skille,</L>
<L>To gile no to fraude wild he neuer tille.
<PB REF="00000357.tif" N="129"></L>
<L>&thorn;e Ersebisshop &thorn;at was &thorn;at tyme died he,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sanetus Thomas factus est archiepis|copus Can|tuar.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Erresdeken Thomas was sacred in his se.</L>
<L>Wele mayntend he holy kirk, &amp; alle &thorn;e dignite,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e lawe to wirke mayntend &thorn;e ordine.</L>
<L>If any man mad pleynt of clerk for hastiuenesse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce con|troversia orta est in|ter regem &amp; clerum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Or if &thorn;ei were atteynt in o&thorn;er wikkednesse,</L>
<L>Thomas suffred nouht<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> clerke.</NOTE> cleke to be alle sehent,</L>
<L>Ne to &thorn;e lay courte be brouht to tak &thorn;er jugement,</L>
<L>Bot tille holy kirke, of whom he bare &thorn;e merke,</L>
<L>&amp; at &thorn;at lawe to wirke, if he were ordeynd clerke.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng for &thorn;at cheson wrathed with Thomas.</L>
<L>Here now &thorn;e reson, whi &thorn;at wreth first was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>CLERKES often tide misdo blithely,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de clero per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>For deynoushede &amp; pride, &amp; for &thorn;er state is hy:</L>
<L>&thorn;ei passe mesure &amp; right, forto haf &thorn;er wille,</L>
<L>&amp; whan &thorn;ei ere in myght, wille &thorn;ei kepe no skille.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei wille vnderfong a fulle gre emprise,</L>
<L>&amp; susteyn it with wrong, with sleiht &amp; quaintise.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at felt &thorn;am greued, of &thorn;er wikked dedis,</L>
<L>To lordes, &thorn;at &thorn;ei to cheued, pleyned &thorn;ei most nedis.</L>
<L>&thorn;at suilk was not lees, it com to &thorn;e kynge's ere,</L>
<L>He comanded his pes to lered and lewed &thorn;at were.</L>
<L>&amp; if a clerke men founde in his lond &thorn;at reft,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh slauhter or wounde, or &thorn;orgh o&thorn;er theft,</L>
<L>Men suld schewe his guilte in &thorn;e courte of lay,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er be saued or splite, bot Thomas said him nay.</L>
<L>Thomas said &thorn;e kyng, &thorn;at othe suld he wele loke,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he suore at &thorn;e gynnyng, whan he &thorn;e coroune toke.
<PB REF="00000358.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>"&thorn;orgh God I &thorn;e forbede to chalange any clerke</L>
<L>"In lay courte for non nede, of holy kirke has merke;</L>
<L>"Ne &thorn;e franchise fordo, &thorn;at it ouh to halde,</L>
<L>"Bot tille &thorn;at courte com to, of whilk he is membre calde.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is was at Clarendoun, &thorn;at Thomas gaf respouns,</L>
<L>&amp; si&thorn;en to Narthamptoun Thomas com eft sons,</L>
<L>Delyuer his clerkes fro dome, bot no grantise was.</L>
<L>Wherfor to &thorn;e courte of Rome &thorn;an kalled S. Thomas.</L>
<L>Thomas toke &thorn;e way, &amp; passed ouer &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng Henry herd say, his messenger sent he.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Torn off. But the sense, notwithstanding, is plain, es|pecially if the passage be com|pared with the French, which is thus</I>: Ceo fu a Claringdoun, ou Thomas ad parlez, Et a Norhampton vint il altre feez, Deliuerer ses clers, mes rien luy fu grantez. A la courte de Rome ad Thomas appellez. Thomas deuers la courte va la mere passer, Et le Reis Henry fet maintenaunt maunder. Ler|ceuesqe de Euerwik son noun fu Roger, Et son fiz Henry le fist corouner, Et oyndre en Reis, le regne pur [<I>the word</I> pur <I>is wanting in Mr. Anstis's Copies</I>] gouerner. Toit fist a Thomas, ke fust outre mere. Kar pur veir a luy appent cel mester.</NOTE>. . . . . . hop Rogere of &yogh;ork &thorn;an kept &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>. . . . . . his powere corouned forto be,</L>
<L>. . . . . oynt also with wrong, &thorn;ei mad alle mirie.</L>
<L>Tille Thomas felle it to &thorn;e kirk of Canterbirie."</L>
<L>Whan Thomas it wist, he did mak a cursyng.</L>
<L>Roger he cursed first, &thorn;at corouned &thorn;e &yogh;ong kyng,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;at wer him with, or in his courte wer sene,</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;e kyng had grith, his childre &amp; &thorn;e quene.</L>
<L>To Thomas &thorn;e kyng bisouht, &thorn;e bishop to assoile,</L>
<L>Bot Thomas wild nouh, bot &thorn;orgh grace of &thorn;e apostoilc.
<PB REF="00000359.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>Wherfor &thorn;e kyng wex wroth, &amp; Thomas did exile,</L>
<L>His kynred lefe &amp; loth he did fleme &amp; reuile.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng suld haf no plight, &thorn;at Thomas so was dede,</L>
<L>He said bot tille a knyght, &thorn;at Thomas him misbede;<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Sancti Thom&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; if he had had men, as he wend, of renoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei suld haf venged him of suilk a clergioun.</L>
<L>Foure kyngtes it herd withouten any more,</L>
<L>To Canterbiri &thorn;ei ferd, &amp; slouh Thomas right &thorn;ore<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the Cathedral Church at St. Bennet's Altar, as even Rastall takes notice, in his most wonderfull rare Chroni|cle, lent me by the curious and ingenious Mr. John Murray.</I> &para; Also (<I>saith he</I>) for dyuers actes that the kynge procured to be made agayne the lybertes of the churche. There<NOTE PLACE="marg">saynt tho|mas of Caunter|bury slayne.</NOTE> fell a great debate betwene hym and Thomas then Arche|byshop of Canterbury &verbar; that the byshoppe fled vnto Rome. But after whan Thomas came agayne to Caunterbury. iiii. of the kynges knyghtes because the kyng beyng in Normandye &verbar; they harde the kyng say these wordes &verbar; if he had any men about hym &verbar; he had ben a veng|ed vpon that traytour longe or that tyme. Therfore these knyghtes came fro the kynge beynge in Normandye &verbar; and slewe this Thomas in the cathe|drall church in Canterbury at saynt Benettes auter: whiche Thomas is nowe by the churche canonysed for a holy saynt &verbar; &amp; dyuers myracles auctorysed by the churche that god hathe shewed for hym.</NOTE>.</L>
<L>&para; Who so wille wit &thorn;is chance his lif &amp; his languour;</L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;e kyng of France did him grete honour;</L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;e pape sent his bulle with a legate;</L>
<L>&amp; how, or he went, he serched alle &thorn;e state;</L>
<L>&amp; how at Pountney &thorn;e angelle to him said;</L>
<L>&amp; how alle his kynde exile was on &thorn;am laid;
<PB REF="00000360.tif" N="132"></L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;e apostoile laid on &thorn;am grete payn,</L>
<L>Or he wilde &thorn;am assoile, &thorn;at had Thomas slayn;</L>
<L>&amp; how for holy kirke he suffred passion,</L>
<L>&amp; how God dos wirke in schrine &thorn;er he is don;</L>
<L>Open his boke &amp; se, for &thorn;er in ere &thorn;ei writen,</L>
<L>Meruailes grete plente, &thorn;at fele of vs ne witen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>COMEN is ti&thorn;ing, &thorn;e bishop slayne is he,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e &yogh;onge kyng is went ouer &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Of Almarle erle William with &thorn;e kyng was &thorn;en,</L>
<L>Tuo castels he nam open &thorn;e Frankis men.</L>
<L>Of Almarle in &thorn;e castelle &thorn;re lordes he toke,</L>
<L>Of messengers fulle suelle he sent hider to loke</L>
<L>Untille Inglond, of Flandres men fulle ille,</L>
<L>In warde or in bond in prison leue &thorn;ei stille.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e fader kyng Henry in herte had he payn,</L>
<L>&amp; anguised greuosly, &thorn;at Thomas was so slayn.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De falsi|tate Scot|torum.</NOTE></L>
<L>William &thorn;e Scottis kyng therfor was fulle blithe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Henry had ille likyng, werre on him gan he kithe.</L>
<L>Burgh his way beforn he sesed &thorn;at kastelle,</L>
<L>Mulgard &thorn;orgh him was lorn, Prudhow saued welle.</L>
<L>His way left he nouht, tille he com tille Alnwik,</L>
<L>&thorn;er was he taken, &amp; brouht to Richemunde also quik.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Captus est rex Scot|torum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Richard &thorn;e Moruile knyght of gode renoun,</L>
<L>Richard Comyn &thorn;at while with him com to &thorn;e toun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Northren so wele stode in treuth to &thorn;e kyng Henry.</L>
<L>&thorn;at gyftes he gaf &thorn;am gode, &amp; &thorn;at was largely.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at alle &thorn;e to&thorn;er com vntille his grith</L>
<L>Of lordes on &amp; o&thorn;er, &amp; fayn to hold him with.
<PB REF="00000361.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>Contek in countes alle was peysed wele,</L>
<L>Baret of baron feez forgyuen ilkadele.</L>
<L>&thorn;an was Inglond in pes &amp; charite,</L>
<L>&amp; alle in Henry gracious kyng &amp; fre.</L>
<L>In his nientend &yogh;ere of his regalte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De consilio &amp; falsitate Franco|rum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Henry his sonne his pere was &yogh;it ouer &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng sister of France Henry allied him to,</L>
<L>Here of a desceyuance &thorn;ei conseild him to do.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle Philip of Flandres gaf him in conseile,</L>
<L>&amp; Thebald of Plesence egged to &thorn;at tirpeile,</L>
<L>Ageyn his fader to rise, &thorn;er he had no right:</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng of France &amp; hise hight him alle his myght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN &thorn;e fader wist &thorn;e sonne wild werre on him,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De remotu obsidionis per Henri|cum.</NOTE></L>
<L>I blame him not if him list turne ageyn fulle grim.</L>
<L>For &thorn;am of Scotland he sent William &amp; Dauid his bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Tille bli&thorn;ely &thorn;ei went, &amp; with &thorn;am many o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Leycestre &thorn;e oste alle did he guye,</L>
<L>Of werre he was &thorn;er maistre, dight &thorn;am to Normundie.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;ei were vp aryued, &thorn;ei fond &thorn;er &thorn;ar chance:</L>
<L>&thorn;at reame was biseged with &thorn;e power of France.</L>
<L>Henry chaced his sonne &thorn;orgh force fro toun to toun,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng of France eftsonne left tent &amp; pauilloun.</L>
<L>Philip of Flandres fleih &amp; turned sonne &thorn;e bak,</L>
<L>&amp; Thebald nouht ne deih, schame of &thorn;am men spak.</L>
<L>Fro toun to toun of reme &thorn;e Frankis did &thorn;ei fle,</L>
<L>Ouertok it to &yogh;eme, &amp; saued &thorn;at cite.
<PB REF="00000362.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>Our Inglis duelled &thorn;er, vnto &thorn;e pes were pleyn.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;er were beforn wild no more com ageyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e moneth of May our Inglis of was &yogh;are,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Reversi sunt in Angliam.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e first day tille Inglond forto fare.</L>
<L>Fulle sone &thorn;e &yogh;ong kyng with gode man &thorn;at wer gayn</L>
<L>Purucid his wendyng, &amp; Richard fitz Alayn,</L>
<L>&thorn;e duke of Peiters, &amp; &thorn;e erle of Bretayn,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise &amp; o&thorn;er pers to sauhtillyng did &thorn;er payn.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise on knees gan falle bifore &thorn;e kyngis face,</L>
<L>For Iuf &thorn;ei praied him alle to grante &thorn;e kyng his grace.</L>
<L>"&yogh;our wrath him forgyue, &thorn;e trespas to amend,</L>
<L>"In pes with &yogh;ow to lyue, &amp; at &yogh;our conseil descend.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sonne cam also sui&thorn;e, &amp; cried his fader mercy.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &thorn;erof was bli&thorn;e, forgaf him gentilly;</L>
<L>&amp; he with scrite &amp; oth mad obligacion,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for leue no loth, &thorn;orgh conseile of treson,</L>
<L>Suld werre on him begynne, bi water ne bi lond,</L>
<L>Ne his pes breke no tuynne, &thorn;e sonne &thorn;ertille him bond.</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;is sauhtillyng bituex &thorn;e fader &amp; &thorn;e sonne</L>
<L>Com &thorn;e Scottis kyng, &amp; asked Henry a bone</L>
<L>Of grantise of grace, to haf his seignorie.</L>
<L>Bifor alle in &thorn;at place he gaf it him bli&thorn;ely.</L>
<L>&thorn;an wer bo&thorn;e &thorn;e kynges brouht alle tille euen,</L>
<L>&amp; pesed in alle &thorn;inges, &thorn;anked be God of heuen.
<PB REF="00000363.tif" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;AN said Sir Henry, nedes burd him wende</L>
<L>To France &amp; Normundie, to witte a certeyn ende.</L>
<L>At Parys wild he be, at &thorn;er parlement.</L>
<L>&thorn;er wille wald he se, to what &thorn;ei wild consent.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e duzepers &thorn;e sothe wild he wite,</L>
<L>&amp; on what maners, &amp; wharto he suld lite,</L>
<L>&amp; whedir &thorn;ei wild to werre, or &thorn;ei wild nouht,</L>
<L>Or alle in luf sperre &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ei had wrouht.</L>
<L>&para; He sauh wele bi signe, he drouh fast tille elde,</L>
<L>Long myght he not regne, ne on his lif belde.</L>
<L>Wherfor Henry said he wild, or he went,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e summe wer laid of his testament.</L>
<L>Liste &amp; I salle rede &thorn;e parcelles what amountes,</L>
<L>If any man in dede wille keste in a countes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEX &thorn;ousand marke tille Acres did he fend.</L>
<L>Ageyn his comyng &thorn;idere, bi marchandz so he wend.</L>
<L>Fifty &thorn;ousand marcs had he lent abbeis,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De testa|mento Hen|ricisecundi, facto apud Waltham, per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at wer in pouerte, vp &thorn;am forto reise.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at was gyuen, &amp; befor hand lent,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was not in cofre, whan he mad testament.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;at was in cofre, &amp; in his cofines,</L>
<L>He mad his testament, als did o&thorn;er pilgrimes.</L>
<L>&para; To Waltham &yogh;ede &thorn;e kyng, his testament to make,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;us quathe he his &thorn;ing, for his soule sake.</L>
<L>&para; To temples in Acres he quath fiue &thorn;ousand marke,</L>
<L>&amp; fiue thousand to &thorn;e hospitale, for &thorn;ei were in karke.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e folk &thorn;at duelled, Acres forto fende,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er fiue &thorn;ousand marke he gaf &thorn;am to spende.
<PB REF="00000364.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>&para; Tille o&thorn;er houses of &thorn;e cuntre fiue &thorn;ousand marke he gaf,</L>
<L>Tille heremites &amp; tille seke men, &amp; o&thorn;er of suilk raf.</L>
<L>&para; Tille monkes &amp; to Chanons, &thorn;at were in Inglond,</L>
<L>Fiue &thorn;ousand marke resceyued &thorn;ei of his hond.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;o of &thorn;at religion, &thorn;at were in Normundie,</L>
<L>Fiue &thorn;ousand mark vnto &thorn;er tresorie.</L>
<L>&para; &amp; to meselle houses of &thorn;at same lond,</L>
<L>&thorn;re &thorn;ousand mark vnto &thorn;er spense he fond.</L>
<L>&para; To ladies of habite, Vilers &amp; Mortayn,</L>
<L>He gaf tuo hundreth mark, I trowe &thorn;ei were fayn.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;o religiouses &thorn;at were in Gascoyne,</L>
<L>He gaf a &thorn;ousand mark, withouten essoyne.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;am of Founz Eberard, &thorn;er his body lis,</L>
<L>He gaf tuo &thorn;ousand mark, &thorn;o ladies of pris.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e ladies of Bretayn, men calle Seynt Suplice,</L>
<L>He gaf a hundreth mark, to mend &thorn;er office.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e houses of Chartres tuo &thorn;ousand mark bi counte,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;re &thorn;ousand mark to &thorn;e order of Grant mounte.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e ordre of Cisteaus he gaf tuo &thorn;ousand mark,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ordre of Clony a &thorn;ousand, to lay vp in arke.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e ordre of Premonstere tuo hundreth mark &thorn;ei had.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e ladies of Markayne a hundreh mark &thorn;ei lad.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e houses of Arroys, &thorn;at ere bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Tuo hundreth mark &thorn;orgh testament gaf he.</L>
<L>&para; To women of Inglond, of gentille lynage,</L>
<L>A hunderth mark of gold, to &thorn;er mariage.</L>
<L>&para; To gentille, &amp; tille o&thorn;er, &thorn;at were in Normundie,</L>
<L>A hundreth mark of gold &thorn;ei had to &thorn;er partie.
<PB REF="00000365.tif" N="137"></L>
<L>&para; To gentille women of Aniowe, of non auancement,</L>
<L>A hundreth mark of gold vnto &thorn;am was sent.</L>
<L>Withouten &thorn;is testament &thorn;at he did writen,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e grete tresore tille Acres was witen,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he lent religiouse to bring &thorn;am aboue,</L>
<L>Fourty &thorn;ousand mark he gaf for Gode loue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Kaunt le Rey Henry ad fet son testament, Al parle|ment de Fraunce son chemyn enprent. Touz les melz va|nez [<I>sive</I> vauez] de Douer a Derwent Sunt oue [<I>sive</I> ouf] le Rey alez, atyrez richement. Dount par my Parys est dist communement, Ke vnkes vi|rent Reis oue si [<I>sive</I> ouf ly] bele gent, <I>Petri nostri ex|emplaria Gallica.</I></NOTE>WHAN &thorn;e kyng Henry had mad his testament,</L>
<L>He dight his oste redy, &amp; to Parys went.</L>
<L>Fro . . erwent to Douere &thorn;at best wer wor&thorn;i</L>
<L>With . . . . . went &thorn;ei ouer, atired richeli.</L>
<L>&thorn;a . . . . . . nd &thorn;e folk in Parys, &thorn;at &thorn;ei wele herd,</L>
<L>With so fayre folk of pris neuer to prince ferd.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kyng of France he asked amendment,</L>
<L>&thorn;e duzepers for chance &thorn;ei ros with on assent,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;er conseile kaste &thorn;er chance on ilk side,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei acordid at &thorn;e laste, &thorn;at pes mot best betide.</L>
<L>Whan pes was set certeyn bituex &thorn;o kynges tueye,</L>
<L>&amp; Normundie &thorn;orgh seyen, tille Inglond he tok &thorn;e weye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e &yogh;ere afterward at midsomer men teld,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng in Oxenford his parlement held.</L>
<L>Bi his writte he sent after kyng William:</L>
<L>William dight him &amp; went, tille Oxenford he cam,
<PB REF="00000366.tif" N="138"></L>
<L>&amp; suore to kyng Henry &thorn;e next Assumpcion,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was of our Lady, suld com to &yogh;ork his toun,</L>
<L>&amp; bring &thorn;ider his clergie of Scotlond &thorn;e barons.</L>
<L>He did so certeynlie &thorn;e day of his somons.</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;ei mad ilkon homage &amp; feaute,</L>
<L>Not to &thorn;e fader alle on, bot tille his heir suld be,</L>
<L>&amp; obliged &thorn;am with scritte, hyngand ilk a seale,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er dede was perfite, &amp; his homage leale.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e kirke of Scotland to Canterbirie ore se</L>
<L>Obliged &thorn;am &amp; band, as to &thorn;er primalte;</L>
<L>&amp; if &thorn;e Scottis kyng mistake in any braide</L>
<L>&para; Of treson in any &thorn;yng, ageyn Henry forsaid,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Statutum factum in|ter Angli|am &amp; Sco|ciam per assensum.</NOTE></L>
<L>The barons &amp; &thorn;e clergie in on wer alle schryuen,</L>
<L>Vnto kyng Henrie ageyn William suld be gyuen.</L>
<L>&amp; if it so betide, &thorn;at any thefe or feloun</L>
<L>Fle fro Inglond side to Scotlond regioun,</L>
<L>Bot he mak &thorn;am to wite, whi &thorn;at he is comen,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e courte may him quite o chance if he be nomen.</L>
<L>If he be els funden, for thefe tald &amp; hent,</L>
<L>Tille Inglond brouht alle bunden, &amp; &thorn;er haf jugement.</L>
<L>&para; Als if it so be, of Scotlond skape a thefe,</L>
<L>&amp; tille Inglond fle, als a felon grefe,</L>
<L>Bot if he to &thorn;er baylifes mak his sikernesse,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei will him maynpis, if he wer cald to stresse,</L>
<L>If he folowand were souht for &thorn;at felonie,</L>
<L>Ageynto Scotland be brouht, &amp; &thorn;er hanged hie.
<PB REF="00000367.tif" N="139"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN &thorn;is &thorn;ing was grant, Henry dred disceite,</L>
<L>He wild, &thorn;at his conant were holden stable &amp; streite,</L>
<L>He sesed fiue castels, &amp; held &thorn;am in his wage,</L>
<L>Foure erles &amp; sextene kynghtes &thorn;erfor in his ostage,</L>
<L>Ilkon of &thorn;e knyghtes had a barony,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei &amp; alle &thorn;er rightes were don in his mercy.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Henry for his owen had holden &thorn;at seignorie,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e dede was knowen &thorn;orghout Albanie,</L>
<L>&thorn;e castels &amp; ostagers he &yogh;ald &thorn;orgh curteysie,</L>
<L>&amp; `with<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Abesse malim. Nam exem|plaria Gallica</I>, par chartre en|sele leRey descoz se lye, <I>i.e.per chartam sigillatam Rex Scoci&aelig; seipsum obligavit.</I></NOTE> William with chartre bond him tille Henrie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he &amp; his heires, &amp; alle &thorn;er progenie</L>
<L>Of Scotlond, suld hold of Henry certeynlie</L>
<L>&amp; of alle his heires, &amp; com to &thorn;er crie.</L>
<L>&amp; homage &amp; feaute to mak &thorn;am redie.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;is was set &amp; stabled, &amp; pes cried on hii,</L>
<L>Henry &thorn;e &yogh;ong kyng &yogh;ede to Normundie,</L>
<L>&amp; died <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>His death was much lamented by his Fa|ther, notwithstanding he had been a disobedient Son; which disobedience arose</I> (<I>in a great measure</I>) <I>out of discontent, that his Father had abandon'd his</I> [<I>young Henry's</I>] <I>Mother</I>, [<I>Q. Eleanor</I>,) <I>and given himself up intirely</I> (<I>as it were</I>) <I>to the Will of the fine young</I> Wench <I>Ro|samond, a thing that struck al|so very much upon the young King's Brothers, Richard and John. For which reason it is, that we have this Passage in Ra|stall's Chronicle:</I> This kynge henry let crowne henry his eldyst sonne kynge of Eng|lande &verbar; and went hym selfe into Normandye &verbar; but his son henry dyed before his fa|ther &verbar; and therfore he is nat accounted in the nombre of kynges of Englande. This Henry his son and his. ii. bretherne &verbar; John &verbar; &amp; Ry|charde &verbar; made warre agaynst theyr father. Some say the cause of the warre was be|cause the kynge imprisoned Elynor his wyfe &verbar; whiche was kept in prison tyll the kynge dyed &verbar; and he kept the wenche Rosamonde.</NOTE>&thorn;er &thorn;at &yogh;ere, &amp; biried solemplie.
<PB REF="00000368.tif" N="140"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;is &yogh;ong kyng was dede &amp; laid in graue,</L>
<L>Fro Jerusalem com tiyng, &thorn;at help burd it haue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAT tyme in Jerusalem <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, was.</NOTE>wad dede a douhty kyng,</L>
<L>(Was blode non of his teme, bot a mayden &yogh;ing)</L>
<L>Baldewyn &thorn;e meselle, his name so hight,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Balde|wino lepro|so, &amp; Wil|lelmo Ac|quitani&aelig;, pro auxilio in Angli|am veni|ente.</NOTE></L>
<L>Noble kyng &amp; lele, &amp; wele &yogh;emed his right.</L>
<L>Neuer in his lyue he lese a fote of lond,</L>
<L>The Sarazins gan him dryue, &thorn;ei were him euer fleand.</L>
<L>For foule meselrie he comond with no man,</L>
<L>Sarazin with maistrie neuer nouht of him wan.</L>
<L>With him was a knyght, &amp; vnder him chefetayn,</L>
<L>&amp; name couth of myght, William of Aquitayn.</L>
<L>Whan Badwyn was dede, he weddid &thorn;e mayden &yogh;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e Cristen rede William was chosen kyng.</L>
<L>For &thorn;is bold Baldewyn Cristen men gan morne,</L>
<L>Gode hap had &thorn;e Sarazin ageyn on vs to turne.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins on vs cam, our Cristen foue gan felle,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at kyng William no langere &thorn;er durst duelle.</L>
<L>Bode com to &thorn;is lond, for help &amp; socour,</L>
<L>Kyng Henry he fond, &amp; schewed him alle his stour,</L>
<L>How &thorn;e fals soudan destroied alle &thorn;e lond,</L>
<L>Slouh ilk Cristen man, or els in prison bond,
<PB REF="00000369.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>"&thorn;erfore I pray to &yogh;ow, haste &thorn;at &yogh;e wer comen,</L>
<L>"Bi &thorn;is is Acres now biseged, or alle nomen.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e kyng it herd, he wept with his ine,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex lacri|matns est.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Cristen so misferd, &thorn;e Sarazins did so pyne.</L>
<L>He said, "My sonne, myn heyre, &thorn;at was corouned late,</L>
<L>"Of his lif was my speyre, he myght haf taken &thorn;e gate.</L>
<L>"Bot now is he dede, myn heyre &thorn;at bare coroune,</L>
<L>"&thorn;erfor I kan no rede, I doute me of tresoune.</L>
<L>"For if I were of lond, &thorn;e werre suld sone bigynne,</L>
<L>"Aliens suld sone fond, our heritage to wynne.</L>
<L>"Richard my sonne is knyght, with me wild he go,</L>
<L>"Sone suld we lese our right, if we were fer &thorn;er fro.</L>
<L>"Fayn I wild purueie for Acres, &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>"Ordeyned wer som weie, how it mot saued be.</L>
<L>William tok his leue at our kyng Henry,</L>
<L>Giftes wele to leue he had richely.</L>
<L>He went to &thorn;e kyng of France, &amp; schewed him his resons,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;er ordenance &thorn;er duzepers gaf respons.</L>
<L>Bifor Sir William &thorn;e duzepers gaf ansuere,</L>
<L>"It er bot tuo kyngdams on &thorn;is half Grece to were.</L>
<L>"France &amp; Inglond &thorn;ise tuo regions,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio Francorum Willelmo Aquitani&aelig; per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&amp; er in diuerse lond, &amp; in sere bandons:</L>
<L>"Henry in Inglond wonnes, &amp; has tresore inouh,</L>
<L>"Richard &amp; Jon his sonnes fulle felle, &amp; wille non bouh.</L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;at &yogh;e were gone, &amp; we went with &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at Richard &amp; Jon wille waken vn mykelle wouh.</L>
<L>"Bot whan kyng Henry &amp; his sonnes wille go,</L>
<L>"We salle be redy, forto wend with &thorn;o.
<PB REF="00000370.tif" N="142"></L>
<L>William went ageyn vnto Jerusalem,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ise kynges tueyn was &yogh;it no bote o beame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HENRY for his trespas did fulle grete honour</L>
<L>To &thorn;e martir Saynt Thomas, for mercy &amp; socour.</L>
<L>Sex &yogh;ere si&thorn;en lyued he in wo &amp; sorow soure.</L>
<L>He went ouer &thorn;e se, &amp; lay in grete langoure.</L>
<L>In grete sekenesse &amp; hard he lay in Normundie:</L>
<L>Tille him com his sonne Richard, forsoth, fulle kyndelie,</L>
<L>&amp; whan Henry suld die Richard &thorn;orgh blissyng bond,</L>
<L>He suld his cheualrie vse in &thorn;e holy lond,</L>
<L>"I salle leue &thorn;e inouh for to do with alle.</L>
<L>"Fader," he said, "for &yogh;ow certes &thorn;ider I salle.</L>
<L>Whan he had regned here, &amp; felt of fele assaies,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Lege</I>, Foure &amp; thritty <I>&amp;c. Nam</I>, Apres. xxx. iiii. annz. vi. mays. xii. jours Du regalte ReyHenry cessaynt ses labours. Il gist al Fount Ebrard en labbeye de sorours <I>in MSS. Gallicis.</I></NOTE>Foure &amp; tuenty &yogh;ere sex monethes &amp; tuelf dayes,</L>
<L>No more of him to seie, he died sone afterward.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mortuus est Henricus secundus, Anno Do|mini. M<SUP>o</SUP>. C. Lxxxix<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>He ligges in an abbeie, men calle &thorn;e Founz Everard.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; a hundred &thorn;e dete fourscore &amp; nyne.</L>
<L>So many &yogh;ers it pundred, whan he passed &thorn;is pyne.</L>
<L>In a moneth mirie, Septembre &thorn;e gynnyng,</L>
<L>Baudwyn of Canterbirie com to coroune &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>Richard at Londoun, opon a Sonenday,</L>
<L>At Westmynstre tok &thorn;e coroun, of &yogh;ork bishop Geffray<NOTE PLACE="marg">Coronacio Regis Ri|cardi apud Londo|ni m.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was sent after &thorn;at tyde, him felle to be &thorn;e to&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e fadere side he was Richarde's bro&thorn;er.
<PB REF="00000371.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>Richard his pallion bi messengere did com,</L>
<L>&amp; his confirmacion fro &thorn;e courte of Rome.</L>
<L>&para; Comen er to kyng Richard bo&thorn;e erle &amp; baroun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at had &thorn;e lond in ward &thorn;orgh out &thorn;e regioun,</L>
<L>Knyghtes &amp; burgeis, serganz als was resoun,</L>
<L>Homage to mak alle weis &thorn;at felle vnto &thorn;e coroun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pes did he crie, &amp; purueid warnisoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins &thorn;orgh maistrie haf won Acres toun.</L>
<L>Inglis &amp; Normant, knyghtes for rewardoun,</L>
<L>With Richard ere in conant ageyn Sarazins feloun.</L>
<L>His fader left him inouh, penyes grete foysoun,</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;at he &thorn;e way not widrouh opon his benisoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng of France was went to Saynt Denys to holde</L>
<L>His priue parlement, &amp; &thorn;er one him it tolde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de stultiloquio reg's Fran|ci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at Richard priuely his purueiyance did gynne</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e paemy, &thorn;e lond Surrie to wynne.</L>
<L>To Paris turned &thorn;e kyng, for &thorn;at ilk sawe,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er a samenyng his barons &thorn;ider gan drawe.</L>
<L>He bisouh in &thorn;am alle, to conseil at &thorn;at nede,</L>
<L>What help mot best falle, for &thorn;e Sarazins drede,</L>
<L>&amp; teld &thorn;am an outrage, &thorn;at Richard &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>Wille stele &thorn;is viage, withouten my wityng.</L>
<L>Loke how kyng Philip said vncurteisly,</L>
<L>Dayet haf his lip, &amp; his nose &thorn;erby.</L>
<L>Forto &thorn;at parlement com Richard messengers,</L>
<L>&thorn;at to Philip wer sent, &amp; to &thorn;e duzepers.</L>
<L>&thorn;e names of &thorn;am &thorn;at cam was &thorn;e erle of Peiters,</L>
<L>Of Almarle erle William, &amp; an erle Rogers,
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>Lucas de Lucie, &amp; Roberd de Coynguers,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise grete Philip of France, &amp; alle his conseilers.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE erle of Almarle said, "Richard our Inglis kyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nuncium Ricardi editum in curia regis Franci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>"His luf is tille &yogh;ow laid, &amp; luf is his gretyng,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &yogh;e wille tak to herte, &thorn;e grete noyse &amp; crie</L>
<L>"Fro Acres &thorn;at comes so smerte, lorn is so doelfullie.</L>
<L>"Our Cristen men ere lorn, &thorn;e Sarazins alle aboue,</L>
<L>"&thorn;erfor Richard beforn praies &yogh;ow for loue,</L>
<L>"For him &thorn;at on &thorn;e croice died for mankynde,</L>
<L>"Bes bo&thorn;e at a voice, in one &yogh;our wille be mynde,</L>
<L>"To help &thorn;e Cristen men, &thorn;at Jhesu Criste bouht,</L>
<L>"Ageyn &thorn;e oste paen, &thorn;at him lufed neuer nouht.</L>
<L>"Richard him atires, his wille &thorn;erto is fest,</L>
<L>"So mykelle he &thorn;ider desires, &thorn;at he may haf no rest.</L>
<L>"If &yogh;e of him haf help, &amp; he for &yogh;ow socour,</L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;is world salle &yogh;elp of &yogh;our grete honour.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e duzepers herd &thorn;e bodword of Richard</L>
<L>To Philip, &thorn;ei ansuerd, "his sond &yogh;e salle reward.</L>
<L>"He bedes &yogh;ow luf inouh, &yogh;e &thorn;ank him of his sond.</L>
<L>"So noble bot on of &yogh;ow is non, be water no land.</L>
<L>"Richer kyng is non in &thorn;is world bot &yogh;e,</L>
<L>"No valianter of bon in Cristendam als he.</L>
<L>"Large er &thorn;o londes, &thorn;at his eldres wonnen,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e dedes of &thorn;er hondes &thorn;orgh reames er ronnen.</L>
<L>"Siluer he has inouh, his fader has him fonden</L>
<L>"Knyghtes to do his prouh, with skrite tille him er bonden.</L>
<L>"To whom Acres salle be &yogh;olden also tite,</L>
<L>"His felauschip to fle, to God &yogh;e do despite.
<PB REF="00000373.tif" N="145"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE>PILIP sent ageyn to Richard curteyly<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio regis Fran|corum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bode bi &thorn;o certeyn, said often grant mercy,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;anked him his gode wille, &amp; his noble sond,</L>
<L>&amp; he wild fulfille, &amp; at his myght suld fond,</L>
<L>&amp; sent Richard to say, &thorn;e next Marche folowand</L>
<L>He suld take &thorn;at way, if wynde wild with him stand,</L>
<L>At Marsile to aryue, if he of lif had space,</L>
<L>&amp; if &thorn;e wynde wild dryue, &thorn;orgh myght &amp; Gode's grace.</L>
<L>He praied Richard &thorn;e kyng, &amp; alle his men of Gode,</L>
<L>To leue for no preching, &thorn;at way &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne &yogh;ode.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Richard had conceyued, &thorn;at Philip &thorn;erto stode,</L>
<L>His mobles on siluer reised &thorn;orgh Inglond alle his gode,</L>
<L>Rentes &amp; som feez he comandid to selle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Vendidit mobilia &amp; maneria.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at burgh no Citez of taliage suld non telle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e tende suld be nouht, no &thorn;e tuende non make.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Durham bouht Saberg, with &thorn;e wapentake.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Wynchestre at &thorn;e kyng he bouht</L>
<L>Two maners tille his estre, &amp; Richard wisly wrouht.</L>
<L>For he wele vnderstode of taliage was grete drede,</L>
<L>It suld neuer do gode, ne &thorn;er withalle suld spede.</L>
<L>Namely to &thorn;e holy lond, &thorn;ider he &thorn;ouht to go,</L>
<L>In taliage non he bond, ne robbed ne did wo.</L>
<L>He sent to &thorn;e Scottis kyng, &thorn;at he suld com &amp; do,</L>
<L>&amp; mak pes for &thorn;at &thorn;ing, &thorn;at he was halden to.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e moneth of Nouembre, after Alhalwemesse,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wele is to remembre, com kyng William alle fresse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De homa|gio &amp; obli|gacione regis Scot|torum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Batand to Canterbiri, &amp; &thorn;er &yogh;ald him his fee.</L>
<L>Kyng Richard our sire homage &amp; feaute
<PB REF="00000374.tif" N="146"></L>
<L>He mad for alle &thorn;o landes, &thorn;at he of Inglond held,</L>
<L>&amp; tille &thorn;e pes he standes, &thorn;at bowes tille his scheld,</L>
<L>&yogh;it of penyes rounde to Richard gan he bede</L>
<L>Sexti &thorn;ousand pounde, to mende his misdede.</L>
<L>&amp; Richard on &thorn;is wise forgaf it William so,</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;at seruise, &thorn;at Malcolme was wone to do</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e Inglis kynges, as right was &amp; skille,</L>
<L>&amp; do alle &thorn;e comynges, whan bodword com &thorn;am tille,</L>
<L>To London forto com, whan parlement suld be,</L>
<L>Als custom was wonne, &amp; tak &thorn;er his liuere.</L>
<L>&amp; Richard als quik &yogh;ald to kyng William</L>
<L>Rokesburgh &amp; Berwik, &thorn;at he in his hand nam.</L>
<L>William tok his leue, his way to Scotland ches,</L>
<L>Wele mot William cheue, &amp; alle &thorn;at lufes pes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>KYNG Richard &yogh;it duellis, &amp; purueis him to fare,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Stabilivit justitiarios &amp; custodes terr&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; mykelle &thorn;ing sellis, siluer forto &yogh;are.</L>
<L>Wardans sette he stable, trewe men at his myght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer lufed fable, bot mayntend pes &amp; right.</L>
<L>Sire Huge of Durham, bisshop &amp; man wor&thorn;i:</L>
<L>An o&thorn;er Sir William, bisshop of Ely.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise suld kepe &thorn;e lond, &amp; &thorn;e dignites,</L>
<L>Justises tille &thorn;am he bond, to kepe &thorn;e lawes &amp; feez;</L>
<L>Huge Bardolf fulle fers, William Marschalle his pere,</L>
<L>Geffrey le fitz Pers, William dela Bruere:</L>
<L>&thorn;ise were mayntenours, to sustene &thorn;e coroun,</L>
<L>&amp; rightfulle gouernours &thorn;e folk in feld &amp; toun.</L>
<L>&para; Now has he brought to stalle, his lond stabled redy,</L>
<L>&amp; now with his folk alle, he wendis to Normundy,
<PB REF="00000375.tif" N="147"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er he purueis him tille Acres &amp; Sully.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Applicuit in Nor|manniam.</NOTE></L>
<L>On Gode's enmys grim he gadres gode party.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cite of Rouhan his &yogh;ole feste he held</L>
<L>With many douhty man, &amp; knyghtes gode of scheld.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E Monenday &thorn;at felle to be next after &thorn;e tuelft day,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng of France &amp; he, at &thorn;e riuer of S. Rymay,</L>
<L>Held a parlement, gode sikernes to make,</L>
<L>&thorn;at bo&thorn;e with on assent &thorn;e way suld vndertake.</L>
<L>Ilkon sikered o&thorn;er with scrite &amp; seale &thorn;erby,</L>
<L>Togidere suore &thorn;am bre&thorn;er, wherfor &thorn;e clergy</L>
<L>Gaf a grete cursyng on whilk of &thorn;am so brak,</L>
<L>Bigan a wikked &thorn;ing, &thorn;at euelle bituex &thorn;am spak.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Modo pa|raverunt se ad terram sanctam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Now is Philip certeyn, he gos to S. Deny,</L>
<L>&amp; Richard turnes ageyn, to dight his nauy.</L>
<L>He serches ilk coste of alle his seignorie,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Guyours of his oste, &thorn;ise wer withouten lie:</L>
<L>&thorn;e Ersebisshop of Anxus, danz Guard of renoun,</L>
<L>With ano&thorn;er bisshop, Bernard of Bayoun,</L>
<L>&amp; Richard de Cameuile, &amp; Roberd du Sabloun,</L>
<L>&amp; William de Fortiz was lord of Oleroun,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise gouerne &thorn;er nauie, now ere &thorn;ei in &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e paemie, &thorn;ider &thorn;ei &yogh;erned to be.</L>
<L>Richard said &thorn;am his wille, "mariners if &yogh;e moun,</L>
<L>"Aryues in to Marsille, with Gode's benisoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;is was &thorn;e first woke of &thorn;e passion,</L>
<L>As I on on boke gan loke, &thorn;e oste clerke &amp; baron</L>
<L>Wer sailand in &thorn;e se toward Marsille &thorn;at toun.</L>
<L>Help &thorn;am &thorn;er &thorn;ei wild be Criste &amp; Say Simioun.
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="148"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei had in &thorn;er route a hundreth schippes &amp; ten,</L>
<L>Bot God &thorn;ei had no doute, ne no defaute of men.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON &thorn;e fifte day changed &thorn;er wynde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce mira|culum &amp; de maris periculo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Reft &thorn;am &thorn;e right way, to wend &thorn;e wer blynde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e right se of Bretayn, &thorn;er out were &thorn;ei went,</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e se of Spayn wer dryuen in a torment</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e Sarazins, bot God, &thorn;at grace &thorn;am lent,</L>
<L>Saued &thorn;am alle &thorn;o tymes fro &thorn;er encumberment.</L>
<L>Ten schippes wer dryuen, &thorn;orgh ille auisement,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh a tempest ryuen, &thorn;e schipmen held &thorn;am schent.</L>
<L>On &thorn;er was on depe kroken &amp; alle to rent,</L>
<L>&thorn;e nien God gan kepe, &thorn;at grace he &thorn;am sent.</L>
<L>Eft God &thorn;ei bisouht, to saue &thorn;am in &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>Sauely to hauen be brouht, for luf of S. Thomas,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for holy kirke suffred martirdam,</L>
<L>&amp; God for &thorn;am gan wirke, her how a voice cam.</L>
<L>A schip &thorn;er was of London, richely atired,</L>
<L>A hundreth &thorn;er in fondon, to serue God desired.</L>
<L>Biside &thorn;am on &thorn;er schip com a bisshop doun,</L>
<L>&thorn;e mast in hand gan kip, with croice &amp; pallioun,</L>
<L>&amp; a kyng &thorn;e sihi, of gold schone his coroun,</L>
<L>A no&thorn;er bisshop &thorn;am bi, &thorn;e first said his sermoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;an said &thorn;e Ersbisshop to Londreis wordes suete,</L>
<L>"I am Thomas &yogh;our hope, to whom &yogh;e crie &amp; grete,</L>
<L>"Martir of Canterbire, &yogh;our bale salle I bete.</L>
<L>"Seynt Edmunde &thorn;e martire his help I &yogh;ow hete,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e bisshop S. Nicholas, whos help is ay redie</L>
<L>"To schipmen in alle cas, whan &thorn;ei on him crie.
<PB REF="00000377.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>"We &thorn;re haf &thorn;e ward of God &amp; our ladie,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e schippes of kyng Richard to kepe &amp; &yogh;ow &thorn;am bie.</L>
<L>After &thorn;is biheste, &thorn;at Thomas to &thorn;am said,</L>
<L>Sone alle &thorn;e tempest in a throwe was laid.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise nine schippes gan ride &thorn;er wyld wynd &thorn;am driue,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei ne wist to what side, ne what hauen in to riue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Leons sur le Rone was Philip &amp; Richard,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Johan|na, sorore sua.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ei spak &amp; mad &thorn;er mone, what hauen &thorn;e mot toward.</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;e cuntre &thorn;orgh so grete folk mot men se,</L>
<L>&thorn;at nou&thorn;er cite ne burgh myght &thorn;ei in herberd be.</L>
<L>Philip toward Gene his oste did alle go,</L>
<L>&amp; Richard oste bidene at Marsille left alle &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&para; To mete on a while &thorn;e trompes blowe alle clere,</L>
<L>Batand fro Cezile com him a messengere,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e quene dam Jone, his awen sister dere.</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;am euerilkone he told kyng Richere,</L>
<L>Dede is kyng William, &thorn;at regned in Cezile,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Jone &thorn;e lady nam, he lyued bot a while.</L>
<L>&thorn;at erle is of Tancre, Geffrey a douhty knyght,</L>
<L>&amp; valiant man of dede, &amp; to &thorn;e coroun has right,</L>
<L>He regnes after him, &amp; late had &thorn;e coroune,</L>
<L>To Jone he is fulle grim, &amp; haldes hir in prisoune.</L>
<L>Herfor kyng Richard wrathes him &amp; sais,</L>
<L>"Dight vs &thorn;ider ward our busses &amp; galais,</L>
<L>"Mi sister I wille out wyn or I ferrer go.</L>
<L>"Bot he bigyn Cezile he turnes fro,</L>
<L>"&amp; bot he wille with pes acorde in reson,</L>
<L>"It salle rewe him &thorn;at res, &thorn;at he to Jone has done.
<PB REF="00000378.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>&thorn;e date was a &thorn;ousand a hundreth &amp; ninetie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. C<SUP>o</SUP>. LXXXX<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at R. was sailand toward paemie.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e seuent day of heruest, in &thorn;at ilk &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I rakend last, writen abouen here,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Richard turned to Gene, &amp; whan he com to lond,</L>
<L>Philip was mykelle to mene, R. seke him fond.</L>
<L>Bot mykelle he comfortid him, &amp; si&thorn;en tok his leue,</L>
<L>Toward Cezile fulle grim, &thorn;e kyng he &thorn;ouht to greue.</L>
<L>&para; Whan his flete was alle at Tibre euerilkone,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape a cardinalle sent Sir Octobone.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Hic venit Octobonus Cardinalis ad Regem Ricardum.</NOTE></L>
<L>What Richard spak, &amp; he conselle is &amp; was,</L>
<L>To me it is priue, I sauh it in no pas.</L>
<L>&thorn;er duellid R. schip &thorn;re daies to gesse,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;at was kyng Philep risen of his sekenesse,</L>
<L>&amp; was in Cezile ariued at Meschyne,</L>
<L>&amp; after in a while com R. euen as lyne,</L>
<L>&thorn;e day of &thorn;e croice, in &thorn;e heruest tide,</L>
<L>Right als Gode's voice had ordeynd him to ride.</L>
<L>Were &thorn;o schippes nine, &thorn;at R. wend haf lorn,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e hauen of Meschyne ariued litille beforn.</L>
<L>It was a Gode's grace, &verbar; at &thorn;at ilk nauie</L>
<L>Ariued in &thorn;at place, &thorn;er Richard suld lie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THRE days in &thorn;at cite duellid kyng Richard,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Misit nun|cium ad Tancredum Regem.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng of Tancre he sent his letter hard.</L>
<L>"To deliuer his sister Jon out of his prison</L>
<L>"Men mad tille him grete mone, it was without reson.</L>
<L>"Bot he deliuer hir me with luf, at my praiere,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at tyme salle he se, scho salle be bouht folle dere.
<PB REF="00000379.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is kyng of Tancrede he was a wys knyght,</L>
<L>He sauh it was to drede, &amp; he did not alle right.</L>
<L>He sauh Richard an ired, &amp; his mykelle myght,</L>
<L>His folk armed &amp; tired, &amp; ay redy to fight.</L>
<L>He sent his sister Jone with mykelle honeste,</L>
<L>With his barons ilkone, to Mischines &thorn;at cite.</L>
<L>Philip was curteise, ageyn dame Jone he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Tille hir bro&thorn;er paleise with grete honour did lede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AN ilde was &thorn;er biside, &thorn;at a Sarazin held,</L>
<L>Trouage he gaf bi tide to Cristen men, &thorn;ei teld.</L>
<L>Allas! said Richard, &thorn;at euer it suld so be,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Cristen &thorn;orgh forward suld grant a Sarazin fre.</L>
<L>A water &thorn;at closed it in, &thorn;at flum was de la fare,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wonnyng of &thorn;e Sarazin, &thorn;at ilde hight Labamare.</L>
<L>Kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> Richad it wan, &amp; tille his sister it gaf,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins ilk man he slouh alle rif &amp; raf.</L>
<L>&para; An o&thorn;er ilde biside, men cald it Griffonie,</L>
<L>Richard &thorn;at ilk tide, he did &thorn;am alle out flie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wonnyng of &thorn;at ilde Richard gon &thorn;am reue,</L>
<L>Was non of &thorn;am so wilde, &thorn;at lenger durst &thorn;er leue.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e folk &thorn;is herd, &thorn;e burgeis of Meschyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;er &yogh;ates ageyn him sperd, &amp; wild not lat him in.</L>
<L>Wherfor &thorn;e contek on &thorn;is maner it cam,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;ei did &thorn;at chek, an oth he suore to gram,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e kyng wilde mende &thorn;at &thorn;ei did him &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>A &thorn;ing he suld sende, to do als lawe it were:</L>
<L>Fulfille &thorn;e testament of kyng William &thorn;at was,</L>
<L>&thorn;at tille his sister ment for dowerie &thorn;at trespas,
<PB REF="00000380.tif" N="152"></L>
<L>&amp; bot he &yogh;ald it alle, &thorn;at is writen &thorn;er in,</L>
<L>With luf, els I salle with werre fond him to wyn.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De fictione regis Phi|lippi.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e kyng of France herd &thorn;o ti&thorn;inges,</L>
<L>&thorn;at so grete distance was bituex &thorn;o kynges,</L>
<L>Conseil gan he take, &thorn;at he suld be partie,</L>
<L>A gode acord to make, forso&thorn;e fulle fayntlie.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles &thorn;e kyng of Tancrede did fulle curteisly,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De humili|tate &amp; sa|pientia re|gis Tan|credi.</NOTE></L>
<L>To kyng R. he &yogh;ede, &amp; said he was redy,</L>
<L>&thorn;e testament to fulfille of kyng William,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at his men fulle ille vnskilfully nam.</L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;at was reson, I wille amend it wele,</L>
<L>"&amp; tille &thorn;i sister haf don plenerly ilka dele,</L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;at me felle to do of William's<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> testament.</NOTE> testamet.</L>
<L>"Witnes I tak hir to hir seluen in present.</L>
<L>"Hir seluen dame Jone acorded with his sawe,</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;e testament alone he has don alle &thorn;e law,</L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;at fellc to me, bot &yogh;it I ask a no&thorn;er,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at fallis vnto &thorn;e kyng Richard my bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>"Of my lordes witeword, witnes &thorn;er of haf I.</L>
<L>"Of gold &thorn;er is a borde, &amp; tretels &thorn;er bi,</L>
<L>"Of siluer o&thorn;er vesselle gilte fulle richeli;</L>
<L>"&amp; &yogh;it a no&thorn;er jowelle fairer &amp; wor&thorn;i,</L>
<L>"A pauillon of honour, with riche atisfement,</L>
<L>"To serue an Emperour at a parlement.</L>
<L>"&thorn;us quath my lorde &thorn;e, &thorn;at tyme he suld die,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e soth forto say, &amp; witnes wille not lie.
<PB REF="00000381.tif" N="153"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"DAME," said Tancred, "of trestels &amp; borde</L>
<L>"Fulfille I salle in dede &thorn;e kynge's witworde.</L>
<L>Fourti &thorn;ousand vnces of gold he bede &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&amp; R. tok &thorn;e pundes, withouten more sayng.</L>
<L>"Bot &thorn;is," he said, "I saue, &thorn;at Arthure my cosyn</L>
<L>"Tancred douhter salle haue, &amp; alle &thorn;at now is &thorn;in.</L>
<L>Of Bretayn Arthure is als erle of heritage,</L>
<L>&amp; he granted to &thorn;is, confermed &thorn;at mariage.</L>
<L>&para; Als &thorn;ise tuo kynge wore about &thorn;is forward,<NOTE PLACE="marg">H&icirc;c venit mater regis R. ad eum.</NOTE></L>
<L>At Meschyne righ &thorn;ore &thorn;e kynge's moder Richard</L>
<L>Ariued at &thorn;at riuale, brouht him busses &thorn;ritti</L>
<L>Charged with vitaile, with gode men &amp; douhti.</L>
<L>Of Flandres &thorn;e erle Philip, a lorde of honour,</L>
<L>Of Helianore schip he was hir gouernour.</L>
<L>Elianore brouht &thorn;er a fair maiden &yogh;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's douhter of Nauere, to R. &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>Hir name was Berengere, faire woman of age,</L>
<L>Was &thorn;er non hir pere of no heiere parage.</L>
<L>In Cipre of &thorn;at may was mad &thorn;e mariage</L>
<L>At kyng R. pay, &thorn;orgh conselle of baronage.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei were trouth plight, &amp; purueied &thorn;e sposage,</L>
<L>Helianore forth hir dight to Rouhan hir menage,</L>
<L>Bileft dame Berengere at Richarde's costage.</L>
<L>Dame Jone kept hir dere, &thorn;ei lyued als birde in cage,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN pes was alle certeyn of Richard &amp; Tancrede.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ricardus &amp; Tancredus peregrinati sunt ad san|ctam Aga|tham virgi|nem.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e cite of Kateyn in pilgrimage &thorn;ei &yogh;ede.
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e fertre of Saynt Agate Richard made offeryng,</L>
<L>&amp; praied hir of grace to duelle &thorn;at with &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;re dayes tide Richard mad soioure,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons bi &thorn;at side did him grete honoure.</L>
<L>Whan Richard suld wend, he tok leue at Tancrez,</L>
<L>Tancrez was fulle hend, conueied him tuo journez,</L>
<L>Gaf him four schippes grete, &amp; were of way beforn,</L>
<L>&thorn;e tuo charged with whete, &thorn;e to&thorn;er with o&thorn;er corn,</L>
<L>&amp; fiue o&thorn;er galeis with alle &thorn;er apparaile,</L>
<L>Richard was curteis, &thorn;anked his trauaile,</L>
<L>&amp; Richard at &thorn;at turne gaf him a faire Juelle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode suerd Caliburne, &thorn;at Arthur luffed so welle.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an said Sir Tancrede vnto Richard our kyng,</L>
<L>"God, &thorn;at saues at nede bo&thorn;e &thorn;e olde &amp; &yogh;ing,</L>
<L>"Kepe &thorn;e fro mischance, &amp; fro &thorn;e fals enmys,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at er with Philip of France, euer ageyn &thorn;i vis.</L>
<L>"Bi Hugh of Burgoyn he sent a letter vnto me,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at I suld, or &thorn;ou went, be bitraied &thorn;orgh &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"&amp; if werre or wo had risen vs bituen,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;ine to slo with me he suld haue bien.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e soth &thorn;an schewes it, &thorn;at my sawe is trewe,</L>
<L>"Sir haf here &thorn;is writ, &amp; schewe him alle newe.</L>
<L>"If he it geynsay, I wille proue it on him.</L>
<L>&para; Tancred went his way, &amp; Richard wex fulle brim.</L>
<L>R. tok his leue, Sir Roger turned &amp; went,</L>
<L>&amp; R. gan him greue, to Philip &thorn;e letter sent.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De alterca|tione inter Ricardum &amp; Philip|pum per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e nauie com on a stounde, to Meschyns &thorn;at cite,</L>
<L>Biforn him he founde his sister &amp; his meyne.
<PB REF="00000383.tif" N="155"></L>
<L>R. with Philip dele wild he nouht.</L>
<L>Philip bote on his lyppe, &amp; perceyued R. &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at it ment, Philip gan aspie:</L>
<L>A wiles to R. sent, how long he wild &thorn;er lie,</L>
<L>&amp; what tyme he had tight forward his nauie,</L>
<L>His sege to sette &amp; dight, to help &thorn;e Cristen crie?</L>
<L>&para; R. ansuerd &thorn;er tille, &amp; said, "it is foly,</L>
<L>"To schewe counseil &amp; skille, &thorn;at not is to affie,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;hit &thorn;er owen writte &thorn;er dede dos certifie.</L>
<L>"Me &thorn;ink in myn in witte it semed traytorie.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an spak Philip ogrefe said, "I wote what &thorn;is menes,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at was a fals brefe, &amp; forged wele, it semes,</L>
<L>"For my sister Aleyse, &thorn;at is now forsaken,</L>
<L>"For on of mor richenesse of Nauer &thorn;ou has taken.</L>
<L>"It salle not so Richard, I wille &thorn;e gif a gyue,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou salle hold forward, if &thorn;ou wost &thorn;at I lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Respouns del Rey de Fraunce qaunt Richard ad oye, Al matyn ly proue de|uaunt la clergye, Qe le Reis son pere, duk de Normendye, A neyt conou Aleys, qaunt lauait en bayllye, Et fylle engendrait, ke mort est &amp; seuelye. La leye de seyncte eglyse trop serrayt blemye. Et Richard &amp; Aleys de dam|pne dieu maldye, Si en ma|ryage Richard par la se lye, <I>Codices Gallici.</I></NOTE>WHAN Richard vnderstode, &thorn;at kyng Philip had suorne,</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e clergie he stode, &amp; proued it on &thorn;e morne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at his fader Henry &thorn;at ilk Aleyse had knowen,</L>
<L>A childe scho him by, &thorn;at he held for his owen.
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="156"></L>
<L>A mayden childe it was, &amp; now dede is it,</L>
<L>"&thorn;is wer agrete trespas, agayn myn owen inwitte,</L>
<L>"So febli forto wirke, for drede of Gode's awe,</L>
<L>"I Richard haf maugre, &amp; I Aleyse take,</L>
<L>"Whan my fader &amp; she suilk samenyng gan make.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an said kyng Philip tille alle &thorn;o of France,</L>
<L>"Of gile &thorn;is is a trip of Richard desceyuance,</L>
<L>"Gisors my gode cite, with alle &thorn;e purueiance,</L>
<L>"Richard I gaf it fre, to mak &thorn;is aliance</L>
<L>"Of him &amp; hir &thorn;o tuo, &thorn;at er now in distance,</L>
<L>"Ten &thorn;ousand mark &amp; mo, &thorn;at now er in balance,</L>
<L>"&amp; I betraised of alle, bi God, &thorn;at alle may auance,</L>
<L>"I salle bring him to stalle, bot he mak me acquitance.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"NOW," said kyng R. "&thorn;e manace late alle be,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou salle haf reward of Gisors &thorn;i cite;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Concordati sunt per barones.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;e tresore ilk a dele, &thorn;at &thorn;ou me bitauht.</L>
<L>"For me salle haf wele alle &thorn;at &thorn;ou euer auht.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons suffred nouht &thorn;e kynges to be wroth.</L>
<L>Luf &amp; pes &thorn;ei souht, &thorn;at &thorn;ei acorded both.</L>
<L>Richard &yogh;ald him his right, his tresore &amp; his toun,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh witnes &amp; sight, of clerk, erle &amp; baroun,</L>
<L>His sistir forto marie, where God wild loke,</L>
<L>To mak certeyn partie, R. a quitance toke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER &thorn;e acord sone, Philip dight him forward,</L>
<L>To boote mad him bone, &amp; toke leue at Richard.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wynde was in his saile, tille Acres gan him driue,</L>
<L>Bot litille was his trauaile, tille R. gan ariue.
<PB REF="00000385.tif" N="157"></L>
<L>Whan Philip tille Acres cam, litelle was his dede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Romance sais grete skam, who so &thorn;at pas wille rede.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Romancer it sais, R. did mak a pele,</L>
<L>On kastelle wise alle wais, wrouht of tre fulle welle,</L>
<L>Ageyns holy kirke tille Aleyse forto drawe.</L>
<L>In schip he did it lede, to reise vp bi &thorn;e walle,</L>
<L>&amp;, if him stode nede, to couere him with alle.</L>
<L>He reised it at Meschines, of werre ti&thorn;ing he herd,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e ilde of Sarazins &thorn;er &yogh;ates ageyn him sperd.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Romance of Richard sais, he wan &thorn;e toun.</L>
<L>His pele fro &thorn;at forward he cald it <I>mate Griffoun.</I></L>
<L>Tancred he was wys, he did R. wille,</L>
<L>To Philip turned his vys, so &thorn;at he held him stille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Philip on flete, kyng R. &yogh;it duellis,</L>
<L>Hes pele &thorn;at he vpsette eft ageyn it fellis.</L>
<L>For wrath first of Tancrede R. vp it reised,</L>
<L>If he had turned to nede, his folk forto haf eised.</L>
<L>Bot whan &thorn;ei were mad frendes, &thorn;orgh sight baroun,</L>
<L>Tancred to him sendes, praied him take it doun;</L>
<L>&thorn;at no man for envie eft ageyn him held,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;orgh non o&thorn;er harie to do him reise his schelde.</L>
<L>&para; Now purueies him Richard ilk a day alle preste,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De navibus periclitan|tibus in mari versus Cipriam, &amp; Cancel|larius sub|incrsus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tille he be forward, he may haf no reste.</L>
<L>Acres &thorn;an is his triste, opon &thorn;e Sarazin feendes,</L>
<L>To venge Jhesu Criste &thorn;iderward he wendes.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's sister Jone, &amp; dame Berenger,</L>
<L>Formast of ilkone, next &thorn;am his Chanceler.
<PB REF="00000386.tif" N="158"></L>
<L>Roger Mankael &thorn;e Chancelere so hight</L>
<L>His tide felle not wele, a tempest on him light.</L>
<L>His schip was dounborn, his self gan &thorn;er deye.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's seale was lorn, with o&thorn;er busses tueye.</L>
<L>Dame Jone &thorn;e fre to Jhesu scho bisouht,</L>
<L>In Cipres scho mot be to hauen sauely brouht.</L>
<L>&thorn;e mayden Berenger scho was alle ofright,</L>
<L>&thorn;at nou&thorn;er fer no nere &thorn;e kyng scho sauh no sight.</L>
<L>Tuo busses wer forfaren, &thorn;at in &thorn;e tempest brak,</L>
<L>&thorn;e godes attached waren to &thorn;e kyng of Cipres Isaac.</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;at askeped &thorn;at drede, &amp; to Cipres wan,</L>
<L>Isaac did &thorn;am lede, to prison ilk a man.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De navi|bus.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Whan kyng R. herd of &thorn;at mischuos tide,</L>
<L>&amp; how his schippis misferd, he turned vnto &thorn;at tide;</L>
<L>Tille Isaac lettres sent bi Roberd of Thornham,</L>
<L>Sir Steuen with him went, a no&thorn;er knyght William,</L>
<L>"Praie him for God aboue, als I am his pilgrime,</L>
<L>"&yogh;eld it me with loue, &thorn;at he holdes of myne.</L>
<L>"My godes &thorn;at he has &thorn;are, my men deliuere of bond,</L>
<L>"&amp; destorbe not our fare, we salle to &thorn;e holy lond;</L>
<L>"&amp; if he wille nouht deliuer me my &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>"Fulle dere it salle be bouht, bi Jhesu heuen kyng.</L>
<L>e messengers kamen to &thorn;e kyng ysaak.</L>
<L>ysaak tille alle samen, &thorn;is ansuere he spak.</L>
<L>"Messengers, wherto chalange &yogh;e my &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>"&amp; what haf I to do with Inglis tayled kyng?</L>
<L>"&thorn;e godes &thorn;at be fonden on my londe o chance,</L>
<L>"Tille him I am not bonden to mak deliuerance.
<PB REF="00000387.tif" N="159"></L>
<L>"It is my profit, to myn I wille &thorn;am holde.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei went ageyn fulle tite, to kyng R. alle tolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN kyng R. herde say ysaak respons,</L>
<L>"Turne we &thorn;iderward, &amp; delyuer our prisons,</L>
<L>"&amp; so it may betide, &thorn;ei salle dere abie</L>
<L>"My &thorn;at &thorn;ei hide, my men in prison lie.</L>
<L>Now he changes his weie, tille Acres may he nouht,</L>
<L>Many &thorn;erfore gon deie, I schrowe Isaak so wrouht.</L>
<L>It was Isaak to wite, tille Acres he com no nerre,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ska&thorn;e on him gan bite, &thorn;at R. turned &thorn;e werre.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Isaak had ti&thorn;and Emperour of Griffons,</L>
<L>&thorn;at R. drow to land with him alle his barons,</L>
<L>He did gadre an oste of Cipre &amp; Griffonie,</L>
<L>&amp; com vnto &thorn;at coste, to waite Richard nauie.</L>
<L>R. was perceyued, &thorn;ei were renged redie,</L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;er pencels weyued, son he mad a crie:</L>
<L>"Arme we vs I rede, &amp; go we hardilie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De capci|one Cipri&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&amp; we salle mak &thorn;am schede, &amp; sondre a partie.</L>
<L>He was first &thorn;at stirte to lond out of &thorn;e boote,</L>
<L>Armed &amp; suerd girte, bot an axe he smote.</L>
<L>With &thorn;at axe he hewe, &thorn;e Griffons mad him weie.</L>
<L>Many to dede he threwe, &amp; to grounde doun leie.</L>
<L>His maryners gan vp riue about in stedes seere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Griffons &thorn;ei gan driue bifor &thorn;am alle plenere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng Isaak fleih, his men had no foyson,</L>
<L>At &thorn;at tyme he ne deih, his partie &yogh;ede doun.</L>
<L>R. cried on hie, "Londreis folowes me,</L>
<L>"Loke &yogh;e be me nehi, fulle gode giftes &yogh;ete &yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="160"></L>
<L>"Take we &thorn;is Emperour, &thorn;at getis &thorn;ise Griffons,</L>
<L>"Falle salle &thorn;is honour for hold of our prisons.</L>
<L>Isaak had a spie, &thorn;at warned him ay beforn,</L>
<L>To tak &thorn;e mountayn hie, &amp; bide &thorn;er tille &thorn;e morn.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e euen cam, R. dred tresoun,</L>
<L>Agen to &thorn;e water he nam, did set his pauilloun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e godes, &thorn;at &thorn;am gan falle geten at &thorn;at iorne,</L>
<L>Felawes were &thorn;ei alle, als forthely as he.</L>
<L>ysaak sauh his vow<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> tille Criste &amp; Syme|oun. <I>Nam</I>, Isaqe ad fet son vowe a dieu &amp; Seint Simouns, <I>Gallice.</I></NOTE> tille &amp; S. Symeoun,</L>
<L>What falle &thorn;er of or how &thorn;e morn he suld com doun,</L>
<L>With schelde &amp; lance in hand to saue his regioun,</L>
<L>To mak &thorn;e Inglis fleand, &thorn;at had robbed his toun,</L>
<L>If he of his mot take ou&thorn;er erle or baroun,</L>
<L>His prison suld he wake, &thorn;at wer deppest donjoun.</L>
<L>For patriarke no pape, for bulle ne pardoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;er of suld he not scape, withouten grete ransoun.</L>
<L>In tentis R. rested alle &thorn;at ilk nyght,</L>
<L>His men wer wele gested with brede, wyne &amp; light.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON &thorn;e morn he ros, &amp; went to Lymosoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mane venit ad civita|tem Lymo|sin.</NOTE></L>
<L>A cite large in clos, &thorn;e folk were fled &thorn;e toun.</L>
<L>Griffons &thorn;ei it held, &thorn;ei wer scaped away,</L>
<L>Vitaile inouh at weld, &thorn;ei fond of corn &amp; hay.</L>
<L>Isaac did it store, to hold for tuo &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Ariued wer &thorn;er bifore dame Jone &amp; Berengere.
<PB REF="00000389.tif" N="161"></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;at tuo barges mot lede, of &thorn;at ware did he fille.</L>
<L>Tille his si&thorn;en he &yogh;ede, &amp; warned &thorn;am fulle stille</L>
<L>In &thorn;e mornyng to rise, &thorn;e tyme at &thorn;e day sterne</L>
<L>&thorn;e Emperour &amp; hise to seke &thorn;ei suld alle &yogh;erne.</L>
<L>His barons euerilkone be &thorn;at tyme wer dight,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng formast to gone, &thorn;e way he led &thorn;am right.</L>
<L>Was non in tente ne toun behind him durst be,</L>
<L>Bot Bernard of Bayoun, &thorn;at was kepand &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>&para; R. rode stilly neihand &thorn;e Emperour,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De fuga Isaac Im|peratoris.</NOTE></L>
<L>He gaf a bold crie, whan he bigan his stour.</L>
<L>&thorn;e tentes doun he hew, Isaac to reuile,</L>
<L>&amp; for non him knew, askaped he &thorn;at while.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">En chemyse, en brayse fuaunt eschapait, Ses chi|uals, ses armes al Rey Ri|chard leissait <I>Gallice.</I></NOTE>Bare in serke &amp; breke Isaac away fled,</L>
<L>It was not told a leke, &thorn;at non of his &thorn;ien led.</L>
<L>R. alle ouer ran, &amp; toke alle &thorn;at he fond,</L>
<L>A faire &thorn;ing &thorn;er he wan, &thorn;e baner of &thorn;e lond.</L>
<L>Som of &thorn;am were gode, to R. gaf bataile,</L>
<L>Bot alle to dede &yogh;ode, &amp; lost alle &thorn;er trauaile.</L>
<L>Taken were a partie, bot maste of &thorn;am were slayn,</L>
<L>Als man &thorn;at wan maistrie R. turned agayn,</L>
<L>To Lymoson &thorn;am led, his fest he did &thorn;er crie,</L>
<L>Berenger wild he wed, &amp; &thorn;er soiorne &amp; lie.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le terce jour de la feste le Rey comaundait, Qe Bernard de Bayoun la dame corounayt <I>Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e &thorn;rid day of &thorn;e fest, Sir Bernard of Bayoun,</L>
<L>Newed eft &thorn;er geste, &thorn;e quene he gaf &thorn;e coroun.
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="162"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO &thorn;at sollempnite com lordes of renoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce tot re|ges &amp; duces venerunt ad nupcias Regis Ri|cardi.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at weddyng forto se, for grete affectioun.</L>
<L>Of Jerusalem cuntre &thorn;e gode kyng Guyoun,</L>
<L>Gaufrey his bro&thorn;er was he, &amp; Aunfrey of Turoun;</L>
<L>Reymoun of Antioche, of Triple &thorn;e erle Bumoun,</L>
<L>Frere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ruffyn dez mounz <I>Gall.</I></NOTE> Ruffyn Delmount, &amp; &thorn;e duke Leoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise mad R. homage douhteli, kneland doun.</L>
<L>Ageyn &thorn;e Sarazin lynage, &thorn;at leues on Mahoun,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ei same &thorn;is same, &thorn;at &yogh;are &thorn;ei were &amp; boun</L>
<L>To die in Jhesu name with gode deuocioun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for vs suffred schame, &amp; died &thorn;orgh passioun.</L>
<L>"We trowe it is our frame, his resurrectioun.</L>
<L>R. said his skille, "lordynges, &thorn;is is resoun,</L>
<L>"Bituex vs if &yogh;e wille mak obligacioun,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at I be &yogh;our aller bro&thorn;er, &amp; &yogh;e in my bandoun,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at non faile o&thorn;er, ne consent to resoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei granted alle &thorn;erto, kyng, erle &amp; baroun,</L>
<L>&amp; who &thorn;at wille not so, gaf him &thorn;er malisoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ALSO sui&thorn;e R. has armes did crie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Divisit tur|mam Gui|doni.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; his oste did parte to &thorn;o &thorn;at couth it guye.</L>
<L>&thorn;e noble kyng Guyon tok of his cheualrie</L>
<L>O&thorn;er lordes of renoun, assigned &thorn;am &thorn;er partie.</L>
<L>Whan Isaac herd seie, what help R. was comen,</L>
<L>&amp; how to stop his weie parties had &thorn;ei nomen,</L>
<L>Of his men most wor&thorn;i, at &thorn;am conseile gan take,</L>
<L>&thorn;e best he mot go bi, a cord with R. make.
<PB REF="00000391.tif" N="163"></L>
<L>&thorn;o messengers camen, &thorn;e conseil &thorn;at he ches</L>
<L>Bifor R. alle samen, &amp; enformed his pes.</L>
<L>"&yogh;our wille wille he alle do, &amp; be at &yogh;our mercy."</L>
<L>R. ansuerd &thorn;erto, "I grante it bli&thorn;ely.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an com &thorn;e Emperour bifore kyng Richard<NOTE PLACE="marg">Imperator dixit Regi humiliando se h&aelig;c ver|ba.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;at I did dishonour, Sir, haf it to no reward.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e dede &thorn;at I did ille, my foly it was,</L>
<L>"I praye &thorn;e with gode wille, forgyue me &thorn;at trespas.</L>
<L>"&thorn;i man wille I be bi water &amp; bi land,</L>
<L>"&thorn;is reame to hold of &thorn;e, &amp; bowe vnto &thorn;i hand.</L>
<L>"&thorn;o men, &thorn;at I did take to prison &thorn;e to&thorn;er morn,</L>
<L>"Amendes I wille make, &amp; bring &thorn;am &thorn;e biforn.</L>
<L>"&thorn;i godes &thorn;e biken, or &thorn;e valow verray,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;i dronkled men tynt &thorn;e to&thorn;er day.</L>
<L>"&amp; with &thorn;e wille I go als felawes in ferd,</L>
<L>"A hundreth knyghtes mo, armed &amp; gird with suerd.</L>
<L>"&amp; four hundreth to bote, squieres of gode aray,</L>
<L>"&amp; fiue hundreth o fote, to whilk I salle pay</L>
<L>"Ilk day &thorn;er wages to &thorn;o ilk plenere,</L>
<L>"Knyght, squier &amp; pages, &thorn;e termes of tuo &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ma fylle eyr de mes te|res te doray a garder, Taunt com coe[<I>sive</I> ceo] couenaunt te aueray fet enteer <I>Codd. Gal.</I></NOTE>My douhter &amp; myn heyre to loke hir I &thorn;e grante,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;ou be in speyre I salle hold conante.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>RICHARD curteise was, &thorn;at sauh bede suilk loue,</L>
<L>Forgaf alle &thorn;e trespas, wirschipid himself aboue.</L>
<L>Tent &amp; pauillon tille Isaac did he signe,</L>
<L>Wirschipped him at reson, right as himself was digne.
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="164"></L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e day was ent, to rest men wer alle laid,</L>
<L>Isaac gan repent, &thorn;at he to R. said.</L>
<L>Fulle stille away he went, &thorn;at was a theues braid;</L>
<L>A messenger he sent &thorn;at &thorn;us to R. said:</L>
<L>&para; "Isaac wille not grante, to oblige him to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"No to be &thorn;i tenante his body bonden be,</L>
<L>"Ne to suilk seruage his heyrs disherite,</L>
<L>"Ne &yogh;eld at terme &amp; stage rent mykelle no lite.</L>
<L>"O deuel," said &thorn;e king, "&thorn;is is a foltid man,</L>
<L>"Whan he with trechettyng bi nyght away so ran.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ei red him alle a mysse, &thorn;at conseil gaf &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>"Wenes he our men Inglisse for to trecther so?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW gos kyng R. his purueiance to make,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De man|sione per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>How &amp; whider ward he hoped Isaac take.</L>
<L>To &thorn;o lordes &thorn;at camen, als Bumund &amp; Sir Guye,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;er alle samen, he toke galeis tuenty,</L>
<L>&amp; busses &thorn;at were gode o hundreth of &thorn;e most,</L>
<L>To fare opon &thorn;e flode, to waite wele bi &thorn;at coste.</L>
<L>&para; Eft bi Cipres side Isaac to aspie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ricardus circuit ter|ram, &amp; ce|pit Nichoci &amp; filiam Isaac</NOTE></L>
<L>If he toke any tide out of lond to flie.</L>
<L>R. south &thorn;e lond with gode folk &amp; hardie,</L>
<L>&thorn;e tounes &thorn;at &thorn;ei fond &thorn;ei felle to his mercie.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Robert de Turnham se mene noblement, La tere souz maryne ad conquys nette|ment <I>Codd. Gallici.</I></NOTE>Roberd of Thornham bare him nobilly,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e se side he nam, &amp; wan it per maistrie.</L>
<L>&thorn;an turned he to &thorn;e kyng after his conquest,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei mad &thorn;an a samenyng, to go toward &thorn;e West.
<PB REF="00000393.tif" N="165"></L>
<L>&thorn;e cite of Nichoci &thorn;ei wan, &amp; were &thorn;er in,</L>
<L>&amp; a no&thorn;er &thorn;erbi, a toun men calle Cherin.</L>
<L>Doun of the kastelle mote Isaac douhter cam,</L>
<L>&amp; felle R. to fote gretand, &thorn;at doole him nam.</L>
<L>"Lord kyng," scho said, "on me &thorn;ou haf mercie,</L>
<L>&amp; R. hand to laid lift hir curteislie,</L>
<L>&amp; sent hir tille his wife, &amp; tille his sister Jone,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er scho led hir life with &thorn;o ladies ilkone.</L>
<L>&thorn;e castels &amp; &thorn;e godes tounes stored wele,</L>
<L>Vitaile vnto &thorn;er fode R. toke ilk dele.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Guyoun &amp; Reymound re|uenent unement, Pur coe [<I>sive</I> ceo] qil ne ount con|quis tere ne tenement <I>in the French, tho' in one of Mr. An|stis's Copies</I> ne ount <I>is wanting.</I></NOTE>Sir Guy &amp; Bumund &thorn;ei com as &thorn;ei &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ne tynd ne fond, ne were at no dede.</L>
<L>Roberd bisouht &thorn;e kyng, to turne toward Bufnet,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er ouer alle &thorn;ing his sege &thorn;er to set.</L>
<L>"In alle Griffonie ne es so strong a toure,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;at &yogh;e wille &thorn;er lie, it is to &yogh;our honoure.</L>
<L>R. also sui&thorn;e to Bufnet he &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>His maistrie gan he kye, engynes dight to dede.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei were alle dight, stalwor&thorn;ely &amp; fast</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e day &amp; nyght vnto &thorn;e toure he kast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO while &thorn;at kyng R. was kastand to &thorn;e toure,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota de Statino se|nescallo consiliando Imperato|rem, &amp; ecce Imperator amputavit nasum suum cum cultello.</NOTE></L>
<L>Statin his stiward spak to &thorn;e Emperoure,</L>
<L>Als his mete he sat, &amp; was his seruitoure,</L>
<L>"Forto amend &yogh;our stat I wille conseiloure.
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>"Sir kyng Isakin I am &thorn;i vauasoure,</L>
<L>"My nam is Statin, I wille be no traitoure.</L>
<L>"I haf kept &thorn;i lande, I se &thorn;at dishonoure</L>
<L>"Is now &thorn;e nerhand, &thorn;orgh &thorn;is conquerour,</L>
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Deest</I> es, (<I>i. e.</I> is.) <I>Nam in Codicibus Gallicis</I>, Qe Reis est des Englays, e sage gwe|reyour.</NOTE> &thorn;at an Inglis kyng, a wys werreour.</L>
<L>"Loke &thorn;ou lese no &thorn;ing for &thorn;i fole erroure,</L>
<L>"Ne &thorn;e lond be not lorn, &thorn;at &thorn;in ancessoure</L>
<L>"So wele kept biforn, als noble gouernoure.</L>
<L>"Go &amp; mak his pes, or he do &thorn;e more stoure,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;ou to &thorn;i deses may haf &thorn;e frute &amp; floure.</L>
<L>&thorn;an said Isaac tille him, "ert &thorn;ou his mayntenour?</L>
<L>Fulle bro&thorn;ely &amp; brim he kept vp a trencheour,</L>
<L>&amp; kast it at Statin, did him a schamfulle schoure.</L>
<L>His nese &amp; his ine he carfe at misauentoure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>STATIN vp he stirte, him &thorn;ouht &thorn;erof grete schame,</L>
<L>"Sir &thorn;ou has me hirte, &thorn;erfor &thorn;ou ert to blame.</L>
<L>Als so sui&thorn;e he &yogh;ede vnto kyng Richard,</L>
<L>&amp; schewed him all &thorn;at dede of Isaac &thorn;e coward.</L>
<L>"Sir be my socoure, &amp; venge myn outrage.</L>
<L>R. did him honoure, &amp; he mad him homage.</L>
<L>Statin wele &thorn;an lete, he &yogh;alde him alle &thorn;e honour</L>
<L>Of Baaf &amp; Bufnet, <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I. e. Diendamour, that he had of Isaack. But it should be rather read</I>, Candare and Diendamour. <I>For the French Copies have</I>, Baffe &amp; Buffenet, Candare &amp; Den|damour, Et totes les citez dount Isake fu gwyour.</NOTE>&thorn;at he of Is Diendamour.
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="167"></L>
<L>Castels &amp; citez &thorn;at he he of Isaac held,</L>
<L>Baronies &amp; feez, he &yogh;ald him ilk a scheld.</L>
<L>&thorn;e grete lordes Inglis, &thorn;at &thorn;e werre had gonnen,</L>
<L>Wer fulle glad of &thorn;is, Cipres so sone was wonnen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BE side of S. Andrew was an Abbay,</L>
<L>Cape &thorn;e name men knew, &amp; &thorn;er in herd &thorn;ei say,</L>
<L>&thorn;at kyng Isaac was priuely hid &thorn;er in,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Captus est Isaac in quadaur abbatia,ubi absconditus fuit.</NOTE></L>
<L>To R. so &thorn;ei spak, he went him out to wynne.</L>
<L>Isaac ti&thorn;ing herd, R. com him to seke,</L>
<L>Ageyn R. he ferd, to fote he felle fulle meke,</L>
<L>&amp; said, "Sir mercy, my life &thorn;ou saue it me,</L>
<L>"Do not &thorn;at vilany, fettred &thorn;at I be.</L>
<L>"In prison &thorn;ou me do, bot nouht in bondes bynde,</L>
<L>"I pray &yogh;ow it be so, for schame of my kynde.</L>
<L>Said R. "&thorn;ou salle haue at &thorn;in owen deuys,</L>
<L>"&thorn;i life I salle &thorn;e saue," Isaac he did vp rise.</L>
<L>"O dele," said &thorn;e kyng, "&thorn;is is a fole Briton.</L>
<L>"He spak no maner &thorn;ing, for regne to gif raunson,</L>
<L>"Ne no &thorn;ing him bisouht, he was of kynge's blode,</L>
<L>"Bot for prison bisouht, als fole &thorn;at couth no gode.</L>
<L>"Now er his anens wrouht, of siluere wele ouer gilt,</L>
<L>"Dayet &thorn;at &thorn;erof rouht, his was alle &thorn;e gilt.</L>
<L>Taken is he to loke to Berenger &amp; Jone,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ei him vndirtoke &thorn;o ladies euer ilkone.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et le Rey Richard ad mayntenaunt donez Al sene|schal de Cypre la garde des citez. Partaunt com il estait si vilement maygnez, Statyn le nase des ore est surnomez <I>in the French, unless it be that in one of Mr. Anstis's Copies this verse</I>, Statyn le nase des ore est surnomez, <I>is wanting.</I></NOTE> To Statin gaf R. &thorn;e cite in kepyng,</L>
<L>&amp; bad him be stiward, als ore was with &thorn;e kyng.
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="168"></L>
<L>For Isaac did him schame, his lord suld be,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei caled him &thorn;is toname, <I>Statin</I> &thorn;e <I>nasee.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Cipres Iorn fro Isaac &amp; hise,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cipria con|qu&aelig;sta est per Regem Ricardum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; to R. suorn for his valiantise,</L>
<L>&thorn;e mene folk (comonly fulle gode men &amp; wise)</L>
<L>Com to his mercy, doand him seruise,</L>
<L>&thorn;at bies woule &amp; wyne, &amp; sellis with conant.</L>
<L>"Do com," said Statyn, "burgeis &amp; merchant,</L>
<L>"&amp; knyght &amp; squiere, &amp; mak &thorn;am &yogh;our tenant,</L>
<L>"Citez &amp; tounes sere, hosbond &amp; sergant,</L>
<L>"&amp; tak of &thorn;am homage, as custom is &amp; haunt</L>
<L>"To do &thorn;at ilk seruage," &thorn;e folk said, "we graunt,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;erto half our &thorn;ing, for to haf &thorn;o lawes,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at Samuel &thorn;e gode kyng gaf bi olde dawes,</L>
<L>"&amp; sikred it with skrite, hyngand set his seale;</L>
<L>&amp; R. gaf it so quite, &thorn;at &thorn;ei suld him be leale.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW has kyng R. of Cipres &thorn;e seignorie,</L>
<L>What with nesshe &amp; hard wonne &thorn;e maistrie.</L>
<L>To Statin &thorn;e nasee did he grete curteisie,</L>
<L>Alle Cipres gaf him fre ageyn his vilanie,</L>
<L>With a suerd to holde, of R. heyres alle</L>
<L>Inglis kynges tolde, to whom &thorn;e chefe salle falle.</L>
<L>Statin &thorn;e reame nam, in &thorn;at ilk conaunt,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Roberd of Thornham, if &thorn;e kyng wild him graunt,
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="169"></L>
<L>With him forto duelle, to maynten &thorn;e pes,</L>
<L>&thorn;e foles forto felle, &thorn;at rise wild in res.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW leues Roberd with Statin nasee,</L>
<L>Tille ti&thorn;ing be more herd, or pes better be,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e kynge's leue &thorn;e lond to justise,</L>
<L>His enmys to greue, &thorn;at ageyn him wild rise.</L>
<L>His wille has R. sped in Cipres fer &amp; nere,</L>
<L>&amp; Isaac forth is led with Jone &amp; Berengere</L>
<L>At Triple to sojourne, &amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ei mad a crie,</L>
<L>Tille Acres forto turne alle holy &thorn;er nauie.</L>
<L>Bihynd left non of hise, bot alle with him &thorn;ei nam,</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at was justise, Roberd of Thornham.</L>
<L>Now er alle on flote, God gif &thorn;am grace to spede,</L>
<L>With douhty fo to note, whan &thorn;ei com to dede.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de navi in mari <NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE>capto.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT none &thorn;e to&thorn;er day &thorn;ei sauh fer in &thorn;e se</L>
<L>A grete busse &amp; gay, fulle hie of saile was he.</L>
<L>&thorn;e weder was fulle soft, &thorn;e wynde held &thorn;am stille,</L>
<L>&thorn;e saile was hie o loft, &thorn;ei had no wynde at wille.</L>
<L>In Philip nauie of France a pencelle &thorn;ei put oute,</L>
<L>His armes on a lance ouer alle &thorn;e schip aboute.</L>
<L>So mykelle was &thorn;at barge, it myght not lightly saile,</L>
<L>&amp; so heuy of charge, &amp; &thorn;e wynde gan faile.</L>
<L>To wite what &thorn;ei were went a marinere,</L>
<L>Respons &thorn;ei gaf him &thorn;ere, "&thorn;ei were men of mistere,</L>
<L>"Fro Antioche were went vnto kyng Philip,</L>
<L>"&amp; for vs has he sent, &amp; his is &thorn;is schip.
<PB REF="00000398.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>Said &thorn;e kyng R. "Sir prince if &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>"Bi tyme turne to me ward, for I wille speke with &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prince com fulle sone, Sir Richard did he calle,</L>
<L>"Do dight &amp; mak &yogh;ow bone, &thorn;e schip ere Sarazins alle,</L>
<L>"Tille Acres &thorn;ei &thorn;am rape, venom for our men lede,</L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;ei vs ascape, &thorn;e Cristen may &thorn;am dede.</L>
<L>&thorn;an cried Richard on hie, "now batale vs belyue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce dicit Rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;orgh help of our ladie, &thorn;at schip salle alle to ryue.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et ait [<I>sive</I> eyt] chescun la gwayne [<I>vel</I> son wayne] saunz altre chalenger <I>Codices Gallici.</I></NOTE>Ilk man &thorn;at may wynne tok to his partie,</L>
<L>To set chalange &thorn;er inne salle no man be hardie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's owen Galeie, he cald it Trencthemere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was first on weie, &amp; com &thorn;e schip fulle nere.</L>
<L>O&thorn;er were &thorn;er inowe, &thorn;at &thorn;er after drouh,</L>
<L>Bot he com with a suowe, &thorn;at &thorn;e schip to rof.</L>
<L>&thorn;e schip cast trokes out, &thorn;e galeie to &thorn;am drouh,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng stode fulle stout, &amp; many of &thorn;am slouh.</L>
<L>Wilde fire &thorn;ei kast, &thorn;e kyng to confound,</L>
<L>His schipmen were fulle wrask, els had he gon to ground.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng abaist him nouht, bot stalworthly fauht,</L>
<L>Alle to dede he brouht, &thorn;at his Galeie ouer rauht.</L>
<L>&thorn;e galeie &thorn;er &thorn;orght schete, &amp; &thorn;e kyng was gode,</L>
<L>&thorn;e schip &thorn;at was so grete, it dronkled in &thorn;e flode.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei teld fiueten hundred Sarazins, &thorn;at drenkled were,</L>
<L>Fourti &amp; sex wer sundred, &amp; alle &thorn;o were saued &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e summe couth no man telle of gold &thorn;at was &thorn;er in</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er riches to selle, bot alle mot &thorn;ei not wyn.
<PB REF="00000399.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>&thorn;e venom alle &thorn;ei hent, in &thorn;e se cast it away,</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk it mot haf schent, &thorn;at about Acres lay.</L>
<L>Armour &thorn;ei had plente, &amp; god besquite to mete,</L>
<L>It sanke son in &thorn;e se, half myght &thorn;ei not gete.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Rey Richard les sy|gles comaunde eschaucer, Et haster vers Akres, les Cri|stiens eyder, <I>Gallice.</I></NOTE>Richard bade, "hale vp hie &yogh;our sailes, &thorn;er God vs lede,</L>
<L>"Our men at Acres lie, of help &thorn;ei haf grete nede.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date was a &thorn;ousand, a hundreth nienti &amp; one,</L>
<L>Fro Cipres he was sailand, a toun he wan Acon.</L>
<L>&para; Als grace of God wild be, &thorn;e wynde gan him dryue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ricardus applicuit ad portum de Acres.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e euen of &thorn;e Trinite vnder Acres R. gan aryue,</L>
<L>Dame Jone &amp; Berengere bifor him fond he eft:</L>
<L>Isaac &thorn;e Emperere at Triples was left.</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk of Griffonie, whan R. was gone,</L>
<L>To Statin had envie, a monk &thorn;ei ches ilkone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Isaac cosyn was, &amp; corouned him for kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei did a foule trespas, it was vnsemly &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Statin wild &thorn;ei greue, mispaied was Roberd,</L>
<L>He said, "&thorn;ei salle mischeue," whan he &thorn;at ti&thorn;ing herd.</L>
<L>Night &amp; day &thorn;ei woke, Roberd &amp; Statyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh force &thorn;e monke &thorn;ei toke, &amp; brouht him to Cheryn.</L>
<L>&yogh;it he skaped out, &thorn;e monke of prisoun,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">On hors de la prisone noctauntre est passe, Statyn &amp; Robert af armes ount crye, <I>Gallice.</I></NOTE>&thorn;ei cried, "has armes about Roberd fro toun to toun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk whan &thorn;ei were comen to Statyn &amp; Roberd,</L>
<L>Eft &thorn;e monke &thorn;ei nomen, at Cheryn &thorn;ei him sperd.</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e &thorn;rid day &thorn;e folk he did somoune,</L>
<L>Lered men &amp; lay, fre &amp; bond of toune.
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>A quest &thorn;an wild he take of &thorn;e monke &thorn;at bare &thorn;e coroune,</L>
<L>His abite he gan forsake, his ordre lete alle doune.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;it a no&thorn;er sawe of behoues be spoken,</L>
<L>Ageyn &thorn;e comon lawe, &thorn;e prison has he broken.</L>
<L>Som chesons &thorn;ei cast, &amp; som for him said,</L>
<L>Bot here now at &thorn;e last, what dome was on him laid.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SAID Sir Roberd, "monk &thorn;ou was whilom,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De mona|cho rege suspenso.</NOTE></L>
<L>"For wirschip of &thorn;e werld forsoke &thorn;ou alle &amp; som.</L>
<L>"To God &thorn;ou mad a vow in &thorn;i professioun.</L>
<L>"His traitour ert &thorn;ou now, &thorn;ou did him a tresoun.</L>
<L>"For &thorn;e worlde's blisse &thorn;ou left &thorn;in habite,</L>
<L>"&amp; now &thorn;ou wost for wisse of bo&thorn;e ert &thorn;ou quite.</L>
<L>"We toke &thorn;e als robboure in &thorn;is ilk cuntre,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou reft &thorn;e kyng his honour, &thorn;at felle not vnto &thorn;e.</L>
<L>"To Cheryn &thorn;at ilk toun, &thorn;ider was &thorn;ou led,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ou brak prisoun, &amp; away &thorn;ou fled.</L>
<L>"Eft we did &thorn;e take, in prison we &thorn;e bond,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at lawe I salle &thorn;e make, &thorn;at is Richard lond.</L>
<L>"Galwes do &yogh;e reise, &amp; hyng &thorn;is cheitefe.</L>
<L>"Better him wer with eise in clostre haf led his life,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e seruise of his song recorded &amp; lered,</L>
<L>"&thorn;an chalange with wrong &thorn;at kyng R. conquered,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;i messe songen, &amp; serued God alle myght,</L>
<L>"&thorn;an to be hongen in &thorn;i frendis sight.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW of &thorn;is olde monk &amp; &thorn;is new kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was not worth a fonk, don has his endyng.
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="173"></L>
<L>&thorn;e folk was alle pesed, to Statyn wild &thorn;ei cheue.</L>
<L>Of Statyn &thorn;at was sesed Roberd toke his leue</L>
<L>With ricchesse inouh, &thorn;at he to Acres led,</L>
<L>&amp; teld kyng R. how of alle &thorn;at he had sped,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e folk of Griffonie a monk &thorn;ei chese to kyng,</L>
<L>"Sib Isaak a partie had mad a chalangyng.</L>
<L>"In Cipres wer &thorn;ei comen, &thorn;er maistrie gan &thorn;ei ki&thorn;e,</L>
<L>"&amp; we ageyn &thorn;am nomen, &amp; tok him als sui&thorn;e.</L>
<L>"To Cheryn we him led, &amp; &thorn;er he brak prisoun.</L>
<L>"Eft we toke him fled, brouht him ageyn to toun,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e courte opon him sat, &thorn;e quest filed him &amp; schent.</L>
<L>"For trespas of &thorn;at, he toke jugement.</L>
<L>"Allas! for vilenie," said R. &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at a kyng suld so die, hanged for no &thorn;ing!</L>
<L>"Roberd &thorn;ou ert to blame, &thorn;ou did ageyn resoun,</L>
<L>"Certes &thorn;ou has don schame tille alle &thorn;at bere coroun.</L>
<L>"Sir," said Roberd, "&thorn;er of is not to speke;</L>
<L>"Late alle &thorn;is be sperd, on Gode's enmys &thorn;e wreke.</L>
<L>"Si&thorn;en Philip hider cam, he gaf neuer non assaut:</L>
<L>"It wer mykelle scham to mak suilk a defaut.</L>
<L>"A partie has &thorn;ou sped, &thorn;anked be God alle myght;</L>
<L>"&yogh;it salle &thorn;ou mak &thorn;am dred, or com a fourtenyght</L>
<L>"Do reise vp &thorn;in engyns, &amp; wyn of &thorn;am &thorn;ise dikes.</L>
<L>"I trowe &thorn;e Sarazins our comyng mislikes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>RICHARD als sui&thorn;e did reise his engyns,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ricardus paravit se ad castel|lum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis wer &thorn;an bli&thorn;e, Normans &amp; Peteuyns.</L>
<L>In bargeis &amp; galeis he set mylnes to go,</L>
<L>&thorn;e sailes, as men sais, som were blak &amp; blo,
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="174"></L>
<L>Som were rede &amp; grene, &thorn;e wynde about &thorn;am blewe,</L>
<L>A selly sight to sene, fire &thorn;e sailes &thorn;rewe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e stones were of Rynes, &thorn;e noyse dredfulle &amp; grete,</L>
<L>It affraied &thorn;e Sarazins, as leuen &thorn;e fire out schete.</L>
<L>&thorn;e noyse was vnride, it lasted alle day,</L>
<L>Fro morn tille euentide, &thorn;er of had many affray.</L>
<L>To while &thorn;ei had wondryng, of &thorn;is &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne knew</L>
<L>Stode R. our kyng, &thorn;e chyne in tuo he hew,</L>
<L>&amp; sesid &thorn;e Sarazin dikes, maugre &thorn;am euerilkon.</L>
<L>Now &thorn;e Sarazins mislikes, to Mahoun mad &thorn;ei mone.</L>
<L>Our Cristen wer f&uacute;lle fayn, &thorn;e sauh R. &thorn;erin,</L>
<L>&thorn;e dikes wer all drawen with iren chynes &thorn;rin.</L>
<L>&para; "Certes," said &thorn;e Soudan, &thorn;at was in Acres toure,</L>
<L>"&thorn;is is a kyng a man, &thorn;is is a werreoure,</L>
<L>"Me &thorn;ink els a wonder, bot he salle do grete wo,</L>
<L>"He salle sched vs o sonder, fro Acres salle we go.</L>
<L>"If he forth haf grace, as he now bigynnes,</L>
<L>"Hi&thorn;en salle he vs chace, &amp; alle &thorn;is lond he wynnes.</L>
<L>&para; The bisshop of Perouse com to kyng Richard,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Lamenta|tio facta ad Regem pro fame Chri|stianorum per episco|pum.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sir, ouer meruailouse our duellyng here is hard;</L>
<L>"Sir, here biforn of men haf we told</L>
<L>"Fourti &thorn;ousand lorn for hungre &amp; cold.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e hungre was so grete, &amp; &thorn;e cold so stark,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at a quarter whete was at tuenty mark.</L>
<L>"For ten mark men sold a litille bulchyn,</L>
<L>"Litille lesse men told a bouke of a motoun.</L>
<L>"Men gaf fiueten schillynges for a goos or a heen,</L>
<L>"For &thorn;e grete lordynges bouht to seke men.
<PB REF="00000403.tif" N="175"></L>
<L>"An ay bi it selue for fiue schillynges was bouht,</L>
<L>"A pere for penyes tuelue, or &thorn;ei had it nouht.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e comon of &thorn;e oste bouht &thorn;am hors flesch,</L>
<L>"Or mules or assis roste, or haf bien mete lesse.</L>
<L>"Many grete mishappes, many hard trauaile,</L>
<L>"Haf comen vs hard clappes, whan &thorn;ei gan vs assaile.</L>
<L>"He told to &thorn;e kyng many hard chance,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at tellis here no &thorn;ing, bot alle in &thorn;e romance.</L>
<L>&para; He tellis in &thorn;e romance, sen Acres wonnen was,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce pro|bitas Ri|cardi.</NOTE></L>
<L>How God gaf him faire chance at &thorn;e bataile of Cayfas.</L>
<L>&para; Si&thorn;en at Nazareth, at &thorn;e Assompcion messe,</L>
<L>At Assur he did to deth &thorn;e Sarazins more &amp; lesse.</L>
<L>&para; Si&thorn;en at Japhet was slayn fanuelle his stede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e romance tellis grete pas &thorn;er of his douhty dede.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e bisshop sais vnto kyng Richard,</L>
<L>How &thorn;am felle o&thorn;er wais so many woes &amp; hard.</L>
<L>"Bot," Sir, "we here wele telle, &yogh;e ere so trew a kyng,</L>
<L>"Our folk &thorn;at here duelle, &yogh;erne &yogh;our comyng.</L>
<L>"Ouer alle now is said, his comyng &thorn;ank we God,</L>
<L>"Our hope is on him laid, &amp; fulle wele is it trod,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &yogh;e salle wele spede, to schorten our soiorne,</L>
<L>"&amp; mend our grete nede, to ioy &thorn;at it mot torne.</L>
<L>"&yogh;our wille is euer so gode, &amp; &yogh;our treuth so treist,</L>
<L>"&yogh;our douhtynesse of blode &thorn;e Sarazins salle freist.</L>
<L>"Now, Jhesu, for &thorn;at croice, &thorn;ou &thorn;oled on passioun,</L>
<L>"Here our sinfulle voice, &amp; grant &yogh;ow wynne &thorn;e toun.
<PB REF="00000404.tif" N="176"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN kyng R. herd, &thorn;e Cristen had suilk pyn.</L>
<L>Fulle soft he him ansuerd, wepand with his ine,</L>
<L>"To Criste for me biseke, &thorn;at he gyue me &thorn;at grace,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e Cristendom to eke, &thorn;e Sarazins to chace.</L>
<L>R. also sui&thorn;e did set his pauilloun,</L>
<L>His maistrie sone gan ki&thorn;e, he dight him to &thorn;e toun.</L>
<L>Now ere &thorn;e dikes wonnen opon Gode's enmys,</L>
<L>&amp; sautes has bigonnen, &thorn;orgh whilk he getis pris.</L>
<L>So did kyng Philip with sautes on &thorn;am gan pres,</L>
<L>Bot for a forgetilschip R. &amp; he bo&thorn;e les.</L>
<L>Philip left his engynes withouten kepyng a nyght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at perceyued &thorn;e Sarazines, with fire brent &thorn;am doun right.</L>
<L>For he com on &thorn;e morne, assaut he wild haf gyuen,</L>
<L>His Engyns fond he lorne, brent &amp; tille askes dryuen.</L>
<L>R. said his avis, blamed him for &thorn;at dede.</L>
<L>A werreour &thorn;at were wys, desceyt suld euer drede,</L>
<L>Wele more on &thorn;e nyght, &thorn;an opon &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>In mirke withouten sight wille enmys mak affray.</L>
<L>R. lent him of hise, Acres for to assaile;</L>
<L>Philip withouten fayntise did alle his trauaile.</L>
<L>&thorn;e to kyng &amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;er assailed it so hard,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e Soudan bro&thorn;er cried pes opon forward.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ei went to here, what &thorn;e Soudan wild say:</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk com alle in fere with &thorn;o kynges tueye.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is was &thorn;e Sarazins sawe, "&thorn;e toun &yogh;eld &yogh;ow we wille,</L>
<L>"If &yogh;e grant vs &thorn;e lawe, I salle say &yogh;ow &thorn;e skille.</L>
<L>"Late vs alle out com, &thorn;is is &thorn;e first we chese.</L>
<L>"&thorn;at non be slayn ne nom, ne life no lymme lese;
<PB REF="00000405.tif" N="177"></L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;at we wille take a baron of &yogh;our oste,</L>
<L>"&amp; Cristen kyng him make, to regne bi &thorn;is coste,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De pace tractata secundum formam in|ter Reges &amp; Saracenos.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Him &thorn;an wille we say, who is moste valiant,</L>
<L>"If &yogh;e consent &thorn;at way, &thorn;e marchis of Mounfraunt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>RICHARD was hastif, &amp; ansuerd &thorn;at stund,</L>
<L>"Certes &thorn;ou lies cheitif, &amp; as a stinkand hund,</L>
<L>"Here ere a &thorn;ousand mo more wor&thorn;i haf pris,</L>
<L>"&thorn;an he &thorn;ou tellis fro, &thorn;at ilk traitoure marchis.</L>
<L>"It salle auaile him nouht, &thorn;at he &yogh;our Soudan sent.</L>
<L>"I se &thorn;at he has bouht &thorn;e lond with his present,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;is lond is oure, &amp; our right wonyng,</L>
<L>"For oure ancessoure hereof was he kyng,</L>
<L>"&amp; &yogh;e ere our enmys, &thorn;e Cristendam to spille,</L>
<L>"&amp; now is &thorn;e marchis turned to &yogh;our wille.</L>
<L>"I rede out of &thorn;is oste &thorn;e marchis go his gate,</L>
<L>"Bi God &thorn;at myght has moste, he may go to late.</L>
<L>"If he &thorn;orgh traytorie salle be at &yogh;our deuys,</L>
<L>"I salle do him hang hie, or drawe with runcys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SAID &thorn;e kyng of France, "R. whi art &thorn;ou wroth,</L>
<L>"What is &yogh;our distance, &thorn;at he is &thorn;e so loth?</L>
<L>"&amp; he is gentille knyght, of kynge's blode comen,</L>
<L>"If he with vnright ouht of &thorn;in haf nomen,</L>
<L>"He salle at &thorn;i wille mak alle &thorn;in amendes,</L>
<L>"&amp; late alle be stille, &thorn;at &thorn;ou him defendes.</L>
<L>&para; Said &thorn;e kyng R. "Sir, at &yogh;our honoure,</L>
<L>"In &thorn;at ilk forward he &yogh;elde me my tresoure,
<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>"&thorn;at my fadere Henry gaf to &thorn;e Holy lond.</L>
<L>"He toke it wikkedly out of &thorn;e Hospitelers hond.</L>
<L>"Fourti &thorn;ousand pounde, &amp; if he &yogh;elde it me,</L>
<L>"We salle fare &amp; founde als frendes falle to be.</L>
<L>Sir Philip stille he stode, worde ne spak he more,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at same way &thorn;ei gode, right als it was ore.</L>
<L>Richard asked &thorn;o landes, &thorn;at &thorn;e Cristen wan</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e Sarazins handes, &amp; chaced &thorn;e Soudan.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins wild not &yogh;elde so mony londes sere,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e kynge's ne wilde acorde in o&thorn;er manere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OFT tille our Inglis men was schewed a mervaile grete,</L>
<L>A darte was schot to &thorn;em, bot non wist who it schete.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e schaft was purtreit, &thorn;orgh &thorn;e holy goste trowe I,</L>
<L><I>In nomine patris</I>, it said, &amp; <I>filii &amp; spiritus sancti.</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce mira|culum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was neuer Cristen man cou&thorn;e perceyue &thorn;e certeyn,</L>
<L>Ne wist what tyme no whan it passed out eft ageyn,</L>
<L>It com fro &thorn;at tureile, &thorn;at R. had doun smyten,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e Sarazins conseile in &thorn;e schaft was writen,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;er ordinance, kyng R. it wiste,</L>
<L>It was a fulle faire chance schewed &thorn;orgh Jhesu Criste.</L>
<L>R. mad &thorn;ankyng to Jhesu for &thorn;at sond,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;at schewyng to wirschip him suld he fond.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">A Phelipp &amp; Richard les Sarecyns volaint Souent la cite rendre &amp; bien promet|taynt, Ke la seinte tere Je|rusalem rendraynt, Et vint mille Cristiens qen prisoun auaint. Ne Phelipp ne Ri|chard de ceo se affyaynt, Mes de jour en altre al assalt a|laynt, <I>in Codd. Gallicis.</I></NOTE>TO Philip &amp; Richard &thorn;e Sarazins said &thorn;ei wild,</L>
<L>In a gode forward, &thorn;e toun to &thorn;am &yogh;eld.
<PB REF="00000407.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>Of Jerusalem &thorn;e land &thorn;ei said he suld it haue,</L>
<L>&thorn;erto tuenti &thorn;ousand of Cristen men to saue.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei treistid not &thorn;er tille, bot &thorn;ei did it in dede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's with gode wille vnto assaut &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>R. had minoures, &thorn;at myned vndere &thorn;e walle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Acres ci|vitas capta est per Ri|cardum.</NOTE></L>
<L>A pece with a grete cours at ons felle doun alle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Frankis bare &thorn;am stoute, &thorn;e myned bo&thorn;e &amp; cast</L>
<L>Vnto a toure Maudut, &amp; wan it at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins som &thorn;ei slouh, &amp; som for drede fied,</L>
<L>At &thorn;at tyme wele inouh &thorn;e Frankis manly sped.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis at &thorn;er triste bifor &thorn;am bare alle doun,</L>
<L>&amp; R. als him liste &thorn;e way had redy roun.</L>
<L>Now has R. entre, &amp; Acres taken es,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins com fulle fre, &amp; offred him grete riches.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>VNTO Philip of France &thorn;e Frankis mad a crie,</L>
<L>"&thorn;i worschip to auance com in als kyng hardie.</L>
<L>"Com in as lord of fe, for hedeles ere &thorn;ei hopped</L>
<L>"&amp; slayn alle may &thorn;ou se, &thorn;at &thorn;i way stopped:</L>
<L>&amp; now is Acres taken &thorn;orgh R. &thorn;e conquerour,</L>
<L>His banere held &thorn;am waken was put of o toure,</L>
<L>Kyng Philip did also, his baner was forth laid,</L>
<L>&amp; righ it felle &thorn;erto, for no man him withsaid.</L>
<L>&para;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Le duk de Austrice i veent, &amp; banere desplye. <I>Gall. quin</I> &amp; duk <I>etiam infra in MSS. Gallicis. Adeo ut apud inter|pretem nostrum idem valeat</I> erle <I>quod</I> duk, <I>id quod paullo post etiam liquet, ubi</I> duke <I>plane habet.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e erle of Ostrece cam, &amp; put his banere out,</L>
<L>&amp; R. asked &thorn;orgh wham &thorn;e erle bare him so stout.
<PB REF="00000408.tif" N="180"></L>
<L>Kyng R. &thorn;orght hatie after &thorn;e Erle sent,</L>
<L>&amp; asked, "of what seignorie holdes &thorn;ou lond &amp; rent,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;ou has put out here &thorn;i baner for maistrie,</L>
<L>"Among kynges baneres, withouten auowrie?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"SIR, said &thorn;e duke, "I am now comen here,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ise Sarazins to rebuke, &amp; slo at my powere.</L>
<L>"My lond I hold with right, at no man's dome,</L>
<L>"Bot of God alle mygh, &amp; Saynt Petir of Rome.</L>
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sire duke, dist le Reis, par le fiz Marie, Si tu nas seygnour, ta tere ert altrye, <I>Gallice.</I></NOTE>If &thorn;ou to non &thorn;at lyues," said R. "&thorn;ou chene ne bowe,</L>
<L>"&thorn;i lond men salle gife tille one &thorn;at may it vowe.</L>
<L>Grete scathe afterward in a litille &thorn;rawe</L>
<L>Com tille kyng R. for &thorn;at envios sawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW haf &thorn;e Cristen won Acres &thorn;at was lorn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De obsidi|one castri Pilgrim, &amp; de remoci|one Phi|lippi.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins ouer ron with force &amp; doun born.</L>
<L>&thorn;e folk was mykelle &amp; strong, of mete &thorn;ei had grete nede,</L>
<L>&thorn;am burd departe &thorn;er &thorn;rong, &thorn;at lond mot &thorn;am not fede.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei parted &thorn;e oste in tuo, &thorn;orgh comon acordance.</L>
<L>R. wille was so, so was Philip of France.</L>
<L>A castelle was &thorn;er biside fro Acres a jorne,</L>
<L>Grete sca&thorn;e it did bi tide to &thorn;e Cristen in &thorn;e cuntre.</L>
<L>&thorn;e castelle hight Pilgrym, of alle it bare &thorn;e flour:</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins kept it &thorn;at tym for &thorn;er chefe warinstour.
<PB REF="00000409.tif" N="181"></L>
<L>&thorn;at castelle was fulle strong, &amp; ille for to wynne,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins kept it long, &thorn;ei wer inow &thorn;er in.</L>
<L>Philip went him &thorn;idere, &thorn;at castelle to conquere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Frankis alle togider did nouh whan &thorn;ei com &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; Richard oste forth ran, &amp; grace bifor him fond,</L>
<L>Auht jornes he wan with in &thorn;e Sarazins lond.</L>
<L>Philip &thorn;at &thorn;er lay to spede had he no grace,</L>
<L>It was not wor&thorn;e an ay, his dede no his manace.</L>
<L>R. herd it say, he dred an oste mot skip</L>
<L>Behind, &amp; stop his way bituex him &amp; Philip,</L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;e Soudan ros opon Philip of France,</L>
<L>"&amp; I wer &thorn;an in clos withouten cheuisance,</L>
<L>"So myght it in a while &thorn;e gode torn tille ille,</L>
<L>"A man salle ay drede gile, &thorn;e gode is not at wille.</L>
<L>R. his oste did turne, tresore he had inouh,</L>
<L>Nouht wild he soiorne, to Philip fast he drouh.</L>
<L>&para; Whan kyng Philip hard, &thorn;at R. was comand,</L>
<L>How faire hap with him ferd, so fer wan in &thorn;e land,</L>
<L>&thorn;at R. turned ageyn, his marschalle teld him why;</L>
<L>&amp; said Philip, "certeyn our dede is not wor&thorn;i.</L>
<L>"Our dede has bene nouht sen we hider camen,</L>
<L>"To turne haf I &thorn;ouht tille Acres alle samen.</L>
<L>"If R. hider com, wynne it bifor vs alle,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at we &thorn;is sege nom, schame it wille vs falle.</L>
<L>"&thorn;an salle men doute vs lesse, men se we do no dede,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e Sarazins our pruesse not so mykelle wille drede.
<PB REF="00000410.tif" N="182"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is &thorn;e oste Frankis tille Acres alle went,</L>
<L>&amp; comen ere &thorn;e Inglis with pauilloun &amp; tent,</L>
<L>&amp; loged &thorn;am right wele ouer alle &thorn;er &thorn;am &thorn;ink,</L>
<L>Inouh &thorn;ei had catele, &amp; plente mete &amp; drynk.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei had alle eten, &amp; watches mad alle preste,</L>
<L>To gete &thorn;at &thorn;ei had geten, R. &yogh;ede to reste.</L>
<L>&para; Orely on &thorn;e morn his messe he &yogh;ede to here,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de|precacio Ricardi per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Jhesu of Mary born &thorn;is was his prayere:</L>
<L>"Lord Jhesu," he said, "als so verrayly</L>
<L>"As my luf is on &thorn;e laid, &amp; on &thorn;i moder Mary,</L>
<L>"Help me to venge &thorn;i dede of &thorn;is Sarazins kynd,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at gaf conseile &amp; rede, &thorn;e to bete &amp; bynd,</L>
<L>"&amp; namly on &thorn;at blode, &thorn;at com of fals Pilate,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at wist sakles &thorn;ou stode, whan he on &thorn;i dome sate.</L>
<L>"Jhesu for &thorn;in honour, if it be &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>"I ask &thorn;e now socoure, my &yogh;ernyng to fulfille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>RICHARD at Godesbord his messe had &amp; his rightes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce qu&aelig; dicit Ri|cardus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here now swilk a word he spak to his knyghtes:</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;is kyng Philip haf we no maner of help,</L>
<L>"Togidir I rede we kip, &thorn;at men of vs &yogh;elp.</L>
<L>"I vowe to Saynt Michael, &amp; tille halwes &thorn;at are,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at for wo ne wele hi&thorn;en ne salle I fare,</L>
<L>"Ne tille Acres go, tille &thorn;e castelle be taken,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at Philip went fro, for vs has it forsaken.</L>
<L>"For his awen defaut with vs he has envie,</L>
<L>"Go we to &thorn;e assaut &thorn;at God vs alle condie.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e dikes were fulle wide &thorn;at closed &thorn;e castelle about,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De capci|one castri per Ricar|dum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; depe on ilk a side, with bankis hie without.
<PB REF="00000411.tif" N="183"></L>
<L>Was &thorn;er non entre, &thorn;at to &thorn;e castelle gan ligge,</L>
<L>Bot a streite kauce, at &thorn;e end a drauht brigge,</L>
<L>With grete duble cheynes drauhen ouer &thorn;e gate,</L>
<L>&amp; fyfti armed sueynes porters at &thorn;at &yogh;ate.</L>
<L>With slenges &amp; magneles &thorn;ei kast to kyng Richard,</L>
<L>Our Cristen bi parcelles kasted ageynward.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Dis seriauntz des plus feres, e de melz vanez, Deua|unt le cors le Reis sa targe ount portez, <I>Codd. Gallici.</I></NOTE>Ten sergeanz of &thorn;e best his targe gan him bere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at egre wer &amp; prest to couere him &amp; to were.</L>
<L>Himself as a Geant &thorn;e cheynes in tuo hew,</L>
<L>&thorn;e targe was his warant, &thorn;at non tille him threw.</L>
<L>Right vnto &thorn;e &yogh;ate with &thorn;e targe &thorn;ei &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Fightand on a gate, vndir him &thorn;e slouh his stede.</L>
<L>&thorn;er for ne wild he sesse, alone in to &thorn;e castele</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;am alle wild presse, on fote fauht he fulle wele.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De probi|tate ejus, quando pugnavit per se in castro.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &amp; whan he was withinne, &amp; fauht as a wilde leon,</L>
<L>He fondred &thorn;e Sarazins otuynne, &amp; fauht as a dragon.</L>
<L>Withoute &thorn;e Cristen gan crie, "allas! R. is taken,</L>
<L>&thorn;o Normans were sorie, of contenance gan blaken.</L>
<L>To slo doun &amp; to stroye, neuer wild &thorn;ei stint,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei left for dede no noye, ne for no wounde no dynt.</L>
<L>&thorn;at in went alle &thorn;er pres, maugre &thorn;e Sarazins alle,</L>
<L>&amp; fond R. on des fightand, &amp; wonne &thorn;e halle.</L>
<L>No body bot he alone vnto &thorn;e Cristen cam,</L>
<L>&amp; slayn he had ilkone, &thorn;c lordes bot &thorn;re he nam.</L>
<L>With &thorn;o &thorn;re o lyue his messengers went,</L>
<L>Tille Acres gan &thorn;ei dryue, to Philip mad present.
<PB REF="00000412.tif" N="184"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is grete honour comen to Inglis men</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh R. &thorn;e conquerour, his douhtynes we ken.</L>
<L>Kyng Philip of France fulle gretely is he noyed,</L>
<L>&thorn;at R. had suilk chance, &thorn;e castelle had destroyed.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh spie &thorn;e Soudan wist, &thorn;at Philip was no payed,</L>
<L>No gamen him ne list, bot held him alle dismayed.</L>
<L>To Philip a letter he sent &thorn;e Soudan Saladyn,</L>
<L>A no&thorn;er to R. went, &thorn;at brouht a Sarazyn.</L>
<L>&thorn;us &thorn;an gan he seye, als it wer for &thorn;er prowe,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e kynges tueye, "&thorn;e Soudan gretes &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>"&amp; sais for seuen &yogh;ere God &thorn;an were &thorn;e trewe.</L>
<L>"If &yogh;our God be so clere, &amp; of so grete vertewe,</L>
<L>"As &yogh;e preche oft tide, for sothe &yogh;e schew &amp; seie,</L>
<L>"We Sarazins on our side be &thorn;at tyme salle purueie,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;is lond salle be &yogh;ours, &amp; we bicome Cristen,</L>
<L>"Withouten mo stours or blode spillyng of men,</L>
<L>"&amp; haf alle &thorn;at &yogh;e wan withouten gansaying.</L>
<L>&thorn;erto ansuer gan Philip &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&amp; said, "&thorn;er men bedis skille, skille men ouh to take.</L>
<L>"&thorn;o &thorn;at wille not &thorn;at tille, skille salle &thorn;am forsake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"ALLAS!" said Richard, "&thorn;at euer it suld be couth,</L>
<L>"Or spoken efterward said of Cristen mouth,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at for a Sarazins sawe, contreued of fals quayntise,</L>
<L>"A Cristen man suld him withdrawe fro Jhesu Criste seruise.</L>
<L>"Alle ere we hider comen, Jhesu Criste to serue,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e way for him we nomen, for him to lyue &amp; sterue.</L>
<L>"His childre ere we alle, of God our fader biforn,</L>
<L>"&thorn;is lond suld to vs falle, &thorn;er our fader was born.
<PB REF="00000413.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>"Jhesu was born here, &amp; alle our first lynage,</L>
<L>"We ere his childre dere, we clayme &thorn;is our heritage,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;ise paen hondes our ancestre haf reft,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;orgh hard woundes of &thorn;am salle reyme it eft.</L>
<L>"Bot if &thorn;ei wille with pes &thorn;is lond &yogh;eld vs alle quite,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ei salle &thorn;an haf reles, of fayth gode respite.</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ei at no certeyn wille &yogh;eld it vs with pes,</L>
<L>"We salle wynne it ageyn, &thorn;at &thorn;ei bifor vs les.</L>
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ke son deuer ne face, pur quay la croice perist, [<I>sive</I> prist, [Hastiement luy prenge la male mort subit, <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;at dos not his deuere with dede no with rede,</L>
<L>"Hastely &thorn;is &yogh;ere falle him &thorn;e ferynges dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>PHILIP vnderstode, R. wild not consent,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ilk conant forth &yogh;ode, &thorn;at &thorn;e Soudan sent.</L>
<L>Philip held him stille, &amp; bigan to smyle,</L>
<L>Men sais &thorn;at comes of ille, &amp; &thorn;inkyng som gile.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles day &amp; o&thorn;er he purueied priuely,</L>
<L>Of mast, saile, &amp; ro&thorn;er he dight his schip redy.</L>
<L>&para; Oft he sent for leue vnto kyng R.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Philippus licentia pe|tita a Ri|cardo ad Franciam se paravir.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sekenes gan him so greue, &thorn;at he mot wende homward.</L>
<L>He was in poynt to &yogh;elde &thorn;e gaste, &amp; sone to die,</L>
<L>For euel he ne myght him welde, in bed behoued him lie.</L>
<L>Sen o&thorn;er wais ne myght vaile, &thorn;an said R. for wo,</L>
<L>"Philip now wille me faile, &amp; alle gate wend me fro.</L>
<L>"Conant holdes he non, &thorn;at he to Jhesu hight,</L>
<L>"With body &amp; soule alon to venge him at his myght.</L>
<L>"Sen Jhesu he wille not venge, ne hold his vowe no &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>"He salle him chalenge &thorn;e day of his endyng.
<PB REF="00000414.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>"If he wille go or duelle, as he wille I wille wele,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e despite, &thorn;at is to telle, to God is don ilk dele.</L>
<L>&para; Fulle oft biforhand bituex &thorn;am was distance,</L>
<L>For wynnyng of &thorn;e land, &thorn;at R. wan &thorn;orgh chance.</L>
<L>Haluendele asked Philip, as for first conant,</L>
<L>&amp; for felawschip of Cipres conquerand.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at Philip of France, for he suld haf grantise,</L>
<L>Mad R. a quite clamance fro him &amp; alle hise,</L>
<L>&amp; neuer &thorn;orgh no destresse suld clayme &thorn;er of no right.</L>
<L>Philip with grete mekenesse his trouth &thorn;erto plight,</L>
<L>Gascoyn &amp; Normundie suld &yogh;eme at his powere,</L>
<L>Withouten vilanie, tille his comyng were nere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>PHILIP tok his leue, withouten more essoyne</L>
<L>His suld alle to cheue, tille Sir Hugh of Burgoyne.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e Frankis oste Sir Hugh had in kepyng,</L>
<L>Now sailes fro &thorn;at coste, home wendes Philip &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e se sailand he lendes toward Lumbardie,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le duk de Austrice <I>Codd. Gallici.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e erle of Ostrice wendes with him companie.</L>
<L>R. stille he leues, &thorn;e lond he wild more se,</L>
<L>&amp; Saladyn he reues &thorn;e flom of <NOTE PLACE="foot">Cesaree, <I>sive</I> Cesa|rye, <I>MSS. Gall. tam h&icirc;c quam &amp; infra.</I></NOTE> Cisare.</L>
<L>At &thorn;at ilk flom Richard gaf bataile,</L>
<L>Greuance had he som, here now of his trauaile.</L>
<L>In Antioche, in Acres, in alle &thorn;o ilk cuntres,</L>
<L>He set wardeyns watres, to kepe alle &thorn;e entres.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en toward Cayfas displaied his banere,</L>
<L>&amp; cuer his nauie was in &thorn;e se biside not fere.
<PB REF="00000415.tif" N="187"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>RICHARD <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> has.</NOTE> his his spie on Soudan Saladyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De pugna ad flumen Cisarie.</NOTE></L>
<L>Som said he suld lie at &thorn;e toun of Joppyn.</L>
<L>To Joppyn whan he cam, &thorn;e Soudan was not &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e flom &thorn;e Soudan nam, R. forto affere.</L>
<L>Saladyn priuely was bussed beside &thorn;e flom,</L>
<L>&amp; spied strete &amp; stie what R. suld com,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he suld not pas, ne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> no. <I>Nam Codices Gallici</I>, De Richard ny passe, ne nul de sa partye.</NOTE> mo man of his oste.</L>
<L>&thorn;e water stopped was, &thorn;er passage suld be moste.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Saladyn les hoers de flum ad saisye <I>Gallice.</I></NOTE> Saladyn did stoppe &thorn;e dikes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> bank.</NOTE> kank &amp; bro,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non suld ouer hoppe, ne man ne hors suld go</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;at enbussement, &thorn;at was so priuely,</L>
<L>R. suld be schent, if &thorn;at way he com by.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>RICHARD fast him drouh toward Cisare,</L>
<L>To witte where or how &thorn;e best passage mot be.</L>
<L>Whan R. &thorn;ider cam, he sauh &thorn;er was tre gette,</L>
<L>Passage non he nam, &thorn;e forthes wer withsette.</L>
<L>R. beheld aboute, of gile he drede him neid,</L>
<L>Of Sarazins a grete route, (&thorn;e lond was vmbeleid,)</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;at suerd mot bere, or o&thorn;er wapen weld,</L>
<L>Were sette R. to dere, enbussed &thorn;orgh &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>He said, "Jhesu mercy, &amp; &thorn;i moder dere,</L>
<L>"Wherfore we com &amp; why, now we fynd &thorn;am here.</L>
<L>Whan he sauh he ne myght passe on non wise,</L>
<L>In &thorn;re parties to fight his oste he did deuise.
<PB REF="00000416.tif" N="188"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIR James<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>In the MS. of the Heralds Office 'tis</I> de Aucunes, <I>in one of Mr. Anstis's</I> de Aucune, <I>but in the other</I> de Auenues. <I>Yet below both of Mr. Anstis's Co|pies have</I> Auenues.</NOTE> of Auenu he had &thorn;e first eschele,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Jacobo Auenue.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was non of his vertu in armes did so wele,</L>
<L>Gentille of norture, &amp; noble of lynage,</L>
<L>Was non &thorn;at bare armure, &thorn;at did suilk vassalage.</L>
<L>Of werre &amp; of bataile he was fulle auise,</L>
<L>&thorn;er wisdom suld auaile was non so trewe als he.</L>
<L>Pere had he non in &thorn;e lond &thorn;er he was born,</L>
<L>He praied &thorn;e kyng on one he mot be first biforn,</L>
<L>&amp; he gaf him &thorn;e vamward, &thorn;e Sarazins oste to cleue,</L>
<L>&amp; he at kyng R. for euer &thorn;an toke his leue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng withoute essoyn suld be in &thorn;e midde,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Al duk de Burgoyne la terce est co|maunde, Et al mestre du Temple oue [<I>sive</I> ou, <I>vel</I> ouf] sa fraternete, <I>MSS. Gallici.</I></NOTE>&amp; &thorn;e erle of Burgoyn he suld haf &thorn;e &thorn;ridde.</L>
<L>With were &thorn;e templers, &amp; &thorn;er fraternite,</L>
<L>Fals in alle maners, so tellis &thorn;e stori me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON &thorn;e to&thorn;er side &thorn;e of &thorn;e Sarazin,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De turmis Saladini.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e vamward suld ride &thorn;e Soudan Saladyn,</L>
<L>Paien most wor&thorn;i of alle &thorn;e lond of his kyn,</L>
<L>So told me &thorn;e stori &thorn;at I fond writen in.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e secund turbe was maister Coradyn</L>
<L>Lord of Damas, his fader was Safadyn.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Soldan plus curtoys ne goustait vnkes vyn. De la terce eschele mestre fu Mel|chyn, Seygnour de Bandas, e Welchifasyn, [<I>sive</I> Wetipha|sin] Seygnour de Galyle &amp; del leu on Cayn Tua son frere Abel par [<I>vel</I> on] feloun en|gyn <I>Codd. MSS. Gallici.</I></NOTE>Soudan so curteys neuer drank no wyne,</L>
<L>&thorn;e same &thorn;e Romans sais &thorn;at is of Richardyn.
<PB REF="00000417.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>&para; &amp; ouer &thorn;e &thorn;rid pas was maister Sir Melchyn,</L>
<L>Lord of Baudas, &amp; Sir Matifasyn,</L>
<L>Lord of Galile, &amp; &thorn;e stede &thorn;at Chayn,</L>
<L>&amp; Sire of &thorn;at cuntre, &thorn;er Abel was slayn.</L>
<L>&para;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sire Jaqes de Aucunes, [<I>sive</I> Auenues] verray pelryn, Se seygne de la croice &amp; prent son chemyn [<I>sive</I> chymyn <I>vel</I> chimyn] <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> James of Auenue, he was verray pilgryn,</L>
<L>He gan first remue &thorn;e croice mad on his bryn.</L>
<L>On &thorn;er first eschel he smot in fulle hastif,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;orgh &thorn;am ilka del, als grehound or mastif,</L>
<L>Tuys withouten encumbre, with suerd in his hand,</L>
<L>He slouh withouten numbre, bifor him mot non stand.</L>
<L>Biside com a Sarazins, bituex him &amp; a bank,</L>
<L>Sir Kalaphes Duryns, he smote of James schank.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an spak James, "&thorn;o a kosyn help Richard,</L>
<L>"Fulle fer ert &thorn;ou me fro, kast &thorn;e now to me ward.</L>
<L>"&thorn;i sister sonne am I, &thorn;ou eam &amp; I cosyn.</L>
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Rey Henry ton pere en cha|stel Constantyn Engendra ma mere sur dame Auelyn, Countesse de la Marche, pur Dieu &amp; Seint Martyn Venez venger ma morte sur ceo Sa|racyn, <I>Codd. Gallici.</I></NOTE>&thorn;i fader kyng Henry in &thorn;e castelle Constantya</L>
<L>"My moder &thorn;an gate he opon dame Auelyn.</L>
<L>"Countas of Marche was sche, &amp; or I &yogh;it do my fyn</L>
<L>"My dede salle I venge on Kalaphes Duryn.</L>
<L>"With a gode suerd of lorenge he smote &thorn;orgh &thorn;e Sarazin,</L>
<L>James lese &thorn;er his hand, &amp; died in &thorn;at pyn.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Jacobi.</NOTE></L>
<L>On &thorn;e morn men him fand, &amp; &thorn;e frere Baudwyn,
<PB REF="00000418.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>A frere of &thorn;e hospitalle, &thorn;e erle's sonne Paulyn,</L>
<L>Was lord of Morian alle &amp; of Mount<NOTE PLACE="foot">Moryn <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE> Modyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN R. herd say, &thorn;at James was slayn,</L>
<L>He wend for dole to dey, he com as a wode man,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Qaunt Saladyn ly vait de bone volentez Aproche al Rey Richard, ia sunt encountrez, <I>Gallice.</I></NOTE>&amp; Saladyn sauh him cam, &thorn;er of fulle wele he lete,</L>
<L>Ageyn R. he nam, togider gan &thorn;ei mete,</L>
<L>A kyng &amp; a Soudan of alle &thorn;e world &thorn;e beste.</L>
<L>R. tille him ran, a stroke on him he fest,</L>
<L>He smote him in &thorn;e helm, bakward he bare his stroupe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e body he did ouerwhelm, his hede touched &thorn;e croupe,</L>
<L>He felle doun with &thorn;e dynt, bot son he ros vp light,</L>
<L>Herneys nouht ne tynt, bot eft on hors fulle wight.</L>
<L>R. at &thorn;at turne &thorn;e flom he wan fulle wele,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De insulta|tione regis Ricardi &amp; Saladini.</NOTE></L>
<L>For Sarazin ne wild he skurne &thorn;at were of his eschele.</L>
<L>Fourti &thorn;ousand paien, what drenkled &amp; what slayn,</L>
<L>&amp; a &thorn;ousand Cristen, so was &thorn;e tale certeyn.</L>
<L>For soth &thorn;e &thorn;rid eschele fulle hard was bisted,</L>
<L>&thorn;e templers ilk a dele failed &amp; &thorn;ien fled.</L>
<L>&thorn;e `erle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Duk de Burgoyne <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE> bakward was born, &amp; alle &thorn;e Frankis men</L>
<L>Fulle nere had &thorn;ei bien lorn, bot &thorn;ei cried, <I>help Cristen.</I></L>
<L>&thorn;e erle bigan to crie, "turne and help vs Richard,</L>
<L>"Or els salle we die, &thorn;at ere in &thorn;is rereward.
<PB REF="00000419.tif" N="191"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">De Jerusalem le Rey Guyoun gentyls Dist al Rey Richard, Sire tournez le vys, Le duk e sa eschele sunt ia taunt supris, Le Soldan Sa|ladyn apoy [<I>sive</I> ad poy, <I>vel</I> a poy] les ad conquys, <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE>"SIR," said kyng Guyon, "turne ageyn, I rede,</L>
<L>"Frankis &amp; Burgoillon, els alle gos to dede.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e Soudan Saladyn has &thorn;am nere conquered,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e templers magre myn, fals &thorn;ei er &amp; ferd.</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ei had standen nere, &thorn;e myght haf wonnen pris,</L>
<L>"Non dos &thorn;er deuere, bot Raynald &thorn;e marchis.</L>
<L>Said &thorn;e kyng R. "if &thorn;e duke be taken,</L>
<L>"It salle be &thorn;am hard, bot &thorn;ei haf him forsaken.</L>
<L>&thorn;e flom sone he left, ageyn toke his gate,</L>
<L>&thorn;e duke fro &thorn;am he reft, welnere he com to late.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le duk pardist cel houre chiualers trent &amp; sys, Treis centz de petayle, seri|auntz cent e dys. Et de cel eschele, quantz qe sount re|mys, Fet le Rey passer le flum a [<I>vel</I> ad] lour amys, <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e duke at &thorn;at bataile lost sex &amp; &thorn;ritty knyghtes,</L>
<L>&thorn;re hundreth of pedaile, a hundreth sergeanz at rightes.</L>
<L>&thorn;e duke alle &thorn;ese les, &amp; &thorn;o &thorn;at were olyue,</L>
<L>R. for alle &thorn;e pres sauely did &thorn;am vp ryue.</L>
<L>At &thorn;at tyme R. &thorn;ere many a man slouh he,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng sonne of Dare he smote in tuo his the.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Soudan Saladyn he was fulle vnfayn,</L>
<L>He fled with mykelle pyn vnto &thorn;e mountayn.</L>
<L>R. has &thorn;e pris at &thorn;e flom of Cisare,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazin force doun his, Jhesu we &thorn;ank &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000420.tif" N="192"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Richard Reis Englays ad saisye Cesaree, Joppen e Scalon, Cades &amp; Japhe, Et al Rey Guyoun la garde ad done. Le duk de Burgoyne est si male mene. Qe ly Si|rogene del duk est desperee, Et le Rey Richard mout [<I>sive</I> mult] desconforte, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&THORN;ISE Sarazins were so fesid, &thorn;at fled was Saladyn,</L>
<L>&amp; Cisare has he sesid, Japht &amp; Joppyn,</L>
<L>Cades &amp; Ascalon, alle has kyng Richard:</L>
<L>Under him kyng Guyon had &thorn;am alle in ward.</L>
<L>&thorn;e duke was in a cas, his wondes wer so grym,</L>
<L>&thorn;at his leche was in ille hope of him,</L>
<L>&amp; R. was fulle dred, &thorn;e leche mot him not saue."</L>
<L>Tille Acres &thorn;ei him led, better hele to haue.</L>
<L>In &thorn;er way ilk dele &thorn;ei fond voide als hethe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e toun of Mount Carmele, &thorn;e toun of Nazareth,</L>
<L>&thorn;e strong castelle Pilryn, &thorn;at first wonnen was,</L>
<L>Alle tok Ricardyn, Caloyn &amp; Kayfas.</L>
<L>Ilkon &thorn;ise &thorn;ei scised, tome alle &thorn;ei fond,</L>
<L>Seke were &thorn;er heised, heled &thorn;am of wound.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Soudan to R. sent, to speke togider in glath,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Saldanus venit tra|ctare pa|cem.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e pes it ment, &amp; of no maner wrath.</L>
<L>Ne no &thorn;ing suld it greue vnto &thorn;e Cristiente,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons said bi leue, welcom mot he be.</L>
<L>Saladyn come &thorn;ider &thorn;at day &thorn;at he sette,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons wer togider, &thorn;e kynge &amp; &thorn;am he grette.</L>
<L>&para; "Sir," said Saladyn, "&thorn;i God has grete powere,</L>
<L>"Er alle &thorn;ise Cristen &thorn;in, &thorn;at &thorn;ou kepes here?</L>
<L>"&thorn;ise Inglis," said R. "in my kepyng &thorn;ei are,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e Frankis haf o&thorn;er ward, wi&thorn; &thorn;e erle of Burgoyn &thorn;ei fare.
<PB REF="00000421.tif" N="193"></L>
<L>"Bot &thorn;ei be of &thorn;i faith, els do &thorn;ei wrong,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ei stand alle to gode graith, whan &thorn;ou ert &thorn;am among,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;ou ert comen fro ferne, &amp; riche kyng is of fe,</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ou pes wille &yogh;erne, for &thorn;e &amp; &thorn;i meyne,</L>
<L>"&amp; trewe for seuen &yogh;ere, I consent &thorn;ertille,</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ou has &thorn;at manere, to do euenhede &amp; skille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"CERTES Saladyn, "said &thorn;e kyng Richere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio Ricardi.</NOTE></L>
<L>"To mak partie ageyn myn &yogh;it ha &thorn;ou gode powere,</L>
<L>"&amp; for &thorn;e pes to seke has &thorn;ou no mystere,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ertille to mak me meke, my herte to &yogh;it in wehere.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou has power inouh, wherto askes &thorn;ou pes?</L>
<L>"&amp; my wille wille not bouh, to grante &thorn;at &thorn;ou ches.</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ou &thorn;e lond wille &yogh;eld, &thorn;erof is to speke,</L>
<L>"&amp; si&thorn;en if &thorn;ou wild &thorn;i lay forsake &amp; breke,</L>
<L>"&amp; take our bapteme of funte, as childre &yogh;ing,</L>
<L>"I salle gyue &thorn;e a reame, &amp; do &thorn;e coroun kyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Sire, dist Saladyn, gre te dey sauer, Ke tu saunz desert me vols honourer, <I>Gallice.</I></NOTE>"SIR," said Saladyn, "&thorn;ank I auh &yogh;ow conne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Saldanus dixit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;ou me profers of &thorn;in, &amp; has non enchesonne.</L>
<L>"If I myght &thorn;e paemie justise &thorn;am ilkone,</L>
<L>"&amp; non had seignorie bot I my self alone,</L>
<L>"&thorn;an I trow my &thorn;ouht myght acord to &thorn;in,</L>
<L>"Bot now dar I nouht. <NOTE PLACE="foot">Mon frere Saf|fadyn teent son regne entere, Ses fiz sunt grantez sey|gnours, ne volent lesser Tere ne tenement, pur nuly prech|er, <I>Gall.</I></NOTE>My bro&thorn;er Safadyn
<PB REF="00000422.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>"Is riche of tenement, his sonnes strong &amp; stith,</L>
<L>"&thorn;er wille wille not be went, ne lete &thorn;er lond ne lith.</L>
<L>"Wild &thorn;e bicom Cristen, fulle eth I were to drawe,</L>
<L>"Bot I dar not for &thorn;am alle one to leue our lawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>RICHARD said, "per fay, go now &amp; conseile &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"&amp; bi &thorn;e &thorn;rid day, &thorn;at salle haf certeynte.</L>
<L>"Bi &thorn;an I salle &thorn;e say, how &thorn;at it salle go,</L>
<L>"Of pes to haf &thorn;e way, or werre, on of &thorn;e tuo.</L>
<L>Listen now a gile of Sir Safadyn,</L>
<L>Contreued a wikked wile on his bro&thorn;er Saladyn.</L>
<L>&para; Now wendes Saladyn &thorn;er his oste gan lie,</L>
<L>His<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> bo&thorn;er Safadyn his comyng did spie,</L>
<L>He sent to kyng R. a stede for curteisie,</L>
<L>On of &thorn;e best reward, &thorn;at was in paemie:</L>
<L>Bad him bi &thorn;at &yogh;ere token, ware him for trieherie;</L>
<L>Said, "Saladyn was fulle foen, on him may non affie,</L>
<L>"He sais behind &thorn;i bak, in strange companie,</L>
<L>"Wordes &thorn;at er to lak, he dar &thorn;e wele diffie,</L>
<L>"If he &amp; &thorn;ou alone myght &yogh;ow togider alie,</L>
<L>"He myght withouten mone of &thorn;e wynne &thorn;e maistrie;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Si tu soys taunt vayllaunt, com le mounde te crye, Rebukez le bien de sa sur quiderye, <I>Codd. Gallici.</I></NOTE>"&amp;, Sir, if &thorn;ou be suilk, als men of &thorn;e crie,</L>
<L>"Rebuke him for &thorn;at ilk of &thorn;at auauntrie.</L>
<L>"If I may be auaile of hors or armurie,</L>
<L>"Forsoth I salle not faile, to mende &thorn;i partie.</L>
<L>Bot or &thorn;at day felle to stand, &thorn;at &thorn;er acorde suld be,</L>
<L>Had R. herd ti&thorn;and out Normundie.
<PB REF="00000423.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>&para; "&thorn;e folk out of France to Normundie were comen,</L>
<L>"To R. desceyuance his londes haf &thorn;ei nomen.</L>
<L>"Bot he com right son, Normundie to fende,</L>
<L>"His right bes nouht doun soner &thorn;an any wend.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Rey Richard as vns la chos certifye, Et a parler de trewe al Soldan plus se plye, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Wherfore to som of his he schewed &thorn;am &thorn;e skille,</L>
<L>To treus on alle wise him burd grant &thorn;ertille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>UNDER &thorn;e mount Thabor, in a faire medue,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e parties wer &thorn;ore to conseile for &thorn;e treue."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Est Sa|ladyn venuz en amour saunz boydie, Et prye al Rey Ri|chard, que son plaisir ly dye, <I>Codices Gall.</I></NOTE>"Sir," said Saladyn, "is it &thorn;i wille to say,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De pace tractata &amp; ordinata per Ricar|dum &amp; Saladinum.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;is day is myn &amp; &thorn;in, chese &thorn;ou now what way.</L>
<L>For Safadyn's sawe R. had enuie,</L>
<L>Wherfore a gode &thorn;rawe he stod in a studie.</L>
<L>&thorn;at sawe &thorn;at he &thorn;er said, so wele it was of leten,</L>
<L>In boke it was vp laid, &yogh;it is it not forgeten.</L>
<L>R. &thorn;is ansuerd to Saladyu for treu,</L>
<L>For &thorn;o men &thorn;at it herd wrote vs &thorn;at word alle new.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"TREUS &thorn;ou askes a &thorn;rowe, for tuo &yogh;ere or &thorn;re,</L>
<L>"&thorn;o men, &thorn;at &thorn;e knowe, say &thorn;ou skornes me.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e folk of paiemie &thorn;e word &thorn;er of fer gos,</L>
<L>"Of alle &thorn;at seignorie &thorn;orghout &thorn;in is &thorn;e los;</L>
<L>"In armes is &thorn;er none, &thorn;at to &thorn;i renoun reches,</L>
<L>"Wherfor &thorn;ou has gone, &amp; of &thorn;i pruesse preches,
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>"&thorn;at if &thorn;ou me mot mete bi our seluen tuo,</L>
<L>"My lif I suld forlete, or my hede for go.</L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;ou wille it proue, &thorn;at &thorn;ou ert so wor&thorn;i,</L>
<L>"A stede tille our behoue here is on alle redi.</L>
<L>"Now for &thorn;i grete valow, I ask &thorn;e a bone,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at or we grante trew, fight we als so sone,</L>
<L>"&thorn;an on non o&thorn;er side body so bolde to be,</L>
<L>"On fote ne hors ride, to socour me no &thorn;e.</L>
<L>"&amp; whilk of vs is doun, &amp; mad is recreant,</L>
<L>"Cleyme &amp; accioun he lese, &amp; &thorn;e remanant</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;at ilk land, &thorn;at Cristen euer auht,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;ei held in &thorn;er hand of God &thorn;at &thorn;am it tauht.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an said Saladyn, "if &thorn;ou fynd any man,</L>
<L>"Cristen or Sarazin,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Id est</I>, that knows or can tell what, <I>&amp;c.</I></NOTE> &thorn;at what tyme or whan,</L>
<L>"I mad auancement with &thorn;e alone to fight,</L>
<L>"Bot I to bataile went for my reame's right,</L>
<L>"Here I salle &thorn;e gyue alle myn heritage,</L>
<L>"&amp; als along as I lyue to be in &thorn;in ostage.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e maister of &thorn;e Temple com procurand &thorn;e pes,</L>
<L>"No more of &thorn;is to demple, tak &thorn;at &thorn;at &yogh;e first ches.</L>
<L>Saladyn for alle hise hette to hold conaunt,</L>
<L>Seuen &yogh;ere at his deuise, &amp; R. &thorn;er to graunt,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ilk a Cristen man suld hold &amp; haue certeyn</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at he &thorn;er wan, &amp; no &thorn;ing &yogh;eld ageyn.
<PB REF="00000425.tif" N="197"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is it in forward alle pesed &amp; wele ent,</L>
<L>Now turne kyng R. tille Acres is he went.</L>
<L>After kyng Guyon &amp; for his sonne he sent,</L>
<L>Of Antioche Reymon him also he ment,</L>
<L>Aunfrey of Turoyn he was &thorn;er present,</L>
<L>Of Triple erle Bumoun fulle sui&thorn;e &thorn;ider glent,</L>
<L>Sir<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>So 'tis also in one of Mr. Anstis's Copies. But in the other, as also in that of the Heralds Office, 'tis</I> Rupyn.</NOTE> Ruffyn bro&thorn;er Leoun, alle &thorn;ise held parlement.</L>
<L>Kyng R. his resoun said &thorn;am, "how he was schent,</L>
<L>"Philip did him tresoun, destroied his tenement.</L>
<L>"For to stanch his foysoun homward haf I ment.</L>
<L>"Normundie alle doun, mykelle &thorn;er of is brent</L>
<L>"&amp; slayn blak &amp; broun of alle &thorn;at he mot hent.</L>
<L>"I wille of &thorn;at feloun tak vengement,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at fo fordos my coroun, if grace be to me lent.</L>
<L>&para; "Wherfor &yogh;e lordynges, &yogh;e ere me lefe &amp; dere,</L>
<L>"I take in &yogh;our kepynges &thorn;e londes &thorn;at we wonne here.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e freres of &thorn;e hospital, &amp; &thorn;e temple also,</L>
<L>"Biseke &thorn;am I salle, &thorn;at &thorn;ei help &yogh;ow &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>"Now haf I don &amp; said, &amp; tauht &yogh;ow &thorn;at I may,</L>
<L>"My hope is on &yogh;ow laid, lordynges haf gode day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE prince of Antioche, &amp; &thorn;e kyng Guyon,</L>
<L>Bumunde erle of Triple, &amp; Aunfrey of Turoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex dixit baronibus suis &amp; pe|ciit licen|ciam ab eis, &amp; iter ar|ripuit ver|sus An|gliam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ise had in &thorn;er ward cite, kastelle &amp; toun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng R. wan of Sarazin feloun,</L>
<L>&amp; Isaac &thorn;e Emperour takes his liuerisoun,</L>
<L>With freres mad soioure in temple dominoun.
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="198"></L>
<L>His douhter with &thorn;e quene was for hir warisoun,</L>
<L>&amp; so felle it to bene, hir fader lese &thorn;e coroun,</L>
<L>&amp; as R. home went toward &thorn;is regioun,</L>
<L>Or he were taken or hent, or holden in prisoun,</L>
<L>He gaf his sistere &thorn;at while vnto &thorn;e erle Reymoun</L>
<L>Lord of Saynt Gile, aman of grete renoun.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Forte</I>, I ne fond.</NOTE>I fond in my boke, what skille ne for whi,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he his folk forsoke, &amp; &yogh;ede so priueli.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Po|tius</I>, Austrice, <I>cum MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Aufrice to aspie him were better haf left,</L>
<L>&thorn;er in &thorn;orgh felonie was he robbed &amp; reft,</L>
<L>Taken with enmys &amp; holden in prisoun,</L>
<L>I kan not say &thorn;e pris was gyuen for his ransoun.</L>
<L>In prison was he bonden, as &thorn;e Romance sais,</L>
<L>In cheynes &amp; lede wonden, &thorn;at heuy was of peis.</L>
<L>A no&thorn;er pyne he had, if it may be trod,</L>
<L>With<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>Without all doubt King Ri|chard was used very roughly, and not agreeable to his Royal Dignity, after he was impri|soned. 'Tis for that very rea|son, that some Historians tell us (notwithstanding it be not mentioned in this Chronicle) that a Lyon was brought to him when he was confined in pri|son, with an intent to have (by that means) destroyed him. But instead of that, he kill'd the Lyon (to the great confusion and astonishment of his ene|mies) by thrusting his arm into his mouth, and thereby bruis|ing him so at the heart, that he died. John Rastall is one of those, that speaks of this memo|rable Action, taking notice, at the same time, of the causes of his being set upon, and of the vast sum of money that was de|manded and paid for his ran|som. At the same time he like|wise observes, that, according to some, he was called</I> Cure de Lyon <I>from this Heroical Exploit, but, according to o|thers, (who take no notice of this Affair) from his invincible Cou|rage. Rastall himself seems to think, this Denomination was oc|casion'd by his killing the Lyon; and for that reason, as I take it, it is, that the wooden Cut, which he hath given us of K. Richard, represents him with the Lyon be|tween his Legs, and thrusting his right Arm down his Throat. 'Tis probable he had seen old Pictures that confirm'd this Re|presentation. 'Tis also likely, that his Brother-in-law Sir Thomas More (from whom he had receiv'd so much assistance in his Historical Enquiries) approved of it. Indeed I have not yet seen (that I remember) any other old Figure, (besides this in Rastall) in which K. Richard is drawn after this manner. And yet I cannot but think, that he was sirnamed</I> Cure de Lyon <I>from some par|ticular Action, rather than from his Courage in general, it being usual with our Ancestors to give Sirnames from particular remark|able Accidents, such as distin|guished them in a peculiar man|ner from other eminent persons. And as Richard I. had got a very great name for his overcom|ing the Lyon (as well as he had for abundance of other very un|common Instances of Courage) so others also strived to follow his Steps, and were forward to encounter Lyons, and were will|ing to have themselves pictured as engaging with them. And, for better remembrance of such Adventures, they were often painted in old Halls, just as were also the Encounters that Gentle|men of Activity in Feats of Arms had with any strange Knights, such as those of the Blesells, hinted at by Leland, Itin. Vol. VII. p. 61. Such Pi|ctures were look'd upon very justly as great Ornaments to Halls, and 'tis pity more care hath not been taken to preserve them. Sometimes there were figures in our old Wainscotts that had Allusion to Heroical Actions, and these, therefore, ought also to be regarded by curious Persons, who may even from thence be capable of illu|strating some Particulars in our History. I have seen curious Works of this nature in some old Houses in Oxford. They were much in vogue in Q. Elizabeth's time, as they had been also in the Reign of her Father K. Henry VIIIth. when Cabi|nets were, withall, finely adorn'd with Pictures of Antiquity, as may appear as well from other instances, as from that which had been Leland's Cabi|net in the Bodleian Library. But instead of exspatiating, I shall give Rastall's own words, as I find them in the Copy of his Chronicle that was lent me by my kind Friend Mr. Murray.</I>&mdash;This kynge Rycharde perceyued that the Chrysten people decresyd in the holy lande &verbar; aswell by in|fyrmytes as lacke of vytell &verbar; toke a truce for. iii. yere and returned whomewarde &verbar; and sent the quene his wyfe by the see &verbar; and he sayled with a small company into Histra &amp; there landed &verbar; where he was takyn prisoner by the duke<NOTE PLACE="marg">kynge rycharde takyn prisoner.</NOTE> of Ostreche and by him put in prison &verbar; and brought to Henry Emperour of Almayne &verbar; whiche put hym in stronge prison &verbar; and after Raunsomed hym at c. M. li. whiche duke of Ostryche was afterwarde therfore accursed of the pope for the wronge done to kynge Rycharde.</P><P>&para; Also for the payment of this sayd Raunsome &verbar; after|warde the woll of all the whyte monkes and chanons in Englande was solde &verbar; and rynges &verbar; iewels of prelates and vessels and chalyces of all the churches thorowe the lande &verbar; and dyuers and many shrynes scraped and spoyled of theyr golde and syluer. Dyuers causes there were as wryters reherse &verbar; that the Emperour sholde owe grudge to kynge Richarde &verbar; one was because kynge Rycharde had promysed to the Emperour an ayde for the wynnynge of the kyngdome of Cicyle &verbar; whiche the Emperour claym|ed as his inheritance &verbar; whiche promyse kynge Rycharde as he sayd brake. Another cause was for that the kyng Rycharde toke from a knyght of the duke of Ostryche the dukes banner and trode it vnder his fete in dispyte of the duke and of the Empe|rour his lorde &verbar; &amp; therfore the duke &amp; the Emperour were gladde to do kynge Ry|charde displeasure.</P><P>&para; It is sayd that a Lyon was put to kynge Rycharde beynge in prison to haue de|uoured hym &verbar; and when the Lyon was gapynge &verbar; he put his Arme in his mouthe and pulled the lyon by the harte so hard &verbar; that he slewe the lyon. And therfore some say he is called Rycharde Cure de lyon &verbar; but some say he is called Cure de lyon because of his boldenesse and hardy stomake.</P></NOTE> iren nayles sad, it sais, his fete was schod.
<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="199">
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="200">
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="201"></L>
<L>&thorn;erfor &thorn;e pape of Rome cursed &thorn;am wro&thorn;erheile,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at did &thorn;at dome, or &thorn;erto gaf conseile.</L>
<L>His moder dame Alienore, &amp; &thorn;e barons of &thorn;is land,</L>
<L>For him trauailed sore, &amp; brouht him out of band.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN he of bond was brouht for raunson &thorn;at was riche,</L>
<L>His moder so bisouht, he aryued at Sandwiche.</L>
<L>To Canterbire fulle euen he souht to haf his bote,</L>
<L>Miles he &yogh;ede seuen to Saynt Thomas on fote.</L>
<L>With fulle riche offeryng he wirschipped S. Thomas.</L>
<L>His praier did him bryng out of his hard cas,</L>
<L>&thorn;anked God &amp; him so wele for him had schaped,</L>
<L>&thorn;at of his anguys grim so lightly was escaped.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO while &thorn;at R. was bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e se in hold,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Dummodo Rex R. in|carceratus fuit ultra mare, Jo|hannes fra|ter ejus commisit <NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE>multis in|juriis con|tra eum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jon did him trespas, his rentes tok &amp; sold,</L>
<L>His castels sesed &amp; brak, bigan a grete distance,</L>
<L>&amp; neuer no word spak of R. deliuerance.</L>
<L>Bot als a kyng of lond Jon bare him fulle stoute,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor R. wele fond with dome to chace him oute,</L>
<L>&amp; deme him als a no&thorn;er, for his vnkynd folie.</L>
<L>To kyng R. his bro&thorn;er Jon mercy gan crie,</L>
<L>&thorn;er moder &thorn;am bisouht, for to be at one.</L>
<L>Of trespas &thorn;at he had wrouht R. forgaf it Jon</L>
<L>&amp; said, "&thorn;i misdede be in &thorn;i mynsyng,</L>
<L>"Euer more to drede, eft to do suilk &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>"&amp; I wille neuer more on &thorn;i trespas &thorn;enk,</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ou repent &thorn;e sore, &thorn;at &thorn;ou did suilk a blenk.
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="202"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>RICHARD to Londen wendes, to hold parlement,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De parlia|mentoapud Londonias.</NOTE></L>
<L>For his barons sendes, &amp; &thorn;ei alle to him went.</L>
<L>At Westminster ilkone parlement &thorn;ei held,</L>
<L>To &thorn;am he mad his mone, &amp; &thorn;us to &thorn;am teld.</L>
<L>&para; "Lordynges of my chance wele &yogh;e auh to wite,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of France wille me disherite.</L>
<L>"For &thorn;at I was bistad bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e se in hold,</L>
<L>"&thorn;erfor Philip is glad, &amp; beres him fulle bold.</L>
<L>"My castels he takes, &amp; seises my citez,</L>
<L>"Destruction he makes of rentes &amp; feez.</L>
<L>"Wherfore barons dere, sais me a gode certeyn,</L>
<L>"&amp; how &amp; what manere my lond to gete ageyn.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an spak &thorn;e erle Rogere, as a man fulle wys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eece comes sapienter &amp; breviter respondit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Erles with &thorn;ar powere, barons &thorn;at er of pris,</L>
<L>"Knyghtes gode &amp; wight, sergeanz alle in ferd,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ise salle alle be dight, &amp; help &thorn;e with &thorn;er suerd.</L>
<L>"Bisshopes &amp; persons, burgeis of citez,</L>
<L>"&amp; rich merchandes eftsons salle help with &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> mones.</NOTE> mone.</L>
<L>"Abbay &amp; priorie, &amp; o&thorn;er religions,</L>
<L>"For vs salle pray &amp; crie in &thorn;er afflictions.</L>
<L>"Better is holy bede of man &thorn;at right lyues.</L>
<L>"&amp; standes vs in more stede, &thorn;an alle &thorn;e gode he gyues.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e comen wele was paied of &thorn;at conseilyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;at it were not delaied so was R. &thorn;e kyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW wille kyng R. alle his lond extende,</L>
<L>Merschalle &amp; stiward &thorn;erfor about dos sende,</L>
<L>&amp; homage &amp; feaute he askes &amp; releue,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons er fulle fre, to do as to &thorn;er chefe.
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="203"></L>
<L>Now has &thorn;e kyng wele sped, &amp; comen ageyn to London,</L>
<L>&amp; penies with him led, &amp; spendyng has he fondon.</L>
<L>His barons alle aboute fast tille him drowe,</L>
<L>With hors &amp; armes stoute, &thorn;er com tille him inowe.</L>
<L>R. wendes to schip, he wille no lenger duelle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e boste of kyng Philip fayn &thorn;an wild he felle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ARIUED is R. at Depe in Normundie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Transfreta|vit versus Normanni|am &amp; Gas|coniam con|tra Regem Franci&aelig;, &amp; cepit Bur|rez &amp; Gi|sors.</NOTE></L>
<L>He lay &thorn;er half a &yogh;ere, estres to aspie.</L>
<L>&amp; whan he sauh he myght, on his folk affie,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Sa gwere fet ordiner, les dutres establye, Deuers A|quytaygne sa banere desplye, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> His werre ordeynd &amp; dight to &thorn;o &thorn;at cou&thorn;e &thorn;am guye.</L>
<L>To Gascoyne &thorn;at he were fulle smertly he gan hie,</L>
<L>Cursels a castelle &thorn;ere he wan with maistrie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sergeanz &thorn;at it held wer in poynt to die,</L>
<L>To prison &thorn;ei &thorn;am &yogh;eld, bot mercy gan &thorn;ei crie.</L>
<L>&yogh;it he tok a pray, &thorn;orgh quayntise &amp; spie,</L>
<L>Burrez he wan &thorn;at day, bo&thorn;e hous &amp; seignorie,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e dangu &thorn;at nyght he tok his herbegerie.</L>
<L>To Cursels Philip had tight with alle his companie,</L>
<L>He ne wist it &yogh;olden was, tille he com so nehi.</L>
<L>Whan he wist, he fled &thorn;at pas, to Gisors tok &thorn;e stie.</L>
<L>R. perceyued &thorn;is, &thorn;at Philip to Gisors fled,</L>
<L>He comanded his Inglis, &thorn;at after fast &thorn;ei sped.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei com Philip so nere, &thorn;at he cried, "tak &thorn;e kyng,"</L>
<L>Bot non so hardi were, to smyte him for no &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ouht kyng Philip inouh was disconfite,</L>
<L>Whan he &amp; alle his trip for nouht fled so tite.
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="204"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Tent e pauyllioun, ke Phelipp werpist, Sunt al Rey Richard tote saunz countre|dit. Phelipp oue [<I>sive</I> ouf] ses Fraunceys al aler se prist, Richard oue [<I>sive</I> ouf] ses Englays chacaunt [<I>sive</I> chas|chaunt, <I>vel</I> chasaunt] les suist Al pount de Gysors, qe nest pas petit. En la rere garde nes vn Fraunceys remist. Molt fu le pople grant, qaunt le pount chaist, Le Reis en la Ryuere entre les altres gist, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Pauillon &amp; tent Philip bihynd him left,</L>
<L>To R. was it sent, no &thorn;ing &thorn;erof reft.</L>
<L>For mykelle lete &thorn;ei ligge, &thorn;erof mad &thorn;ei no force,</L>
<L>Philip vnto &thorn;e brigge &thorn;ei chaced him of Gisors.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e brigge were alle &thorn;e vamward &amp; &thorn;e rere,</L>
<L>Under &thorn;am &thorn;e brigge gan falle doun in to &thorn;e riuere.</L>
<L>Philip &amp; his meyne in &thorn;e water lay,</L>
<L>Schame him was to fle, &amp; so him com &thorn;at day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Knyght a bourdour kyng R. hade,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Markade dixit deri|sionem regi Franci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>A douhty man in stoure, his name was Markade.</L>
<L>He sauh kyng Philip als he lay in &thorn;e water,</L>
<L>"Sir kyng rise vp &amp; skip, for &thorn;ou has wette &thorn;i hater.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou fisshes not wor&thorn;e a lekc, rise &amp; go &thorn;i ways,</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou has wette &thorn;i breke, schent is &thorn;i hernays.</L>
<L>&thorn;e brigge was brode &amp; long, bo&thorn;e of tre &amp; stoncs,</L>
<L>Whan so mykelle &thorn;rong was &thorn;er on at ones.</L>
<L>Sex hundreth mot men se, so fele fallen &thorn;er were,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ritty &amp; &thorn;re did &thorn;er endyng &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>R. comanded alle gate, &thorn;at Philip suld men saue,</L>
<L>For no &thorn;ing suld &thorn;ei late, bot help &thorn;at lif mot hauc.</L>
<L>Of Mount Morice Mathi a baron renome,</L>
<L>Sir Alayn of Russie, Sir Fouke de Geffre,
<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>&thorn;ise grete were alle taken, &amp; &thorn;er knyghtes &thorn;am bi,</L>
<L>Makade held &thorn;am waken, &amp; tok of &thorn;am tuenti.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prisons he had in ward, for he was gode &amp; trewe:</L>
<L>Now turnes kyng R. to se his lond Anjowe.</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;is ilk tyme bifore or afterward,</L>
<L>I knowe no more to ryme of dedes of kyng R.</L>
<L>Who so wille his dedes alle &thorn;e soth se,</L>
<L>&thorn;e romance &thorn;at men redes &thorn;er is the propirte.</L>
<L>&thorn;is &thorn;at I haf said it is Pers sawe,</L>
<L>Als he in romance laid, &thorn;er after gan I drawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE ferth day formest next Palmesonenday,</L>
<L>&thorn;e tyme, as I gest, R. &yogh;ede to play<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Ricardi per bali|sterium.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;orgh a cuntre, men calle it Lymosin,</L>
<L>&thorn;e castelle manaced he &thorn;at Philip had &thorn;er in.</L>
<L>R. com ouer nere, &thorn;e castelle to aspie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at sauh an alblastere, a quarelle lete he flie,</L>
<L>&amp; smote him in &thorn;e schank, for &thorn;at stroke, allas!</L>
<L>It bigan to rank, &thorn;e querelle envenomed was.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en on &thorn;e nyent day died kyng Richard,</L>
<L>He ligges at an abbay men calle Founz Ebrard.</L>
<L>He regned nien &yogh;ere, &amp; sex monethes mo,</L>
<L>Maugre &thorn;e alblastere, &thorn;at &thorn;us R. gan slo.</L>
<L>I wene it hate Chahalouns, or it hate Galiard,</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er &thorn;e castelle or &thorn;e toun, &thorn;er smyten was R.</L>
<L>A thousand &amp; a hundred &thorn;e date nienti &amp; nien,</L>
<L>&thorn;at R. fro vs sundred, dede he was with pine.<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. C<SUP>o</SUP>. XC<SUP>o</SUP>. IX<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="206"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is kyng R. dede, &amp; laid in stone,</L>
<L>Non heire was afterward, bot his bro&thorn;er Jon.</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er erle Geffrey right heire felle to be,</L>
<L>(Bot after R. day Jon tok &thorn;e dignite</L>
<L>Or Arthure his<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Id est</I>, Geffrey's.</NOTE> sonne,) if he had had his lif.</L>
<L>Bot Jon was &thorn;e enchesonne, &amp; moued &thorn;er a strif.</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;ing here we say, &thorn;at Jon wille wedded be,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Aquiley his douhter takes he,</L>
<L>Elizabeth &thorn;e gent, fair lady was sche,</L>
<L>Tuo sons of &thorn;er descent, tuo douhters ladies fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE Ersbisshop Hubert of Canterbire &thorn;e se<NOTE PLACE="marg">Johannes Rex coro|natus est per Huber|tum Archi|episcopum Cantuari&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Com with gode hert, to do &thorn;e solempnite.</L>
<L>At Westmynster, &thorn;orgh assent of erle &amp; baroun,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">A Johon le fiz Richard ad done la coroun, Enoynt est en Reis oue [<I>sive</I> ouf] grant deuo|cioun, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>To &thorn;at I ore ment Hubert gaf &thorn;e coroun,</L>
<L>&amp; enoynted he was als kyng &thorn;orgh resoun.</L>
<L>Jon did ay trespas, men fond in him enchesoun,</L>
<L>He lyued in wo &amp; strife, &amp; in tribulacioun.</L>
<L>He was of licherous life, &thorn;orgh what his nacioun</L>
<L>Partie ageyn him ches, &amp; wild haf born him doun.</L>
<L>Normundie he les at his confusioun,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e courte of France he was cald a feloun</L>
<L>For Arthure dede &thorn;at chance, his bro&thorn;er sonne Geffroun,</L>
<L>Erle was of Bretayn, &thorn;at to &thorn;is lond had right</L>
<L>For to haf bien cheftayn. If Jon his dede had dight</L>
<L>My maister nouht he wrote, to write he me forbede.</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles wele I wote, si&thorn;en &thorn;e child was dede,
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="207"></L>
<L>Jon had right &thorn;ertille, &thorn;e lond to haf in ward.</L>
<L>&thorn;at Arthur suld bi skille haf bien heyre next Richard:</L>
<L>Arthure sister &yogh;ing for dole &thorn;at maiden suete</L>
<L>For sorow scho mad endyng, hir name was Margarete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW &thorn;e bode is gon to France, Arthure is dede,</L>
<L>&amp; somond haf &thorn;ei Jon, to Philip courte him dede,</L>
<L>To tak his Jugement of &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> felonie.</NOTE> felonse,</L>
<L>His dede to him &thorn;ei ment, Arthur's &thorn;e Bretaynie.</L>
<L>Jon dred &thorn;at wendyng, to France wild he nouht,</L>
<L>Wherfor Philip &thorn;e kyng on londes souht,</L>
<L>Tolouse &amp; Tolousan seised &amp; Normundie,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh slauhter of &thorn;at man Jon les &thorn;at seignorie.</L>
<L>What dos &thorn;e kyng of France? atires him gode nauie</L>
<L>Tille Inglond, ochance to wynne it with maistrie.</L>
<L>He wend haf wonne &thorn;is lond as he did Tolousan,</L>
<L>&thorn;e cuntre sone he fond in his berd redy ran.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Walsch &amp; o&thorn;er inow, with &thorn;am of Peuenese,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Frankis men &thorn;ei slow, Philip was fayn to fle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Philip fled, here wan he bote lite,</L>
<L>&amp; Jon Northward him sped, his lond for to visite.</L>
<L>Unto Scotlond he sent after kyng William,</L>
<L>To Lincoln William went, &amp; Jon ageyn him cam,</L>
<L>Withoute &thorn;e toun a myle, &amp; in &thorn;e wyntertide,</L>
<L>&thorn;e day of Saynt Cecile &thorn;er parties gan abide.</L>
<L>Homage he did him suere, &amp; feaute in fere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at faith he suld him bere, at alle his powere.
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>Boke &thorn;er was non fette, ne non &thorn;er after fore,</L>
<L>Hubert his croice doun sette, &amp; William &thorn;eron suore.</L>
<L>&thorn;is is &thorn;e same Hubert, &thorn;at &thorn;e saw of nam,</L>
<L>&thorn;at trrnslate S. Gilbert in &thorn;e hous of Sempyngham.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW Hubert is dede our Sire, &amp; to God is gon,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Huberti, &amp; electione conventus, &amp; minaci|one Regis apud con|ventum &amp; archiepi|scopum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Prioure of Canterbire sendes to kyng Jon,</L>
<L>Bisouht him of leue, to mak eleccion,</L>
<L>To chese &thorn;e suld cheue aman of gode renoun.</L>
<L>Jon wrote to &thorn;e couent, bisouht &thorn;am alle holyche,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei wille make present to &thorn;e bisshop of Norwyche.</L>
<L>Of som he had grantise his wille forto do,</L>
<L>&amp; som said o&thorn;erwise, &thorn;at it suld not be so.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e priour side &thorn;e suppriour &thorn;ei ches,</L>
<L>O&thorn;er for enuie &amp; pride &thorn;e voice of many he les.</L>
<L>&thorn;e priour said, "&thorn;is day &thorn;e suppriour chese we,</L>
<L>&thorn;e to&thorn;er side said, "nay, &thorn;e kynge's praier salle be.</L>
<L>With him of Norwiche grete partie gan hald,</L>
<L>Wherfor bo&thorn;e holyche to Rome &thorn;e parties cald.</L>
<L>Monkes fourtene with him of Norwyche held,</L>
<L>In a voice alle bidene vnto &thorn;e kyng &thorn;e teld,</L>
<L>&amp; suore him in leaute, how so euer bitid,</L>
<L>Norwyche he suld be Ersbisshop sacrid.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise monkes stoute &amp; stark, to spede wele &thorn;ei wend,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &thorn;re hundreth mark gaf &thorn;am forto spend.
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="209"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW er &thorn;ei alle on gate, vnto &thorn;e courte &thorn;ei cam,</L>
<L>Eleccion &thorn;orgh hate it falles to no fram.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e pape of Rome &thorn;ei mostred &thorn;er resoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape at his dome &thorn;er elites quassed doun,</L>
<L>Eft he bad &thorn;am chese a man of gode renoun,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ei suld &thorn;er voice lese of alle &thorn;er eleccioun.</L>
<L>Now is &thorn;er voice alle laid to Norwyche partie,</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e pape &thorn;ei said, Norwyche is most wor&thorn;ie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape wild not consent, he quassed &thorn;er elite.</L>
<L>&thorn;e monkes alle were schent, suspended &thorn;am als tite.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape &thorn;ei felle biforn, mercy gan him crie,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e kyng &thorn;e suorn, to maynten his partie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape &thorn;am assoled, &amp; set &thorn;am vp at des,</L>
<L>So &thorn;ei were conseiled, of Langton Steuen &thorn;ei ches.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise monkes were dismaied for Steuen of Langton,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape &thorn;er of was paied, mad &thorn;e confirmacion.</L>
<L>Maister Steuen of Langtone Ersebisshop salle be,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng casten doun. who was wroth bot he?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN &thorn;e kyng vnderstod, &thorn;at his clerk was forsaken,</L>
<L>For soth &thorn;an was he wode, &amp; maister Steuen taken.</L>
<L>&thorn;e clergie of &thorn;at schire so euelle he &thorn;am led,</L>
<L>&thorn;e monkes of Canterbire fro &thorn;er cloistere &thorn;am fled,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De feritate Johannis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; gaf it to Brabans &thorn;e cloister in kepyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh conseil of Sathans wrouht &thorn;er Jon &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape sauh out of cours &thorn;e wikkednes of Jon,</L>
<L>Him &amp; his fautours he cursed euerilkon,</L>
<L>&amp; enterdited &thorn;is Iond, &thorn;at messe was non said,</L>
<L>A ded man if men fond, in kirke &yogh;erd was non laid.
<PB REF="00000438.tif" N="210"></L>
<L>He was a fole of lif, &amp; vsed lichorie,</L>
<L>Both mayden &amp; wif alle wild he ligge bie.</L>
<L>What did &thorn;e baronage &amp; burgeis of Cite?<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Anglia interdicta &amp; Rege ex|communi|cato.</NOTE></L>
<L>Distroied &amp; did outrage of castelle, toun &amp; fe.</L>
<L>About &thorn;ei gan him chace, &amp; hunted him als hayre,</L>
<L>Long had he no space to duelle no wele fare.</L>
<L>Many men of his kynde sauh him so abaued,</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ei fauht with mynde, &amp; oft so was he saued.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ALS &thorn;is wo was lastand in cursyng perilouse,</L>
<L>Kyng William of Scotland did his douhter spouse<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Rege Scottorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e erle of Boloyn, &amp; whan Jon it wist,</L>
<L>Withouten any essoyn, North alle gate him list.</L>
<L>Son he wan Berwik, a castelle he &thorn;ouht to reise,</L>
<L>He cast &thorn;e ground walle &thorn;ik, his folk he &thorn;ouh &thorn;er eise.</L>
<L>William he &thorn;ouht to greue, for &thorn;at grete despite,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he withouten leue, his douhter gaf marite.</L>
<L>Edenburgh &amp; Rokesburgh vp &thorn;at he asked quite,</L>
<L>&amp; his sonne Alisandere for ostage &yogh;eld him tite.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e kyng William alle &thorn;is ageynsaid,</L>
<L>In conaunt &thorn;at &thorn;ei nam with pes alle was it laid.</L>
<L>&para; Of William has Jon &thorn;e pris, toward &thorn;e South he drouh,</L>
<L>&amp; rennes on his enmys, &amp; dos &thorn;am schame inouh,</L>
<L>&amp; his enmys on him, &amp; destroyed alle his fez,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De contu|melia regis &amp; baro|num.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ilk one tille o&thorn;er were grim &thorn;orgh tounes and citez.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at holy kirke, &amp; alle &thorn;e ordinez,</L>
<L>&amp; bisshop wo he wike, &amp; clerkes of dignitez:</L>
<L>&thorn;ei rene &thorn;am prouendes, &thorn;orgh power &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue,</L>
<L>&amp; no man &thorn;am defendes, no wille &thorn;am help no saue.
<PB REF="00000439.tif" N="211"></L>
<L>&para; Oft was &thorn;e pleynt mad vnto &thorn;e pape.</L>
<L>&thorn;e manfesours ateynt, &amp; cursed ouer &thorn;e nape.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape of &thorn;er erroure had fulle grete pite,</L>
<L>H sent to &thorn;er socoure tuo legates ouer &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>At Douere &thorn;ei gan ariue, Pandolf &amp; Durand,</L>
<L>To London gan &thorn;ei driue, &thorn;e barons &thorn;er &thorn;ei fand,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh Pandolf prechyng &thorn;er werre was brouht tille ende.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons &amp; &thorn;e kyng were mad felauhes &amp; frendes,</L>
<L>Asoiled &amp; alle on euen, bot &thorn;e kyng an oth suore,</L>
<L>He suld him venge on Steuen, whider so euer he fore,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;o fourtene monkes, where men mot &thorn;am finde,</L>
<L>Be beten alle fonkes or in prison &thorn;am binde.</L>
<L>&para; Pandolf &amp; Durand did com forth &thorn;e Ersbisshop,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De pace per legates.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e monkes for&thorn; &thorn;ei fand, Jon said, &thorn;ei suld hedeles hop.</L>
<L>Pandolf proued &thorn;e kyng, in his disputeson,</L>
<L>He mayntend wrongfulle &thorn;ing, &amp; wild to no reson.</L>
<L>He proued &thorn;orh wisdam in ilk manere cas,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng misnam, &amp; did grete trespas.</L>
<L>Alle gate &thorn;e kyng he pesed, so &thorn;at &thorn;e werre was ent,</L>
<L>&amp; ilk a clerke sesed ageyn to haf his rent.</L>
<L>Pandolf tok his leue, &amp; to Rome went,</L>
<L>I trow on him gan cleue many riche present.</L>
<L>Now is Pandolf gone, &amp; Steuen Ersbisshop es,</L>
<L>Assoiles kyng Jone of alle his wikkednes.</L>
<L>Jon has sonnes tuo bi Elizabeth &thorn;e quene,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De filiis &amp; filiabus Regis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; tuo douhters also, fairere were non sene.</L>
<L>Henry was eldest, heyre of alle his &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&amp; Richard &yogh;ongest, of Almayn chosen kyng.
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="212"></L>
<L>Isabelle fair as floure, &thorn;at neuer childe had,</L>
<L>Frederik &thorn;e Emperour Emperice home hir lad.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Leycestre &thorn;e to&thorn;er weddid here,</L>
<L>&amp; Jon regned in &thorn;is estre kyng auhten &yogh;ere.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Johannis.</NOTE></L>
<L>At &thorn;e abbay of Suynesheued &thorn;er he drank poyson,</L>
<L>At<NOTE PLACE="foot">What he says here about King John's dying at Haughe (which is in Calceworth hun|dred in Lincolnshire) is very remarkable, and contrary to other Historians, who make him die in the castle of New|ark. But it seems Robert of Brunne (for 'tis not in the French) had it from tradition, the people of Haughe talking frequently of it in his time.</NOTE> Hauhe his lif he leued, so say men of &thorn;at toun.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundred &thorn;e date was &amp; sextene,<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>mo</SUP>. <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> XVI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE>XIIII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>His tyme was alle forwondred, &amp; endid alle with tene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>It should be rather</I> Worcester, <I>as it is in other Historians, and indeed in the French Peter de Langtoft.</I> En labbeye de Swynheued home lenpusonayt, Il gist a Wircestre, il memes le volait. Ore est le Rey Jon mort, e senelye Lerceuesqe Esteuen ad coroune Henry. Prodhome fu touz jours, des pouers aueyt mercy, Plus ama seinte Egleyse qe nul Rey deuauntly. Clers ke chaunter|ent bien sunt tost enrichy. Eglyses &amp; prouandes ne sunt esparny, Ke Clerk de la cha|pele nait porcioun par my, <I>in the MS. of the Heralds Of|fice. But in one of Mr. Anstis's Copies we have</I>, home lem poy sonayt, Egista Wyrcestre, <I>and a little after</I>, plus ama seynt Eg|lises, <I>and after that</I>, Eglises ne prouandres. <I>Which variations are not of so much consequence as those in the other of Mr. Anstis's Copies, where the whole passage is read thus:</I> Al Abbaye de la Swyne|heued home lenponsonait, Il gist a Wilecester, il meme le volait.</P><P>Anno Domini M. cc. xvi.</P><P>Ore est le Ray Joh mort, et en senely Lerceueske E|steuene ad corounet Henri. Prodhome fust tuz jeurs, de pouers auait mercy, Plus ama seint eglise ke nul Rays deuaunt ly. Deus en sa cha|pele fu noblement seruy, Par chapelayns et clers de la re|uestery. Clers ke chauntent ben sunt tost en richi. Egli|ses et prouendes ne sunt pas esparny, Ke clerk de la cha|pele nad porcioun par my.</P></NOTE> Westmynstere euen es Jon laid solempnely,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Henricus tercius coronatus est.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Ersbisshop Steuen corouned his sonne Henry,</L>
<L>A gode man alle his lyue, of pouer men had mercie,</L>
<L>Clerkes &thorn;at wild &thorn;ryue, auanced &thorn;am richelie:
<PB REF="00000441.tif" N="213"></L>
<L>Kirkes wild he dele prouendis &thorn;at wer wor&thorn;ie,</L>
<L>To clerkes of his chapele, &thorn;at wele cou&thorn; syng &amp; hie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HENRY kyng our prince at Westmynster kirke</L>
<L>&thorn;e erlys douhter of Prouince, &thorn;e fairest may o lif,</L>
<L>Hir name is Helianore, of<NOTE PLACE="foot">De gentyl parente <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> gentille norture,</L>
<L>Bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e se &thorn;at wore was non suilk creature.</L>
<L>In Inglond is sche corouned &thorn;at lady gent,</L>
<L>Tuo sonnes, tuo douhteres fre Jhesus has &thorn;am lent,</L>
<L>Edward &amp; Edmunde, knyght gode in stoure,</L>
<L>Of Laicestre a stounde was Edmunde erle &amp; floure.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e Scottis kyng was married Margarete,</L>
<L>Of Bretayn Beatrice &yogh;ing &thorn;e erle had &thorn;at mayden suete.</L>
<L>Faire is &thorn;e werk &amp; hie in London at Westmynster kirke,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng Henrie of his tresore did wirke.</L>
<L>Grace God gaf him here, &thorn;is lond to kepe long space,</L>
<L>Sex &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Rectius</I>, fourty, <I>cum Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE> fifty &yogh;ere withouten werre in grace;</L>
<L>Bot sone afterward failed him powere,</L>
<L>Bot his sonne Edward was his conseilere.</L>
<L>Our quene &thorn;at was &thorn;en dame Helianore his wife,</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode erle of Warenne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sire Huge lespenser <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> Sir Hugh was &thorn;an olife,
<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="214"></L>
<L>Sir William of Valence, Sir Roger Mortimere,</L>
<L>Jon Mauncelle &thorn;e clerke, &amp; an erle Richere,</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er knyghtes inowe of bi &yogh;ond &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng drowe, auanced wild &thorn;ei be.</L>
<L>Edward suffred wele, his fadere haf his wille,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons neuer a dele said &thorn;e kyng did ille,</L>
<L>Aliens to auaunce ou&thorn;er in lond or rent.</L>
<L>To mak disturbaunce &thorn;ei held a parlement.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e aliens ilk taile &thorn;e lond voided clere,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kyng &amp; his consaile &thorn;ei sent a messengere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e <NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Reis les respount, [<I>vel</I>, Le Rays pur respouns] jour les fet doner, Tut drait [<I>vel</I>, droyt] a Oxenforde la parle|menter, [<I>vel</I>, a Oxenford v tout parlementer,] <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> kyng sent &thorn;am ageyn, his barons alle &thorn;ei grette,</L>
<L>At Oxenford certeyn &thorn;e day of parlement sette.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT &thorn;is parlement rested &thorn;at distaunce,</L>
<L>For &thorn;er was it ent, aliens to auaunce.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's state here paires, &thorn;orgh conseil of baroun,</L>
<L>To him &amp; his heyres grete disheriteson.</L>
<L>Of wardes &amp; relefe &thorn;at barons of him held,</L>
<L>&thorn;er ne was ore of chefe, tille him no &thorn;ing suld &yogh;eld;</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at held of &thorn;am, &thorn;er &thorn;e kyng felle be partie,</L>
<L>Nouht of &thorn;at suld claym of all &thorn;at seignorie.</L>
<L>Tille ilk a lordyng suld ward &amp; relefe falle,</L>
<L>Bot tille &thorn;e kyng no &thorn;ing, he was forbarred alle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng perceyued nouht of &thorn;at ilk desceit,</L>
<L>&thorn;e chartre was forth brouht with wittnes enseled streit.
<PB REF="00000443.tif" N="215"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et qe nul estraunge en court eyt pussaunce, Ne qe le Rey saunz els de tere nul auaunce, Ne mette en baylle saunz lour ordinaunce, <I>in the French MS. of the Heralds Office. And so also in one of Mr. Anstis's Copies, unless it be that it hath</I> ey <I>for</I> eyt; <I>but in the other of his Copies the pas|sage is read thus:</I> Ke nul alyens en curt eust pussaunce, Si noun par assent de commun volyaunce. Et ke la Rays apres de terres nul auaunce, Si Englays ne sait et de la nessaunce.</NOTE>Ne no men &thorn;at were strange in courte suld haf no myght,</L>
<L>Ne office to do no chance withouten &thorn;e comon sight.</L>
<L>&thorn;is &thorn;ei did him suere, als he was kyng &amp; knyght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at oth suld he were, &amp; maynten wele &thorn;at right.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE kyng was holden hard, &thorn;orgh &thorn;at he had suorn,</L>
<L>His frendes afterward, &thorn;o &thorn;at were next born,</L>
<L>&thorn;e com to him &amp; said, "Sir, we se &thorn;in ille,</L>
<L>" &thorn;i lordschip is doun laid, &amp; led at o&thorn;er wille.</L>
<L>" We se &thorn;is ilk erroure nouht &thorn;ou vnderstode.</L>
<L>" It is a dishonoure to &thorn;e &amp; to &thorn;i blode,</L>
<L>" &thorn;ou has so bonden &thorn;e, &thorn;ei lede &thorn;e ilk a dele.</L>
<L>" At &thorn;er wille salle &thorn;ou be, Sir, we se it wele,</L>
<L>" Calle ageyn &thorn;in oth, drede &thorn;ou no manace,</L>
<L>" Nou&thorn;er of lefe ne loth, &thorn;i lordschip to purchace,</L>
<L>" &thorn;ou may fulle lightly haf absolutioun,</L>
<L>" For it was a gilery, &thorn;ou knew not &thorn;er tresoun.</L>
<L>" &thorn;ou has frendis inowe in Inglond &amp; in France,</L>
<L>" If &thorn;ou turne to &thorn;e rowe, &thorn;ei salle drede &thorn;e chance.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng listned &thorn;e sawe, at &thorn;at consail wild do,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Barones miserunt pro Sy|mone de `de<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dele.</NOTE> monte forti.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e barons had grete awe, whan &thorn;ei wist he wild so,
<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="216"></L>
<L>&thorn;ei tok &amp; sent &thorn;er sond after Sir Symoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Mountfort out of lond was, whan &thorn;is was don.</L>
<L>A message &thorn;ei him sent, &thorn;e Mountfort son home cam,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons with on assent to Sir Symon &thorn;ei nam.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei teld him &thorn;e processe of alle &thorn;er comon sawe,</L>
<L>&amp; he as fole alle fresse fulle eth &thorn;er to to drawe.</L>
<L>Withouten his conseile, or &thorn;e kynge's wittyng,</L>
<L>To maynten &thorn;er tirpeile he suore ageyn &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;e statute for to hold in werre &amp; in pes,</L>
<L>&thorn;e poyntes &thorn;at &thorn;ei him told, &thorn;erfor his life he les.</L>
<L>Hardely dar I say he did a perte folie,</L>
<L>Als wys men &thorn;is way, here ferst &thorn;e to&thorn;er partie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIR Symon was hastif, his sonnes &amp; &thorn;e barons<NOTE PLACE="marg">De guerra inter regem &amp; barones &amp; de Mounfort.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone &thorn;ei reised strif, brent &thorn;e kynge's tounes,</L>
<L>&amp; his castels tok, held &thorn;am in &thorn;er bandoun.</L>
<L>On his londes &thorn;ei schok, &amp; robbed vp &amp; doun.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;er purueiance of Oxenford not held,</L>
<L>With scheld &amp; with lance fend him in &thorn;e feld.</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;is barette &thorn;e kyng &amp; Sir Symon</L>
<L>Tille a lokyng &thorn;am sette, of &thorn;e prince suld it be don.</L>
<L>An oth suore &thorn;ei &thorn;are, to stand to &thorn;e ordinance,</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e se to fare bifor Philip of France,</L>
<L>At his dome suld it be, withoute refusyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;er for went ouer &thorn;e se Sir Henry our kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e quene wild not duelle, to &thorn;e kyng gan hir hie.</L>
<L>&thorn;us my boke gan telle, scho tok grete vilanie</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Londreis alle, whan scho of London went.</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at it suld falle I ne wote what it ment;
<PB REF="00000445.tif" N="217"></L>
<L>Bot whan &thorn;e kyng of France had knowen certeynly,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e purueiance disherite kyng Henry,</L>
<L>He quassed it ilk dele &thorn;orgh jugement.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng was paied wele, &amp; home to Inglond went.</L>
<L>Whan Sir Symon wist, &thorn;e dome ageyn &thorn;am gon,</L>
<L>His felonie forth thrist, samned his men ilkon,</L>
<L>Displaied his banere, lift vp his dragoun,</L>
<L>Sone salle &yogh;e here &thorn;e folie of Symoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE erle did mak a chare at London &thorn;orgh gilery,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De bello apud Leaus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Himself &thorn;er in suld fare, &amp; seke he wend to ly.</L>
<L>Sexti &thorn;ousand of London armed men fulle stoute</L>
<L>To &thorn;e chare were fondon, to kepe it wele for doute.</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;e bataile suld be, to Leaus &thorn;ai gan &thorn;am alie,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &amp; his meyne were in &thorn;e priorie.</L>
<L>Symoun com to &thorn;e feld, &amp; put vp his banere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng schewed forth his scheld, his dragon fulle austere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng said on hie, "<I>Symon ieo vous defie;</I></L>
<L>Edward was hardie, &thorn;e Londres gan he ascrie.</L>
<L>He smote in alle &thorn;e route, &amp; sesid him &thorn;e chare,</L>
<L>Disconfited alle aboute &thorn;e Londreis &thorn;at &thorn;er ware.</L>
<L>Edward wend wele haf fonden &thorn;e erle &thorn;er in,</L>
<L>Disceyued ilk a dele, he went &amp; myght not wyn.</L>
<L>Towhille Sir Edward was aboute &thorn;e chare to take,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's side, allas! Symoun did doun schake.</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e kynge's partie Edward turned tite,</L>
<L>&thorn;an had &thorn;e erle &thorn;e maistrie, &thorn;e kyng was disconfite.</L>
<L>&thorn;e soth to say &amp; chese, &thorn;e chare's gilerie</L>
<L>Did Sir Edward lese &thorn;at day &thorn;e maistrie.
<PB REF="00000446.tif" N="218"></L>
<L>&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P><I>Others say the</I> 12<I>th. of May. See Stowe's Annals, pag.</I> 194. <I>Ed. fol. But not so rightly, as I take it. See Dug|dale's Baronage, Tome I. p.</I> 408. <I>Rastall says in his Chronicle, that it was fought the</I> 23<I>d. of May.</I>&mdash;And than<NOTE PLACE="marg">The ba|tell at Lewys.</NOTE> (<I>says he</I>) the barons with a great multytude of the citye of London &verbar; and with a great hoost of other people came agaynst the kynge&mdash;betwene whome the. xxiii. day of May was fought a maruelous cruell battell at Lewys &verbar; and the Lon|doners that gaue the fyrst as|sent &verbar; by reason of the sharpe shot of Arowes &amp; strokes gyuen by them of the kynges partes began to drawe backe.</P><P>But the barons incurrag|ed theyr men in suche wyse that they nat onely set vpon them with fresshe men &verbar; but incurraged so them that gaue backe &verbar; that they turned a|gayne &amp; fought so fersly that the kynges parte gaue backe &verbar; &amp; the kyng lost the fylde. where the kyng hym selfe &amp; the kyng of Romayns &amp; Edwarde the kynges son were takyn prisoners &amp; many other mo &verbar; and. xx. M. men slayne for this battell conty|nued the more part of the day.</P></NOTE> fourtend day of May &thorn;e batail of Leaus was</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundreth sexti &amp; foure in pas.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng of Almayn was taken to prisoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex Al|manni&aelig; captus est, multi alii.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Scotlond Jon Comyn was left in a donjoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Warenne, I wote, he scaped ouer &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>&amp; Sir Hugh Bigote als with &thorn;e erle fled he.</L>
<L>Many faire ladie lese hir lord &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>&amp; many gode bodie slayn at Leaus lay.</L>
<L>&thorn;e numbre non wrote, for telle &thorn;am mot no man,</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at alle wote, &amp; alle &thorn;ing scs &amp; can.</L>
<L>Edward, &thorn;at was &yogh;ing, with his owen rede,</L>
<L>For his fader &thorn;e kyng himself to prison bede.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e kyng of Almayn his neuow was ostage,</L>
<L>In prison nere a &yogh;ere was Edward in cage.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pr&oelig;fige, &amp;.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000447.tif" N="219"></L>
<L>Aboute with Sir Symoun &thorn;e kyng went &thorn;at &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Cite, castelle &amp; toun alle was in &thorn;e erle's dangere.</L>
<L>It was on a day Edward &thorn;ouht a wile,</L>
<L>He said he wild asay &thorn;er hors alle in a mile.</L>
<L>He asayed &thorn;am bi &amp; bi, &amp; retreied &thorn;am ilkone,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Edwardus evasit de carcere Herfordi&aelig;; Et de eva|sione ejus.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; stoned &thorn;am alle wery, standand stille as stone.</L>
<L>A suyft stede &thorn;er was a lady &thorn;ider sent,</L>
<L>Edward knowe his pas, &thorn;e last of alle him hent,</L>
<L>Asaied him vp &amp; doun, suyftest he was of alle.</L>
<L>&thorn;at kept him in prisoun, Edward did him calle,</L>
<L>"Maister haf gode day, soiorne wille no more,</L>
<L>"I salle &yogh;it, if I may my soiorne, trauaile sore.</L>
<L>&thorn;e stede he had asaied, &amp; knew &thorn;at he was gode,</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e watere he straied, &amp; passed wele &thorn;at flode.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Edward was ouere graciously &amp; wele,</L>
<L>He hoped haf recouere at Wigemore castele.</L>
<L>Edward is wisely of prison scaped oute,</L>
<L>Felaus he fond redy, &amp; mad his partie stoute.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle's sonnes wer hauteyn, did many folie dede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at teld a knyght certeyn to &thorn;e erle als &thorn;ei bo&thorn;e &yogh;ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE erle &yogh;ede on a day, to play him with a knyght,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce dic|tum milit's ad comitein de filiis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; asked him on his play, "what haf I be sight?</L>
<L>&thorn;e knyght ansuerd &amp; said, "in &yogh;ow a faute men fynde,</L>
<L>"&amp; is an ille vpbraid, &thorn;at &yogh;e ere nere blynde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle said, "nay perde, I may se right wele.</L>
<L>&thorn;e knyght said, "Sir nay, &yogh;e vnne&thorn; is any dele.</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou has ille sonnes, foles &amp; vnwise,</L>
<L>"&thorn;er dedes &thorn;ou not mones, ne nouht wille &thorn;am chastise.
<PB REF="00000448.tif" N="220"></L>
<L>"I rede &thorn;ou gyue gode tent, &amp; chastise &thorn;am sone,</L>
<L>"For &thorn;am &yogh;e may be schent, for vengeance is granted bone.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle ansuerd nouht, he lete &thorn;at word ouer go,</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing &thorn;er on he &thorn;ouht, tille vengeance felle on &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Euer were his sonnes hauteyn, &amp; bold for &thorn;er partie,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to knyght &amp; sueyn did &thorn;ei vilanie.</L>
<L>For lefe ne for loth, folle wild &thorn;ei not spare,</L>
<L>Wherfor wex with &thorn;am wroth Sir Gilbert of Clare.</L>
<L>Sir Gilbert herd say of &thorn;er dedes ille,</L>
<L>Of non &thorn;e had ay to stynt ne hold &thorn;am stille.</L>
<L>&thorn;er of Edward herd say, &thorn;at Gilberd turned his wille,</L>
<L>To Gilbert tok his way, his luf to tak &amp; tille.</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;ei were at one, with wille at on assent</L>
<L>His luf fro Munfort gon Itelle Symon for schent.</L>
<L>Treuth togidere &thorn;ei plight Edward &amp; Gilbert,</L>
<L>Ageyn Symon to fight, for ouht &thorn;at mot be herd.</L>
<L>Mercy suld non haue Symon no his sonnes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De filiis Symonis &amp; stultitia eo|rum per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>No raunson suld &thorn;am saue for doute of drede eftsones.</L>
<L>Schent is ilk baroun, now Gilbert turnes grim,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Mountfort Sir Symoun most affied on him.</L>
<L>"Allas! Sir Gilbert &thorn;ou turned &thorn;in oth,</L>
<L>"At Stryuelyn men it herd, how God &thorn;er for was wroth.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE erle sonnes vp &amp; doun of parties mad &thorn;ei bost,</L>
<L>Towhils at Northamptoun &thorn;ise kynges gadred ost.</L>
<L>Symon sonnes it left, to Killyngworth &thorn;ei went,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;e soiorned eft, &thorn;er rioterie &thorn;am schent.</L>
<L>Suilk ribaudie &thorn;ei led, &thorn;ei gaf no tale of wham,</L>
<L>Towhils Sir Edward had seisid alle Euesham.
<PB REF="00000449.tif" N="221"></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e fift day it was after Lammesse tide,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De bello de Euesham per totum lege.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; writen is in &thorn;at pas, at Euesham gan &thorn;ei ride.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e alder next &thorn;at &thorn;e bataile was of Leaus,</L>
<L>&thorn;e gynnyng of heruest, as &thorn;e story scheawes,</L>
<L>Com Symon to feld, &amp; &thorn;at was maugre his,</L>
<L>Or euer he lift his scheld, his wist it &yogh;ed amys.</L>
<L>He was on his stede, displaied his banere,</L>
<L>He sauh &thorn;at treson &yogh;ede, doun went his powere.</L>
<L>He sauh Sir Edward ride, batailed him ageyn,</L>
<L>Gloucestre &thorn;e to&thorn;er side, &thorn;an wist &thorn;e erle certeyn,</L>
<L>His side suld doun falle, tille his he said sone:</L>
<L>"God haf our saules alle, our dayes ere alle done,</L>
<L>Edward first in rode, &amp; perced alle &thorn;e pres.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at him abode &thorn;er lyues alle &thorn;ei les.</L>
<L>He mad his fader quite of prison &thorn;er he lay,</L>
<L>Deliuerd him als tite with dynt of suerd &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>Hard was &thorn;at bataile, &amp; ouer grete &thorn;e folie,</L>
<L>So scharply gan &thorn;ai assaile, so mykille folk gan die.</L>
<L>Stoutly was &thorn;at stoure, long lastand &thorn;at fight,</L>
<L>&thorn;e day lost his coloure, &amp; mirk was as &thorn;e nyght.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lif of many man &thorn;at ilk day was lorn,</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at it first bigan wrotherhaile wer &thorn;ei born.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is &thorn;e bataile smyten, Sir Symon is &thorn;er slayn,</L>
<L>His sonnes, als &yogh;e witen, died on &thorn;at playn.</L>
<L>His membres of &thorn;ei schare, &amp; bare &thorn;am to present</L>
<L>Sir Hugh Despenser, &thorn;are als he to dede went.</L>
<L>Sir Rauf &thorn;e gode Basset did &thorn;er his endyng,</L>
<L>Sir Pers of Mountfort fet his dede at &thorn;at samenyng.
<PB REF="00000450.tif" N="222"></L>
<L>Sir Guy Baliol died &thorn;ore a &yogh;ong knyght &amp; hardy,</L>
<L>He was pleyned more &thorn;an o&thorn;er tuenty.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise &amp; many mo died in &thorn;at stoure,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng may sauely go, &amp; maynten his honour.</L>
<L>Pris &thorn;an has &thorn;e sonne, &thorn;e fadere maistrie,</L>
<L>&thorn;er went Northampton, so wild kyng Henrie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT &thorn;e parlement was flemed barons fele,</L>
<L>&thorn;e countas of Leicestre, hir sonnes wild no man spele.</L>
<L>O&thorn;er lordes inowe of erles &amp; barouns,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De parlia|mento apud Northam|ptoniam.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e wod som drowe, &amp; som left in prisouns.</L>
<L>To say longly or schorte, alle armes bare.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Emerike de Mountfort sloqes fu pryuez De la tresorye, dount fust estallez En leglyse Seint Pere, de Euerwik nomez, Als fiz le Mortymer le Rey lad donez, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Almerik or Mountfort depriued was &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e tresorie, &thorn;at he had in kepyng,</L>
<L>&amp; gaf &thorn;at ilk bailie tor &thorn;e Mortimere sonne &yogh;ing.</L>
<L>&para; A legate Ottobon &thorn;e pape hider sent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Octobo|no legato.</NOTE></L>
<L>To mak &thorn;e barons on &thorn;orgh his prechement.</L>
<L>&thorn;e quene com out of France, &amp; with hir alle &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for &thorn;e purueiance were exild to go,</L>
<L>Saue Jon &thorn;e Maunselle, he died bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Als chance for him felle, &thorn;e to&thorn;er welcom be.</L>
<L>&para; A thousand &amp; tuo hundred, &amp; sex &amp; sexti,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A<SUP>o</SUP>, M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>mo</SUP>. LXVI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;at er fled &amp; sundred &thorn;o rise ageyn Henri.</L>
<L>For after &thorn;e takyng of Kilyngworth castelle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e flemed ageyn &thorn;e kyng ros eft fulle rebelle.
<PB REF="00000451.tif" N="223"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e men &thorn;at were fled disherited of &thorn;er londes,</L>
<L>To purches &thorn;am &thorn;ei sped, now ilk of &thorn;am so fondes.</L>
<L>Robert of Ferers he robb&edot;d bo&thorn;e &amp; slouh</L>
<L>Bi nyght in stede sers, &amp; tille his felawes drouh.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am was &thorn;er non &thorn;at lufed kyng Henry,</L>
<L>To Chestrefeld ilkon &thorn;e com vngratiously.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng did &thorn;am spie with gode men of renoun,</L>
<L>Com on &thorn;am priuelie, assailed &thorn;am in &thorn;e toun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons fauht ageyn, &thorn;ei wist of no socoure,</L>
<L>Many of &thorn;am wer slayn, &amp; som passed at honour.</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e gode Deyuile, he did wele his deuere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at stoure he held a while, &amp; passed quite &amp; clere.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;e monyng eft bigan a new stoure,</L>
<L>Robert Ferers &thorn;er left, Baudewyn &thorn;e vauasoure</L>
<L>Lord of Chestrefeld, &thorn;ise myght not lightly fle.</L>
<L>&thorn;er side alle doun held, taken were &thorn;er meyne</L>
<L>Robert Wollerton, I trowe for som trespas,</L>
<L>He had grete renoun, on Kene hanged he was.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is douhty Deyuile his name was Sir Jon,</L>
<L>Of Axholm to &thorn;e Ile he scaped himself alon.</L>
<L>For to robbe &amp; reue, &thorn;er he held his haunt,</L>
<L>He wild spare ne leue burgeis no merchaunt.</L>
<L>&amp; whan he dred him ouht, for ouercomyng of mo</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e South he souht, als he were non of &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Bot as a passand man, felawes forto seke,</L>
<L>So often away he wan, &amp; vmwhile cheke bi cheke.</L>
<L>&thorn;us did &thorn;e Deyuile more &thorn;an haf a &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; gadred him &thorn;at while inouh of powere.
<PB REF="00000452.tif" N="224"></L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;ei wer inowe, on whilk &thorn;ei mot afie,</L>
<L>To Lyncoln &thorn;ei drowe, &amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ei suld relie.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De rapaci|tate Judeis|mi apud Lincol. niam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e tuelft day of Aprile, whan &thorn;er powere was grete,</L>
<L>&amp; went alle at o wile, in to Lyncoln &thorn;ei schete.</L>
<L>&thorn;orghout &thorn;e Juery &thorn;ei robbed &thorn;am &amp; slouh,</L>
<L>&thorn;e cofres with tresory &thorn;e braken &amp; &thorn;e awey drouh.</L>
<L>&thorn;e chartres &amp; &thorn;e scris &thorn;at noied Cristen men,</L>
<L>&thorn;at lay for vsure in pris elleuen als for ten,</L>
<L>Were casten in fire &amp; brent in podels vilaynly,</L>
<L>Of Jues slayn &amp; schent a hundred &amp; sexty.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Sir Edward herd, &thorn;at &thorn;ei had Lyncoln taken,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e Juerie misferd, &thorn;er tresorie ouerschaken,</L>
<L>He sped him &thorn;ider in haste, with hilled hors of pris,</L>
<L>He com &amp; fond alle waste, away were &thorn;o enmys,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei went to &thorn;e ilde of Hely vnto Sir Hugh Pecche,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei manned &thorn;am so boldely, on &thorn;am had non entre.</L>
<L>Edward lete not wele, &thorn;at he with &thorn;am not mette,</L>
<L>To Kilyngworth castele he went, &thorn;e sege to sette.</L>
<L>Fro Midsomeretide to &thorn;e Apostle S. Thomas</L>
<L>&thorn;e fled mayntend &thorn;er side, &thorn;e castelle holden was.</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at &thorn;ider went, Sir Edward &amp; ilkon,</L>
<L>Untille &thorn;e pape sent his legate Ottobon.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;is legate was comen, of som he was bisouht,</L>
<L>In forward out &thorn;ei nomen, els wild &thorn;ei nouht.</L>
<L>Sir Henry of Hastyng he &yogh;ald it bi his wille,</L>
<L>Ouer alle maner &thorn;ing life &amp; lymmes haf stille,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;er tresorie, &thorn;at &thorn;erin was fonden,</L>
<L>Withouten vilenie vnto &thorn;e pes bonden.
<PB REF="00000453.tif" N="225"></L>
<L>&thorn;is legate Ottobone mad a cursyng hard</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am euerilkone, &thorn;at brak &thorn;at afterward;</L>
<L>&amp; som of &thorn;er heyres so hard charged wore,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;it many it peyres, &amp; som has satled sore.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;an went &thorn;is Ottobone &thorn;orghout &thorn;e cuntre,</L>
<L>&amp; quaynted him with ilkone, lewed &amp; ordine,</L>
<L>&amp; many of &thorn;am wer mendid of folies &thorn;orgh his dome,</L>
<L>&amp; he &thorn;e better spendid als he went to Rome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIR Edward vnto &thorn;e ilde he went of Hely,</L>
<L>With many man fulle wilde to bataile redy.</L>
<L>Edward alle aboute he spied in to ride,</L>
<L>With in had &thorn;ei no doute, defendid on ilk side.</L>
<L>So ageyn Edward &thorn;ei held it half a &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei sauh &thorn;e sege so hard, &thorn;ei sent a messengere,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei ilde forto &yogh;elde at his owen biddyng,</L>
<L>If he &thorn;am saue wilde ageyn Henry our kyng.</L>
<L>Edward was curteys, &amp; man fulle of mercy,</L>
<L>With hors &amp; herneys he went to kyng Henry.</L>
<L>&para; Right in alle &thorn;is fare wex an euel chek,</L>
<L>Ageyn Gilbert of Clare &thorn;e kyng was in contek.</L>
<L>Sir Edward was witnes, whi &thorn;e wrath suld be,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it to me it es forsoth als priuete.</L>
<L>&thorn;e men &thorn;at were in &thorn;e ilde of &thorn;is contek herd,</L>
<L>&thorn;e conseiled &thorn;am a while, &amp; si&thorn;en to London ferd</L>
<L>To Gilbert of Clare, &amp; mayntend his powere.</L>
<L>With him bileft &thorn;ei &thorn;are a quarter of a &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Men in hert it kast, &thorn;at were of gode avis,</L>
<L>It myght not long last suilk werre &amp; partis.
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="226"></L>
<L>&thorn;e partis conseile hent, messengers &thorn;ei ches,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e kyng &thorn;ei sent, for a finalle pes.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last right nede, pesed behoued it be,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at ilk man &yogh;ede with pes to his cuntre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EDWARD als so quik toward &thorn;e North him sped,</L>
<L>&thorn;e castelle of Alnewik he tok, &amp; with him led</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode lord Vescy, &thorn;at was so trew a knyght,</L>
<L>To kepe &thorn;at seignory he tok tille on &thorn;at myght.</L>
<L>Sir Edward com to London, &thorn;er was his fader Henry.</L>
<L>On knes he felle to grounde, &amp; praied for the Vescy.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng was fulle curteis, forgaf him ilk a dele,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lord of Kilyngworth als &thorn;at tyme sped wele.</L>
<L>His body did &thorn;e saue withouten prisoun,</L>
<L>His londes forto haue, he gaf &thorn;e kyng raunson.</L>
<L>&para; Right als &thorn;is werre was ent, &amp; &thorn;e lond in state,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape his bulle sent hider vnto &thorn;e legate,</L>
<L>&amp; comanded him to preche &thorn;orgh alle &thorn;e lond,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins do grete wreche, &thorn;e Cristen for to schond.</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e kyng of France was sent an o&thorn;er legate,</L>
<L>&thorn;at teld him of &thorn;at chance, whan Lowys herd of &thorn;at,</L>
<L>Himself &thorn;e first was croised on his flessh.</L>
<L>Forto wend &thorn;at pas, his wille was euer fressh.</L>
<L>Sir Henry of &thorn;is lond was &thorn;at ilk wille,</L>
<L>His sonne &thorn;er to him bond, his fader mot leue stille.</L>
<L>Sir Edward toke &thorn;e croice, for his fader to go,</L>
<L>Jhesu &thorn;ou grant him voice, to venge him on &thorn;i fo.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand tuo hundred mo, &amp; sexti &amp; ten,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>mo</SUP>. LXX<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sir Edward forto go he gadres him douhty men.
<PB REF="00000455.tif" N="227"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE next Letenes tide Sir Lowys went his way,</L>
<L>No langere wild he bide, for &thorn;ing &thorn;at men mot say,</L>
<L>With erles &amp; barouns, with knyghtes gode of plight,</L>
<L>Als suilk prince of renoun felle to haf &thorn;orgh right.</L>
<L>He hied him fulle &yogh;are toward &thorn;e Grekis se,</L>
<L>&thorn;ank God his gode fare, whan he schipped suld be.</L>
<L>Withouten any hime &thorn;e wynde gan him driue</L>
<L>Untille &thorn;e lond of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic MS. Rectius</I>, Tune, (<I>i.e.</I> Tunes, <I>sive</I> Thounes, <I>ut in Codd. Gall.</I>)</NOTE> time, &amp; &thorn;er he gan vp ariue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazins to destroie fulle nobilly he gan,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Cristendam mot it noie &thorn;e dede of suilk a man.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Mout fu grant damage, qe viuer ne poayt, Mort le prist, allas! sa vie terminayt, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Long dured he nouht, si&thorn;en he comen was,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at God wille haf wrouht els his dede, allas!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE next heruest folowand Edward was fulle &yogh;are,</L>
<L>Bi Rome he went &thorn;at land, with &thorn;e pape spak he &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en in Cezile alle &thorn;e wyntere he lay,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Iter arri|puit versus terram sanctam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e somer com in a while, &amp; he went on his way,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e se sailand to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic etiam &amp; hoc loco MS. nostr. Angl. at</I> Tune <I>potius legend. Nam.</I> Tunes <I>sive</I> Tounes <I>in Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE> time, &amp; whan he com to lond</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;ing com him vntime, Sir Lowys dede he fond.</L>
<L>&thorn;er duelled he no more, tille Acres went our kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Cristen &thorn;at &thorn;er wore wer fayn of his comyng.</L>
<L>Grete folk of Frisland, &thorn;at to Acres were comen,</L>
<L>Tille him &thorn;ei were willand, for lord &thorn;ei alle him nomen.</L>
<L>&thorn;e oste was sprede fulle wide, about Acres &thorn;at lay,</L>
<L>Alle paemie &thorn;at tide was in grete affray.
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="228"></L>
<L>Of men of armes bold &thorn;e numbre &thorn;ei ame,</L>
<L>A thousand &amp; tuo hundred told of Cristen men bi name. </L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">La tere fu lour wayne par poer saunz desceit, Ne fust la meschaunce, qe les encombrayt, <I>Gallice.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e lond &thorn;ei suld haf wonne &thorn;orgh powere &thorn;at &thorn;ei had,</L>
<L>Bot if treson had gonne, &amp; &thorn;orgh disceit bien lad.</L>
<L>Mykelle was &thorn;e drede &thorn;orgh out paemie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Cristendam at nede mot haf suilk cheualrie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Soudan was in wehere &thorn;e Cristen had suilk oste,</L>
<L>Sir Edwarde's powere ouer alle he dred moste,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor day &amp; nyght he was in grete studie,</L>
<L>On what manere he myght Edward slo &thorn;orgh spie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THER es a stede of wynne, &thorn;ei calle it <I>haut assise</I>,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De haut assise, <NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE>locus nobilit&aacute;tis inter Sara|cenos, ubi custodiun|tur pueri cum gaudio, nec metuunt mortem, sed &aelig;stimant semper vi|vere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Men norise childre &thorn;er inne, on merveilous wise,</L>
<L>Euer in joy &amp; blisse, in alle &thorn;at &thorn;ei may do,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei wene it salle neuer misse, ne o&thorn;er dede com to.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei faire right als dos foles, &thorn;ei do as men &thorn;am say,</L>
<L>&thorn;e childir of &thorn;o scoles, &thorn;ei &thorn;ink to lyue ay.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Soudan of &thorn;o in clo&thorn;es of gold him clad,</L>
<L>Tille Edward suld he go, &amp; do as &thorn;e Soudan bad.</L>
<L>A letter &thorn;is fole tok, bad him for nessh or hard</L>
<L>&thorn;eron suld no man loke, bot only Sir Edward.</L>
<L>Envenomed knyfe he bare also priuely,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non &thorn;er of were ware, who so stod him by.</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;am self alone in chambir suld &thorn;ei be,</L>
<L>So bad &thorn;e Soudone schewe him his priuete.
<PB REF="00000457.tif" N="229"></L>
<L>"&amp; whan &thorn;ou sees leysere, &thorn;at he ne perceyue &thorn;i witte,</L>
<L>"With &thorn;e knyf him<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic cum spatio. quodnam vero verbum desitvernaculum, &egrave; Gallicis non colligo.</NOTE> to with &thorn;e knyfe him to smite.</L>
<L>&para; Comen is &thorn;e Sarazin to speke with Sir Edward,</L>
<L>Clad in clo&thorn;es fyn, himself is a mosard.</L>
<L>He said he wild speke with &thorn;e kyng priuely,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De vulne|racione Edwardi.</NOTE></L>
<L>Conseile non to breke, no telle it alle on hy.</L>
<L>Sir Edward granted wele, tille his chambre him brouht,</L>
<L>Of treson neuer a dele, no &thorn;ing &thorn;er on he &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>&thorn;e letter in his hand laid, enselid &amp; in silke bounde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e envenomed knyfe out braid, &amp; gaf Edward a wounde.</L>
<L>To, I wene, he lauht, als his Romance sais,</L>
<L>A trestille Edward rauht, &thorn;at heuy was of pais.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Sarazin so he smote in &thorn;e hede with &thorn;at treste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at brayn &amp; blode alle hote &amp; i&yogh;en alle out gan brest.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW for Edward woundes &thorn;e Cristen ere sori,</L>
<L>&thorn;at with in fo stoundes ere chances fallen selli.</L>
<L>His surgien him tolde, if he suld him saue,</L>
<L>&amp; his lif holde, reste behoued him haue.</L>
<L>&thorn;at was a mischance, &thorn;at &thorn;er hede doun lay,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e kyng of France died &thorn;at o&thorn;er day.</L>
<L>A no&thorn;er &yogh;it more stark, &thorn;e pape &thorn;at tyme was dede,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e patriark &thorn;e legate liggis in lede.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng of Nauer hight his help to Sir Edward,</L>
<L>In Cecile &thorn;e dede him dight, als he was &thorn;iderward.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Sire Edward par ses playes est en grant torment, Le Rey Henry son pere ad fet soun testament. Apres le seint Martyn kaunt Maladye luy prent, L. &amp;. vi. annz fu Reis enterement. Il gist a Wemonstere en toumbe [<I>vel</I> en toumbez] richement, Sachez ke dieu [<I>vel</I> deus] pur ly ouer apertement, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>To God his fader foundes mad his testament,</L>
<L>Sir Edward of his woundes was in grete tourment.
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="230"></L>
<L>After &thorn;e Martynmesse &thorn;at he died here,</L>
<L>He regned more ne lesse &thorn;an sex &amp; fifty &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>At Westmynstere he lis toumbed richely,</L>
<L>In a marble bis of him is mad story.</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;at he was dede God has schewed his life.</L>
<L>Edward with his rede in his lyue tok a wife,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's douhter of Spayn da Helianore fulle &yogh;ing.</L>
<L>Of hir fairhede was fayn Edward our &yogh;ong kyng.</L>
<L>In Acres of hir is born a mayden childe dame Jone,</L>
<L>Was non fairer biforn of Inglis als scho one.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundred &thorn;e date sexti &amp; tuelue<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno. M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>mo</SUP>. LXXII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sir Edward help is sundred, o lyue is bot him selue.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e day of Saynt Edmound, &thorn;at martir<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>This is the</I> 20<I>th. of Nov. but then others (among whom is Rastall) observe, that he died on the day of Saint Edmund archbishop of Canterbury, which is the</I> 16<I>th. of that Month, and this I look upon as the truest account, notwith|standing the former is followed</I> (<I>through mistake</I>) <I>by Dr. Brady, contrary to his own Author Matthew Paris.</I></NOTE> is &amp; kyng,</L>
<L>Sir Henry at Londoun in God mad his endyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Henrici Regis tertii.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme his sonne Edward was in paemie,</L>
<L>His chance felle &thorn;er so hard, &thorn;at home behoued him hie.</L>
<L>For alle his help was dede, als I said beforn,</L>
<L>&thorn;is lond behoued haf hede, his heritage in born.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date of Criste pundred, &thorn;es fele &yogh;eres to mene</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundred sexti &amp; fourtene.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno. M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>o</SUP>. LXXIII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="235"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e &yogh;ere folowand &thorn;at I rekened here<NOTE PLACE="marg">Coronacio Edwardi filii pr&aelig;|dicti Hen|rici.</NOTE></L>
<L>Edward com to land, als prince of grete powere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e next Sonenday<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Others say it was the very day of the Assumption, or the</I> 15<I>th. of August.</I></NOTE> after &thorn;e assumpcioun</L>
<L>Of Mari moder &amp; may Sir Edward had &thorn;e coroun.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e kyrke of Westmynstere, at &thorn;e abbay sollempnely,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Canterbere, Robert of Kilwardeby,</L>
<L>Corouned Edward &thorn;ore biforn alle &thorn;e clergy,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Ausint la Rayne Elyanore sa amye Fu coroune le jour, vnqes a seint Dynie Ne fu si bele feste, ne si grant noblye, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&amp; dame Helianore corouned quene &amp; lady.</L>
<L>Was neuer at Saynt Denys feste holden more hy,</L>
<L>Ne was of more pris, ne serued so redy.</L>
<L>Was neuer prince, I wene, &thorn;at I writen of fond,</L>
<L>More had treie &amp; tene, &thorn;an he had for his lond.</L>
<L>In Scotlond &amp; in Wales, in Gasconie also,</L>
<L>If &yogh;e liste alle &thorn;e tales, &thorn;is storie tellis &yogh;ow to.</L>
<L>Pray we alle to God of myght, &amp; his modere Marie,</L>
<L>Grante him conquere his right Gascoyne &amp; Normundie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of France chalanges falsly.</L>
<L>Help him to &thorn;at chance moder of mercy,</L>
<L>&amp; Thomas &thorn;e martire, St. Jon of Beuerle,</L>
<L>St. Cutbert be &thorn;er fere, he trestres on &yogh;ow &thorn;re.</L>
<L>Towhile in Gascoyne es &thorn;e pes &yogh;it alle certeyn,</L>
<L>We salle leue &thorn;at pas vnto we com ageyn,
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="236"></L>
<L>&amp; telle &yogh;ow o&thorn;er tales of Edward curteisie,</L>
<L>&amp; of Leulyn of Wales, &amp; his beryng hie,</L>
<L>Of Dauid his bro&thorn;ere &amp; of his felonie,</L>
<L>Resaunraduk an o&thorn;ere how he did folie.</L>
<L>How &thorn;e contek was laid of Scotlond &thorn;at first gan.</L>
<L>How eft &thorn;ei mad a braid, &amp; on Inglond ran.</L>
<L>Of Madok &thorn;e Morgan, of &thorn;er nyce ribaudie,</L>
<L>Of Jon Baliol no man, &amp; of his treccherie,</L>
<L>&amp; of his duze pers togider &thorn;ei gan alie,</L>
<L>I schrowe alle &thorn;er maners, &thorn;at lufes &thorn;er partie.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; ii<SUP>o</SUP>. hundred sexti &amp; fiftene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e date of Criste so pundred whan Leulyn gan &thorn;is tene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE next &yogh;ere folowand of Edward coronment,</L>
<L>Leulyn of Walsland in to France he sent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Leulini.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Mountfort douhter to wedde, hir frendes alle consent,</L>
<L>Almerik hir ledde, to schip now er &thorn;ei went.</L>
<L>Now &thorn;ei saile &amp; rowe to Wales to Leulyns,</L>
<L>A burgeis of Bristowe charged was with wynes,</L>
<L>He ouertoke &thorn;er schip, &amp; asked whe&thorn;en &thorn;ei ware?</L>
<L>He said, with kyng Philip to Wales wild &thorn;ei fare.</L>
<L>What did &thorn;is burgeis? desturbled his wendyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;e may &amp; hir herneis did led vnto &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e mayden Edward toke, als he was fulle curteys,</L>
<L>In saufte did hir loke, &amp; &thorn;anked &thorn;e burgeis.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Leulyn herd say, to werre sone he bigan,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Movit bellum.</NOTE></L>
<L>For tene he wende to deie, &thorn;at taken was his lemman.
<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="237"></L>
<L>Edward wex fulle grim, whan he wist he was risen.</L>
<L>Sone he hasted him, to mak &thorn;am alle ogrisen.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Walssh wer alle day slayn, now rewes &thorn;am &thorn;er res,</L>
<L>&amp; Leulyn is fulle fayn, to pray Edward for pes,</L>
<L>Gyues Edward for his trespas fifti &thorn;ousand mark,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er tille bonden was with scrite &amp; oth fulle stark,</L>
<L>To com tuys in &thorn;e &yogh;ere vnto his parlement.</L>
<L>&thorn;e may on &thorn;is manere with Leulyn home scho went,</L>
<L>&amp; held his heritage in pes as he did ore,</L>
<L>Mad was &thorn;e mariage at Snowdon biside Bangore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN<NOTE PLACE="foot">Le [an] secounde apres le encorounement, Le Reis a Wemonstere tynt son par|lement. E statuz fist fere par commune assent, Ke de We|monstere sunt dist propre|ment, <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e &yogh;ere seconde after his corounment,</L>
<L>New statute &thorn;ei fonde, to Westmynstere &thorn;ei ment.</L>
<L>&thorn;e nex Paske folowand Edward sent his brefe</L>
<L>To Leulyn for his land, to com als tille his chefe.</L>
<L>Leulyn had despite of Edwarde's sonde,</L>
<L>Bot werred also tite on him with nyth &amp; onde.</L>
<L>Edward raised scheld, after his men alle sent,</L>
<L>&thorn;at seruise of him held, manly tille him went,</L>
<L>&amp; ran on Sir Leulyn, &amp; alle his folk him with,</L>
<L>&amp; maugre bo&thorn;e his bryn was fayn to com to grith.</L>
<L>Dauid at &thorn;at while was with Edward &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&yogh;it auanced he &thorn;at file vntille a faire &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>To Frodesham with &thorn;e fe, &amp; alle &thorn;at longed &thorn;er tille,</L>
<L>To Leulyn forgaf he alle his euelle wille.
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="238"></L>
<L>Now is Leulyn bonden eft to Sir Edward,</L>
<L>If he with faute be fonden, I trowe, it falles him hard.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW turnes Edward ageyn to London his cite,</L>
<L>&amp; wille wite certeyn, who schent has his mone.</L>
<L>Of clippers, of roungers, of suilk takes he questis.</L>
<L>Olde vsed traitoures ilk at o&thorn;er hand kestis.</L>
<L>Ilk thefe o&thorn;er out said, ilk a schrewe o&thorn;er greues,</L>
<L>Of fele wer handes laid, &amp; hanged &thorn;er as theues.</L>
<L>Edward<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>See my Preface to Robert of Gloucester's Chronicle, p. LXIII. where I have printed these eight Rhythms, that relate to K. Edward the first's altera|tion of the Coyn. As I had a desire my self to see how they are express'd in the French, so, it may be, some readers may have the same curiosity, and for that reason I shall here publish them in that language, only noting, that all that I have in|clos'd in Crotchets or Hooks is wanting in the MS. of the He|ralds Office, tho'exstant in both Mr. Anstis's Copies, and that what is put in a parenthesis is a various Reading:</I> Ester|lyng, maylle, (<I>vel</I> male) fer|thing (<I>vel</I> ferlynge) fet forger roundement, Et gros Tour|nais Englays qe valent ver|rayment Quatre esterlinges en achate &amp; vent. (<I>vel</I> ester|lyngs a chat e a vent) [De ren (<I>vel</I> rien) se lo ly prestre ke le offrande (<I>vel</I> offrant) atent, Ne ly chaytif pouers ke ren nad (<I>vel</I> rien ayd) dount despent.] En tote la moneye la croice par my se tent. (<I>vel</I> sestent) [Par quay le ferlynge (<I>vel</I> ferthing) rounde est communement. Offert v (<I>vel</I> ou) done pur deu (<I>vel</I> dieu) omnipotent, Le sterlynge et la maylle uie|nent (<I>vel</I> venent) rerement, Sur deu (<I>vel</I> dieu) et sur les sons chet len payrement.] (<I>vel</I> foens chiet lempeyrement) Mil. cc. et octaunte (<I>vel</I> vt|taunt) annz del incarnacioun Sunt passez par acounte kaunt de religioun (<I>vel</I> del Regioun) Est fet lestatut, qe counte ne baroun, Ne seyn|gnour de tere par my la Re|gioun, <I>&amp;c.</I></NOTE> did smyte rounde peny, halfpeny, ferthyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;e croice passed `passed<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dele.</NOTE> &thorn;e bounde of alle &thorn;orghout &thorn;e ryng.
<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="239"></L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's side salle be &thorn;e hede &amp; his name writen.</L>
<L>&thorn;e croyce side what cite it was in coyned &amp; smyten.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pouere man ne &thorn;e preste &thorn;e peny prayses no &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Men gyf God &thorn;e lest, &thorn;e feffe him with a fer&thorn;ing.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundred &amp; fourscore &yogh;eres mo,<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>mo</SUP>. LXXX<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>On &thorn;is mone men wondred<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic, pro</I> first.</NOTE> fist whan it gan go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WAS mad an o&thorn;er statute, &thorn;at non erle no baroun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Quod terr&aelig; nec tene|menta de|bent vendi vel dari ad manum mortuam sine Regis licentia.</NOTE></L>
<L>No o&thorn;er lorde stoute, ne fraunkeleyn of toun,</L>
<L>Tille holy kirke salle gyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> tenenement, rent no lond,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;o &thorn;at now lyue in to &thorn;e dedis hond,</L>
<L>Without leue of &thorn;e kyng, or of his consaile.</L>
<L>&thorn;e encheson of &thorn;is &thorn;ing may mykille auaile.</L>
<L>For freres of &thorn;e croice, &amp; monk &amp; chanoun,</L>
<L>Haf drawen in ovoice his feez to &thorn;er almoyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh whilk drauht his seruise is lorn &amp; laid doun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at is tille him &amp; hise in disheritsoun.</L>
<L>Not for &thorn;i he wille, &thorn;at alle religioun</L>
<L>Haf &amp; hold in skille &thorn;at gyuen is at resoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;e londes &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue now in possessioun.</L>
<L>His seruise he wille now saue, &thorn;at non be &thorn;orgh tresoun.</L>
<L>Ne no baron so bold, to selle &thorn;am lond ne gyue.</L>
<L>For myght &thorn;ei as &thorn;ei wold, no man suld bi &thorn;am lyue;</L>
<L>Men here biforn haf gyuen &thorn;am out of skille.</L>
<L>It lies now waste &amp; lorn, half may &thorn;ei not tille.
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="240"></L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundred &thorn;e date fourscore &amp; tuo,</L>
<L>On Leulyn has men wondred, no gynnes Dauid to thro.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOR now bigynnes Dauid to wax a werreour,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Defalsitate Leulini &amp; Dauid.</NOTE></L>
<L>With Leulyn gan he kith to be &thorn;e kynge's traytour.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei mad a samenyng, &amp; did als &thorn;ei were wonne,</L>
<L>To disherite &thorn;e kyng, &amp; his &yogh;ongest sonne.</L>
<L>On his londes &thorn;ei rais, &amp; robbed ilk a toun,</L>
<L>Brent &amp; slouh ilk man, his kastelle bette &thorn;ei doun.</L>
<L>Sir Edward herd wele telle of his grete misdede,</L>
<L>&thorn;er power forto felle, it catchis him to spede.</L>
<L>He sent North &amp; South after his baronage,</L>
<L>Sone it was fulle couth, &thorn;at Leulyn did outrage.</L>
<L>Atired &thorn;er wendyng toward &thorn;e Marche right sone.</L>
<L>Leulyn ageyn &thorn;e kyng &amp; Dauid were alle bone,</L>
<L>To maynten forth &thorn;e werre, &amp; susteyn &thorn;er treson;</L>
<L>&thorn;e entres did &thorn;ei sperre, &amp; hold &thorn;am in Snowdoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN Wales it is fulle strong to werre in Wynter tide,</L>
<L>For Wynter is &thorn;er long, whan Somer is here in pride.</L>
<L>&thorn;at was to &thorn;am grete pyne, &thorn;at werryng vndertoke,</L>
<L>&amp; Snowdoun did Leulyne wele to kepe &amp; loke.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng knowe no side, how he mot com &thorn;er inne,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er go no ride, ne how he suld it wynne.</L>
<L>A water in Snowdoun rennes, Auber is the name,</L>
<L>An arme of &thorn;e se men kennes, &thorn;e depnes may non ame.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng controued &thorn;er ouer, a brigge forto make,</L>
<L>&amp; of Leulyn to couere, Snowdoun forto take.
<PB REF="00000469.tif" N="241"></L>
<L>Botes he toke &amp; barges, &thorn;e sides togidere knytte,</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e water &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, large.</NOTE> lage is, fro bank to bank rauht itte.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei fleked &thorn;am ouerthuert, justely forto ligge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De ponte pr&aelig;parato &amp; facto. Ecce ruina facta in medio pon|tis super gentem An|glorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;ewater smerte was so ordeynd a brigge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN &thorn;e brigge was ent at Inglis men pay,</L>
<L>Withouten auysement, &thorn;e brigge &thorn;ei wild asay.</L>
<L>Sent &thorn;ei non bifore, to wite how &thorn;ei mo passe,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore had &thorn;ei lore, for non avisement wasse.</L>
<L>Forth went knyght &amp; sueyn, &amp; fote men alle in fere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Walsch com &thorn;am ageyn, did our men alle arere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at turnyng &thorn;er vnthank, as heuy was &thorn;e charge,</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;am alle sank, bothe batelle &amp; barge.</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode men &thorn;at were lorn, on our Inglis partie,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Clifford first biforn Sir Roger did folie.</L>
<L>William of Lyndeseie &amp; Jon le fitz Roberd,</L>
<L>Sir Lucas of Tame, &thorn;ise grete &thorn;er misferd,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;er squierie, &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at with &thorn;am nam,</L>
<L>Alle drenkled &thorn;orgh folie, &amp; faut of wisdam.</L>
<L>A man &thorn;at oste salle lede, &amp; controues no quayntise,</L>
<L>Howe he disceit salle drede, sca&thorn;e vmwhile salle rise.</L>
<L>Had &thorn;ei had a spie among &thorn;e Walssh oste,</L>
<L>&amp; warned &thorn;am priuelie, &thorn;at &thorn;ei were bi &thorn;at coste,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei had bien men lyuand, &thorn;at &thorn;er to dede went,</L>
<L>&thorn;at folie tok on hand withouten avisement.
<PB REF="00000470.tif" N="242"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THAT tyme &thorn;at &thorn;is crie com of &thorn;ise barouns,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De domino Johanne Vescy, ve|nit cum basklis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> &amp; super Leu|linum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Com Sir Jon Vescy fro &thorn;e kyng of Aragouns,</L>
<L>Brouht fote folk inouh of baskles &amp; Gascouns,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e Walsh men slouh raumpand as leouns.</L>
<L>&thorn;orghe mountayn &amp; more &thorn;e baskles &yogh;e &thorn;er weie,</L>
<L>Oure nesch &amp; hard &thorn;ei fore, &amp; did &thorn;e Walsch men deie.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei passed alle &thorn;e Marche, Snowdoun &thorn;ei wan in,</L>
<L>Of tounes &thorn;ei mad &thorn;am parche, &amp; souht after Leulyn.</L>
<L>Dauid couth non o&thorn;er, &thorn;e folowed &thorn;am so streite,</L>
<L>Bot fled fro his bro&thorn;er skulkand with disceite.</L>
<L>Sir Roger &thorn;e strange, &amp; Sir Reynald &thorn;e Gray,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei ne wold turne ne change, bot spied &thorn;er Leulyn lay.</L>
<L>&para; Leulyn in a wod a bussement he held,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eece de|collatio Leulini per Robertum Body.</NOTE></L>
<L>Biside a more a mod quayntly was he teld.</L>
<L>Sir Roger lay biside with priue folk &amp; stoute,</L>
<L>&amp; spied tyme &amp; tide whan he suld issue oute.</L>
<L>Leulyn wend no gile had bien &thorn;er so nere,</L>
<L>He went to play a wile with fo of his banere.</L>
<L>Sir Roger was perceyued whan Leulyn out cam,</L>
<L>&thorn;er pencels &thorn;ei weyued, tille Sir<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> Leuly he nam.</L>
<L>"Traitoure," said Rogere, "what salle &thorn;e werre auaile,</L>
<L>"Now I find &thorn;e here, wele set is my trauaile.</L>
<L>"Tuys ert &thorn;ou forsuorn, &amp; tuys &thorn;i feaute broken,</L>
<L>"Tuys was &thorn;ou doun born, &amp; for pes eft spoken.</L>
<L>"&thorn;is is &thorn;e &thorn;rid tyme, &thorn;at mykelle &thorn;ou him misbede,</L>
<L>"Dayet who &thorn;e kyme, for &thorn;ou has souht &thorn;i dede.</L>
<L>"Salle &thorn;ou neuer &thorn;i lyue do Inglis man more wo,</L>
<L>"Hastilie &thorn;e schryue, &thorn;i hede &thorn;ou salle for go.
<PB REF="00000471.tif" N="243"></L>
<L>Sir Roberd Body a knyght his suerd best bote,</L>
<L>Doun sone he he light, &amp; Leulyn hede of smote.</L>
<L>Now is Leulyn forsuorn, &amp; his hede of smyten,</L>
<L>His heritage is lorn fro his heyres &yogh;e wyten.</L>
<L>More &thorn;an a &yogh;ere beforn &thorn;at he lauht &thorn;is schame,</L>
<L>A douhter was him born, Wencilian hir name.</L>
<L>In hir credille &yogh;ing tille Inglond scho cam,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh conseile of &thorn;e kyng was brouht to Sempyngham,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er was scho inne four &amp; fifty &yogh;ere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De filia Leulini monacha in Sempyng|ham.</NOTE></L>
<L>Norised with Wynne, nunne and seculere.</L>
<L>Now haf we new tateles, dede is Wencilian,</L>
<L>Leulyn douhter of Wales, &thorn;at on Inglond ran.</L>
<L>Hir dede was mykelle ment, for scho was fulle curteys,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e ladies gent, &thorn;e los of hir so seys.</L>
<L>&thorn;e seuent day of Juny, Whitson euen &thorn;at tyme,</L>
<L>Died &thorn;at lady, bituex vndron &amp; prime.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date of Criste pundred, &thorn;us many &yogh;eres euen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. CCC<SUP>o</SUP>. XXXVII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; &thorn;re hundred &thorn;ritty &yogh;ere &amp; seuen.</L>
<L>Hir cosyn dame Gladous, of Dauid douhter born,</L>
<L>A Nunne of Sixille hous died a &yogh;ere beforn.</L>
<L>Of Wencilian wrote I here next Leulyn story,</L>
<L>Scho was his douhter dere, to bere him company.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW skulkes Dauid aboute, to wynne it ilk a dele,</L>
<L>His heritage &thorn;at is oute, he wenes fulle wele.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at Leulyn held lond &amp; tenement,</L>
<L>Holy to haf &thorn;e scheld &thorn;orgh heritage descent.</L>
<L>With lordes &thorn;at were nehi he held his parlement</L>
<L>At &yogh;ole at Denebeghi, after &thorn;am alle he sent,
<PB REF="00000472.tif" N="244"></L>
<L>To fend &thorn;e Walschrie with him at &thorn;er powere,</L>
<L>To him &thorn;ei gan alie, &amp; ros fulle austere.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e kyng herd say, &thorn;at Dauid werred on him,</L>
<L>To Wales he went his way fulle scharply &amp; fulle brim.</L>
<L>Edward did him chace, fulle febilly he defendes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Captus est Dauid.</NOTE></L>
<L>To rest had he no space, his tyme he tynes &amp; spendes.</L>
<L>&thorn;e euen of Saynt Morice was taken Sir Dauid,</L>
<L>Als a fole nyce he brak &thorn;e kynge's grith.</L>
<L>His hede &thorn;ei of smyten, to London was it born,</L>
<L>&thorn;e dede body &thorn;e britten on four quarters corn.</L>
<L>&thorn;e quarters wer sent to henge at four citez,</L>
<L>So is he worth be schent, who so traytour bez.</L>
<L>&para; Leulyn &amp; Dauid haf born grete honour,</L>
<L>And Snowdon com to grith, ilk castelle &amp; toure</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng is eschete, als to chefe of alle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Qe fount les Waleis, qe sunt de valour? Fount che|uaunce al Reis, com a go|uernour, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> lordes &thorn;at er grete &thorn;e cheued as tenauntz salle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng &thorn;orghout &thorn;e lond he did crie his pes,</L>
<L>&amp; with &thorn;e lawe &thorn;am bond, als skille wild he ches.</L>
<L>Wardeyns gode he sette, to stabille &thorn;e lond &amp; mende,</L>
<L>Justice &thorn;at &thorn;e lawe gette to vnkonand &thorn;ei kende.</L>
<L>Whan alle was don &amp; ent, &thorn;at felle to conqueroure,</L>
<L>To London he went, a while to mak soioure.</L>
<L>He sent to his barouns, a parlement to hold,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei com at his somouns, in parlement he &thorn;is told:</L>
<L>To Gascoyn bihoued him go, &amp; &thorn;at hastilie,</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;ing com him &thorn;er fro, &thorn;er was contek &amp; crie,
<PB REF="00000473.tif" N="245"></L>
<L>&thorn;ider bihoued him nede, to set &thorn;at lond in pes,</L>
<L>For foles haf no drede, &thorn;at long is justiseles.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundred, &amp; fourscore &yogh;ere &amp; sex,<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>o</SUP>. LXXX. VI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>On Wales many on wundred, for more wo &yogh;it &thorn;er wex.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EDWARD wele has sped of alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at has bien,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Iter<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> ari|puit versus Gasconiam.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tille Gascoyn with him led dame Helianore our quene.</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode erle of Cornwaile &thorn;is lond had in kepyng,</L>
<L>In luf &amp; pes sanz faile went Edward our kyng,</L>
<L>&amp; spak with &thorn;e kyng of France at Paris as he went.</L>
<L>&thorn;an felle a fair chance, &thorn;ei wer at on assent.</L>
<L>Forth he gan him hie, tille Gascoyn is he comen,</L>
<L>&thorn;e rightes he did attrie of &thorn;o &thorn;at wrong had nomen.</L>
<L>Rightfulle dome he gaf on foles for &thorn;er misdede,</L>
<L>No man be ouerhaf, bot alle &thorn;orgh lawe &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&para; Towhile Sir Edward gos to Gascoyn forto apese,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de Reseamira|duk.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wales to werre vp ros, &thorn;orgh conseile of a Rese.</L>
<L>On<NOTE PLACE="foot">Rees amereduke, <I>vel</I> Res admyraduck, <I>in Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE> Reseamiraduk, of Wales a lordyng,</L>
<L>Our Inglis did rebuk, &amp; werred on our kyng.</L>
<L>I kan not telle &yogh;ow whi &thorn;at werre was reised olofte,</L>
<L>Men said &thorn;e wrath &amp; cri com &thorn;orgh &thorn;e lord Tiptofte.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng herd &thorn;at pleynt, vnto &thorn;e Rese he sent</L>
<L>A letter enselid fulle quaynt, for &thorn;e pes it ment.</L>
<L>He praied to hold him stille, tille his tocome mot be,</L>
<L>&amp; he suld do his wille, in alle &thorn;at skille mot se.</L>
<L>His pleyntes he wild here in skille at lordes sight,</L>
<L>&amp; if he baron were, he suld haf fulle gode right.
<PB REF="00000474.tif" N="246"></L>
<L>&thorn;is Reseamiraduk, als fole &amp; vnwise,</L>
<L>His letter gan rebuk, sette it at light prise.</L>
<L>&thorn;e ska&thorn;e &thorn;at he myght do with slauhter or prison hard,</L>
<L>Alle he brouht &thorn;am to, &thorn;at longed tille Edward.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundred &thorn;e date forscore &amp; nine,</L>
<L>On our men &thorn;ei wondred, in Wales did &thorn;am pyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN Edward had bien in Gascoyn &thorn;re &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Ageyn he &amp; &thorn;e quene on lond ryued vp here.</L>
<L>At his comyng he fond of clerkes &amp; men of pleynt,</L>
<L>&amp; justise of &thorn;e lond of falsnes was atteynt.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De falsi|tate justi|ciariorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>For giftes som justise lete &thorn;e lowe go doun,</L>
<L>&amp; som on o&thorn;er wise did wrong to &thorn;e coroun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e first justise in benk Sir Thomas of Weland,</L>
<L>For falshed &amp; for wrenk he forsuore &thorn;e land.</L>
<L>He went ouer to France, &amp; com neuer ageyn,</L>
<L>His<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ses compaygnouns ses clers sunt pris &amp; mene A [<I>sive</I> ad] la tour de Loundres, de|liuerez par mone, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> clerkes stode to chance passed for a certeyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei wer out of &thorn;e tour delyuerd for mone,</L>
<L>&thorn;er held &thorn;ei long soiour, bot penies mad &thorn;am fre,</L>
<L>Opon his forward, or &thorn;ei wer out gon,</L>
<L>To serue kyng Edward, neuer more suld &thorn;ei non.</L>
<L>Sir Elys of Bekyngham to do lawe him was lefe,</L>
<L>Sir Jon of Metyngham he left &thorn;e justise chefe,</L>
<L>Sir Rauf of Heyngham &thorn;e wrong oft he ches,</L>
<L>He departed with gram, &amp; &thorn;e benk les.</L>
<L>Sir Adam of Stretton fulle hard was he led,</L>
<L>Nouht without encheson, I lay my gloue to wed.
<PB REF="00000475.tif" N="247"></L>
<L>For gold &amp; siluer strong he gaf so grete plente,</L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e kyng it song, <I>Placebo domine.</I></L>
<L>With wrong alle it cam, with gile salle gyuen be,</L>
<L><I>Dilexit</I> Sir Adam gilerie &amp; falste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THISE justise er atteynt of falshed &amp; folie,</L>
<L>Now comes a new pleynt, to destroie &thorn;e Juerie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng was enquere of &thorn;er wikked dedes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De iniqui|tate Judeis|mi sive Ju|d&aelig;orum.</NOTE></L>
<L>So many &thorn;er were, dome on &thorn;am salle nedes.</L>
<L>For &thorn;am &thorn;e kyng was sette his priue parlement,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei said, &thorn;orgh &thorn;e rescette &thorn;e Cristen men were schent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons alle said, alle holy &thorn;e clergie,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lond &thorn;ei wild voide of &thorn;at herisie.</L>
<L>I wene &thorn;e kyng alegid, &thorn;ei were of his tresour,</L>
<L>No&thorn;eles he wild haf briggid, &thorn;e fals leue &amp; erroure.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e penie fiftend, &thorn;e Jues wild he fleme.</L>
<L>&thorn;e clergie said at &thorn;e end, "we grante it as &yogh;e deme.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lerid &amp; &thorn;e lay granted &thorn;at &thorn;ei said,</L>
<L>&amp; assigned a day, &thorn;at taxe to be laid.</L>
<L>&thorn;e dettes &thorn;at men &thorn;am auht, &thorn;er stedes &amp; &thorn;er wonyng.</L>
<L>Wer taxed &amp; bitauht to &thorn;e eschete of &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Rees ameraduk, <I>vel</I> Rees admiraduk <I>sive</I> Rees amereduk, <I>in Codd Gall.</I></NOTE> Reseamiradie was taken &thorn;at ilk &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>In Wales &thorn;orgh a spie, for all his powere.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e kyng herd it seie, to &yogh;ork he did him lede,</L>
<L>Schames dede to deie, als traytour for his dede.</L>
<L>First was he drawen for his felonie,</L>
<L>&amp; as a &thorn;efe &thorn;an slawen, on galwes hanged hic.
<PB REF="00000476.tif" N="248"></L>
<L>Now is non of age of his ancestrie</L>
<L>May haf his heritage, to whom it salle alie.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundred, four score &amp; elleuen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>o</SUP>. LXXXXI<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>On Wales men &yogh;it wondred, &thorn;e pes not &yogh;it euen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE next &yogh;ere folowand Acres was assaled,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Cristen myght no stand, of help alle &thorn;am failed,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e cite lorn, &amp; alle don to &thorn;e suerde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De capci|one Acres.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at were Cristen born, &thorn;e lewed &amp; &thorn;e lerid.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e pape had ti&thorn;ing, it was in a Sarazins handes,</L>
<L>He gaf Edward our kyng, &thorn;e tende of alle &thorn;e landes.</L>
<L>Inglond, Scotlond &amp; Wales, Ireland &thorn;erto was laid,</L>
<L>&thorn;an mot he fille his males, no man him withsaid.</L>
<L>Holy who salle spare, if it nede stode,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;o &thorn;at hedes are do &thorn;er to no gode?</L>
<L>&thorn;at ilk &yogh;ere &thorn;e quene died in Lyndseie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Regin&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>At Westmynster, I wene, his body did &thorn;ei leie.</L>
<L>&para; A litelle &thorn;er biforn died Margarete,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Et Marga|reta, filia &amp; heres Alexandri Regis Scot|torum, mor|tua est.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e heyr of Scotlond born, of Alisander bi&yogh;ete.</L>
<L>Wherfor Sir Edward, for &thorn;at maiden dede,</L>
<L>Hied him Northward, his barons he asked rede.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e North at Norham, he wamssed &thorn;e castelle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons &thorn;ider cam, &amp; conseild &thorn;at beste felle,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei brouht &thorn;e cronykles, &thorn;at wer in Scotland,</L>
<L>&thorn;e olde chartres &amp; titles, &thorn;at wer in Abbays hand,</L>
<L>Of ilk a bisshop se, &amp; ilk a priourie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at were of dignite, of olde ancestrie,</L>
<L>Examend &thorn;am &amp; cast ilk amountment,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei said alle at &thorn;e last &thorn;orght of on assent,
<PB REF="00000477.tif" N="249"></L>
<L>Of Inglond suld &thorn;ei hold &thorn;orgh right &amp; skille,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> to.</NOTE>Fo wild &thorn;e feffementes ald, &amp; &thorn;ei granted &thorn;ertille.</L>
<L>&thorn;is was certified, &amp; sikere on ilk side.</L>
<L>It myght not be denied, for &thorn;ing &thorn;at mot betide.</L>
<L>&thorn;is conseild Sir Antoyn, &thorn;e bisshop of Durham,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce mur|mur factum pro rege Scottorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at non eft mad essoyn, &thorn;e kynge's right to clame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW wex &thorn;e Scottes wode, now haue &thorn;ei nythe &amp; onde,</L>
<L>Who of &thorn;at fals blode ouh to be kyng of &thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>&thorn;at was right heire is dede, on &thorn;at side is no mo,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh blode &amp; right rede to Dauid salle it go.</L>
<L>Dauid of Huntyngton was kynge's Wiliam bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Tille his heires &thorn;orgh reson, of William is non o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Of William now is non, Dauid heire salle be,</L>
<L>&amp; his heirs of him gon salle haf &thorn;e regalte.</L>
<L>Dauid had douhtres &thorn;re were gyuen to &thorn;re lordynges,</L>
<L>&thorn;at claymes &thorn;e regalte, Baliol, Brus, Hastynges.</L>
<L>&thorn;is ilk &thorn;re barons, &thorn;orgh descent of blode,</L>
<L>Haf right &amp; resons to &thorn;e coroune fulle gode.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise &thorn;re &yogh;ald &thorn;er right vp to Sir Edward,</L>
<L>Tille it wer atried &thorn;orgh sight, whom it felle afterward.</L>
<L>Sir Edward is seised in Scotland ilk a dele,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise &thorn;re barons pesid, &amp; hold &thorn;am paied wele.</L>
<L>&para; Now com &thorn;is barons eft, &amp; ask jugement,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce Angli &amp; Scotti tractant pro regno Scoci&aelig;</NOTE></L>
<L>To whom it salle be left, &thorn;orgh comon assent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng wille bot wele, &thorn;e lawe alle vnderstandes,</L>
<L>&thorn;e hie folk ilk a dele, he did com of bo&thorn;e &thorn;e landes</L>
<L>Scottis &amp; Inglis, he said to &thorn;e wisest,</L>
<L>"Gyue now gode dome of &thorn;is, whilk of &thorn;ise may best
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="250"></L>
<L>"To resceyue &thorn;e ooroune, Scotlond forto &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;e right go not doune, &amp; best may &yogh;ow alle &yogh;eme.</L>
<L>What for &thorn;e kynge's sawe, &amp; skille &thorn;ei vnderstode,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;orgh &thorn;e londe's lawe, &amp; descent of blod,</L>
<L>&thorn;e triours alle &thorn;at caste, &amp; put &thorn;er saw tille on.</L>
<L>"We say with word stedfaste, we chefe Baliol Jon.</L>
<L>"Sir Jon &thorn;e Baliol es a man &thorn;e reame may saue,</L>
<L>"&amp; nere of blode &amp; flessh, &thorn;e heritage to haue,</L>
<L>"For euer we vnderstond, tille him &amp; alle hise,</L>
<L>"Holdand of Inglond, for homage &amp; seruise.</L>
<L>Our kyng Sir Edward held him wele payed,</L>
<L>He did &thorn;am no more hard, ne langer was delayed.</L>
<L>Disseised him self of alle, &yogh;ald it to Sir Jon,</L>
<L>Bot Jon his homage salle mak or he be gon.</L>
<L>Saynt Steuenday it felle, &thorn;at Jon mad his homage,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e Newe castelle, listnes &thorn;e langage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>This form is thus express'd (but not in Rhythm) in the French Cop&icirc;es:</I> Moun sey|gnoure<NOTE PLACE="marg">Homagium Johannis Baliol.</NOTE> Sire Edward, Reis Dengleterre. &amp; souerayne seignour du realme descoez, [<I>vel</I> de Escoce <I>sive</I> descoce] Jeo Jon de Balyol, Rey de|scoce, deuenk vostre home lige de tut le realme descoce, oue les [<I>vel</I> ouf tuz les] apur|tenaunces, e ou qaunt qe apent, [<I>vel</I> ouf kauncke apent] le quel ioe [<I>vel</I> io, <I>sive</I> ieo] tenk de dreit e [<I>vel</I> et] clayme a tenir [<I>vel</I> tenir, <I>absque</I> a] heritablement de vous &amp; de vos heyrs reis de Engleter|re, de vie &amp; de membre, e de terrien honour en countre qe [<I>vel</I> honour countre totes genz ke, <I>sive</I> honur encontre genz qe] pount viuer ou mo|rir. Et le Rey le rescent [<I>vel</I> rascent, <I>sive</I> receyt] en la fourme saune son dreit &amp; autry. Cest homage fu fet a Noue chastel sur Tyne le iour [<I>vel</I> sur Tyne en Engle|terre le iour] Sent Esteuen, le an [<I>vel</I> lan] de grace. M.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno do|mini M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>o</SUP>. nona|gesimo iii<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> cc. xc. secound, e du regne la Rey Edward. xxi<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE>MY lord Edward &thorn;e kyng Inglis,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Forma ho|magii Jo|hannis Ba|liolensis a|pud Novum castrum.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&amp; chefe lord of &thorn;e Scottis,</L>
<L>"I Jon Baliol &thorn;e Scottis kyng,</L>
<L>"I bicom &thorn;i man for Scotlond &thorn;ing,
<PB REF="00000479.tif" N="251"></L>
<L>"With alle &thorn;e purtenance &thorn;ertille,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at to &thorn;e reame longes with skille,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e whilk I hold, &amp; salle &thorn;orgh right</L>
<L>"Clayme to hald, at alle my myght,</L>
<L>"Heritagelik of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"&amp; of &thorn;in heires &thorn;at after &thorn;e be.</L>
<L>Of Inglond, with lif &amp; lymme,</L>
<L>For erthly worschip &thorn;at I nymme,</L>
<L>Ageyn alle &thorn;o may lyue &amp; deye,</L>
<L>&amp; with &thorn;am hold in luf &amp; eye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON &thorn;is maner &thorn;e kyng it toke,</L>
<L>His right forto saue &amp; loke.</L>
<L>&thorn;is was at &thorn;e Newe castelle,</L>
<L>On Saynt Steuen's day it felle.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand. CC<SUP>o</SUP>. fourscore &amp; &thorn;re<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>o</SUP>. LXXXIII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;ers o Jhesu wer, whan &thorn;is felle to be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OUR kyng gode Edward &thorn;orgh Scotlond ferd,</L>
<L>As he com <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> homward.</NOTE> howard he souht S. Cutberd,</L>
<L>&amp; mad &thorn;er his offryng, si&thorn;en com to Beuerlay,</L>
<L>&amp; offred &thorn;er fair &thorn;ing, to London his way.
<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="252"></L>
<L>On fele &thorn;inges he &thorn;ouht, &amp; wex heuy als lede,</L>
<L>How chances on him souht, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e quene was dede.</L>
<L>His solace was alle reft, &thorn;at scho fro him was gon,</L>
<L>Ne no sonne him left, bot &yogh;ing Edward alon.</L>
<L>He was tendre &amp; &yogh;ing, of him had he no speyre,</L>
<L>Himself in ille likyng, &amp; had no waxen heyre,</L>
<L>&thorn;at mot kepe &thorn;e coroune, if he of lond went,</L>
<L>He drouped &thorn;erfore donne, &amp; said &thorn;e lond were schent,</L>
<L>If<NOTE PLACE="foot">Et si le Reis Edward vers Akres fust ale, Mult serreyt en perylle regne &amp; re|galte, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> he tille Acres &yogh;ede, in perile sulle alle be,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e child wer drede &thorn;e lond als wele as he.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;inkeng of alle &thorn;is, &thorn;e batailed in &thorn;e se,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De bello inter Porti|cos &amp; Nor|mannos.</NOTE></L>
<L>Normans &amp; Inglis were slayn grete plente.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Normans &thorn;at day les, for &thorn;er powere was nouht,</L>
<L>&thorn;e portes had als &thorn;ei ches schippes inow &thorn;am brouht.</L>
<L>To Douer &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gerne|meue, <I>vel</I> Gernemue <I>sive</I> Ger|newe, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> Germne cam, &amp; vnto Wynchilse,</L>
<L>To Romeneye &amp; Schorham, &amp; to Peueneshe,</L>
<L>To Gipwiche &amp; Sandwiche, &amp; to Southamptoun,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Irays &amp; Baonays [<I>vel</I> Bayonays) ount grant partye waygne, <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE>Alle &thorn;e portes were riche, Irays &amp; Bayoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e fiue portes &thorn;orgh powere &thorn;e se had so conquerd,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Normans alle &thorn;at &yogh;ere durst not be sene for ferd.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e lond of France was said fulle sone,</L>
<L>Philip herd &thorn;at chance, how &thorn;e Inglis had done,</L>
<L>&amp; alle how it bigan, &amp; alle &thorn;e skille why,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei togider ran, &amp; we had &thorn;e maistrie.
<PB REF="00000481.tif" N="253"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIR<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ly Reis sir Edward ad grant volente, Esposer gen|tyl femme de halt parentee, Dount auer engendrure pur son herite, Pur refourmer la pees, e norir amiste, <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE> Edward God him saue, he is in grete longyng</L>
<L>A where he mot haue, &thorn;at auenant is &amp; &yogh;ing</L>
<L>&thorn;at wer of hie perage, suilk on wild he take</L>
<L>His euenhed in mariage, gentille gendrure to make.</L>
<L>His herte gaf tille dame Blanche, if hir wille wer &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>&amp; holy kirke wild stanche sibred bituex &thorn;am tuo,</L>
<L>Hire &thorn;an wild he wedde, forto saue &thorn;e pes<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Blan|chia sorore Regis Franci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>In luf &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;am ledde, in werre &thorn;at nou&thorn;er les.</L>
<L>For Blanche his cosyn he sent how it mot be,</L>
<L>To mak a mariage fyn, Philip sister was sche.</L>
<L>&amp; als vnto &thorn;e pape, for to wite &thorn;e certeyn,</L>
<L>What &thorn;e clergie wild schape, whan &thorn;e courte were pleyn.</L>
<L>&para; Edward<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sire Edward en Fraunce ad messagers maun|de, De vere la damoy|sele enquere de sa bounte. Les messangeres [<I>vel</I> bounte, Si elesait, <I>sive</I> E si ele soyt, auenaunte en face, en cors taylle. Les messagers] i vount, e le ount refigure En cors, en facoun, en mayn, en iaumbe, &amp; pe. [<I>vel</I> en pe] Al Reis sunt reuenuz, e le ount nouncye, Plus bele creature est nule part troue. Sire Ed|ward, allas! deueent en a|moure, Et a la damoysele par lettre ad monstre, [<I>vel</I> admu|stre, <I>sive</I> ad mustre] Et al Rey Phelipp son quoer, &amp; sa pen|se, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> messengers vnto &thorn;at mayden sent,</L>
<L>To wite of hir maners, to se hir body gent.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei com vnto &thorn;at may, &amp; sauh hir contenance,</L>
<L>So fair lady &thorn;at day was not in alle France.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei had sene &thorn;at sight, &thorn;ei com &amp; teld our kyng,</L>
<L>Creature non myght be fayrer bi no &thorn;ing.
<PB REF="00000482.tif" N="254"></L>
<L>Fro Rome hiderward fayrer non was,</L>
<L>Enamoured bicom Edward of dame Blanche, allas!</L>
<L>Blanche did write stille, a letter Philip sent,</L>
<L>Hir herte &amp; hir wille alle wist he what scho went.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp;. cc. fourscore &amp; fourtene,</L>
<L>&yogh;it salle Edward be encombred &thorn;orgh dame Blanche schene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OFT &thorn;ad &thorn;e parties spoken of &thorn;is mariage,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Forma ma|ritagii inter Edwardum &amp; Blan|chiam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; teld bo&thorn;e &thorn;er avis to messengers of passage.</L>
<L>Philip &amp; dame Blanche granted &thorn;e aliance,</L>
<L>No &thorn;e les of a branche &thorn;er was a disceyuance.</L>
<L>How &thorn;e granted &thorn;er tille &thorn;ei tald bi a messengere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e fourme of &thorn;er skille &thorn;ei said on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L>"Edward withut essoyn salle gyue Philip &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>"Alle holy Gascoyn, withouten disturblyng.</L>
<L>"After &thorn;e forty dayes of &thorn;at feffement,</L>
<L>"Philip, without delayes, salle gyue &thorn;at ilk tenement</L>
<L>"Tille Edward &amp; tille Blanche, &amp; &thorn;er heires of &thorn;am comen.</L>
<L>"If it be so no branche in wedlaike of &thorn;am be nomen,</L>
<L>"If Blanche ouer lyue Edward, scho salle haf hir lyue</L>
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE>Goscoyn afterward, ageyn &thorn;at non salle stryue;</L>
<L>"&amp; after Blanche desces, withouten gaynsaying,</L>
<L>"Salle turne to &thorn;e heires in pes of &thorn;e Inglis kyng,</L>
<L>To &thorn;at ilk scrite Edward set his seale,</L>
<L>&thorn;at his gift was perfite, &amp; with witnes leale.</L>
<L>Whan alle was spoken, wist not Sir Antoyn,</L>
<L>Fulle sone it had bien broken, &amp; Philip fro Gascoyn,</L>
<L>Philip seysed Burdews, &thorn;orgh Sir Edward scrite,</L>
<L>&thorn;e to&thorn;er, as so say deus! &yogh;ald &thorn;am also tite.
<PB REF="00000483.tif" N="255"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAT did kyng Philip, whan alle &thorn;is was ent?</L>
<L>To Paris gan he skip, &amp; held his parlement,</L>
<L>&amp; Charles his bro&thorn;er with him com he &thorn;idere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Artous &thorn;e to&thorn;er, &thorn;re fals men togidere.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise &thorn;re ageyn Edward mad a compassement,</L>
<L>For Normand &amp; Pikard to courte after &thorn;am sent.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De tradi|tione Ka|roli &amp; co|mitis de Artous.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at were in &thorn;e bataile, &thorn;at on &thorn;e had lorn,</L>
<L>&thorn;at portes gan assaile, as I told biforn,</L>
<L>Edward &thorn;ei cald &amp; teld, &thorn;at he was mayntenoure,</L>
<L>&thorn;e robbed he alle held, as a resceyuour.</L>
<L>Of suilk felonie Edward in courte &thorn;e cald,</L>
<L>Did non &thorn;at curteisie, &thorn;at &thorn;er for him wild hald.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at fals controueyng gaf &thorn;ei jugement,</L>
<L>Depriued &thorn;ei our kyng of alle &thorn;e tenement</L>
<L>Of londes of Gascoyn, &thorn;at neuer more suld he,</L>
<L>For no maner essoyn, eft chalange &thorn;at fe,</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e kyng of France holden suld it be.</L>
<L>Edward kepe &thorn;i chance, &thorn;ei haf bitraised &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MEN sais in &thorn;e courte of France, among &thorn;e deze pers,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De curia Franci&aelig; &amp; jure ejus.</NOTE></L>
<L>With right he leses his chance, &thorn;orgh faut &thorn;at not apers.</L>
<L>&thorn;er may ne write be brouht, to wynne ageyn his right,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;orgh force be souht, &thorn;orght dynt of suerd &amp; fight.</L>
<L>Edward sore it ment, whan he wist &thorn;at tirpeil,</L>
<L>For Sir Antoyn he sent, to com to his conseil,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;o barouns, &thorn;at were his wele willand,</L>
<L>For conseil &amp; resons, &amp; chance &thorn;at was comand.
<PB REF="00000484.tif" N="256"></L>
<L>Sir Antoyn first bigan, spak hastily &amp; wilde,</L>
<L>"Sir kyng &thorn;ou was a man, be not now hold a childe.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou suld do right nouht without &thorn;e comon sight,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at may of sca&thorn;e be wrouht ageyn &thorn;e reame's right.</L>
<L>"Do &yogh;it be be consaile, &thorn;ou salle not it repent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce dicta Antonii.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Bot som &thorn;at may not auaile, &thorn;i wille to suilk es went.</L>
<L>"&thorn;i manace drede &thorn;ei more, in hastynes suorn,</L>
<L>"&thorn;an if &thorn;i reame alle wore in poynt forto be lorn.</L>
<L>"Sir Antoyn," said &thorn;e kyng, "I wite &thorn;is no man,</L>
<L>"Bot myn vnconyng, &thorn;is foli&egrave; my self bigan.</L>
<L>&para; "Sen &thorn;ou has don<NOTE PLACE="foot">Said &thorn;e bishop <I>addenda sunt, si Codices Gallicos sequamur.</I></NOTE> amysse, at &thorn;in vnconyng,</L>
<L>"We may not faile at &thorn;is, to help &thorn;e in alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;ou &thorn;ink to wynne Gascoyn ageyn &thorn;i lond,</L>
<L>"Hastily bigynne Philip to folow &thorn;ou fond.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou may not ligge &amp; slepe as monke in his dortoure,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou salle rise vp &amp; lepe, &amp; stirre vnto &thorn;e stoure,</L>
<L>"&amp; gete &thorn;e frendes fele, &thorn;orgh gifte of mone,</L>
<L>"Tresore may &thorn;ou non spele of lordes bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e kyng of Almayn, &amp; &thorn;e duke of Boloyn,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e to help were fayn, &amp; &thorn;e erle of Burgoyn,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e kyng of Aragoun, &amp; &thorn;e erle of Sauuay.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ise er redy boun, to help &thorn;e nyght &amp; day.</L>
<L>"Whan &thorn;ou of &thorn;ise ert sikere to &thorn;e &thorn;orgh aliance,</L>
<L>"&thorn;an is tyme to bikere with &thorn;e kyng of France.
<PB REF="00000485.tif" N="257"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN Antoyn his resons to &thorn;e kyng said &thorn;us,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Consilium baronum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;an spak &thorn;e barons, "Sir kyng listen tille vs.</L>
<L>"Forsoth ilk lordyng, whilk Sir Antoyn has said,</L>
<L>"Disherited is &thorn;orgh &thorn;e kyng, chalanges &thorn;am of neid.</L>
<L>"He has spared non, &thorn;er he mot fynd encheson,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at he disherites ilkon of castelle &amp; of toun.</L>
<L>"&thorn;erfore we rede &yogh;e sende to &thorn;e kyng of Almayn,</L>
<L>"&amp; &yogh;our londes to defende, &amp; reue Philip his wayn.</L>
<L>"&amp; to &thorn;e kyng of Aragoun, &amp; tille alle &thorn;e to&thorn;er,</L>
<L>"Be calle &thorn;am of tresoun, Philip &amp; Charles his bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>"Bynd &yogh;ow alle togider, to lyue &amp; to deie,</L>
<L>"We se nou&thorn;er whidere &thorn;ou may haf sikerer weie.</L>
<L>"Siluer may &thorn;ou non spare of &thorn;o &thorn;at with &thorn;e be,</L>
<L>"For Philip is euer &yogh;are, &amp; has so grete pouste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO &thorn;at ilk consail &thorn;e kyng acorded to,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Antonius factus est nuncius.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sir Antoyn wille trauail, &thorn;e message forto do.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Par commune counsaylle Antoyne est alez, Et luy [<I>vel</I> ly] erceuesque de Diuelyn sa|crez, Hug le Despensere ba|roun renomez, Et Jon de Cracoumbe clerk bien auy|sez, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e ersbisshop of Deuelyn he was chosen his pere,</L>
<L>A baron bold &amp; fyn, Sir Hugh Despensere,</L>
<L>Of Krawecombe Sir Jon, a clerke gode &amp; wys.</L>
<L>Now is Antoyn gon to procure &thorn;e partys,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Almanz alle wer lefe be suorn to &thorn;e Inglis,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er kyng was chefe in wille to do alle &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&amp; bisshop &amp; baron alle &thorn;ei had gode wille.</L>
<L>With obligacion &thorn;e Inglis suore &thorn;ei tille
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="258"></L>
<L>Be helpand &thorn;e Almanz in alle maner of nede.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e to hold couenaz with scrite enselid &thorn;e dede.</L>
<L>Now Antoyn is of lond, God saue him &amp; his pers,</L>
<L>Edward sendis his sond, to France messengers,</L>
<L>Frere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hugh de Mauncestre, <I>vel</I> Huge de Maumecestre, <I>in Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE> Hugh of Malmcestre was a Jacobyn,</L>
<L>&amp; William of Gaynesburgh was a Cordelyn.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ise passid &thorn;e se, so com &thorn;e erle of Artoys</L>
<L>In prison did &thorn;am be a seuenyght in Caleys.</L>
<L>To Paris si&thorn;en &thorn;ei cam, &amp; &thorn;er fond &thorn;ei &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;e letter forth &thorn;ei nam, to trowe &thorn;er sayng.</L>
<L>&thorn;is letter of credance &thorn;ei schewed in his present,</L>
<L>Here now &thorn;e acordance, what &thorn;er sayng ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIR Hugh was man of state, he said as I salle rede,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Duo fratres facti sunt nuncii ad Regem Franci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>"To prince &amp; to prelate men salle loute &amp; drede,</L>
<L>"&amp; for lord dere his biddyng salle men do,</L>
<L>"To lesse &amp; more in fere haf fayth &amp; treuth also,</L>
<L>"&amp; for our lord Edward, <NOTE PLACE="foot">Qe dieu de mal defent, <I>Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;at God him saue &amp; se,</L>
<L>"We tok &thorn;is trauaile hard, his bode to bere to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&para; "He settes &thorn;e terme &amp; stage bi vs, whan &amp; why</L>
<L>"&thorn;at he has don homage for Gascoyn plenerly,</L>
<L>"In forward formed in pes, as was &thorn;er acordance,</L>
<L>"As &yogh;our ancestres ches of Inglond &amp; of France,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ei mad a pes final aftere &thorn;er contek,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou has broken it alle, &amp; don him many ille chek.</L>
<L>&para; "Now at his last goyng, whan he to Gascoyn went,</L>
<L>"&yogh;e sette a certeyn &thorn;ing, at &yogh;our bo&thorn;e assent,
<PB REF="00000487.tif" N="259"></L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;at suld holden be, euer withouten ende,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou brak &thorn;at certeynte wikkedly &amp; vnhende.</L>
<L>&para; "&yogh;it he biddes &thorn;e se, how wrong &thorn;ou wilt him lede,</L>
<L>"Bituex him &amp; &thorn;e was mad a priue dede,</L>
<L>"Of Gascoyn certeyn was &thorn;at feffement,</L>
<L>"Forto feffe him ageyn in &thorn;at tenement.</L>
<L>"&thorn;i seisyn is wele knowen, &thorn;e days has &thorn;ou plenere,</L>
<L>"To restore him his owen, he sent to &thorn;e duzepers,</L>
<L>"As lawe wild &amp; right, &amp; couenant was in scrite.</L>
<L>"&yogh;eld it, &thorn;ou has no right, with wrong holdes it in lite,</L>
<L>"Ageyn alle maner skille, &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ou ert so grefe.</L>
<L>"For whilom &thorn;ou wrote him tille, &amp; cald him in &thorn;i brefe,</L>
<L>"&thorn;i kynde, faythfulle &amp; leale of Gascoyn noble duke,</L>
<L>"&thorn;erto &thorn;ou set &thorn;i seale, &thorn;at right wilt &thorn;ou rebuke.</L>
<L>"Neuer si&thorn;en hiderward suilk speche vnto him touched,</L>
<L>"Werfore our kyng Edward in &thorn;ouht fulle wele has souched.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou holdes him not &thorn;i man, no &thorn;ing holdand of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"Ne he &thorn;inkes neuer for &thorn;an, to mak &thorn;e more feaute.</L>
<L>"He hopes to wynne &thorn;at land with dynt of douhty<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> knyght.</NOTE> kyght,</L>
<L>"Of God he claymes holdand, &amp; neuer of no right.</L>
<L>&para; "At &thorn;is tyme is not els of Sir Edward to seye,</L>
<L>"Bot of Edmunde &thorn;at duellis with him als bre&thorn;er tueye,</L>
<L>"Forbi any o&thorn;er with him wille hold &amp; be.</L>
<L>"He is his lord &amp; bro&thorn;er, he certifies &thorn;at to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at no man in &thorn;is werld he lufes so mykelle no dredis,</L>
<L>"Ne with him is non herd so mykelle may help at nedis.</L>
<L>"For he sees so wele &yogh;our grete controued gile,</L>
<L>"Ageyn his bro&thorn;er ilk dele compassed in a while,
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="260"></L>
<L>" Reft him his heritage, sais on him felonie,</L>
<L>" He &yogh;eldes vp his homage, forsakis &thorn;i companie,</L>
<L>" &amp; &thorn;erto all &thorn;e londes, &thorn;at he held of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>" &amp; &yogh;eldes vp alle &thorn;e bondes of homage &amp; feaute,</L>
<L>" Saue &thorn;e right &thorn;at may falle of ancestres olde,</L>
<L>" Unto &thorn;er heires alle to haf &amp; to holde.</L>
<L>" We er pouer freres, &thorn;at haf nought on to lyue,</L>
<L>" In stede of messengeres, saue condite vs gyue.</L>
<L>" &thorn;orgh &thorn;i lond to go in &thorn;in anowrie,</L>
<L>" &thorn;at non vs robbe ne slo, for &thorn;i curteysie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE respons were redy, &thorn;at Philip did &thorn;am bere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio Regis Franci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>A knyght fulle anerty gaf &thorn;am &thorn;is ansuere.</L>
<L>" <NOTE PLACE="foot">Lour dist ke les coue|naunce fet de sca [<I>sive</I> sa] en arere, Sunt tenuz en touz poyntz, saunz rien violer, Par le Rey de Fraunce, &amp; par luy. xii. peer, Et par le Reis En|glays e luy mariner Rumpi sunt couenaunce par tere &amp; par mere. Paroles ke sunt dites, de teres resigner, Des homages rendre, de seygnour refuser, Le Reis Phelipp resceyt, en meme la maner, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e conantz &thorn;at wer sette in nessh &amp; in hard,</L>
<L>" Kyng Philip has &thorn;am gette fro &thorn;at tyme hiderward.</L>
<L>" Bot &thorn;orgh &thorn;e kyng Inglis, &amp; &thorn;orh his maryners,</L>
<L>" &thorn;e conantz ere gan mis, in many stedes sers.</L>
<L>" Homage vp to &yogh;eld, lordschip to forsake,</L>
<L>" So Philip it wild, on &thorn;at wise we it take,</L>
<L>" As &yogh;e haf mad present, &thorn;e kyng vouches it saue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e messengers went, condute he did &thorn;am haue,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei hed redy wendyng, at Douer &thorn;ei toke lond,</L>
<L>&amp; sped &thorn;am to &thorn;e kyng, at London &thorn;ei him fond.
<PB REF="00000489.tif" N="261"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHAN Edward &thorn;er respons knowe, &amp; what &thorn;ei ment,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Peticio Ed|wardi ad barones.</NOTE></L>
<L>For clerkis &amp; barons son after he sent,</L>
<L>&amp; eft &thorn;am alle biforn teld &thorn;am alle &thorn;e chance,</L>
<L>How Gascoyn was lorn &thorn;orgh &thorn;er gilerie of France.</L>
<L>" Withouten help of &yogh;ow wyn it may I nouht,</L>
<L>" To saue &thorn;e londe's prow, to ask &thorn;is haf I &thorn;ouht:</L>
<L>" I ask half &thorn;e godes to haf of &thorn;e clergie,</L>
<L>" &amp; saue &yogh;our o&thorn;er fodes, to maynten my partie.</L>
<L>" Marchant &amp; burgeis to &thorn;e sext be laid.</L>
<L>He wild on no weis, &thorn;at it were geyn said.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons alle plenere in &thorn;e tende him seised,</L>
<L>So in &thorn;at self &yogh;ere it suld be payed &amp; reised.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e lond fulle hard was sette in &thorn;at ilk laying,</L>
<L>No &thorn;eles we ere in dette, at nede to help &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&amp; praye God for his right bo&thorn;e foles &amp; wys,</L>
<L>To saue him day &amp; nyght ageyn his enmys.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ei &thorn;at tyme had wonnen, &amp; venquised Sir Edward,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;orgh &thorn;is lond wonnen Normanz &amp; Pikard,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kirke of Inglond fulle ille &thorn;ei suld haf said,</L>
<L>&amp; had alle gon to schond, &thorn;e clergie ille bisted,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer bisshop, ne person, ne riche perronendere,</L>
<L>Ne erle, ne baron, ne knyght, ne squiere,</L>
<L>Ne burgeis of cite, merchant ne Frankeleyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer had bien fre, bot seruage leyn.</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;is &thorn;raldam, &thorn;at now on Inglond es,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh Normanz it cam, bondage &amp; destres,</L>
<L>&amp; if &thorn;ei now powere had of vs, wite &yogh;e wele,</L>
<L>Streiter we suld be lad bi &thorn;e tend dele.
<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="262"></L>
<L>Better vs is to giue, &amp; saue vs fro disceite,</L>
<L>&thorn;an with our fo men lyue in seruage so streite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE kyng &thorn;is pay has nomen, &amp; in cofres has,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De adven|tu Antonii.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sir Antoyn home is comen fro Almayn &thorn;er he was.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Deuelyn don has his endyng,</L>
<L>Sir Hugh gode hele is in, &amp; comen is to &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e ersdeken of Richemunde to &thorn;e pape is sent,</L>
<L>Sir Jon of Crawecombe with him is he went,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape forto telle &thorn;e sothe how it was,</L>
<L>&amp; in his dome to duelle, who did most trespas.</L>
<L>Toward Portesmouthe &thorn;e kyng fast drouh,</L>
<L>To werre as he wele couthe, he ordeynd whilk &amp; how,</L>
<L>First to be cheftayn, to Gascoyn forto go,</L>
<L>Sir Jon of Bretayn formast on of &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Sir Jon Sayn Jon he knewe wele &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Robert de Tiptoft, e son fiz aynez, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Roberd Tiptoft an o&thorn;er, on his sonne salle with him be;</L>
<L>Sir Laurence of Sauueye, also he was &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei aryued alle o weye at Burgh sur la Mare.</L>
<L>&thorn;iderward <NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Count de Nichole fu laun|dreit aprestez, Par maunde|ment le Reis le Count est retournez, La resoun pur quay, vous dirray escotez, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>as als he went, Sir Henry &thorn;e Lacie,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng eft for him sent, I salle telle &yogh;ow whi.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN Wales is a schreward to werre risen on,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Resmira|duk iterum movet bel|lum in Wal|lia.</NOTE></L>
<L>For he wend Sir Edward ouer &thorn;e se wer gon,
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="263"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Snawedoun ad saysie, cum ses heritez, Se fet apel|lere prence, par noun de pa|rentez, <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE>Snowdon gan he hald, als his heritage,</L>
<L>&amp; prince &thorn;ei him cald, &thorn;at bastard outrage.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis men he slouh, &amp; robbed alle &thorn;er &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;e castelles doun drouh, &thorn;at longed tille &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;is ti&thorn;ing com him eft, how Wale him bitrayed,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor is Gascoyn left, &amp; &thorn;erat werre delayed.</L>
<L>Schortly forto say, to <NOTE PLACE="foot">Et de Souz [<I>vel</I> South] Snawe|doun en Gales est entrez, En Abreconwaye chastel affer|mez, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Snowdon has he tight,</L>
<L>&amp; in Abretonway a castelle vp he dight,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er he held his &yogh;ole with fele of his baronage,</L>
<L>Of Gascoyn was dole &thorn;at he left &thorn;at viage.</L>
<L>Fro &yogh;ole vnto &thorn;e Pask werred Sir Edward,</L>
<L>Grete trauaile it askes, colde &amp; greuance hard.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh pite mykelle he les, &amp; reufulhed of herte,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e folk he with him ches wer first auster &amp; smerte,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Wales mot haf bien wonnen, if he had done &thorn;am tille,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;orgh out Gascoyn ronnen, if he had don &thorn;am skille.</L>
<L>If he had don so wele, gyuen &thorn;am alle &thorn;er lyue,</L>
<L>&thorn;er wynnyng ilk a dele, &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot reyme &amp; gyue,</L>
<L>Holdand in warantie, of him &amp; of his heyres,</L>
<L>Chef of &thorn;at seignorie to &thorn;am &amp; to &thorn;eirs,</L>
<L>For soth Wales had bien wonne at &thorn;at dynt,</L>
<L>&amp; Gascoyn had bien seen wonne &thorn;at is tynt.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e pes to haue, he mad so long a trayne,</L>
<L>&thorn;e knyghtes mot &thorn;am not saue, &thorn;at were in Aquitayne.</L>
<L>For Charles wan Riouns, &thorn;orgh fight had he &thorn;e pris,</L>
<L>&amp; fettred &thorn;e Gascouns led &thorn;am to Paris.
<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="264"></L>
<L>Saynt Seuere was &yogh;olden &thorn;orgh force in couenant,</L>
<L>Burdeus wild &thorn;ei no wolden, had Frankis &amp; Normant.</L>
<L>&thorn;an &yogh;ede ilk a Pikard, scornand &amp; makand ryme,</L>
<L>Lorn is now Edward, Gascoyn in alle his tyme.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Inglis wend haf help of &thorn;e kyng of Aragoune,</L>
<L>Of Edward had &thorn;ei mad &yogh;elp, &amp; his bro&thorn;er Edmoun,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e erle of Lincoln, &thorn;ei wend &thorn;ei suld com &thorn;ider,</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;ei were forholn, &amp; failed &thorn;am alle togider.</L>
<L>To while our Inglis alle wer in tribulacioun,</L>
<L>Wales (wo mot it falle!) ros eft &thorn;orgh tresoun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Mad|dok &amp; Morgan.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot after &thorn;e Pask tide &thorn;e kyng so on &thorn;am ran,</L>
<L>Maugre alle &thorn;er pride, Snowdon on &thorn;am wan.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en in Angleseie did set his pauilloun,</L>
<L>Romand in his weie, cried pes in ilk a toun.</L>
<L>Tille alle &thorn;at pes wild haue, pes he wille gyue.</L>
<L>&amp; lyue &amp; lymme suld saue &thorn;o, &thorn;at in pes wild lyue.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e erle of Gloucestre so had him misborn,</L>
<L>Southwales, &thorn;at was his estre, &thorn;orgh Morgan had he lorn.</L>
<L>I ne wote whi it was bituex him &amp; Morgan,</L>
<L>Ne how com &thorn;at trespas, &thorn;at Morgan on him ran.</L>
<L>Tille Edward our kyng wild Morgan not be gode,</L>
<L>Bot Maddok mad werryng, &amp; cald him prince of blode.</L>
<L>Was taken &thorn;orgh consaile, &amp; led to Londoun,</L>
<L>Now is Maddok wro&thorn;erhaile don in &thorn;er prisoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh Edward long trayne Gascoyn is born doun,</L>
<L>Non defendes his chayne, bot only Bayoun.</L>
<L>If he bi tyme had gon &thorn;orh help of his Gascons,</L>
<L>&thorn;er suld haf standen non, Philip no Charlons,
<PB REF="00000493.tif" N="265"></L>
<L>He suld haf wonnen Saynt Seuer &amp; Rions,</L>
<L>Tolouse &amp; Tolousan, Burdeus with his somons.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WALES wo! &thorn;e be, &thorn;e fende &thorn;e confound.</L>
<L>Scotland whi ne mot I se be sonken to Helle ground?</L>
<L>Was neuer in &thorn;am both terme set ne stounde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Wallia &amp; Scocia, &amp; falsitate eorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei discorded wroth, &thorn;e pes tion in &thorn;am founde.</L>
<L>In Wales said beforn alle day is mischance,</L>
<L>&amp; Gascoyn now is lorn, &thorn;orgh treson of France.</L>
<L>What did Jon Baliol, &thorn;at Edward did auance,</L>
<L>Bot falsly, as a fole, bigan a disceyuance?</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh conseile of hise he sent vnto &thorn;e pape,</L>
<L>&amp; controued a quaintise, a new falsnes did schape,</L>
<L>&amp; said Scotlond suld be, &thorn;orgh right &amp; olde setnesse,</L>
<L>Holden of his se, &amp; of non els &thorn;at es,</L>
<L>&amp; Edward of Inglond, &thorn;orgh force &amp; myght,</L>
<L>In his homage him bond, ageyn his wille &amp; right.</L>
<L>"We ask &yogh;ow grace of &thorn;is, assoyle him of &thorn;at othe,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at he did maugre his, to wrong was him lothe,</L>
<L>"Bot he mot quitely go in world where he fore,</L>
<L>"&amp; frely passe him fro, fro whom &thorn;at he to suore.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le pape Celestine trop desauise Assolt le Rey descoce par lettre enbulle, <I>Gall.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e pape Celestyn, of non avisement,</L>
<L>With letter bulled fyn assoyled to Scotlond sent.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;is bulle was brouht home bi messengres,</L>
<L>A vileyine &thorn;ami &thorn;ouht, to mak &thorn;am duze pers,
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="266"></L>
<L>Desherite Edward of alle his seignorie,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><Q><L>Pur le grant honour, qe Edward le sene</L><L>Fist a Jon Baliol, tel est la bounte.</L><L>Est reguerdone.:</L><L>Dount le Reys Edward</L><L>Du Reys Jon musard</L><L>La gest auaunt parle, <I>MSS. Gall.</I>:</L><L>Descoce seyt cum poet</L><L>Parfourmir nous estoet</L></Q></NOTE>Of Jon Baliol musard suilk was his curteysie.</L>
<L>a wikked bounte.:</L>
<L>For Edward gode dede</L>
<L>&thorn;e Baliol did him mede</L>
<L>a Maddok &thorn;er left we.:</L>
<L>Turne we ageyn to rede</L>
<L>&amp; on our geste to spede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Morgan &yogh;olden, &amp; Maddok he bendes,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng comen to London, bi consail of his frendes.</L>
<L>Tuo Cardenalles of Rome &thorn;e pape hider sent,</L>
<L>To Paris bo&thorn;e &thorn;ei come, to &thorn;e parlement,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei said luf to make, &thorn;e pape wild entermet,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non ageyn o&thorn;er take, tille tyme &thorn;at he had set.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise cardinals so bond Edward &amp; Philip,</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er suld werri bi lond, no in water bi schip,</L>
<L>Bot hold &thorn;am stone stille in pes at &thorn;er cuntre,</L>
<L>&thorn;at nou&thorn;er of &thorn;am did ille, &thorn;e pape wild justise be.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise kynges stille &thorn;ei left at &thorn;e pape's request,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Normanz com now eft, &amp; mak a newe gest.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ALS pes was mad of partie &thorn;orgh cardinals &thorn;at com ouer,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Normanni fecerunt insultum ad Douere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e folk of Normundie aryued vp at Douer,
<PB REF="00000495.tif" N="267"></L>
<L>&amp; men of Caleis camen with &thorn;am wele I wene,</L>
<L>To brenne &thorn;e toun alle samen, &amp; slouh men &thorn;rittene.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wardeyn herd it telle of &thorn;e castelle biside,</L>
<L>A monke of a Celle bare him wele &thorn;at tide.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei sette so wele &thorn;er wardes, &amp; stifly samen stode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Normanz &amp; Pikardes left bo&thorn;e hede hode.</L>
<L>A monke &thorn;er was I wene, he slouh tuenti,</L>
<L>&thorn;er hedes quyte &amp; clene, he laid &thorn;am bi &amp; bi.</L>
<L>A monk was of &thorn;at celle, &thorn;ei slouh him danz Thomas,</L>
<L>A saynt he men telle, with Normanz slayn he was.</L>
<L>I wene &thorn;at &thorn;ei &yogh;ede, mykelle not &thorn;ei wonnen,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Frankis &thorn;at mot spede, to schippes fast ronnen.</L>
<L>After alle &thorn;is fare, &thorn;e cardinals went &thorn;er weie,</L>
<L>What ansuere &thorn;ei bare, &thorn;e so&thorn;e can I not say.</L>
<L>No &thorn;e les of fele &thorn;is was &thorn;e comon sawe,</L>
<L>&thorn;er folk alle sulle &thorn;e spele, &amp; fro werryng &thorn;am drawe</L>
<L>Edward &amp; Philip, &amp; late &thorn;e folk ouer wend</L>
<L>&amp; passage haf in schip, to londes forto lend.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e sufferance of pes, tille &thorn;e acorde wer ent,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis &thorn;erto ches, if Almanz wild consent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO while &thorn;ise cardinals trauaild for &thorn;e pes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De tradici|one Turbe|uile.</NOTE></L>
<L>Here of a wikhals how he bigan a res.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Thomas de Turbeuyle, qe a Riouns fu pris, En taunt ad parle al prouost de Parys, Ke [<I>vel</I> Qe] fet ad son homage, &amp; hostages mys Les. ii. fiz en garde, &amp; sure|ment promys, Aler en En|gleterre, espyer le pays, Et dire al Reis Edward, qil veent futyfs, Eschape de pri|soun par my ses enemys, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Thomas Turbeuile was taken at Rions,</L>
<L>At Paris he duelte a while in hold with o&thorn;er prisons.
<PB REF="00000496.tif" N="268"></L>
<L>To &thorn;e prouest he spak, &amp; bed him his homage,</L>
<L>His oth &thorn;at he ne brak, he left in his ostage</L>
<L>&amp; hise childre tuo, &amp; suore him his leaute,</L>
<L>Tille Inglond suld he go, to spie ilk a cuntre,</L>
<L>Tille &thorn;e kyng suld he say, &thorn;at he of prison fled,</L>
<L>He wist non sikerer way, for socour tille him sped.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prouest als tite to Thomas &thorn;erfor him bond,</L>
<L>&amp; granted him with scrite tuo hundreth pounde of lond,</L>
<L>&amp; Thomas trouht him plight, &amp; suore on &thorn;e messe,</L>
<L>Of Inglond alle &thorn;e right, &amp; Wales more &amp; lesse,</L>
<L>&amp; of Scotlond alle &thorn;e men, &thorn;at were of pris,</L>
<L>Suld enclyn &amp; falle to Philip fitz Lowys.</L>
<L>Now gos &thorn;is Thomas, his treson to purchace,</L>
<L>Bot<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Id est</I>, lo! how.</NOTE> how Edward was warned &thorn;orgh<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Adde</I>, grace.</NOTE> Gode's.</L>
<L>Thomas tille Inglond com to kyng &amp; said,</L>
<L>Bi nyght he skapid of bond of prison &thorn;er he was laid,</L>
<L>For his luf to haue, suilk perille on him drouh,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he vouched saue for his luf wele inouh.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng tille him &thorn;erfore did grete curteysie,</L>
<L>Wynnyng for his lore he gaf him largelie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW gos Turbeuile, &amp; serchis day bi day,</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e kyng a gile, how &amp; whan he may.</L>
<L>He serchis alle &thorn;e coste, where were best comyng,</L>
<L>To bring in Frankis oste, forto tak our kyng.
<PB REF="00000497.tif" N="269"></L>
<L>Whan he had serched alle, &amp; knew ilk a coste,</L>
<L>His man with &thorn;e cardinalle he sent to &thorn;e prouoste.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prouest mad grete joye for &thorn;at ilk sond,</L>
<L>It turnes bot tille &thorn;e bo&thorn;e, if Gode's grace may stond.</L>
<L>&thorn;e clerke &thorn;at wrote &thorn;e lettere to Thomas Turbeuile,</L>
<L>He &thorn;ouht forto do bettere, &thorn;an kyng Edward to gile,</L>
<L>Tille on &thorn;at was priue &thorn;e kynge's conseiloure,</L>
<L>&thorn;e clerk lete him alle se &thorn;e dede of &thorn;at traytoure.</L>
<L>Whan Thomas was perceyued, his lettres wer away,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's courte he weyued, for he dred to deie.</L>
<L>A seruant &thorn;er was, &thorn;at wist whan Thomas fled,</L>
<L>Fulle sone after Thomas better pas he sped.</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e &thorn;rid day, at a toun hamelet,</L>
<L>Thomas was his pray, as he to mete was set.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW Thomas taken es, &amp; to London brouht:</L>
<L>Grete was &thorn;e wikkednes, &thorn;at T. had wrouht.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e justis&eacute; he said, he wild speke with &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>Of his traytours neid, to warn him of a &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>T. &thorn;erfor was don to prison eft ageyn,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng als son &thorn;e sent bode certeyn.</L>
<L>At Malmesbirie &thorn;e kyng with his moder was,</L>
<L>Whan him com tiyng of Turbuile Thomas.</L>
<L>He teld &thorn;e kyng ilk dele, Thomas wild speke with him,</L>
<L>&amp; warn him he suld wele, whilk wer his traytours grym.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Consilium matris Re|gis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; His moder Helianore abated &thorn;er grete bale.</L>
<L>"Sonne," said scho, "neuer more trowe &yogh;e traytours tale,</L>
<L>"Suilk traytours als he for hate wille mak a lie,</L>
<L>"&thorn;orgh &thorn;e whilk mot be vengeance &amp; felonie.
<PB REF="00000498.tif" N="270"></L>
<L>"Sonne, on my blissyng, trowe &thorn;ou not his sawe,</L>
<L>"Bot late him haf endyng, als a traytour &thorn;orgh lawe.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng wrote his lettere agayn to &thorn;e Justise,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wist non bettere, bot do him to Juwise,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at he has said he don vnder fote</L>
<L>Tille &thorn;is werld be, it it &yogh;it no tyme to mote.</L>
<L>&para; Now &thorn;e Turbeuile has his jugement,</L>
<L>Drawen is a while on London pauiment,</L>
<L>&amp; si&thorn;en was he hanged as thef for treson,</L>
<L>Faire grace Edward fanged in his tribulacion.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is &thorn;is wikhals dede &thorn;orgh vengeance,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e Cardinals gon er in to France.</L>
<L>Oft for &thorn;e pes with Philip mad bergayn,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;at conseil ches &thorn;e kyng of Almayn,</L>
<L>Clerkis bituex &thorn;am sent hidir to Edward,</L>
<L>What &thorn;er conseil ment, &thorn;e distance so hard.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wrath was so grete bituex &thorn;ise kynges tuo,</L>
<L>Unnethis acorde &thorn;ei schete, bot &thorn;us with mykelle wo.</L>
<L>&para; To Kaunbray suld &thorn;ei send men &thorn;at were of Gode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er greuance kend, &thorn;e distance vnderstode.</L>
<L>Clerkis &amp; lewed men suld deme at Kaunbray,</L>
<L>&amp; trie &thorn;e soth &amp; ken, in whom &thorn;e wrong lay:</L>
<L>To what manere of pes &thorn;e parties wille descend,</L>
<L>&amp; who &thorn;e wrong first ches, &thorn;at partie suld amend.</L>
<L>To &thorn;o ilk resons &thorn;e Inglis wer assent,</L>
<L>Bisshopes &amp; barons were gode of &thorn;o &thorn;at went.
<PB REF="00000499.tif" N="271"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO while our men were out, for to mak &thorn;e pes,</L>
<L>Men of armes stout &thorn;e kyng to Gascoyn ches.</L>
<L>Sir Edmound his bro&thorn;er &thorn;e first was redy,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Milicia versus A|quitaniam.</NOTE></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Counte de Nichole, oue tote [<I>vel</I> of tut] son me|nage, Sire William de Vescy, chiualer pruz &amp; sage, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Of Lyncoln &thorn;e erle a no&thorn;er, Sir Henry &thorn;e Lacy,</L>
<L>Sir William &thorn;e Vescy wys man &amp; bold baroun,</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er lordes wor&thorn;i, &thorn;at were of gode renoun.</L>
<L>Sex &amp; tuenty baners of Inglond alder best,</L>
<L>Of armes &thorn;at knewe &thorn;e maners, to werre were alle prest.</L>
<L>&para; In Inglond were left als douhty as &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am &thorn;e kyng toke eft, to Scotlond wild he go.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic, pro</I> kyng.</NOTE> kyns withsaid, he auht him non homage,</L>
<L>Now &thorn;enkes he mak a braid, for &thorn;at grete outrage.</L>
<L>Of Marche &thorn;e first day at &thorn;e New castelle</L>
<L>Our kyng &thorn;er he lay, his purueiance so fel,</L>
<L>To Scotlond for to go, to wite whi &amp; what wise,</L>
<L>&thorn;er kyng &amp; o&thorn;er mo withsaid him his seruise.</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand &amp; tuo hundred, fourscore &amp; sexten,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Anno M<SUP>o</SUP>, CC<SUP>o</SUP>, XC<SUP>o</SUP>, <NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE>IIII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>On &thorn;e Scottes has many wondred, &thorn;at bigan his tene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SIR Roberd Roos of Werk with &thorn;e Scottis fled,</L>
<L>He set so ille his merk, &thorn;at neuer eft he ne sped.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng his castelle sesis, &amp; held &thorn;er his Pask day,</L>
<L>Him &amp; his &thorn;er esis, &amp; alle &thorn;at feste &thorn;er lay.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis did first mys, &thorn;ei wakend alle &thorn;at wouh,</L>
<L>Tuo schippis of our Inglis, &thorn;e folk &thorn;er in &thorn;ei slouh.</L>
<L>Sir Edward herd it telle, &amp; dight him to Berwik,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De capci|one Berwik per totum die Veneris.</NOTE></L>
<L>No stounde wille he duelle, bot seged it also quik.
<PB REF="00000500.tif" N="272"></L>
<L>What did &thorn;an Sir Edward? pere he had non like,</L>
<L>Opon his stede bayard first he wan &thorn;e dike.</L>
<L>In Pask weke it was, &thorn;e Friday &thorn;ei it wan,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e non tyme felle &thorn;is cas, &thorn;at slayn was ilk a man,</L>
<L>&thorn;at were in Berwik<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>'Tis only</I> four thousand, <I>according to the French Copies.</I></NOTE> fourti &thorn;ousand &amp; mo,</L>
<L>Was non of &thorn;am left quik, bot alle to dede &yogh;ede &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Inglis sanz faile bot o knyght dede I wote,</L>
<L>Sir Richard of Cornwaile, a Flemmyng him smote.</L>
<L>Right out of &thorn;e rede haule schot was a quarelle,</L>
<L>Fire &thorn;ei fest on it alle, &amp; brent it &thorn;at it felle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wardeyn of &thorn;e castelle sauh &thorn;er chance fulle hard,</L>
<L>Untille mercy he felle, &amp; &yogh;alde him tille Edward.</L>
<L>William of Duglas &yogh;alde him also tite.</L>
<L>Symon Freselle &thorn;er was, he wild haf don dispite.</L>
<L>He wend haf had fulle light, Edward at his wille,</L>
<L>Bot, &thorn;anked be God alle myght, his prisoun leues he stille.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of &thorn;e Marche Patrik, lord of next cuntre,</L>
<L>He did no maner wik, &thorn;e kyng gaf him his gre.</L>
<L>Sir Gilberd Umfreyvile wholom was with &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>Sir Robert Brus &thorn;at while ageyn him did no &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Golde &amp; siluer &thorn;ei fonde, &amp; o&thorn;er metalle plente,</L>
<L>Now has &thorn;e Baliol a stounde lorn issu &amp; entre,</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;e fairest toun, &thorn;at was in his pouste,</L>
<L>Of ricchesse it had renoun, &thorn;at felle to a cite.</L>
<L>Now is Berwik born doun, abaist is &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L>Jon gete &thorn;i coroun, &thorn;ou losis &thorn;i dignite.</L>
<L>Now dos Edward dike Berwik brode &amp; long,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ei bad him pike, &amp; scorned him in &thorn;er song.
<PB REF="00000501.tif" N="273"></L>
<L>Pikit him, &amp; dikit him, on scorne said he,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Couwe.</NOTE></L>
<L>He pikes &amp; dikes in length, as him likes, how best it may be,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou has for &thorn;i pikyng, mykille ille likyng, &thorn;e so&thorn;e is to se,</L>
<L>Without any lesyng, alle is &thorn;i he&thorn;ing, fallen opon &thorn;e.</L>
<L>For scatred er &thorn;i Scottis, &amp; hodred in &thorn;er hottes, neuer &thorn;ei ne the.</L>
<L>Right als I rede, &thorn;ei tombled in Tuede, &thorn;at woned bi &thorn;e se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Edward left Berwik forto dike,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Fecit fossas circa Ber|wik.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis er risen eft, Inglond to bisuike.</L>
<L>&thorn;e gadred &thorn;am an oste, fourti &thorn;ousand &amp; mo,</L>
<L>&thorn;at com bi an o&thorn;er coste, &thorn;e Inglis forto slo.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise were hede &amp; meste, &thorn;at led &thorn;at meyne,</L>
<L>Rosse &amp; Meneteste, Assetelle &thorn;ise erles &thorn;re.</L>
<L>Corbrigge is a toun, &thorn;e brent it whan &thorn;ei cam,</L>
<L>Tuo hous of religioun, <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>They commonly call it</I>, Lanercost.</NOTE>Leynertofte &amp; Hexham.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei chaced &thorn;e chanons out, &thorn;er godes bare away,</L>
<L>&amp; robbed alle about, &thorn;e bestis tok to pray.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei had slayn &amp; brent, robbed toun &amp; feld,</L>
<L>To Dunbar alle &thorn;ei went, als &thorn;er vnhap wild.</L>
<L>&thorn;e <NOTE PLACE="foot">Le chastel ount pris, estendent pauyllouns Al count de la Marche, estoy|ent les mesouns, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>castelle sone &thorn;ei toke, &amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ar pauilloun</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle Patrik men schoke, it was his owen donjoun.</L>
<L>Edward herd it say, &thorn;at Dunbar was so taken,</L>
<L>His folk was sone on away, with sege to hold &thorn;am waken.</L>
<L>&para; In alle &thorn;is ilk goyng so com &thorn;e Cardinalle<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Car|dinali.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro Kaunbray to &thorn;e kyng with ansuere of alle,
<PB REF="00000502.tif" N="274"></L>
<L>&amp; fro &thorn;e kyng of France here after salle &yogh;e here,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise men mette him o chance, &amp; com with him in fere.</L>
<L>Sir Amys of Saueye, an erle of grete renoun,</L>
<L>An o&thorn;er com in his weye, Sir Otes de Grauntsoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise fro Cipres cam, &amp; tille our kyng &thorn;am sped,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e Sarazins Acres nam, passand away &thorn;ei fled.</L>
<L>How of &thorn;ise ilk traytours, &thorn;at holy kirke had schent,</L>
<L>Felle misauentours, or &thorn;ei fro Dunbard went.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e moneth of May at Berwik was Edward,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De ombu|stione Hex|ham &amp; La|nertoft per Scottos.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e first Tuesday com him ti&thorn;inges hard,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e erles of Scotlond had reysed baner oloft,</L>
<L>&amp; brent &amp; slayn with hond Exham &amp; Lanertoft,</L>
<L>&amp; Dunbar had &thorn;ei seised, &thorn;at standes on &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle Patrik was fesed, &thorn;at tyme &thorn;er in was he.</L>
<L>Edward also quik sent &thorn;e erle of Warenne,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e erle of Warwik, an oste did &thorn;am bikenne.</L>
<L>A douhty erle in stours, Sir Hugh Despensere,</L>
<L>Barons &amp; vavasours, knyghtes &amp; squiere,</L>
<L>&amp; fote folk inowe, &thorn;at wele couth of barete,</L>
<L>To Dunbar &thorn;ei &thorn;am drowe, &thorn;e sege &thorn;er to sette,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De religa|cione Scot|torum apud Dunbare.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ei tirede &thorn;am to kest smertly to &thorn;e assaute,</L>
<L>&thorn;er to &thorn;ei were alle prest, in &thorn;am was no defaute.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis &thorn;at were with inne, &thorn;e hoped of socoure,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Baliol suld &thorn;am wynne out of &thorn;at soioure.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Scottis now &thorn;ei &thorn;enk of gile &amp; quaintise,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ei mot do a blenk tille Edward &amp; hise.</L>
<L>A knyght was &thorn;am among, Sir Richard Seward,</L>
<L>Tille our faith was he long, &amp; with kyng Edward.
<PB REF="00000503.tif" N="275"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Cil les vint &amp; dist, qe mult treuolenter Les fra le chastel rendre, si il voillent graunter Treis iours de re|spit, qil [<I>vel</I> ke il] pussent conseyller Luy Reis de Baliol &amp; lour estat maunder. Et si cel houre ne veygne le sege remuer, Le chastel rendrount saunz plus par la targer. Hostage par taunt i mette, &amp; fet nouncier Al hoste des Escotz en meme la maner, Com vous orrez apres, le fet recorder, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Tille our men he com tite, &amp; said, "&thorn;e Scottis wilde</L>
<L>"&thorn;re dayes haf respite, &amp; &thorn;an &thorn;e castelle &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>"To &thorn;e Baliol suld &thorn;ei send, &thorn;er castelle to rescue,</L>
<L>"Bi &thorn;at bot he vs mend with for &yogh;ow to remue,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e castelle &yogh;e salle haue, without any delay.</L>
<L>Ostegers &yogh;e to haue our Inglis toke &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>A messengere &thorn;ei sent, to telle alle &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> manere.</NOTE> maners.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Scottis he went, &amp; said as &yogh;e may here.</L>
<L>&para; He com to Baliol Jon, &amp; tille alle &thorn;e oste,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nuncius venit ad Regem Scottorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;am euer ilkon, he spak &thorn;ise wordes boste,</L>
<L>Right as Sir Richard tauht him forto say.</L>
<L>"&thorn;i men er biseged hard in Dunbar with grete aye,</L>
<L>"Whan &thorn;ei fro Ingland cam, Dunbar &thorn;e toke tille hold,</L>
<L>"To Berwik ti&thorn;ing nam, &amp; tille Sir Edward told.</L>
<L>"Edward &thorn;ider sent folk a grete partie,</L>
<L>"Doun Sir Richard went, &amp; spak to &thorn;am lufly,</L>
<L>"Many of &thorn;am he knewe, so fair spak &amp; so suete.</L>
<L>"For &thorn;re days trewe &thorn;e Inglis him hete.</L>
<L>"Whan our company wist of trewe certeyn,</L>
<L>"Tille &yogh;ow &thorn;ei bad me hie, ilka knyght &amp; sueyn,</L>
<L>"&thorn;is bodword to telle, vn to &thorn;e treus is hote,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &yogh;e ne rest ne duelle, for &yogh;it no man wote.
<PB REF="00000504.tif" N="276"></L>
<L>"To morn in &thorn;e none tide, whan &thorn;ei ere at &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ider &yogh;e alle salle ride, a faire pray salle &yogh;e gete.</L>
<L>"Whan &thorn;ei of &thorn;e castelle se, &thorn;at &yogh;e com so stoute,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at ere of wille fulle fre, to issue on &thorn;am oute.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e Inglis wille not wene, &thorn;at &yogh;e be comand now,</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;o &yogh;e salle mak clene, lap &thorn;am bituex &yogh;ow,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;ei neuer eft rise, to do &yogh;ow more trauaile,</L>
<L>"I knowe non o&thorn;erwise, what way may &yogh;ow auale.</L>
<L>"Armes now &yogh;ow alle, &thorn;at non him withdrawe.</L>
<L>"How it may best falle, I haf &yogh;ow said &thorn;e sawe.</L>
<L>&para; "Whan &yogh;e haf &thorn;e pris of &yogh;our enmys, non salle &yogh;e saue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Couwe.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Smyte with suerd in hand, alle Northumberland with right salle &yogh;e haue,</L>
<L>"&amp; Inglond &yogh;it alle, for werre salle be tint for &thorn;is drede.</L>
<L>"Scotte neuer bigan vnto Inglis man to do so douhty dede.</L>
<L>"&thorn;er on &thorn;at grene, &thorn;at kynrede kene, gadred als &thorn;e gayte,</L>
<L>"Right, als I wene, on som was it sene, &thorn;er &thorn;e bit bayte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOR &thorn;is manne's sawe, &thorn;e route of rascaile,</L>
<L>Tille armes gan drawe, &amp; dight &thorn;am to bataile.</L>
<L>Richard &thorn;at first gaf rede to &thorn;at consaile,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De multi|tudine Scot|torum ad bellum pr&aelig;paran|cium, &amp; de ruina eorumapud Dunbar.</NOTE></L>
<L>He sauh &thorn;am rif &amp; raf comand ilka taile.</L>
<L>Also sui&thorn;e he &yogh;ede doun to &thorn;e Inglis men,</L>
<L>"I se an oste to spede comand bi batailes ten,</L>
<L>"&amp; &yogh;it me &thorn;ink &thorn;er mo, &thorn;at er neghand nehi.</L>
<L>"If &yogh;e wille I wille go, &amp; do &thorn;am hold o drehi.</L>
<L>"Nay," said &thorn;e Inglis men, "we trost not on &thorn;i tunge,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e castelle we salle biken Sir Umfrey Boun &thorn;e &yogh;on&yogh;e,
<PB REF="00000505.tif" N="277"></L>
<L>"&thorn;at non salle passe out, nou&thorn;er &thorn;e ne &thorn;ou.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis armed stout toward &thorn;e Scottis drouh,</L>
<L>&thorn;er stedes broched &thorn;ei fast, &thorn;at myght formast he &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Baliol was agast, for he stode tille no dede,</L>
<L>For so&thorn;e at &thorn;e first, in poudre as dos &thorn;e chaf,</L>
<L>Fleand fast &thorn;ei &thorn;rist, &amp; fled bo&thorn;e rif &amp; raf.</L>
<L>Was neuer non of &thorn;am, &thorn;at bode wik no gode,</L>
<L>Bot Sir Patrik Graham a while to bataile stode.</L>
<L>He was a man douhty, bot slayn he was fulle sone,</L>
<L>Ten &thorn;ousand &amp; fyfti &amp; four &thorn;er were so done.</L>
<L>Was neuer in no bataile so mykelle folk misferd,</L>
<L>With so litelle trauaile, &thorn;at man sauh ne of herd.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Scottis had no grace, to spede in &thorn;er space, for to mend &thorn;er nisse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Couwe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ei filed &thorn;er face, &thorn;at died in &thorn;at place, &thorn;e Inglis rymed &thorn;is.</L>
<L>"Oure fote folk put &thorn;am in &thorn;e polk, &amp; nakned &thorn;er nages,</L>
<L>"Bi no way herd I neuer say of prester pages,</L>
<L>"Purses to pike, robis to rike, &amp; in dike &thorn;am schonne,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou wiffin Scotte of Abrethin, kotte is &thorn;i honne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> thise.</NOTE>SHISE erles &thorn;at I of red, &thorn;at in &thorn;e castelle were,</L>
<L>Sauh &thorn;er folk not sped, bot slayn alle &thorn;er here.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De ruina Scottorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan our men out camen to &thorn;o &thorn;at left &thorn;er stille,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei com out alle samen, &amp; &yogh;ald &thorn;am tille our wille.</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e to&thorn;er dai Edward &thorn;ider cam,</L>
<L>&thorn;e prisons of &thorn;er pray alle &thorn;at euer &thorn;ei nam,</L>
<L>Were brouht him bifore, &thorn;re erles &thorn;re barons,</L>
<L>&amp; mo be fiue score kynghtes &amp; lordes of touns,
<PB REF="00000506.tif" N="278"></L>
<L>&thorn;ise wer in his wardes, &amp; auht &amp; tuenti mo,</L>
<L>Tuo clerkes tuo Pikardes &yogh;it were among &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e toure of London &thorn;e &thorn;re erles were sent,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e barons bondon also &thorn;ider went.</L>
<L>Tille o&thorn;er castels about &thorn;ei sent tueye &amp; tueye</L>
<L>In anens for doute, ilk on on his hakneye.</L>
<L>In kartes o&thorn;er were sent with anens on &thorn;er fete.</L>
<L>&thorn;us in sorow it ent, &thorn;er gamen turned to grete.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh out Inglond men said of &thorn;am schame,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ei were in bond men scorned &thorn;am bi name.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Scottis<NOTE PLACE="foot">See my Glossary to Robert of Gloucester's Chronicle, p. 737.</NOTE> I telle for sottis, &amp; wrecchis vnwar,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Couwe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Unsele dyntis to dele &thorn;am drouh to Dunbar.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is tyme to telle of &thorn;e duze pers,</L>
<L>&thorn;at in Scotlond duelle, wille mak &thorn;er parti fers.</L>
<L>&yogh;it held &thorn;e kyng of France Gascoyn with outrage,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at mischance of Blanche mariage.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at abatement he chalenges it &thorn;orgh right,</L>
<L>Edward &thorn;idir had sent many a hardy knyght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at while &thorn;ei were werand in Gascoyn euer ilkon,</L>
<L>&thorn;e clergi of Scotland egged &thorn;er kyng Jon.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Clero Scoci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>His barons did also for &thorn;e comon prow,</L>
<L>To France suld he go &thorn;e bisshop of S. Androw,</L>
<L>&thorn;er nedes forto mone, to procure an aliance</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Baliol sonne, &amp; Charles douhter of France.</L>
<L>&amp; if it myght, &thorn;at weys he brouht to certeynte,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis &amp; Franceys togider suorn suld be,
<PB REF="00000507.tif" N="279"></L>
<L>Inglond to destroye fro Tuede vnto Kent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Frankis withouten noye hauen mot &thorn;ei hent</L>
<L>In Tuede at &thorn;er wille, wan &thorn;ei wild com or go,</L>
<L>Northumberland to spille, &thorn;e folk to robbe &amp; slo.</L>
<L>Right sone afterward &thorn;e stiward of Scotland</L>
<L>Com to kyng Edward, &amp; brouht vntille his hand,</L>
<L>Erles &amp; barons, bisshopes plenerly,</L>
<L>Knyghtes, lordes of tounes, &amp; alle com to his crie.</L>
<L>Kyng Jon &amp; his sonne withouten lond or rent</L>
<L>Er now led to London, to bide &thorn;er jugement.</L>
<L>Now is Scotland hole at our kynge's wille,</L>
<L>&amp; Jon &thorn;e Baliol at London leues stille.</L>
<L>Right as Merlyn spak had Edward &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>Scotlond, als Albanack had at &thorn;e gynnyng.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Couwe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Walsh &amp; &thorn;e Irish, tille our men Inglysh, halp douhtily,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we &thorn;e Scottis had, &amp; to prison lad, &amp; com tille our crie.</L>
<L>Now es alle ent, &amp; home ere &thorn;ei went, &thorn;e Iris &amp; Wals,</L>
<L>God gyue at &thorn;e parlement, &thorn;e Scottis be alle schent, &amp; hanged bi &thorn;e hals.</L>
<L>Edward now &thorn;enk, &thorn;ei did &thorn;e a blenk, brent Hexham.</L>
<L>&thorn;e croice &amp; &thorn;e rode, brent &thorn;er it stode, or &thorn;ei &thorn;ien nam.</L>
<L>Now has &thorn;ou myght, gyf&thorn;i dome right, &thorn;er dede is wele sene,</L>
<L>Els wille &thorn;ei eft, on &thorn;o &thorn;at er left, bigynne newe tene.</L>
<L>Men may merci haue, traytour not to saue, for luf ne for awe,</L>
<L>Atteynt of traytorie, suld haf no mercie, wi&thorn; no maner lawe.</L>
<L>Jon &thorn;e Baliol, no witte was in &thorn;i pol, whan &thorn;ou folie &thorn;ouhtis,</L>
<L>To leue &thorn;e right scole, &thorn;ou did als a fole, &amp; after wrong wrouhtis.
<PB REF="00000508.tif" N="280"></L>
<L>For boule bred in<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Lege, ad fidem Codicum Gallicorum</I>, his boke, whan.</NOTE> his, whan he tynt &thorn;at he toke, alle his kyngdome,</L>
<L>For he has ouerhipped, his tippet is tipped, his tabard is tome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>PRIUE pride in pes es nettille in herbere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Exem|plum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e rose is myghtles, &thorn;er nettille spredis ouer fer.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Baliol so ferd with &thorn;e duze pers,</L>
<L>His reame, as &yogh;e herd, he lost &thorn;orgh conseilers.</L>
<L>First he was a kyng, now is he<NOTE PLACE="foot">Soiorner, <I>vel</I> soiourner, in <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE> soudioure,</L>
<L>&amp; is at o&thorn;er spendyng bonden in &thorn;e toure.</L>
<L>Edward now he wille, &thorn;at Scotlond be wele gemed,</L>
<L>&amp; streitly in skille &thorn;orgh wise men demed,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non slo ne brenne, ne eft ageyn him rise.</L>
<L>Sir Jon of Warenne he is chef justise,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Hii sunt custodes Scoci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sir Henry Percy kepes Galweye,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise tuo had baly of &thorn;is londes tueye.</L>
<L>To Berwik cam &thorn;e kynge eschekere,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et Hug de Cressyngham iloqes est Tre|sorer, Et luy Amundesham Walter est chaunceler. Ly Reis pur pees norir baunk i fist [<I>vel</I> ifet] cryer, Et ju|stices. v. la ley a gouerner. Vescountz &amp; bayliffs sunt mys a ly mester. Des En|glays qi seuent &amp; volent dreit iuger La garde est establye, si bon e [<I>vel</I> et] si enteer, Qe Flemyng ne Fraunceys des ore auera poer, &amp;c. <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Sir Hugh<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> of of Cressyngham he was chancelere,</L>
<L>Walter of Admundesham he was Tresorere.</L>
<L>For justise with him nam, to mak &thorn;e lawe clere.
<PB REF="00000509.tif" N="281"></L>
<L>Forto norise pes, his benk he did &thorn;er crie.</L>
<L>Shireues, balifes he ches, &thorn;at office cou&thorn;e guye.</L>
<L>Of Inglis men trewe, &thorn;at lufed alle &thorn;e right,</L>
<L>He mad wardeyns newe, &amp; gaf &thorn;am alle his myght,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Frankis no Flemmyng power suld non haue,</L>
<L>Bot forto selle &thorn;er &thorn;ing, merchandise to saue.</L>
<L>&thorn;at to &thorn;e pes &thorn;am toke, &amp; com vnto his mercy,</L>
<L>He did &thorn;am suere on &thorn;e boke, to com vnto his crie.</L>
<L>Homage &amp; feaute mad him with &thorn;er hand,</L>
<L>At his wille to be, bi se &amp; bi land.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;e werre bigan, &amp; kid it so couth,</L>
<L>Were taken ilk a man, &amp; sent in to &thorn;e South.</L>
<L>&para; Oure men ere in Gascoyn, to werre on &thorn;er enmys.</L>
<L>&thorn;e gode bisshop Antoyn &thorn;er he bare &thorn;e pris,</L>
<L>His dedes ere to alowe, for his hardynesse.</L>
<L>He did many on bowe in &thorn;at lond &thorn;orgh stresse,</L>
<L>His boldhede did &thorn;am wynne, &amp; com vnto his crie,</L>
<L>Were it now to gynne, we wan it not lightly.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;ise duze pers com to &thorn;e freres, &thorn;am for to schriue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Couwe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e jugement ageyn &thorn;am went, to schorte &thorn;er liue.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Kambyn hoye se teent tut coye, ne volt eyder. La sorcerye de Albanye ne put valer. Andreu se dort, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Cambinhoy beres him coy, &thorn;at fende's whelp,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Cam|binhoy.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er with craft he has &thorn;am raft, it may not help.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Trulle &thorn;e drenge on se, &thorn;ei lenge &thorn;e fendes tueye,</L>
<L>&thorn;e hold &thorn;am fer, &amp; dar no ner, &thorn;an Orkeneye.</L>
<L>Andrew is wroth, &thorn;e wax him loth, for &thorn;er pride.</L>
<L>He is &thorn;am fro, now salle &thorn;ei go, schame to betide.
<PB REF="00000510.tif" N="282"></L>
<L>&thorn;ou scabbed Scotte, &thorn;i nek &thorn;i hotte, &thorn;e deuelle it breke,</L>
<L>It salle be hard to here Edward, ageyn &thorn;e speke.</L>
<L>He salle &thorn;e ken, our lond to bren, &amp; werre bigynne,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou getes no &thorn;ing, but &thorn;i riuelyng, to hang &thorn;er inne.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sete of &thorn;e Scone is driuen ouer Done, to London led,</L>
<L>A hard wele telle, &thorn;at bagelle &amp; belle be filchid &amp; fled.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW tels Pers, on his maners, a grete selcouth,</L>
<L>He takis witnes, &thorn;at it soth es, of Merlyn mouth.</L>
<L>A wondere were, tuo watres &thorn;er er togidir gon,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De unione Scoci&aelig; &amp; Angli&aelig;, secundum dicta Petri <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> de.</NOTE>&amp; Brid|lingtone.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; tuo kyngdames, with tuo names, now er on.</L>
<L>&thorn;e ildes aboute alle salle loute vnto &thorn;at lond,</L>
<L>Of whilk Edward is justise hard, &thorn;at so &thorn;an bond.</L>
<L>He sais he has wonen, &amp; &thorn;orgh ronnen, many landes.</L>
<L>Alle salle &thorn;ei loute tille him for doute, &amp; dede of handes.</L>
<L>He sais Scotland is in his hand for now &amp; ay,</L>
<L>At myn inwitte it is not &yogh;it alle at our fay.</L>
<L>He sais, Merlyn, in his deuyn, of him has said,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;re regions, in his bandons, salle be laid,</L>
<L>Scotland &amp; Wales, &thorn;ise er his tales, &thorn;is lond al on</L>
<L>Was Brutus wayn, &amp; cald Bretayn, first Albion.</L>
<L>I calle &thorn;erto, it is no so, &thorn;ei er o sundere.</L>
<L>&thorn;at he has spoken, it is now broken, with mykelle wondere.</L>
<L>A prophecie sais he salle die, &amp; whan he is ouere,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at day Scotlond may haf gode recouere.</L>
<L>&yogh;e haf wele herd, &thorn;e Brus Roberd was Scottis kyng,</L>
<L>Wele tuenti &yogh;ere in gode powere mayntend &thorn;at &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Als he it left &yogh;it wille &thorn;ei eft rise fulle austere.</L>
<L>It is not alle brouht to stalle for no powere,
<PB REF="00000511.tif" N="283"></L>
<L>&thorn;at Pers said, me &thorn;ink it is laid, &thorn;e pes so trewe,</L>
<L>Now ilk &yogh;ere, bi tymes sere, &thorn;ei gynne alle newe.</L>
<L>Jhesu so meke, I &thorn;e biseke, on croice &thorn;at was wonded,</L>
<L>Grante me &thorn;at bone, &thorn;e Scottes sone alle be confonded.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ATTE Seynt Edmond toun &thorn;e Parlement was sette,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De parlia|mento apud Sanctum Edmun|dum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bisshop &amp; baroun, &thorn;e clergie alle &thorn;er mette.</L>
<L>&thorn;e baronage holy &thorn;er &thorn;ei gan alle samen,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng alle &thorn;e clergie praied &thorn;am bi name,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ei wild at &thorn;er myght help him bi &thorn;at weye,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ei bifore hight in Westmynster abbeye.</L>
<L>"Of help I haf grete nede, my werre is not alle ent</L>
<L>"To wite what &yogh;e me rede, I set &thorn;is parlement.</L>
<L>"&thorn;is lond forto saue, my were to mayntene,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e tuelft penie to haue," &thorn;ei granted alle bidene.</L>
<L>&amp; of merchandie &thorn;e seuent penie to haue</L>
<L>Vnto his tresorie, &thorn;e barons vouched saue.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et luy Erceuesqe, qe te|ent la primacye Du se de Caunterbire, sure respouns estudye, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Forto gyue ansuere Roberd of Wynchelse</L>
<L>Studied how he mot, were alle his primaute.</L>
<L>He sent to &thorn;e kyng tuo bisshops of renoun,</L>
<L>&amp; schewed &thorn;at spiritualle &thorn;ing &thorn;orgh pouert &yogh;ede alle doun.</L>
<L>Afterward he &yogh;ede himself to &thorn;e kyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Archiepi|scopus dixit ad Regem.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; said, "Sir, God forbede, to greue &thorn;e ony &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>"Sir, I schewe &thorn;e here, for alle holy kirke,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at no man has powere &thorn;er of to deme no wirke,</L>
<L>"Withoute &thorn;e pape of Rome, Gode's vicarie.</L>
<L>"He salle at his dome set it lowe &amp; hie,
<PB REF="00000512.tif" N="284"></L>
<L>"He has mad a statute, &thorn;at vs hard byndes,</L>
<L>"Of forfeture of frute, &amp; rent &thorn;at vs fyndes,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at tende ne tuende half no partie</L>
<L>"&thorn;orgh gift to non salle lende, bot in his auowrie.</L>
<L>"Opon &thorn;at he giffes a solempne cursyng,</L>
<L>"Tille &thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;er on liffes, without his wittyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"SIR clerke," said &thorn;e kyng, "&thorn;ou has said folie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio Regis.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Hote is dette &thorn;ing, &thorn;er treuth has maistrie.</L>
<L>"Bot if &thorn;e bulle vnfolden were red among vs here,</L>
<L>"&yogh;our hote salle be holden, als dette in &thorn;at manere.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou &amp; alle &thorn;in salle help me as &yogh;e hight.</L>
<L>"&yogh;our hette wille I not tyne, bi Jhesu in Marie light.</L>
<L>&para; "Sir," &thorn;e bisshop said, "fulle gladly we wille,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Archiepi|scopus dixit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;at our godes be laid &yogh;ow to help at skille,</L>
<L>"&thorn;orgh leue of &thorn;e pape, &thorn;at has of vs powere,</L>
<L>"&yogh;our clerke &yogh;e &thorn;ider rape with our messengere.</L>
<L>"Whan &thorn;ei had schewed him alle our state &amp; &yogh;our askyng,</L>
<L>"With his leue we salle help &yogh;ow at his biddyng.</L>
<L>&para; "Certis," Sir bisshop, "terme ne wille I sette,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio Regis.</NOTE></L>
<L>"To conseile with &thorn;e pope for &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ou me hette.</L>
<L>"Bot if &thorn;ou wilt haf now respite in &thorn;is cas,</L>
<L>"Of &yogh;our hote conseile &yogh;ow with &thorn;e clergie &thorn;at &thorn;ou has.</L>
<L>"For &yogh;our hote is dette als to me,</L>
<L>"At Saynt Hillarimesse at Westmynster salle be,</L>
<L>"No lenger may I lette, me comes on ilk half werre,</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;at &thorn;at &yogh;e me hette gyues me &thorn;an ansuer&edot;.
<PB REF="00000513.tif" N="285"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"SIR," &thorn;e bisshop said, "of &thorn;is we pray &thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Archiepi|scopus dixit.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&thorn;at no wikked braid of minystres &thorn;at be,</L>
<L>"Tille vs ne non of ours, ne nouht of our lay fe</L>
<L>"Be taxed with non of &yogh;our's grante it per charite.</L>
<L>&para; "Sir bisshop drede &thorn;e nouht, &thorn;ou salle no &thorn;ing tyne,</L>
<L>"Sca&thorn;e salle non be wrouht &thorn;orgh no man of myne.</L>
<L>"Sir bisshop I pray &thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;ou alle holelyche,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &yogh;e pray for me &thorn;orghout &yogh;our bisshopriche.</L>
<L>Ilk bisshop tille his se, whan it was don &thorn;ei went,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e kyng &amp; his meyne forto pray &thorn;ei sent.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;ider to Saynt Edmoun com &thorn;e tresorere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Thesaura|rius venit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Walter of Langtoun, &thorn;at had bien messengere</L>
<L>With &thorn;e Cardinalle forto enforme &thorn;e pes.</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er of som no alle, ne wist what &thorn;ei ches,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;o &thorn;at were priue, o&thorn;er myght not witen,</L>
<L>Tille my maister no me was not told no writen.</L>
<L>&para; &yogh;it com afterward o&thorn;er messengers</L>
<L>Tille our kyng Edward, with luf &amp; faire maners,</L>
<L>&thorn;at contek suld not skip eft, &thorn;orgh no treson,</L>
<L>Bituex him &amp; Filip for &thorn;e lond of Gascon.</L>
<L>&thorn;e cardinalle was wys, ordeynd how it suld be:</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng at his auys sent messengers &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Sir Waltere of Langton, Sir Hugh Despensere,</L>
<L>Jon of Berwik was boun &thorn;e &thorn;rid messengere.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise wist &thorn;e certeyn of alle &thorn;e kynge's wille,</L>
<L>God bring &thorn;am wele ageyn, &amp; saue &thorn;am fro ille.</L>
<L>&para; Of &thorn;e barons of Scotland at &thorn;e parlement</L>
<L>Were non had &yogh;it in hand, no gyuen jugement.
<PB REF="00000514.tif" N="286"></L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;orgh right dede were wor&thorn;i,</L>
<L>&amp; atteynt, &thorn;orgh &thorn;e kyng did &thorn;am merci.</L>
<L>With Wales did he so, &amp; &thorn;ei were neuer trewe,</L>
<L>Whan he had most to do, &thorn;ei mad him sorow newe.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e day of Saynt Hillari &thorn;e kyng set &thorn;am bituen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De parlia|mento apud London.</NOTE></L>
<L>At London certeynli his parlement to haf bien.</L>
<L>Was brouht him &thorn;is ti&thorn;ing comen fro Kaunbray,</L>
<L>Of pes to speke no &thorn;ing, bot werre fro day to day.</L>
<L>Where for &thorn;e kyng wille fonde, forto purueie him</L>
<L>Trewe men bi water &amp; londe, for doute of treson grim.</L>
<L>He sent his day to hold of parlement &thorn;at he sette,</L>
<L>&thorn;e certeyn wite he wold, what &thorn;e clergi him hette.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e bisshop of Canterbire fulle bold his ansuere was,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio archiepi|scopi ad Regem.</NOTE></L>
<L>For him &amp; alle his schire he vouwed to S. Thomas,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at no kirke of hise taliage suld non gyue,</L>
<L>"Ne do to non seruise, to while &thorn;at he mot lyue,</L>
<L>"Without &thorn;e pape's leue, &thorn;at has of vs powere.</L>
<L>Tille his partie gan cheue &thorn;e bisshop Oliuere,</L>
<L>He turned not forbi for leue ne for loth.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng vnto &thorn;e clergi was &thorn;erfor fulle wroth,</L>
<L>&amp; said with euel wille, "despite he suld him do.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex dixit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop said &thorn;er tille, "I am redi &thorn;erto.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Archiepi|scopus.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Nay, Sir," said &thorn;e kyng, "&thorn;ou ert not so wor&thorn;i,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ne I wille for no &thorn;ing be so fole hardi.</L>
<L>Tille &thorn;o was he so hard out his pes did &thorn;am deme,</L>
<L>Bot sone afterward som gan him queme.</L>
<L>Som of &thorn;e bisshops said, "&thorn;at help behoued him haue,</L>
<L>"At skille &thorn;ei wild be laid, his right forto saue,
<PB REF="00000515.tif" N="287"></L>
<L>"&amp; holy kirke defende, saue it &amp; vs fro schame.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of &yogh;ork so kende, &amp; wild do &thorn;at same,</L>
<L>He granted for to gyue &thorn;e fifte penie to &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>In his werre wele to lyue, &amp; saue &thorn;er o&thorn;er &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN alle &thorn;is grete gram of &thorn;e clergi &amp; &thorn;e kyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Venerunt nuncii co|mitis Flan|dri&aelig; ad Regem.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Flandres &thorn;e erle William sent him a ti&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh his conseilers &amp; sauhtillyng wild he schewe,</L>
<L>With &thorn;re lordes pers of Blankmonte &amp; of <NOTE PLACE="foot">Ken <I>Codd. Gall.</I></NOTE>Kewe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;rid messengere a lord of grete honoure,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e tresorere of Flandres resceyuoure.</L>
<L>Of Hanaud &thorn;e erle first bigan, &amp; alle his Henners,</L>
<L>&thorn;e duke Jon of Braban with &thorn;e Holanders,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise praied &thorn;e erle William, for &thorn;er aller sake,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei tille Edward nam &thorn;e aliance to make.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise sent &thorn;is men &amp; said, "&thorn;at &thorn;er conseile so ches,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ei wild tille vs be laid, in gode lufe &amp; pes,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at our merchantz mot go forto bie &amp; selle,</L>
<L>"With luf withouten wo, &amp; at &yogh;our hauens duelle.</L>
<L>"If he wild ageyn France reise werre &amp; baners,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e Flemmynges wild &thorn;at chance to be his souders,</L>
<L>"Ageyn kyng Philip &amp; his duze pers,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at with wrong wild skip, &amp; reue him &thorn;o maners,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, Arthur.</NOTE> Arthu gaf Sir Beduers,</L>
<L>"In Gascoyn alle &thorn;oru to his botlers,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e whilk kyng Henry, &amp; now his sonne Edward,</L>
<L>"His ancestres holy haf had it afterward.
<PB REF="00000516.tif" N="288"></L>
<L>&thorn;ise teld to &thorn;e kyng alle &thorn;er lorde's wille,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;is ti&thorn;ing leue &yogh;it &thorn;e prisons stille.</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;ise ilk chances, &thorn;at I haf of tolde,</L>
<L>Was no deliuerance of &thorn;e Scottis bolde.</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, at.</NOTE> as Saleberi, no at Saynt Edmunde's toun,</L>
<L>Was non &yogh;it at &thorn;e wiri, ne &yogh;olden for raunsoun.</L>
<L>Of many foule mischeue com him ti&thorn;ing &thorn;ikke,</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;er was oure greue, &amp; &thorn;at him &thorn;ouh most wikke.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e ti&thorn;ing is so nowe, his courte it dos to blaken,</L>
<L>&thorn;e soth ilk on &thorn;ei knew, Sir Jon of Saynt Jon is taken.</L>
<L>He kept his castels, his vitaile, his mone,</L>
<L>Undere &thorn;e kyng seales, &thorn;e chance listnes me.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Wednesday next at euen befor Kandilmesse<NOTE PLACE="marg">De cap|cione Do|mini Jo|hannis de Sancto Jo|hanne apud Belgarde.</NOTE></L>
<L>A spie did Sir Jon leue, &thorn;at Frankis oste non was.</L>
<L>Namely in &thorn;at pas, &thorn;at he suld lede &thorn;am bi,</L>
<L>He lied &thorn;at Judas, ten &thorn;ousand were redi.</L>
<L>Sir Jon mad him prest, he trost &thorn;at losengere,</L>
<L>His bataile was formest, displaied his banere,</L>
<L>&amp; passed alle &thorn;e pas, &thorn;at &thorn;ei alle so dred,</L>
<L>Biside enbussed was fiften hundred sped,</L>
<L>In foure grete escheles alle to batail sette,</L>
<L>&thorn;e first he disconfet wele, &thorn;e to&thorn;er with him so mette.</L>
<L>Sir Jon fulle hardely to fight did his peyn,</L>
<L>&amp; bad Sir Henry Lacy, &thorn;at he suld turne ageyn.</L>
<L>"&thorn;is oste is grete biforn, I rede &thorn;at &yogh;e fle.</L>
<L>&thorn;er vitaile was alle lorn, herneis &amp; &thorn;er mone.</L>
<L>Sir James of Beauchamp wonded, &amp; may not stand,</L>
<L>In a water stampe he was dronkled fleand.
<PB REF="00000517.tif" N="289"></L>
<L>Sir Jon &thorn;orgh &thorn;am brast, bifore &yogh;e herd me neuen,</L>
<L>Was taken at &thorn;e last &amp; his knyghtes elleuen,</L>
<L>&amp; of his squierie gentille men auhtene.</L>
<L>&thorn;er pride &amp; &thorn;er folie, I trowe, on &thorn;am was sene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BOSTE &amp; deignouse pride &amp; ille avisement</L>
<L>Mishapnes oftentide, &amp; dos many be schent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e proude kyng Pharaon, &thorn;at chaced Israel,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Exempla viciorum, quibus gra|tia extin|guitur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dronkeld euerilkon, &amp; Gode's folk went wel.</L>
<L>Sodom &amp; Gomor fulle vile synne &thorn;at stank,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e for euer more doun tille helle &thorn;ei sank.</L>
<L>Dauid &thorn;at simple was, slouh he grete Golie,</L>
<L>Jacob sonne Judas solde Josep for envie.</L>
<L>Lucius &thorn;e emperour was slayn for couetise,</L>
<L>Arthur had dishonour for wronges many wise.</L>
<L>Modred a fole aperte was slayn licherie,</L>
<L>Cadwaldre for pouerte fled fro Bretanie.</L>
<L>Harald &thorn;is lond les, for he was forsuoren,</L>
<L>Leulyn brak &thorn;e pes, his hede he lost &thorn;erforn.</L>
<L>Allas! non with o&thorn;er chastised &yogh;it wille be,</L>
<L>Edward do turne &thorn;e ro&thorn;er, &amp; fare ouer &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>&amp; socoure &thorn;o &thorn;at are &yogh;it in Gascoyn left,</L>
<L>Ne late &thorn;am not misfare, ne &thorn;er powere be reft.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et Thomas de Kent, e Jon de Beuerlye, Et Cuth|bert de Dureme te vendrount en aye. <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Saynt Thomas salle be &thorn;i help &amp; &thorn;i socoure,</L>
<L>St. Jon of Beuerle, Cutbert &thorn;e confessoure.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou haf help of God &thorn;orgh praiere of som Saynt,</L>
<L>I telle not wor&thorn;e a cod, for alle &thorn;i faire is faynt.
<PB REF="00000518.tif" N="290"></L>
<L>On &thorn;o &thorn;at God lufes lest mishappenyng salle falle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at kepe not his bihest, &thorn;ei ere vngraciouse alle.</L>
<L>&para; It sais in a storie, &thorn;e bible may not lie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Machab&aelig;|orum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> God God gaf &thorn;e maistrie to &thorn;e childre of Mathatie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bible sais bot seuen &thorn;e were, &amp; no mo,</L>
<L>Seuen thousand euen ageyn alle durst &thorn;ei go.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei wer stedfast &amp; traist, lufed God &amp; held his lawe,</L>
<L>Folie wild &thorn;ei no fraist, ne to no falshede drawe.</L>
<L>God lufed &thorn;am &amp; &thorn;ei him, he halp &thorn;am at &thorn;er nede,</L>
<L>Ensample I rede &yogh;e nym, &thorn;at &yogh;e may so wele spede.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e date was a &thorn;ousand &thorn;re hundred alle bot &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Edward tok on hand Flandres forto se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER<NOTE PLACE="foot">Apres la seinte feste del Assensioun, Maunda ly Reis [<I>vel</I>, le Roy] Edward par my sa regioun, Aerceuesqe, [<I>vel</I>, Lerceuesk] euesqe, count &amp; a baroun, Et a touz luy al|tre, que ount pur garysoun Vint liuere de tere en posses|sioun, Venir a sa court, a fere redempcioun, Ou passer oue son cors, sur ly Fraunceis feloun, Ke atort luy defor|cent la tere de Gascoun, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e haly &thorn;orsday &thorn;e kyng sent his sond,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De parlia|mento apud Westmona|sterium.</NOTE></L>
<L>Messengers of way, for barons of &thorn;e lond,</L>
<L>For bisshopes &thorn;at &thorn;ei kende, &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;ei found,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ilk &yogh;ere mot dispende of londes tuenty pound,</L>
<L>Suld com &thorn;er he was, &amp; with him mak &thorn;er frette,</L>
<L>Or with his body pas tille Gascoyn als he sette.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e barons &amp; of hise said, "&thorn;ei suld not so,</L>
<L>"Suilk a new seruise to reise ne to do.</L>
<L>"For our state it apeires, without any reson,</L>
<L>"&amp; tille alle our heires grete disheriteson.
<PB REF="00000519.tif" N="291"></L>
<L>&thorn;e barons were alle in ire, &amp; spak for &thorn;at tirpeile,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Canterbire &thorn;ei praied him of conseile.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop knewe &thorn;e right, &thorn;e wille of bo&thorn;e what ment,</L>
<L>Als holy kirke's knyght, he com to &thorn;e parlement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE<NOTE PLACE="foot">Luy Reis lors les parle, &amp; dist en son sermoun, I eo su chastel pur vous, &amp; mur &amp; mesoun, Et vous la bar|becane, &amp; porte &amp; pauyllioun. Ma tere de Gascoygne est pardue par tresoun, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> kyng spak for his prow, whan &thorn;ei were alle sette,</L>
<L>"I am castelle for &yogh;ow, toure, hous, &amp; rescette,</L>
<L>"&amp; &yogh;e als naked berd loken in pauilloun,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at to fight is ferd, or &yogh;ate &thorn;at first is doun.</L>
<L>"My lond of Gascoyn is lorn &thorn;orgh tresons,</L>
<L>"I may not cast essoyn, bot felow my somons.</L>
<L>"I haf mad a vowe to leue for wele ne wo,</L>
<L>"At my nede now with me behoues &yogh;ow go.</L>
<L>"Salle non finde encheson &thorn;orgh quaintise to say,</L>
<L>"Bot &thorn;at &yogh;e be alle boun with me to wende &thorn;at way.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;en ansuerd Sir Roberd, bisshop of Canterbire,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio archiepi|scopi Can|tuari&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Sir, ert &thorn;ou not ferd of wreche of Gode's ire,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;ou wilt werre bigynne, without amendment,</L>
<L>"Ageyn God don synne, ageyn holy kirke has went?</L>
<L>"I rede &thorn;ou mak amendes of &thorn;at grete misdede.</L>
<L>"Praye God &thorn;at alle defendes als holy kirke wille rede,</L>
<L>"&amp; bot &thorn;ou do, Sir kyng, as I conseile &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"I salle mak cursyng on alle &thorn;at passe with &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="292"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER &thorn;e ersbisshop &thorn;e erle Marschalle Rogere<NOTE PLACE="marg">Dixit co|mes Mar|schalle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bifor &thorn;e kyng ros vp, &amp; spak tille him austere,</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;is we ask respite, oure conseile to take,</L>
<L>"No&thorn;eles also tite I say for &thorn;e comon sake.</L>
<L>He said for &thorn;e barons, &thorn;at non of &thorn;er homage</L>
<L>Suld passe for somons, bot at &thorn;e kynge's costage;</L>
<L>Ne non of &thorn;er powere to passe &thorn;e se suld grante,</L>
<L>Without conseile of pere &amp; costage in conante.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng his wordes toke wra&thorn;efully tille herte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>For ire nere he quoke, &amp; ansuerd him fulle smerte.</L>
<L>"Sir Erle, I comand &thorn;e, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be &thorn;e ton,</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou salle wende with me, whedere &thorn;ou wille or non,</L>
<L>"Or &thorn;in office for go of &thorn;e marschalcie,</L>
<L>"Respite I gyue no mo, but mak alle redie.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Subintellige</I>, said, <I>vel</I>, answer'd.</NOTE> erle, "wend I nouht so sone myn office lete,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Comes.</NOTE></L>
<L>"I haf not &yogh;it so wrouht, to haf maugre &thorn;e grete.</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e courte he went, duellid he no while,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng for on sent, Sir Geffrey Geneuile,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e marschalcie presented him &thorn;e &yogh;erde,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et sur ceo co|maunde ses priuez gentz ar|mer, Et bye lendemayne les barouns arester, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Bad arme him priuelie, &amp; priues alle herde</L>
<L>Now tille armes &thorn;at may, als &thorn;ei suld lyue or deie,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei hoped &thorn;e to&thorn;er day &thorn;e barons resteie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle wist it sone, in him was no defaute,</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons were alle bone, to mak &thorn;e kyng assaute.</L>
<L>&para; Right als &thorn;e parties togider suld haf smyten,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Episcopus Dunelmi Antonius.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sir Antoyn was wys, he did &thorn;e kyng to witen,
<PB REF="00000521.tif" N="293"></L>
<L>What perille salle betide, if &thorn;ei &amp; his barons</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F. in</I> werre.</NOTE>&amp; werre togidere ride, als enmys felons.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e barons he &yogh;ede, &amp; praied &thorn;am to bowe,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e kyng to &yogh;ow has nede, help him if &yogh;e mowe.</L>
<L>"If him com any sca&thorn;e tinselle of seignorie,</L>
<L>Tille &yogh;ow it wille be wa&thorn;e, leues alle &thorn;is folie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE barons at &thorn;e last tille Antoyn gaf ansuere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio baronum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ei wild ask bad him &thorn;e copie bere,</L>
<L>&amp; said to Saynt Alban's, &thorn;ider wild &thorn;ei com,</L>
<L>To parlement alle at ans, &amp; stand to right dome.</L>
<L>If he &amp; his conseile to &thorn;am wild him meke,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wild him auaile, &amp; do &thorn;at he wild biseke.</L>
<L>Sir Antoyn turned ageyn, &amp; schewed him &thorn;er assent,</L>
<L>If he wild hold certeyn &thorn;e day of parlement.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng wild not &thorn;ider, ouer &thorn;e se wild he fare,</L>
<L>To wite where &amp; whidere &thorn;e ferd his frendes &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Withouten rede of mo in schip to Flandres went,</L>
<L>Non erle wild with him go, for baron non he sent.</L>
<L>His folie was &thorn;e more, &thorn;ar he non with him toke,</L>
<L>Suilk ti&thorn;ing sauh he &thorn;ore, fulle fayn fro Brigges schoke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW is Edward ariued in Flandres, bot with fo.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex trans|fretavit in Flandriam.</NOTE></L>
<L>With his barons he striued, with him wild non go.</L>
<L>A kyng &thorn;at striues with hise, he may not wele spede,</L>
<L>Whore so he restis or riues he lyues ay in drede.</L>
<L>His vitaile he has purueid in Brigges forto be,</L>
<L>His wynes were &thorn;er leid, &amp; warnised &thorn;at cite.
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="294"></L>
<L>God &thorn;at wote alle &thorn;ing, what is don or whi,</L>
<L>He saue Edward our kyng &thorn;ore &thorn;orgh his merci.</L>
<L>&para; Bituex &thorn;e kyng of France &amp; &thorn;e erle William<NOTE PLACE="marg">Tradicio Flandro|rum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was &thorn;at tyme a distance, a wrath bituex &thorn;am nam.</L>
<L>&thorn;e prouest of &thorn;e toun, a wik traytour &amp; cherle,</L>
<L>He &thorn;ouht to do tresoun vnto his lord &thorn;e erle.</L>
<L>To Philip priuely a letter did he make,</L>
<L>If he had oste redy, Brigges mot he take.</L>
<L>Com what tyme he wild, &thorn;e toun suld he wynne,</L>
<L>&thorn;e comon he suld him &yogh;eld, &amp; Edward &thorn;erinne.</L>
<L>Edward mot he haue, if he wild him rape,</L>
<L>&thorn;e toun he suld so saue, &thorn;at he suld not ascape.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is whan Philip herd, oste he did sone &yogh;are,</L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme &thorn;at he forth ferd, he herd not of his fare.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e preuest with &thorn;e burgeis &thorn;at day to conseile gede,</L>
<L>Edward herd it say of gilerie, as som drede.</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er were perceyued, &thorn;at &thorn;er &yogh;ede disceite,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it was it not reyued, so Edward &thorn;ouht him streite.</L>
<L>A child of &thorn;at land, &thorn;at knew not Sir Edward,</L>
<L>Edward sauh him stand, `&thorn;e Flem<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dele.</NOTE> &thorn;e Flemmynges to reward.</L>
<L>Fast he gan behald &thorn;e samenyng of Flemmynges.</L>
<L>Edward child cald, &amp; asked him ti&thorn;inges.</L>
<L>"Sonne, what hers &thorn;ou say of burgeis of cite?</L>
<L>He said, "Sir grete aye, &thorn;at &thorn;e Inglis here in be,</L>
<L>"&amp; for &thorn;e Inglis sake tille it wille falle hard.</L>
<L>"For &thorn;e Frankes hope take &thorn;e toun &amp; Sir Edward.</L>
<L>Sir Edward also sone &thorn;er gile gan he knowe,</L>
<L>Dight him to bataile bone, his trumpes did he blowe.
<PB REF="00000523.tif" N="295"></L>
<L>&thorn;e Flemmynges vndirstode, &thorn;e kyng warned was,</L>
<L>&thorn;e cheynes &amp; &yogh;ates gode &thorn;ei sperd, &thorn;at non mot pas.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Walsch without &thorn;e toun euerilkon &thorn;ei lay,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e enchesoun for fight &amp; for affray.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei &thorn;e trumpes herd, &thorn;at he to bataile blewe,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Salvatus fuit Rex per Gual|lias.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; saw &thorn;e &yogh;ates sperd, &thorn;an gamened &thorn;am no glewe.</L>
<L>Ouh! for Saynt Dauy! &thorn;e Flemmyng wille him gile,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kest alle suilk a crie, &thorn;at men mot here a myle.</L>
<L>Fire &amp; brondes &thorn;ei nam in houses of &thorn;er gatis,</L>
<L>&amp; ouer &thorn;e water suam, &amp; set fire on &thorn;e &yogh;atis.</L>
<L>Maugre &thorn;e Flemmynges on &thorn;am &thorn;e &yogh;atis &thorn;ei brent,</L>
<L>Cheynes &thorn;ei hew &amp; rynges, &amp; tille Sir Edward went,</L>
<L>&amp; fond him alle redy armed on his stede,</L>
<L>Was no cheyne so hie, &thorn;at he ne sprong ouer als glede,</L>
<L>&amp; comandid ilk man, to schip sui&thorn;e to go,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e Flemmynges he ran, &amp; many on did slo.</L>
<L>His stede was blak as rauen, &thorn;ei kald his name Feraunt,</L>
<L>He rode vnto &thorn;e hauen, &amp; said he wild to Gaunt.</L>
<L>Unne&thorn;is fro &thorn;at felons ascaped he &thorn;at wo.</L>
<L>If he had had his barons, he had not gyuen of &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng of Almayn had hight him his help,</L>
<L>He mad a fals trayn, of him is not a &yogh;elp.</L>
<L>He sent Edward to say, help him mot he nouht,</L>
<L>Werrand on ilk a way his enmys on him souht.</L>
<L>Allas! &thorn;at a kyng es fals ageyn his pere!</L>
<L>Edward dred him no &thorn;ing, bot was ay glad of chere.
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="296"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AN erle &thorn;er was of Bare, he werred fast on France,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Walsh with him war &yogh;ere, forto do mischance.</L>
<L>&thorn;er markettis &amp; &thorn;er faires &amp; &thorn;er castels reft,</L>
<L>Now alle &thorn;e cuntre peires, vnne&thorn;is ouht &thorn;ei left.</L>
<L>Philip on his partie did &thorn;e erle grete tene,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at he mot com bie, he robbed alle bidene.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Durhem trauailed day &amp; nyght,</L>
<L>Of strife to felle &thorn;e stem, &thorn;e pes to mak alle right.</L>
<L>Bot Philip was ay hard, his ansuer euer so light,</L>
<L>His wist &thorn;at Edward had bot litelle myght.</L>
<L>Has he had his erles, his barons with him lad,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e Frankis cherles &thorn;e maistrie suld he haf had.</L>
<L>&para; A man &thorn;at beris him stoute, whan &thorn;at he suld bowe,</L>
<L>In chance if &thorn;at he loute, he findes foos inowe.</L>
<L>Listnes now &thorn;is pas, why &thorn;at I &thorn;us said,</L>
<L>In wham defaut was &thorn;at &thorn;ertille may be laid.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GESTES &thorn;at er olde writen of many man,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Exemplum verum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ritti reames men tolde, &thorn;at kyng Arthur wan.</L>
<L>He parted his wynnyng tille his men largely,</L>
<L>&thorn;at nou&thorn;er erle ne kyng wille withsitte his cry.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei were at his wille, were he neuer so hie,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e of gode &amp; ille at alle his nede redie.</L>
<L>&para; Oure kyng Sir Edward ouer litille he gaf,</L>
<L>Tille his barons was hard, ouerhipped &thorn;am ouerhaf.</L>
<L>He wild not be so hende, so large, no so fre,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor &thorn;ei lete him wende alon ouere &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;at wendyng alon, nere he had bien schent,</L>
<L>It was to mak of mone, &thorn;at non erle with him went.
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="297"></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;orgh ti&thorn;ing brouht bi tide &thorn;e Scottis wist of &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Ilk Scotte on his side mad &thorn;erof joy &amp; blis.</L>
<L>&thorn;e rascail of &thorn;er route bigan to werre alle newe,</L>
<L>Now Edward is oute, &thorn;e barons be not trewe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e suffred, as it sais, &thorn;e Scottis eft to rise,</L>
<L>&amp; William &thorn;e Walais &thorn;er hede &amp; &thorn;er justise.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh fals concelement William did his wille,</L>
<L>Our castels has he brent, our men slayn fulle ille.</L>
<L>&para; Sir Hugh of Crissengham he did nycely &amp; mys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Hugone Cressyng|ham.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e tresore with him he nam, sperd it in his coffris,</L>
<L>&amp; wild gif no wages to &thorn;e folk &thorn;er ware,</L>
<L>&thorn;erfor &yogh;omen &amp; pages home gan alle fare.</L>
<L>&para; Whan Sir Jon of Warenne &thorn;e soth vnderstode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e Waleis gan brenne, an oste he gadred gode,</L>
<L>&amp; went to Striuelyne agayn Waleis William,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e erle with mykelle pyne disconfite away nam.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at was his folie, so long in his bed gan ligge,</L>
<L>Untille &thorn;e Waleis partie had vmbilaid &thorn;e brigge.</L>
<L>With gauelokes &amp; dartes suilk ore was non sene,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Striue|lyn &amp; de Domino Johanne de Warenne.</NOTE></L>
<L>Myght no man &thorn;am departe, ne ride ne go bituene.</L>
<L>&thorn;ore first &thorn;am tauht, how &thorn;ei did fawe kirke.</L>
<L>Alle gate &thorn;e brigge he rauht, of nouht our men were irke.</L>
<L>&para; Whan &thorn;e erle herd say, &thorn;e brigge how William toke,</L>
<L>He douted to die &thorn;at day, &thorn;at bataile he forsoke.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis were alle slayn, &thorn;e Scottis bare &thorn;am wele,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Waleis had &thorn;e wayn, als maistere of &thorn;at eschele.</L>
<L>At &thorn;at ilk stoure was slayn on our side</L>
<L>God men of honour, &thorn;at wald to &thorn;e bataile bide.
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="298"></L>
<L>Sir Roberd of Somervile, &amp; his eldest sonne,</L>
<L>He held &thorn;e stoure a while, for dede ne wild he schonne.</L>
<L>&amp; knyghtes &amp; sergeantz, noble men fulle couth,</L>
<L>Of prowes fulle valiantz, bo&thorn;e bi North &amp; South.</L>
<L>&para; Sir Hugh of Cressyngham in armes nouht ne deih,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte &amp; obpro|brio Hugo|nis de Cres|syngham.</NOTE></L>
<L>For ridyng lauht he skam, out of his sadelle he fleih.</L>
<L>His stede ouer him ran, he lay vnder his fete,</L>
<L>&thorn;at sauh &thorn;e Scottis man, &amp; &thorn;er of wele he lete.</L>
<L>He &amp; o&thorn;er inowe, &thorn;at Sir Hugh wele knewe,</L>
<L>I wene &thorn;ei quik him<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, slouh.</NOTE> flouh, &amp; his lymmes to hewe.</L>
<L>&para; Sir Marmeduk of Thuenge in &thorn;e felde bare &thorn;e flour,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De probi|tate Mar|meduk de Thuenge.</NOTE></L>
<L>With &thorn;e Scottis gan he menge, &amp; stifly stode in stoure.</L>
<L>Fightand he couerd alle weys &thorn;e castelle of Striuelyn,</L>
<L>Maugre &thorn;e Waleys, Sir Marmeduk went in.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER<NOTE PLACE="foot">Mainte|naunt apres ad luy Escot maundez De la la mere en Flaundres vn ribaud deguy|sez, Espier sire Edward en viles &amp; cytez, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> &thorn;is bataile, &thorn;e Scottis sent ouer &thorn;e se<NOTE PLACE="marg">Scotti mise|runt nun|cium ultra mare in Flandriam q. explora|torem.</NOTE></L>
<L>A boye of &thorn;er rascaile, quaynt &amp; doguise.</L>
<L>To Flandres bad him fare, &thorn;orgh burgh &amp; cite,</L>
<L>Of Edward whore he ware bring &thorn;am certeynte.</L>
<L>&amp; whan he com ageyn, he teld &thorn;am &thorn;is ti&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>&thorn;at sothly &amp; certeyn dede was Edward &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;at stede he ferd, &thorn;er he was laid in graue,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis whan &thorn;ei it herd, more joye ne bad &thorn;ei haue.</L>
<L>&para; To werre &thorn;an ros &thorn;ei cft, tille God &thorn;ei mad a vowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at no &thorn;ing suld be left, &thorn;at myght to Inglond prowe,</L>
<L>Mercy suld non haue, tille alle &thorn;ei suld do wo,</L>
<L>Kirke suld no man saue, bot brenne &thorn;er in &amp; slo.
<PB REF="00000527.tif" N="299"></L>
<L>In Northumberland &thorn;er first &thorn;ei bigan,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;at com tille hand, &thorn;ei slouh &amp; ouer ran</L>
<L>To Flandres tille Edward ti&thorn;inges men him sent,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Scottis com in hard, &thorn;e North is nere alle brent,</L>
<L>&amp; more salle &yogh;it be lorn, bot if we haf socoure.</L>
<L>Nouht standes &thorn;am biforn, toun, castelle, ne toure.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng for &thorn;o ti&thorn;inges was noyed greuoslie,</L>
<L>To conseil &thorn;e lordynges he cald &thorn;at wer him bi.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei had alle cast &thorn;er conseil vp &amp; doun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De carta libertatis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng was at &thorn;e last avised on &thorn;is reson,</L>
<L>&thorn;at nede behoued him grante to clerke &amp; baroun,</L>
<L>&amp; hold &thorn;am &thorn;e conante of ilk peticioun.</L>
<L>Bi letter he &thorn;am sent, &amp; grantid &thorn;er askyng,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at reson ment of ilk maner &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Bi letter &amp; bi mouth he praied &thorn;am of socoure,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he myght &amp; couth, &thorn;at wer to &thorn;er honoure,</L>
<L>He granted at &thorn;er wille, if &thorn;ei wild socoure him,</L>
<L>Ageyn &thorn;e Scottis ille, &thorn;at bere &thorn;am now so brim,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE bisshop of Canterbire &thorn;erof payed was he,</L>
<L>For him and alle his schire &thorn;is gift gaf fulle fre,</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;e pape statute, &thorn;at &thorn;em bihoued defende,</L>
<L>Of holy kirke's frute he gaf &thorn;e kyng &thorn;e tende,</L>
<L>Gadred with clerkis hand, &amp; kept to &thorn;at viage,</L>
<L>Wendand to Scotland, biteched it &thorn;e baronage,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lond forto saue, &amp; holy kirke's dignite,</L>
<L>&thorn;is grantid he &thorn;am to haue Roberd of Wynchelse.</L>
<L>&thorn;e clergie of &thorn;e North &thorn;e fifte peny suld gyue,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e barons ferd forth, in pes &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot lyue,
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="300"></L>
<L>&amp; grantid &thorn;am self at &thorn;e first gynnyng,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e kyng asked half of alle &thorn;er moble &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Now er at on assent &thorn;e barons &amp; &thorn;e clerkis,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis hold &thorn;am schent, of &thorn;er conseil now herkis</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Scottis vnderstode, &thorn;at holy &thorn;e clergie<NOTE PLACE="marg">De consilio Scottorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Were alle in wille gode, to help &thorn;e kynge's partie,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e barons also in luf with him wild dele,</L>
<L>For he had grantid &thorn;er to &thorn;e Chartre forto sele,</L>
<L>&amp; after &thorn;at selyng alle suld &thorn;ei come</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons &amp; &thorn;e kyng, &amp; tak of &thorn;am hard dome</L>
<L>What did &thorn;e Scottis &thorn;o, bot &thorn;is conseil &thorn;ei ches?</L>
<L>To Striuelyn suld &thorn;ei go, in manere of pes,</L>
<L>Sir Marmeduk biseke, his wrath forto asuage,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;am mak him meke, for luf &amp; for ostage.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei <NOTE PLACE="foot">Et en lour baptesme promistrent &amp; ioraint, Si hors volsift [<I>vel</I> vousint] ve|nir, de pees ly parleraynt, &amp;<I>c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>suore &thorn;er Cristendam, if &thorn;at he wild com oute,</L>
<L>Withouten any gram tille &thorn;ei wild loute,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e loude &amp; stille, in nesch &amp; in hard,</L>
<L>&amp; to pes with gode wille &yogh;eld &thorn;am tille Edward.</L>
<L>Sir Marmeduk out cam, he trosted on &thorn;er fayth,</L>
<L>To him &amp; his &thorn;ei nam, &amp; smertly did &thorn;am grayth</L>
<L>Toward <NOTE PLACE="foot">Dunbretayn, <I>vel</I> Dunbrettayn, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Dun Bretayn, &amp; him in prison &thorn;er sperd,</L>
<L>His frendes were vnfayn, for non wist how he ferd.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei did &thorn;at treson, if &thorn;am felle any chance,</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ei mot eftson of &thorn;ers make deliuerance.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e clergie of &thorn;e South mad a disputesoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Disputacio Cleri.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; openly with mouth assigned gode resoun,
<PB REF="00000529.tif" N="301"></L>
<L>&thorn;at sca&thorn;e ne mot bifalle, ne forto wrath &thorn;e pape,</L>
<L>Bot for him &amp; vs alle myght it better schape.</L>
<L>&para; In alle &thorn;is spekyng com &thorn;e tresorere<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce The|saurarius venit.</NOTE></L>
<L>Fro Edward our kyng, to schewe &thorn;e chartere here.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Cil vers la clergye co|menca parler, Et a les ba|rouns issi [<I>vel</I> ency] nouncier, A nous li Reis vos sires bee de gentyl qoer De sa sey|gnorye, tut Engleterre eyser, La chartre des fraunchises vous volt confermer, De la foreste le assise [<I>vel</I> lassise] amender, Cum jadis puruist le Rey Henry son peer. La chartre fu monstre &amp; leu a Wemonster, &amp;<I>c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>He spak vnto &thorn;e clergie, "&yogh;e barons &thorn;at here be,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e kyng fulle curteislie gretis &yogh;ow wele bi me,</L>
<L>"&amp; sais, &thorn;at he wille Inglond alle ese,</L>
<L>"&amp; &thorn;at &yogh;e ask in skille &yogh;our hertes forto pese,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e chartre of franchise conferm it &yogh;ow he salle,</L>
<L>"&amp; of &thorn;e first assise as his fader gaf it alle.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Chartre was red on hi, in Westmynstere &amp; schewed,</L>
<L>Ilk poynt bi &amp; bi, to lerid &amp; to lewed.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Canterbire in comon alle o liche</L>
<L>Schewed it in ilk schire, alle his bisshop riche.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei &thorn;e Chartre in alle had schewed day bi day,</L>
<L>Sir Roger &thorn;e erle Marschalle, of Herford &thorn;e erle Umfray,</L>
<L>At &yogh;ork &thorn;ei tok on hand, &thorn;er parlement to sette,</L>
<L>&thorn;e hie folk of &thorn;e land, &thorn;er alle togidere mette.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce comi|tiva baro|num apud Eboracum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e erle Jon of Surray com with grete powere,</L>
<L>Of Gloucestre stoute &amp; gay Sir Rauf &thorn;e Mohermere,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Oue Jone la Countesse sa lige mulier, Et trestouz ly altre, qe portent baner, De Douer a Dureme i venent volenter, &amp;<I>c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&amp; his wif dame Jone, whilom Gilberde's of Clare,</L>
<L>&thorn;o banerettis ilkone fro Douer to Durham ware.
<PB REF="00000530.tif" N="302"></L>
<L>At &thorn;e kirke of Saynt Petir &thorn;e day of Saynt Agnes,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop on his mitere of Carlele it says.</L>
<L>He stode vp in pulpite, &thorn;e office forto do,</L>
<L>&thorn;er Chartre he red it bituex &thorn;e erles tuo,</L>
<L>&amp; cursed alle &thorn;o, &thorn;at &thorn;e Chartre brak,</L>
<L>Or stroied or did ouht fro ony poynt &thorn;er in spak.</L>
<L>After &thorn;is sentence gyuen, tille armes alle &thorn;at myght,</L>
<L>Was it no lenger dryuen, to Scotlond alle &thorn;am dight.</L>
<L>In alle Northumberland, &thorn;er &thorn;e Waleis had bene,</L>
<L>Alle was in &thorn;e kynge's hand, &thorn;e Scottis wer non sene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN alle &thorn;is nesch &amp; hard, euer lasted &thorn;e distance</L>
<L>Bituex kyng Edward, &amp; &thorn;e kyng of France,</L>
<L>Bot it was delaied tille a day certeyn</L>
<L>Of right dome set &amp; saied, how pes mot be pleyn.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei consentid bo&thorn;e, &thorn;orgh conseil of &thorn;e pape,</L>
<L>To pese &thorn;am tuo wro&thorn;e, with sight he wild schape.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh mariages was hopyng of &thorn;e pes,</L>
<L>&thorn;at were certeyn stages, &thorn;at bo&thorn;e parties ches.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng on suld haue, a may was in spekyng,</L>
<L>Tille his sonne suld men saue, Philip douhter &yogh;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN alle &thorn;is ordenance our kyng sent messengers<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex misit nuncios ad Romam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, knewe.</NOTE> kewe &thorn;e greuance, wyse men barons pers,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e courte of Rome, &thorn;e pape to schew &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>How wondere chances come, &amp; who did most trespas,</L>
<L>Of Inglis &amp; Frankis who was most culpable,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e pape leues alle &thorn;is, to mak mende &amp; mak alle stable.
<PB REF="00000531.tif" N="303"></L>
<L>&para; To while pape Boniface duellid opon &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rediit in Angliam, &amp; incarce|ratis Scottis dedit licen|ciam &amp; li|bertatem exeundi.</NOTE></L>
<L>To gyue dome &thorn;orgh grace, to mende bo&thorn;e &thorn;er mys,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng tok his consaile, &amp; home to Ingland went.</L>
<L>Gode wynde in his saile Jhesu Criste him lent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erles of Scotlond &thorn;at atteynt wer of treson,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng him self willand, deliuerd &thorn;am fro prison.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise wer of &thorn;er gest, as I kan names fynde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Menetest was of Edward kynde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Ascetelle, Sir Jon &thorn;e Comyn,</L>
<L>Badenauh sonne I telle, &amp; &thorn;retty of &thorn;er couyn,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ise &amp; wele mo atteynt of traytorie,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng lete &thorn;am go of his curteisie,</L>
<L>Withouten siluere or golde, or any o&thorn;er treuage,</L>
<L>&thorn;er penance was, &thorn;ei suld go in pilgrimage.</L>
<L>&para; Here of &thorn;is wikked hals, &thorn;at our kyng gaf leue,</L>
<L>To France &thorn;ei &yogh;ede &thorn;o fals, to Philip wild &thorn;ei cheue,</L>
<L>Bisouht him of socoure &amp; auancement,</L>
<L>To maynten &thorn;am in stoure, &thorn;ei mad<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>There is a little stroke over the</I> i <I>in the MS. which shews that</I> him <I>is to be read.</I></NOTE> hir &thorn;er present,</L>
<L>Scotlond of him to hold euer withouten ende,</L>
<L>If he in luf wold as lord vnto &thorn;am lende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>PHILIP gaf respons, &amp; bad &thorn;am go &thorn;er way,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de falsitate Scottorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&yogh;e ere foles Bretons, disceit is &thorn;at &yogh;e say.</L>
<L>"&thorn;e pape me defendes with bulle &thorn;at bindis hard,</L>
<L>"To renne on &thorn;o landes, &thorn;at longes tille Edward.</L>
<L>"To whils &thorn;at oure trewe duellis on jugement,</L>
<L>"For me salle neuer be newe no fals compassement.
<PB REF="00000532.tif" N="304"></L>
<L>Confused &thorn;ei went away &thorn;at fals companie,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei failed of &thorn;er pray, to hauen gan &thorn;ei hie,</L>
<L>&amp; hired &thorn;am a schip, gaf siluere largelie,</L>
<L>To Scotlond gan &thorn;ei skip, &thorn;e wynde was &thorn;am redie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EDWARD vnderstode, &thorn;orgh oft heryng say,</L>
<L>How &thorn;e fals blode compassed tene &amp; tray.</L>
<L>He mad his pilgrimage to Saynt Thomas of Kent,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en North on his viage to Beuerley he went,</L>
<L>Bifor Saynt Jon he woke a nyght or he &thorn;ien nam,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE>Perigrina|tus est Rex.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &yogh;ork &thorn;e gate he toke, &amp; souht Saynt William.</L>
<L>Saynt Cutbert he souht, to help him at his nede,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he dred him nouht, Northward als he &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>Northward in his weie he held his parlement,</L>
<L>To speke &amp; to purueie to be of on assent,</L>
<L>To Scotlond forto go, to take vengement</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am his folk did slo, destroied his tenement,</L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;ei were alle lorn, &thorn;at com to &thorn;at couent.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei were forsuorn, vengeance on &thorn;am went.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date was a &thorn;ousand, &thorn;re hundred alle bot one,<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. CC<SUP>o</SUP>. <NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE>LXXXIX<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>At Foukirke in Scotlond, Scottis escapid none.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Bellum apud Fau|kirk.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ON &thorn;e Maudeleyn day, a litelle bifor Lammesse,,</L>
<L>Of Scotlond &amp; Galway com mykelle folk alle fresse,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Marche &amp; &thorn;e ildes, a spere &thorn;ei suld bring,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei com &thorn;e lond to schilde, to Faukirke in &thorn;e mornyng.</L>
<L>Our Inglis men &amp; &thorn;ei &thorn;er togidere mette,</L>
<L>&thorn;er formast conrey, &thorn;er bakkis togidere sette,
<PB REF="00000533.tif" N="305"></L>
<L>&thorn;er speres poynt ouer poynt, so sare &amp; o &thorn;ikke,</L>
<L>&amp; fast togidere joynt, to se it was ferlike.</L>
<L>Als a castelle &thorn;ei stode, &thorn;at were walled with stone,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei wende no man of blode, &thorn;orgh &thorn;am suld haf gone.</L>
<L>&thorn;er folk was so mykelle, so stalworth &amp; so clene,</L>
<L>&thorn;er foyntes forward prikelle, nonhut wild &thorn;ei wene.</L>
<L>&thorn;at if alle Inglond fro Berwik vnto Kent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ad Fau|kirke.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e folk &thorn;erin men fond had bien &thorn;ider sent,</L>
<L>Stength suld non haf had, to perte &thorn;am &thorn;orgh oute,</L>
<L>So wer &thorn;ei set sad with poyntes rounde aboute.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng sauh &thorn;am comand so sadly in &thorn;e mede,</L>
<L>His folk he did with stand, &amp; dight &thorn;am alle to dede,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he to &thorn;am said, "go we &thorn;er God vs spede.</L>
<L>&thorn;er lances alle forth laid, &amp; ilk man broched his stede,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei sauh kynge's banere, raumpand &thorn;re lebardes,</L>
<L>&thorn;er hors folk alle plenere, &thorn;ei fled as fals cowardes.</L>
<L>&thorn;e fotefolk left alon, if &thorn;ei wild stand or fle,</L>
<L>Help had &thorn;ei non, of &thorn;am &thorn;er hede suld be.</L>
<L>&thorn;us &thorn;e Waleis wrouht, &amp; said &thorn;an &thorn;is bi skille,</L>
<L>"To &thorn;e renge ere &yogh;e brouht, hop now if &yogh;e wille.</L>
<L>&thorn;er scheltron sone was shad with Inglis &thorn;at were gode,</L>
<L>Pite of non &thorn;ei had, bot alle to dede &yogh;ode,</L>
<L>Als fleihes doun &thorn;ei fleih, ten &thorn;ousand at ones.</L>
<L>To stand non ne degh, bot felle doun als stones.</L>
<L>Bituex prime &amp; none alle voide was &thorn;e place.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bataile slayn &amp; done alle within &thorn;at space.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et nes vn des Englays fu &middot; mort ne maygne, Fors Bryan de Jay, chiualer alo|se, Haut mestre du temple de ca mere assigne, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Was no man Inglis maynhed no dede &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Bot a templer of pris, Sir Brian &thorn;e geay,
<PB REF="00000534.tif" N="306"></L>
<L>Maister templere he was on &thorn;is half &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>He folowed &thorn;e Scottis pas, whan &thorn;e bigan to fle,</L>
<L>Fer in tille a wod, men calle it Kalenters,</L>
<L>&thorn;er in a mire a mod, withouten help of fers,</L>
<L>Slouh &thorn;ei Sir Brian alon wi&thorn;outen mo.</L>
<L>Allas! &thorn;at douhty man, &thorn;at he so fer suld go!</L>
<L>&thorn;e Walsch folk &thorn;at tide did nou&thorn;er ille no gode,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei held &thorn;am alle bi side, opon a hille &thorn;ei stode.</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;ei stode &thorn;at while, tille the bataile was don,</L>
<L>Was neuer withouten gile Walsh man no Breton.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei were euer in wehere, men so of &thorn;am told,</L>
<L>Whilk was best bauere, with &thorn;at side forto hold.</L>
<L>&para; Saynt Bede sais it for lore, &amp; I say it in ryme,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Dicta San|cti Bed&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Walsh man salle neuer more luf Inglis man no tyme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER &thorn;is bataile &thorn;e kyng turned ageyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Expedivit se ad nup|cias secun|dum man|datum pap&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;at fals pedaile he ordeynd a wardeyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;at held &thorn;am in suilk awe, &thorn;ei durst no more rise,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh smerthed of &thorn;e law he did &thorn;am justise.</L>
<L>He &yogh;ared his `his<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dele.</NOTE> wendyng, to London gan him rape,</L>
<L>&thorn;ider him com ti&thorn;ing, lettres fro &thorn;e pape,</L>
<L>&amp; bad &thorn;at he suld take &thorn;e kyng sister of France,</L>
<L>For Gascoyn pes to make &thorn;orgh &thorn;at aliance,</L>
<L>Not dame Blanche &thorn;e suete, &thorn;at I first of spake,</L>
<L>Bot dame Margarete, gode withouten lak.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e pape's maundement he resceyued curtasly,</L>
<L>Bi tyme &thorn;at it were ent he dight &thorn;erto redy,
<PB REF="00000535.tif" N="307"></L>
<L>In purueiance of alle as he had most to don</L>
<L>So com &thorn;e erle Marschalle baitand to London;</L>
<L>Of Herford &thorn;e erle Umfray also com he &thorn;idere,</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er barons of nobley, &amp; alle samned togidere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle for &thorn;am alle with luf bisouht &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>Of poyntis behoued falle, do &thorn;am at &thorn;er praying.</L>
<L>"Withoute any delay do mak &thorn;e purale</L>
<L>"Be a certeyn day, Sir, &thorn;at pray we &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng wild his myght delaied it were alle weys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Pulcra pro|missio Regis &amp; vana.</NOTE></L>
<L>No&thorn;eles semand bi sight his ansuere was curteys.</L>
<L>He schewed &thorn;e erle Rogere &thorn;e pape's mandement,</L>
<L>He myght on no manere do nouht or it were ent,</L>
<L>Bot he suore on his fayth, &amp; certeynly &thorn;an hete,</L>
<L>Whan it were don in grayth &thorn;e weddyng of Margarete,</L>
<L>To mak &thorn;e purale, it suld not be delaied,</L>
<L>With suilk men suld it be, &thorn;at &thorn;ei suld hald &thorn;am paied.</L>
<L>So faire with his respons, so faithfulle &thorn;ei bisemed</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e erles &amp; barons, his wordes alle &thorn;ei quemed,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle Umfray &thorn;at was, for euer tok his leue,</L>
<L>&thorn;e dede him slouh, allas! tille his pers it gan greue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE pape &thorn;an sent his bulle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, vnto.</NOTE> vnt Philip of France,</L>
<L>&thorn;e curte of Rome fulle has ordand aliance,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng Edward suld wed Margarete,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Bulla pap&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;at ilk forward, &middot; &thorn;er werryng suld &thorn;ei lete</L>
<L>For euer in Gascoyn of alle maner of skille,</L>
<L>Without any essoyn, Philip grantid &thorn;er tille.</L>
<L>Philip for &thorn;at may mad purueiance redy,</L>
<L>With folk of gode aray to Douer com in hy,
<PB REF="00000536.tif" N="308"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er oure Inglis men resceyued fulle miry.</L>
<L>&thorn;e barons alle with blis brouht hir to Canterbiri,</L>
<L>&amp; as &thorn;e courte of Rome had ordeynd &thorn;at spousale,</L>
<L>Right opon &thorn;at dome he weddid hir sanzfaile.</L>
<L>Robert of Wynchelse, &thorn;at corseynt is verray,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De nupciis Regis &amp; Marga|ret&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Did &thorn;at solem pnite opon a Wednesday,</L>
<L>Next &thorn;e lattere fest &thorn;at is of our Lady.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Wednesday formest &thorn;e kyng had fulle grete hy.</L>
<L>For on &thorn;e morn he went his way toward Scotland,</L>
<L>With ille auisement he did, &amp; &thorn;at he fand.</L>
<L>Whan he was in &thorn;e Marche, he samned his oste,</L>
<L>&thorn;an was it bot a parche, &amp; litelle with &thorn;e loste.</L>
<L>For him self alone toke &thorn;at viage,</L>
<L>Help asked he none of alle his baronage,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was for &thorn;e purale, &thorn;at he had &thorn;am hette,</L>
<L>He wild not do &thorn;er gre, &thorn;at terme &thorn;at he sette.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis wist &thorn;at wele, &amp; schewed him &thorn;e vis,</L>
<L>&thorn;er side was ilk a dele, in poynt to wynne &thorn;e pris.</L>
<L>Boldely &thorn;ei bed bataile with visage fulle austere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kynge's side gan faile, for he had no powere.</L>
<L>Ferrere mot he nouht, Scotlond forto se,</L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme no &thorn;ing he wrouht, bot spendid his mone.</L>
<L>&thorn;e marche vnder wardeyn he left als it was ore,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e South ageyn he went, &amp; did no more.</L>
<L>Whi &thorn;at he not sped, &thorn;is skille mot it be,</L>
<L>With hauelon &thorn;am led, to mak &thorn;e purale.
<PB REF="00000537.tif" N="309"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE kyng after &thorn;e Pask his messengere sent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De parlia|mento apud Londone.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e bisshopes askis to com to &thorn;e parlement,</L>
<L>For erles &amp; barons at London suld it be,</L>
<L>Four<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, knyghtes.</NOTE> knyghtes be somons chosen in ilk counte.</L>
<L>&para; First &thorn;e nemnid alle &thorn;e, &thorn;e purale suld make,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prima ra|cio.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;orgh &thorn;e reame suld go, &thorn;e boundes forto stake.</L>
<L>Whan it wer brouht tille ende, &amp; stabled &amp; sette,</L>
<L>To gyue &thorn;e penie tuentende &thorn;e kyng &thorn;er &thorn;ei hette.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is was &thorn;e to&thorn;er reson, men &thorn;an suld &thorn;ei &yogh;are<NOTE PLACE="marg">Secunda.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e lond of Gascon, to Rome forto fare,</L>
<L>To wite at &thorn;e pape, why he mad delay,</L>
<L>&thorn;e tyme he wild not rape, no set a certeyn day,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Edward suld haue &thorn;e lond of Gascoun,</L>
<L>His seignorie to saue, als it was resoun.</L>
<L>&para; Now was &thorn;is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde of &thorn;at parlement,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Tercia.</NOTE></L>
<L>For chance &thorn;at him bitidde, &thorn;e kyng &thorn;us &thorn;am bisent.</L>
<L>"I praie &yogh;ow in &thorn;is nede, to help me with &yogh;our oste,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e Scottis on me bede, I wild abate &thorn;er boste.</L>
<L>To maynten his partie &thorn;ei hete to help him wele,</L>
<L>He aiorned &thorn;am to relie in &thorn;e North at Carlele,</L>
<L>After Midesomer's tide &thorn;orgh comon ordinance,</L>
<L>No lenger suld &thorn;ei bide, bot forth &amp; stand to chance.</L>
<L>Norreis &amp; Surreis, &thorn;at seruise auht &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>With hors &amp; herneis at Carlele mad samnyng.</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle Marschalle Rogere no hele &thorn;at tyme mot haue,</L>
<L>He went with his banere Sir Jon &thorn;e Segraue,</L>
<L>To do alle &thorn;o seruise &thorn;at longed &thorn;e office tille,</L>
<L>&amp; mayntend alle &thorn;e prise, &thorn;er he sauh lawe &amp; skille.
<PB REF="00000538.tif" N="310"></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e quene Margerete with childe &thorn;an was sche,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng bad hir not lete, bot com to &thorn;e North cuntre<NOTE PLACE="marg">Natus est Thomas fi|lius Regis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Unto Brotherton, on wherfe &thorn;er scho was</L>
<L>&amp; lighter of a sonne, &thorn;e child hight Thomas.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e kyng herd say, sho had so wele farn,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Ly Reis vers Escoce son chemyn reprent, La Rey|ne oue son fiz a Cawode atent Sure Owse la ryuer assez esement, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;ider he went way, to se hir &amp; hir barn,</L>
<L>&amp; with hir he soiorned, tille sho was purified,</L>
<L>&thorn;an eft agayn he turned, &amp; tille his ost hied.</L>
<L>&thorn;e quene with hir sonnc at Cawod leues she,</L>
<L>Tille tyme com eftson on Ouse fulle ese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Karlele is &thorn;e kyng with erles &amp; barons,</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;ei mad spekyng, to renne on &thorn;er felons.</L>
<L>Bot som of &thorn;am &thorn;at ware conseild o&thorn;er manere,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh pastours forto fare, for bestes to lardere.</L>
<L>Men said &thorn;er were inowe in mores &amp; in medis,</L>
<L>"&amp;, if &yogh;e wille, we mowe of bestis do gode nedis.</L>
<L>&thorn;e cuntre herd it seie, &thorn;e folk of ilk a schire</L>
<L>Had &thorn;er bestis aweie &thorn;orgh mede &amp; &thorn;orgh mire,</L>
<L>&thorn;at no strange man knewe ne myght so go,</L>
<L>&thorn;er to &thorn;e rayne bigan, &amp; flowand bank &amp; bro.</L>
<L>It ran doun on &thorn;e mountayns, &amp; drenkled &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> playn.</NOTE> playnes,</L>
<L>Sir Edward sauh &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> paynes, &amp; tok &thorn;e gate agayn,</L>
<L>&thorn;e more<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>L.</I> he.</NOTE> h forsoke, &thorn;e fote men ilk a flok,</L>
<L>A pouere hamlete toke, &thorn;e castelle Karclauerok.
<PB REF="00000539.tif" N="311"></L>
<L>In alle &thorn;is grete pres praied &thorn;e kyng of France,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis suld haf pes &thorn;orgh Edward sufferance.</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e messengere, &thorn;at Philip to him sent,</L>
<L>He gaf &thorn;e treus a &yogh;ere, &amp; &thorn;an to London went.</L>
<L>Feyntise, li&thorn;t duellyng, on mornes long to lie,</L>
<L>Surfeyte in euenyng, &amp; luf of licchorie,</L>
<L>Affiance of feloun, of enmys haf pite,</L>
<L>Wille without resoun, conseile of wise men fle,</L>
<L>Wynnyng forto hold, &amp; gyue not largely,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Bretons men of told, forsoke suilk party.</L>
<L>Of Arthure men say, &thorn;at rede of him in pas,</L>
<L>Alle tymes in medle euer more first he was</L>
<L>Mornyng &amp; euenyng, sobre &amp; honest.</L>
<L>Felons &thorn;at wild him greue, or enmys &thorn;at mad chest,</L>
<L>Als he was wor&thorn;i had he jugement.</L>
<L>Had he of non merci, for praiere no present,</L>
<L>At conseil &amp; at nede he was a skilfulle kyng,</L>
<L>So curteis of non men rede, ne prince of more praysing</L>
<L>Was non in Cristendam, als he was in his tyme,</L>
<L>Ne suilk on &yogh;it non cam &thorn;at man may mak of ryme.</L>
<L>I told &yogh;ow &thorn;is resoun, &amp; for ensample sette,</L>
<L>If &thorn;e kyng wild haf don &thorn;e purale als he hette,</L>
<L>&thorn;orghout Inglond, enselid &amp; with scrite,</L>
<L>Bi tyme had mad &thorn;at bond, &amp; drawen it not o lite,</L>
<L>It had bien his heires prowe, &thorn;e lond had bien alle his,</L>
<L>Long tyme or now, &thorn;at now in aucnture is.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date a &thorn;ousand was, &amp; &thorn;re hundred euen,</L>
<L>At Lincoln &thorn;e parlement was in Lyndesay &amp; Kesteuen.
<PB REF="00000540.tif" N="312"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT &thorn;e Pask afterward his parlement set he,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Parliamen|tum apud Lincolne.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e gode kyng Edward, at Lyncoln his cite.</L>
<L>At Sant Katerine hous &thorn;e erle Marschalle lay,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e brode gate lay &thorn;e Brus, erle was he &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng lay at Netilham, it is &thorn;e bisshope's toun.</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er lordes &thorn;er cam in &thorn;e cuntre vp &amp; doun.</L>
<L>&para; Erles &amp; barons at &thorn;er first samnyng,</L>
<L>For many maner resons pleyned of &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e purale did not als he suld,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;er chartre gaf fre, &thorn;e poyntes vse ne wuld,</L>
<L>Ne suffre &thorn;am to hold, &thorn;at &thorn;e chartre of spake,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh mayntenours bold, &thorn;e poyntes alle &thorn;ei brake.</L>
<L>&yogh;it &thorn;ei said him tille, his ministres wasted &thorn;e lond,</L>
<L>Tak &thorn;ing out of skille, &amp; pay not with hond.</L>
<L>&para; &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei mad pleynt of his tresorere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at fele &thorn;inges atteynt he mayntend &thorn;orgh powere,</L>
<L>Fordos vsages olde, &amp; lawes of &thorn;e chekere,</L>
<L>"Of many has it bien tolde, to &thorn;e we pleyn vs here,</L>
<L>"Him for to remue &thorn;orgh comon assent.</L>
<L>"Assigne it for more prow at &thorn;is parlement,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at can &thorn;at office guye, &amp; do &thorn;e right vsage,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at no man thar eft crie, for wrong &amp; outrage.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kynge's ansuere was smert, &amp; said, "I se<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> &thorn;he wille,</L>
<L>"&thorn;orgh pride of hert, reuile me with vnskille,</L>
<L>"&amp; so lowe me to chace, myn officers to change,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Responsio Regis.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&amp; mak &thorn;am at &yogh;our grace, &thorn;at were me ouer strange.</L>
<L>"It is non of &yogh;ow, &thorn;at he ne wille at his myght</L>
<L>"IIaf sergeanz for his prow, withouten o&thorn;er sight.
<PB REF="00000541.tif" N="313"></L>
<L>"Salle no man put &thorn;orgh skille his lord lowere &thorn;an he,</L>
<L>"Ne I ne salle no wille, to while I kyng salle be.</L>
<L>"If any of myn mad strife, or tak &thorn;ing not right,</L>
<L>"Stiward or balife, schewe &thorn;er wrong &thorn;orgh sight:</L>
<L>"&thorn;at wrong I wille so mende, if &thorn;at it be atteynt,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at non thar com no sende to courte to mak eft pleynt.</L>
<L>&para;<NOTE PLACE="foot">La chartre des fraunchises &amp; du puraler Deffrount ma coroune, si ieo les day graun|ter, La quele ouesk moy vous deuez en moy susport, Qele ne soit blamye par prise ne par prier. Par qai ieo vous graunte, le drait examiner Par. xxvi. descrez, qe voysent iorer, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gull.</I></NOTE> "&thorn;e chartre &thorn;orgh resoun &amp; &thorn;e purale</L>
<L>"&thorn;ei for do my croune, if &thorn;ei granted be,</L>
<L>"&thorn;e whilk &yogh;e salle &amp; ouh, to maynten with me</L>
<L>"To mak it lesse no louh, ne peired salle it be.</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;is I grant to morn, &thorn;at &yogh;e trie &thorn;is &thorn;ing</L>
<L>"With sex &amp; tuenti suorn, if I to &yogh;our askyng</L>
<L>"May acorde right wele, &thorn;e coroune forto saue</L>
<L>"Dismembred not a dele, &yogh;our askyng salle &yogh;e haue.</L>
<L>"A no&thorn;er I am withoute of penie in tresorie,</L>
<L>"In lond withouten doute salle help me a partie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE wisest of &thorn;e clergie, with erles &amp; barons,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Consilia inter se fe|cerunt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Togider went to trie of &thorn;er peticions.</L>
<L>&thorn;o sex &amp; tuenti &yogh;ede, &thorn;at were suorn &thorn;er tille,</L>
<L>Of ilk doute &amp; dredc &thorn;ei said &amp; set &thorn;e skille,</L>
<L>Discharged wille &thorn;ei be of &thorn;e grete oth &thorn;ei suore,</L>
<L>Perille forto fle, &thorn;e poyntes were so store.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Dicta ba|ronum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e sent ageyn &amp; said to kyng, "it was no haunte</L>
<L>"Of certeyn sette &amp; laid, to trechet &thorn;er conaunte,
<PB REF="00000542.tif" N="314"></L>
<L>"No tille prince no kyng it is no maner told</L>
<L>"To mak eft lokyng, ne deme &thorn;at dere was sold.</L>
<L>"Sir, fairere &thorn;e wore, graunte vs &thorn;i curteysie,</L>
<L>"&thorn;an parties pinched more, &thorn;e auantage set so hie,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;ou may gyue with right, whan &thorn;ou wille &amp; how,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at salle not be &thorn;orgh sight demed of lesse &thorn;an &thorn;ou.</L>
<L>"Put &thorn;e not so louh, to deme &thorn;i power fre,</L>
<L>"&yogh;eld vs &thorn;at &thorn;ou ouh, &amp; we salle luf &thorn;e,</L>
<L>"&amp; serue &thorn;e we wille alle at &thorn;in avis,</L>
<L>"&amp; help &thorn;e at skille, to renne on &thorn;in enmys.</L>
<L>&para; He sent &thorn;am bode ageyn, schortely to say &amp; here,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Non vult Rex adqui|escere dictis baro|num.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;er prayere was in veyn, to ese &thorn;am in no manere;</L>
<L>His wille &amp; his auise, &thorn;at he asked certeyn.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei &yogh;ede be partise, disputed &thorn;er ageyn.</L>
<L>&thorn;e parties wer so felle altercand on ilk side,</L>
<L>&thorn;at non &thorn;e soth couth telle, whedir pes or werre suld tidc,</L>
<L>Bot God &thorn;at is of myght, &amp; may help whan he wille.</L>
<L>For for bo&thorn;e &thorn;e parties dight, &amp; put &thorn;am in &thorn;is skille,</L>
<L>&thorn;at or Michelmesse &thorn;ei suld reise to &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L>&thorn;e fiftend penie no lesse, for &thorn;er Chartre selyng,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;e purale, set with certeyn bounde,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e lond suld be delaied no lengere stounde,</L>
<L>On &thorn;at &thorn;ei grantid, &amp; abated alle &thorn;er &thorn;ro,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e kyng wild &thorn;am calle, to Scotlond suld &thorn;ei go.</L>
<L>&para; &yogh;it our<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> messengrs for Gascoyn were at Rome,</L>
<L>Foure lordes fulle fers, to here &thorn;e pape's dome,</L>
<L>&thorn;er foure at Rome ware, to areson &thorn;e pape,</L>
<L>&thorn;e right forto declare, &amp; for &thorn;e parties so schape,
<PB REF="00000543.tif" N="315"></L>
<L>To whom &thorn;e right suld be of Gascoyn euer &amp; ay,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;orgh his decre &thorn;e pes pronunce a day.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape Boniface tok Philip messengers,</L>
<L>&amp; ours in o place, sette &thorn;am to mete als pers,</L>
<L>&amp; preched to &thorn;am alle, als &thorn;ei sat in fere,</L>
<L>"Lordyng &thorn;us salle falle, as I salle say here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"MEN say in &yogh;our tuo londes ere men of grete resoun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce qu&aelig; pa pa dixit Nunciis Franci&aelig; &amp; Angli&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&amp; wele vnderstondes, &amp; knowes &thorn;er enchesoun.</L>
<L>"&thorn;o ilk men so wise suld go, &amp; enforme &yogh;our kynges,</L>
<L>"Withouten mo justise or trauaile of o&thorn;er lordynges.</L>
<L>"&thorn;erfore gos ageyn, &amp; tille &yogh;our kynges say,</L>
<L>"Bot &thorn;ei with luf certeyn acorde in euen way,</L>
<L>"&amp; if &thorn;ei ne do, be Saynt Petir of Rome,</L>
<L>"Our courte sallc ordeyn so on &thorn;am so hard dome,</L>
<L>"At &thorn;e next feste &thorn;at comes of S. Andrew,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at &thorn;ei &amp; alle &thorn;er geste &thorn;at dome salle doute &amp; rew.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e messengers &thorn;ei &yogh;ede, bare &thorn;ei with &thorn;am no more,</L>
<L>I turne ageyn to rede of &thorn;e parlement we spak ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE kyng gaf his sonne at &thorn;e parlement<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex dedit Walliam filio suo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wales in to wonne, &amp; Chestre shire to rent.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et Pountif &amp; Monstroyl|le, oue lonour qe apent, Le fiz &amp; [<I>vel</I> est] Prince &amp; Count, e les homages prent, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Mustrelle &amp; Pountif, &thorn;at er bi&yogh;ond &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>Prince he was vp rif, &amp; erle also was he.</L>
<L>Of him &thorn;at held &thorn;er londes &thorn;ei mad him alle homage,</L>
<L>To Scotlond now he fondes, to redy his viage,
<PB REF="00000544.tif" N="316"></L>
<L>With &thorn;ritti &thorn;ousand Walsh redy at his banere,</L>
<L>Erles &amp; barons als, bo&thorn;e knyght &amp; squiere</L>
<L>Alle com to Carlele, to conseil how were best,</L>
<L>To passe &thorn;e Scottis se wele, to tak to ward &thorn;e West.</L>
<L>His fader also &yogh;ede, &amp; chefe &thorn;e Est side,</L>
<L>At Berwik opon Tuede, his ost did &thorn;er bide.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ALS &thorn;ei were alle plenere to counseil &amp; to schape,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nuncins pap&aelig; epi|scopus de Spolete ve|nit ad Re|gem.</NOTE></L>
<L>So com a messengere fro Boniface &thorn;e pape</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Spolete, with a newe ordinance.</L>
<L>A no&thorn;er him gan mete, comand fro &thorn;e kyng of France.</L>
<L>I herd neuer telle, for what maner discert,</L>
<L>&thorn;er on I most nede duelle, tille it com out aperte.</L>
<L>&para;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Resceu ad ly Reis la let|tre de creaunce, Et ly messa|gers entendu la sustaunce. Sa gwere sur Escoce ad mys en suffraunce, A Lynliscou reuent, son fiz saunz tari|aunce, <I>&amp;c. MSS Gall. nisi quod</I> saunz <I>de sit in Cod. Anstisiano.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e kyng has &thorn;e letter in hand, to trowe &thorn;at &thorn;ei said,</L>
<L>&thorn;e werryng in Scotland now is delaied &amp; laid.</L>
<L>Ho com to Linliscow, &amp; did &thorn;er crie his pes,</L>
<L>&amp; teld his barons how, &thorn;at nede behoued him ses.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he &amp; his sonne turned toward &thorn;e South,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Marche als it was wonne, keped wardeyns couth.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e turned to London, of &thorn;e treus to speke,</L>
<L>&amp; fey&thorn;ly &thorn;erto bondon, on no manere to breke.</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e terme for told, of Saynt Andrewmesse,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape did him hold, with gode sikernesse.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape set &thorn;at terme, for his hopyng was,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pes &thorn;ei suld afferme, for drede of hardere kas.
<PB REF="00000545.tif" N="317"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Luy quens Gyllam de Flaundres, vers qi conten|cioun Ly Rey de Fraunce aueit, par sodayn achesoun, Vilement estait trahy par Charloun, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>KYNG Philip of France had erle William<NOTE PLACE="marg">Bellum in|ter Fran|ciam &amp; Flandriam.</NOTE></L>
<L>A cheson for a chance, I ne wote whi it cam.</L>
<L>Charles to William hette, he suld him sauely lede</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e parlement sette ageyn withouten drede.</L>
<L>Whan William was comen, &amp; wende no tresoun,</L>
<L>Sone was he nomen, &amp; don in prisoun.</L>
<L>Now is &thorn;e erle &thorn;us schent, bondon in iren &amp; stele,</L>
<L>Philip to Flandres sent, &amp; sesid it ilk a dele,</L>
<L>&amp; mad suilk wardeyns in his name to be,</L>
<L>Destroied at &thorn;e geyns, &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot find or se,</L>
<L>Defoules &thorn;er wyues, &thorn;er douhtres lay bi,</L>
<L>&thorn;er lordes slouh with knyues, of fo had &thorn;ei merci.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e tounes spak of &thorn;is, &thorn;e folk gadred aboute,</L>
<L>To renne on &thorn;e Frankis, &thorn;ei samned gret route.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei folowed on &thorn;am hard &thorn;orgh out &thorn;at cuntre,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Frankis &amp; Pikard alle were fayn to fle.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at fleih &thorn;ei ferd vnto &thorn;e kyng of France,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng he it herd, tak he wille vengeance.</L>
<L>Of knyght &amp; of burgeis an oste he did relie,</L>
<L>Bitauht it &thorn;e erle of Arteys, &thorn;at oste forto guye.</L>
<L>He did &thorn;er no prow, he was first was doun,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Un ribaud li tuayt saunz confessioun, <I>Gall.</I></NOTE>A foule herlote him slowe, trut for his renoun;</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er withouten numbir, &thorn;er names I may not telle,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ei &yogh;ede tille encumbir, &amp; er went to Helle.
<PB REF="00000546.tif" N="318"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne Normaund, ne Pi|kard, ne ly Burgylloun, Ne Vienays, ne Bascle, ne Bra|ban, ne Bretouns, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Of Huneys er &thorn;ei clene, Pikard &amp; Burgoilloun,</L>
<L>Of Bascel &amp; Viene, of Braban &amp; Bretoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;at tyme no at a no&thorn;er had &thorn;e Frankis no foisoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei &amp; alle &thorn;e to&thorn;er &thorn;e Flemmynges laid &thorn;am doun.</L>
<L>&thorn;at schame has &yogh;it non ende, no &thorn;at vpbraidyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;at on France salle lende, for falsnes of &thorn;er kyng.</L>
<L>Now salle we turne ageyn tille our owen lessoun,</L>
<L>Whan Charles courte is pleyn, I gyue it my malisoun.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e date was euenlik, a &thorn;ousand &thorn;re hundred &amp; tuo,<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. CCC<SUP>o</SUP>. II<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Count de Kar|ryk les Escotz werpist As genz le Rey Edward de gre se rendist. Ly quens Vum|fray de Boune cel an a fem|me prist La fylle al Rey Edward, Elizabeth est dist, <I>&amp;c. Gall.</I></NOTE>Whan &thorn;e erle of Karrik turned &thorn;e Scottis fro.</L>
<L>Sir Umfrey Boun &thorn;e kyng his wife wedded &thorn;at &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Edward douhter &thorn;e kyng, Elizabeth &thorn;at clere.</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;ise spekynges men &yogh;ede &thorn;at wer wise</L>
<L>Bituexen &thorn;ise tuo kynges, &thorn;at no contek suld rise,</L>
<L>Bot contene forth &thorn;e trew vnto &thorn;e Paske's terme</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e Saynt Andrew, so long &thorn;e pes to afferme.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is &thorn;e kyng of France praied Sir Edward,</L>
<L>&thorn;at with his sufferance &amp; leue in forward</L>
<L>Suffre &thorn;e Scottis to go, &thorn;at men &thorn;at he for sent.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Peticio pro Scottis facta.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng tille alle &thorn;o gaf leue, &amp; &thorn;ei alle went.</L>
<L>&para; For perille of suilk goynges &thorn;e kyng purueied to go,</L>
<L>Sir Jon of Hastynges he was first of &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; Sir Emery &thorn;e Brette, to<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic.</NOTE> Goscoyn forto wende,</L>
<L>To bide &thorn;e terme sette, &thorn;e treus how it suld ende.
<PB REF="00000547.tif" N="319"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Nos Englays crioums, laschesse sait maldist, [<I>vel</I>, soit maudit] Kar qaunt al melz ferir, [<I>vel</I>, a meuz ferrir,] plus auoms delit. Deshonour nous veent [<I>vel</I>, vynt] &amp; pert par respit, Jeo parle pur le|scot, qe laltrere assayllist, Nos Englays en Escoce par as|saut subit. Sire Jon de Se|graue son chemyn reprist, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e Inglis men were wone, to wery long trayne;</L>
<L>Of bataile better cone, lite was alle &thorn;er payne.</L>
<L>Dishonour haf &thorn;ei ay of &thorn;er long respite,</L>
<L>I spak &thorn;is for a day, &thorn;e Scottis assailed &thorn;am tite,</L>
<L>&para; Our men in Scotland with sautes sodeynly.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Segraue myght not stand, Sir Jon tok the gayn stie.<NOTE PLACE="marg">De fuga Johannis Segraue &amp; occisione Anglorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>His sonne &amp; his bro&thorn;er of bedde als &thorn;ei woke,</L>
<L>&amp; sextene knyghtes o&thorn;er, &thorn;e Scottis alle &thorn;am toke.</L>
<L>Sergeantz wele &thorn;ritty alle &yogh;ald &thorn;am &thorn;at while,</L>
<L>On &thorn;ei slouh smertly, Sir Thomas de Neuile.</L>
<L>Sir Rauf &thorn;e Coffrers &thorn;at tyme was Tresorere,</L>
<L>He was on of &thorn;er pers, his life was alle in wehere.</L>
<L>He bed grete catelle, his lif forto saue,</L>
<L>Sir Symon &thorn;e Freselle &thorn;at ilk catelle suld haue.</L>
<L>Symon was austere, to Rauf spak fulle grim:</L>
<L>"&thorn;at mad &thorn;e Tresorere &thorn;ou has desceyued him,</L>
<L>"&amp; me &amp; many mo, fro our wages &yogh;ede quite.</L>
<L>"Sir Rauf &thorn;ou resceyued &thorn;o, bi taile &amp; bi scrite,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou did vs more trauaile, ilk man &thorn;ou reft his wage.</L>
<L>"Now salle I wite &thorn;e taile, &amp; put &thorn;e in &thorn;e Arerage,</L>
<L>"Of preste &thorn;ou has no merke, albe ne non amite,</L>
<L>"Bot laced in a hauberke, &thorn;ai is no clerkis abite.</L>
<L>"For alle &thorn;o clerkes of Rome, &thorn;at sing in kirk or rede,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou salle haf &thorn;i dome, als &thorn;ou serued in dede.
<PB REF="00000548.tif" N="320"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Cofrere vn ribaud maintenant saisist, Les mayns ly copayt, la teste ly partist, <I>&amp; c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>A boye fulle pantenere he had a suerd &thorn;at bote,</L>
<L>He stirte vnto &thorn;e Cofrere, his handes first of smote,</L>
<L>&amp; fro &thorn;e body his heued a dynt &thorn;an did &thorn;e cleue,</L>
<L>His werryng so he leued, at armes he tok leue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN alle &thorn;is mykelle frape wex a grete distance<NOTE PLACE="marg">Contra|rietas facta inter pa|pam &amp; Re|gem Fran|ci&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of Boniface &thorn;e pape, &amp; &thorn;e kyng of France.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng said &amp; did crie, &thorn;e pape was heretike</L>
<L>Usure &amp; symonie, &amp; synne sodomike,</L>
<L>Errid mislyuyng, haunted Maumetrie,</L>
<L>Wastid kirkis &thorn;ing, &amp; lyued in bugerie,</L>
<L>&amp; was wor&thorn;i to schende bo&thorn;e soule &amp; lyf,</L>
<L>To die withouten ende, &thorn;is mad &thorn;e kyng vp ryf.</L>
<L>Pape Boniface herd telle of &thorn;at crie,</L>
<L>He did bifor his face com holy &thorn;e clergie,</L>
<L>To conseil what were best for &thorn;at vilanie,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei ageyn him kest, said on him heresie.</L>
<L>&thorn;is conseile alle &thorn;ei said, "lat it &yogh;it rest &amp; slepe,</L>
<L>"&thorn;is fame of &yogh;ow is laid, <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>F.</I> &thorn;ro.</NOTE>&thorn;o wise men &thorn;at were &yogh;epe.</L>
<L>"Wite, if he wille avowe alle his wikked sawe,</L>
<L>"Or amend &amp; bowe, &thorn;er on behoues vs drawe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape on &thorn;at couenaunt, he said, he wild so wirke,</L>
<L>&thorn;e amendis if he wild graunt to God &amp; holy kirke;</L>
<L>&amp; if he wild nouht com to amendement,</L>
<L>Alle France suld be brouht tille encumberment,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh comon enterdite, &amp; &thorn;orgh croiserie,</L>
<L>Als lond &thorn;at is alle quite fro God on ilk partie.
<PB REF="00000549.tif" N="321"></L>
<L>After salle &yogh;e here &thorn;e ende of &thorn;is folie,</L>
<L>Turne we tille our matere, &amp; on our gest to hie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date a &thorn;ousand was, &thorn;re hundred mo bi &thorn;re,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng did grete trespas, diffamed &thorn;e pape's se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e next somerestide Sir Edward had haste,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Devastatio Scottorum.</NOTE></L>
<L>No lenger wild he bide, Scotland for to waste.</L>
<L>Conseil he had of on, a brigge he suld do wrihte,</L>
<L>Botes &amp; barges ilkon, with flekes mak &thorn;am tighte,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis se to passe, if &thorn;at he had nede.</L>
<L>&thorn;er passage neuer ore wasse, he rode ouer on his stede.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis sauh him com, fleand fast &thorn;ei &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>Mores &amp; mountayns nom, bifore &thorn;ei dryue for drede.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng did parte his oste, to sprede in parties sere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Dividebat turmam suam circi|ter Scociam.</NOTE></L>
<L>West alle bi &thorn;at coste &yogh;ede &thorn;e erle of Hulnestere.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Luy Rey vers lorient enprent son aler, Hamelez &amp; villes, graunges &amp; gerner, Et playnes e voydes, par tote fet arder, <I>&amp; c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e kynge's oste at gesse in &thorn;e Est mad lardere,</L>
<L>Of tounes &amp; hamelesse, of granges &amp; garner,</L>
<L>More &amp; mede did rynce, wod &amp; playn he brent.</L>
<L>&thorn;e same way &thorn;e prince destroied &thorn;er he went,</L>
<L>So fer Northward he ferde, &thorn;e Scottis to cliace,</L>
<L>Of Inglis no man herde, &thorn;at euer kyng had &thorn;at grace,</L>
<L>So fer baner to bere, &amp; suilk oste forto lede,</L>
<L>No wasted with no werre, &thorn;e cuntres gan &thorn;am drede,</L>
<L>Saue kyng Athelstan, &thorn;at wastid alle Catenesse.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en was no man, &thorn;at so fer mad stressc,
<PB REF="00000550.tif" N="322"></L>
<L>&thorn;e tounes, &thorn;e countes, &thorn;e foreyns alle aboute,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng felle on knes, his powere did &thorn;am loute,</L>
<L>Un to his pes &thorn;am &yogh;ald, feaute did him suere,</L>
<L>Treuly with him to hald, non armes ageyn him bere.</L>
<L>&para; Be &thorn;at &thorn;e werre was ent wynter was &thorn;er &yogh;are,</L>
<L>To Dounfermelyn he went, for rest wild he &thorn;are.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e quene he sent, &amp; scho did dight hire chare,</L>
<L>Fro Cawod scho glent, to Dounefermelyn to fare.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lord of Badenauh, Freselle &amp; Waleis</L>
<L>Lyued at theues lauh, euer robband alle weis.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei had no sustenance, &thorn;e werre to mayntene,</L>
<L>Bot skulked opon chance, &amp; robbed ay bituene.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei com vnto &thorn;e kyng, for pes if it mot tide,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;er askyng, he iorned &thorn;am to bide.</L>
<L>Men bred for &thorn;at iorne, &thorn;ei suld haf had &thorn;e pes,</L>
<L>For eft &thorn;an suld men se, bigyn alle new &thorn;e res.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;at &yogh;ere it sais, &thorn;e pape had grete despite<NOTE PLACE="marg">De contro|versia inter papam &amp; Columpnos.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">See Platina <I>de vitis Pontifi|cum Rom.</I> p. 231. <I>Col. Agrip.</I> M.DC.XXVI. See likewise Lassels's <I>Voyage of Italy</I>, Part I. p. 246. Paris 1670. Ed. 2d.</NOTE> Columpneis, Cardinalles of habite.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei were born in Rome alle &thorn;e Columpneis,</L>
<L>&thorn;at kynde bare &thorn;e blome, riche men &amp; curteis.</L>
<L>Men said alle &thorn;at kynde had whilom &thorn;e dignite,</L>
<L>If clerke of &thorn;am myght fynde, pape suld he be.</L>
<L>&thorn;us &thorn;an was &thorn;e sawe whilom in &thorn;at cite,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape fordid &thorn;at lawe, &thorn;e skille can I not se.
<PB REF="00000551.tif" N="323"></L>
<L>Cardinals were &thorn;ei, &thorn;e pape did &thorn;am doun,</L>
<L>&amp; exiled &thorn;am awey, &amp; mad distructioun</L>
<L>Of londes &amp; feez, &thorn;er kastels doun he cast,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Destructio Columpno|rum per pa|pam Boni|facium.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;er dignitez, ne lengere suld &thorn;ei last,</L>
<L>Grete was &thorn;at linage &amp; many to &thorn;am cheued,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;at ilk outrage &thorn;e fest &thorn;am sore agreued.</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e pape did &thorn;am reuile of &thorn;o in Rome &thorn;at wore,</L>
<L>Went vnto Cezile, &thorn;ore help &thorn;ei fond wele more.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng of France &thorn;idere sent &thorn;am help inouh,</L>
<L>&thorn;er kynde &amp; &thorn;ei togidere vntille Anayne &thorn;ei drouh.</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;e Columpne kynde, &thorn;e pape forsoth &thorn;ei toke,</L>
<L>Tresore &thorn;at &thorn;ei mot fynde, with &thorn;am away &thorn;ei schoke.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Pape saunz viaunde fu. ii. iours en subit, Par eyde suruenaunt le terce iour issist [<I>vel</I> assit] <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>Tuo days &thorn;e pape withouten mete lay,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;rid day com grete frape, &amp; conged him away.</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at grete tresoure &thorn;at euer he biwan,</L>
<L>Als bare was his toure as Job &thorn;e pouere man.</L>
<L>Men sais he gaf pardoun, assoiled &thorn;am of pyne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at with deuocioun brouht him brede or wyne.</L>
<L>Grete pite it was, &thorn;at &thorn;e hede of Cristendam</L>
<L>Suld for any trespas take so foule a scham.</L>
<L>Wele I wote alle frayed he went fro &thorn;at cite</L>
<L>Vnto Rome mispayed to &thorn;e pape's se.</L>
<L>He cursed &thorn;e kyng of France, &amp; alle &thorn;at with him held,</L>
<L>&thorn;at did him &thorn;at mischance, ageyn him reised scheld.</L>
<L>He lyued bot &thorn;re days, &amp; died sone &thorn;ei said,</L>
<L>&thorn;e soner for &thorn;at affrays, at Petir kirke is he laid.
<PB REF="00000552.tif" N="324"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW haf we bulle certeyn, a newe pape Benet,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Absoluti sunt per Benedic|tum pap&amacr;m.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at calles &thorn;er ageyn, &thorn;at Boniface set,</L>
<L>Assoyles alle bi name, &thorn;o robbours &thorn;orgh grace,</L>
<L>&thorn;at did despite &amp; schame to pape Boniface.</L>
<L>Who may now in Rome haf any sikernesse,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;er is hiest dome, &amp; &yogh;it vncerteyn es?</L>
<L>&thorn;at Boniface bond with sentence so brim,</L>
<L>Eft men Benet fond, &thorn;at he assoiled him,</L>
<L>&para; <NOTE PLACE="foot">Molt est sotz &amp; fous, en Rome qe ceo fist, Pur quant posse dare, a graunt &amp; a petit, Par fare &amp; par defare, Rome nus derist, Ho la de choses par de ca dalyer nous suffist, <I>in the French Copy that be|longs to the Heralds Office, but in Mr. Anstis's</I>, Mult est fort &amp; fous en Rome qe ceo fit, Pro quante posse dare, a grant &amp; a petit, Bo la de chose par de cea dalier nous fit.</NOTE>He is folc &thorn;at affies in &thorn;e courte of Rome,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota bene.</NOTE></L>
<L>Comes a no&thorn;er &amp; bies, &amp; fordos &thorn;at dome.</L>
<L><I>Pur quante posse dare</I>, what &thorn;ing &amp; how mykelle,</L>
<L><I>Pur fare &amp; defare</I>, Rome is now fulle fikelle.</L>
<L>Turne we now o&thorn;er weys vnto our owen geste,</L>
<L>&amp; speke of &thorn;e Waleys, &thorn;at lies in &thorn;e foreste.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e forest he lendes of Dounfermelyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Willel|mo Waleys.</NOTE></L>
<L>He praied alle his frendes, &amp; o&thorn;er of his kyn,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at &yogh;ole &thorn;ei wilde biseke Edward,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he mot him &yogh;elde tille him in a forward</L>
<L>&thorn;at were honorable to kepe wod or beste,</L>
<L>&amp; with his scrite fulle stable, &amp; seled at &thorn;e lest,</L>
<L>To him &amp; alle hise to haf in heritage,</L>
<L>&amp; non o&thorn;er wise, als terme, tyme &amp; stage,
<PB REF="00000553.tif" N="325"></L>
<L>Bot als a propire &thorn;ing, &thorn;at were conquest tille him.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei brouht &thorn;at ti&thorn;ing, Edward was fulle grim,</L>
<L>&amp; bitauht him &thorn;e fende, als his traytoure in lond,</L>
<L>&amp; euer ilkon his frende, &thorn;at him susteynd or fond.</L>
<L>&thorn;re hundreth marke he hette vnto his warisoun,</L>
<L>&thorn;at with him so mette, or bring his hede to toun.</L>
<L>Now flies William Waleis, of pes nouht he spedis,</L>
<L>In mores &amp; mareis with robberie him fedes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HERE now how &thorn;ei sped, &thorn;e Scottis in his mercie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Symone Freselle.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e Freselle first fled, out taken on &thorn;er partie.</L>
<L>Tuo &yogh;ere out of Kith, in strange reame suld be,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;rid suld he haf grith, ageyn to haf his fe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e to&thorn;er alle suld haue bo&thorn;e lif &amp; lymmes,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er tenement saue, bot raunson of &thorn;am nunn es.</L>
<L>Raunson suld &thorn;ei gyue after &thorn;er folie,</L>
<L>&amp; in his pes to lyue, &amp; haf &thorn;er manauntie.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en in &thorn;e Lenten tide he went to Saynt Andrew,</L>
<L>About on ilk a side, did crie his pes alle new.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Glascow &thorn;e clergie alle out ches,</L>
<L>&thorn;e best men &amp; trew, &amp; com vnto &thorn;e pes.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng was so curteis, he granted &thorn;am &thorn;er wille,</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;e amendes he sais raunson for &thorn;er ille,</L>
<L>&amp; suld be bot right bifor &thorn;e baronie,</L>
<L>&amp; at &thorn;e comon sight of alle &thorn;er clergie.
<PB REF="00000554.tif" N="326"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER &thorn;e Pask sone &thorn;e kyng did make alle &yogh;are,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De capci|oneStriue|lyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is oste were bone, to Striuelyn to fare.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei were alle comen, &thorn;ei &yogh;ede about to se,</L>
<L>How it mot be nomen, &amp; &thorn;e engynes set suld be.</L>
<L>Thrittene grete engynes, of alle &thorn;e reame &thorn;e best,</L>
<L>Brouht &thorn;ei to Striuelyne, &thorn;e kastelle doun to kest.</L>
<L>Tuo knyghtes were &thorn;er in, &thorn;e castelle had in warde,</L>
<L>Sir William of Depplyn, Sir William Olifarde,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et. xx. gentyls homes, saunz pages &amp; porter, Un frere Jacobyn, vn moygne counsayller, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&amp; tuenti of honour, without page &amp; portere,</L>
<L>&amp; a frere prechoure, a monke &thorn;e conseilere.</L>
<L>&thorn;er was with in &thorn;rittene maydens &amp; ladies,</L>
<L>&amp; no mo men to mene, &thorn;at felle to telle of pris.</L>
<L>An engyn had &thorn;ei &thorn;er in, &amp; profred for to kast,</L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;erde brast in tuyn, to help mot it not last.</L>
<L>&thorn;e engyns with oute, to kast were &thorn;ei sette,</L>
<L>Wallis &amp; kirnels stoute, &thorn;e stones doun bette.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e kyng did mak right &yogh;are an hidous engyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;e name &thorn;ei cald Ludgare or Lurdare of Striuelyn.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei kest &thorn;erto, &thorn;e walle &thorn;orghout &thorn;ei clef,</L>
<L>&amp; non o&thorn;er did so bifor him alle doun dref.</L>
<L>&thorn;re monethes &amp; &thorn;re days &thorn;e sege so long &thorn;ei teld,</L>
<L>Fulle &amp; hard affrays had alle &thorn;o &thorn;at it held.</L>
<L>Sore &thorn;ei were trauailed, &amp; socour com &thorn;am non,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;er store failed, &thorn;er mete was nere gon.</L>
<L>Tille &thorn;er kyng &thorn;ei sent, &thorn;ei wild be at his wille,</L>
<L>Bot he wild not consent, he &thorn;ouht to do &thorn;am ille.
<PB REF="00000555.tif" N="327"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Taunt fust la traine longe de la pees parler, Ke ioe ne say ne pusse la maite recorder, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>So long was &thorn;e trayne, or it wer brouht to stalle,</L>
<L>It were to me grete payne, forto telle it alle.</L>
<L>I wote wele at &thorn;e last alle com &thorn;ei oute,</L>
<L>Withouten conaunt cast, tille his mercy gan loute.</L>
<L>Boldely &thorn;ei camen, &amp; schewed &thorn;am to his face,</L>
<L>Felle it to gode or grame, &thorn;ei did &thorn;am in his grace.</L>
<L>&thorn;e castelle now is &yogh;olden, &thorn;e kyng dos wardeyns wise,</L>
<L>To kepe &thorn;e lond &amp; dres, &thorn;e folk forto justise.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lond was so wast, he mad &thorn;er no soioure,</L>
<L>Tille Inglond in hast he turned with honoure.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e moneth of September &yogh;olden was Striuelyn,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecce de Traileba|stoun.</NOTE></L>
<L>Edward may remembre &thorn;e trauaile &amp; &thorn;e pyn.</L>
<L>With many grete encumbre of in hard stoure,</L>
<L>At Brustwik opon Humbre &thorn;er he mad soioure.</L>
<L>Sir Jon of Warenne &thorn;at ilk tyme gan deie,</L>
<L>His body was redy &thorn;en in graue forto leie.</L>
<L>After &thorn;e enterment &thorn;e kyng tok his way,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e South he went &thorn;orgh Lyndesay.</L>
<L>He spired as he &yogh;ede, who did suilk trespas,</L>
<L>Brak his pes with dede, tille he in Scotlond was,</L>
<L>Of suilk suld be spoken, if men of &thorn;am pleyned,</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;e pes had broken, if &thorn;ei mot be atteyned.</L>
<L>&para;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Re|spouns ount fet al Reiz gentz de bien voillaunce, Coment par my la tere fet est graunt greuaunce, Par commune contekours, qe sunt par fi|aunce Obligez ensemble a vne purueaunce, Traylba|stouns sunt nomez de cel re|tenaunce. En faires &amp; en marches se profrerent [<I>vel</I> proferent] fere couenaunce, Pur. iij. souz ou. iiii. ou pur la vayllaunce Batre vn prod|home, qe vnqes fist nosaunce, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> Wise men of gode gaf ansuere to &thorn;e kyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Traile|bastone per totum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at suilk foles &yogh;ode, it was certeyn &thorn;ing,
<PB REF="00000556.tif" N="328"></L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e lond is don suilk grete greuance,</L>
<L>Bot it be mendid son, a werre may rise o chance.</L>
<L>&thorn;ise contekours whidere &thorn;ei assigned a stede &thorn;at es,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;er &thorn;ei com togidere &amp; mak a sikernes,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei salle alle go, to whom or where &thorn;ei wille,</L>
<L>To robbe, bete or slo, ageyn alle manere skille.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei profere a man to bete, for tuo schilynges or &thorn;re,</L>
<L>With piked staues grete, beten salle he be.</L>
<L>In feire &amp; markette &thorn;ei salle seke him oute,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e lond is sette with suilk foles stoute.</L>
<L>If a chapman wille not lene of his merchaundie,</L>
<L>In his hous for tene &thorn;ei do him vilenie,</L>
<L>Or els he be at one largely to gyue of his,</L>
<L>Els &thorn;ei salle him ilkone bete him &thorn;at he pis.</L>
<L>For men of suilk maners, bot &thorn;er be som justise,</L>
<L>Sone in for &yogh;ers per chance a werre salle rise.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng herd alle &thorn;e fame, &thorn;e pleynt of ilka toun,</L>
<L>&amp; gaf &thorn;am a newe name, &amp; cald &thorn;am Traile bastoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e date was a &thorn;ousand &thorn;re hundred mo bi fiue,</L>
<L>Suilk men &thorn;orgh &thorn;e land he did &thorn;am tak bilyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE kyng &thorn;orgh &thorn;e lond did seke men o resons,</L>
<L>&amp; with &thorn;e justise &thorn;am bond, to site on Trailebastons.</L>
<L>Som &thorn;orgh quest &thorn;ei demed be bonden in prisons,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o &thorn;at fled &thorn;ei flemed als &thorn;e kynge's felons.
<PB REF="00000557.tif" N="329"></L>
<L>Som men out &thorn;e kast of lond was holden wrong,</L>
<L>Fals couenantz &thorn;ei brast &thorn;orgh powere holden long,</L>
<L>&amp; som gaf raunson after &thorn;er trespas,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e dede was don, so &thorn;e amendes was.</L>
<L>Bot men did amend suilk folie openly knowen,</L>
<L>Non suld &thorn;am defend, ne dur wonne in &thorn;er owen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A! Jhesu, whan &thorn;ou wille how rightwis is &thorn;i mede?<NOTE PLACE="marg">De cap|cione Willelmi Waleys.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;e wrong has gilt, &thorn;e endyng may &thorn;ei drede.</L>
<L>William Waleis is nomen, &thorn;at maister was of theues,</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;ing to &thorn;e kyng is comen, &thorn;at robberie mischeues.</L>
<L>Sir Jon of Menetest sewed William so nehi,</L>
<L>He tok him whan he wend lest, on nyght his leman bi.</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;orght treson of Jak Schort his man,</L>
<L>He was &thorn;e encheson, &thorn;at Sir Jon so him nam.</L>
<L>Jak bro&thorn;er had he slayn, &thorn;e Waleis &thorn;at is said,</L>
<L>&thorn;e more Jak was fayn, to do William &thorn;at braid.</L>
<L>Selcouthly he endis &thorn;e man &thorn;at is fals,</L>
<L>If he trest on his frendes, &thorn;ei begile him als</L>
<L>Begiled is William, taken is &amp; bondon.</L>
<L>To Inglond with him &thorn;ei cam, &amp; led him vnto London,</L>
<L>&thorn;e first dome he fanged, for treson was he drawen.</L>
<L>For robbrie was he hanged, &amp; for he had men slawen,</L>
<L>&amp; for he had brent abbeis, &amp; men of religion,</L>
<L>Eft fro &thorn;e galweis quik &thorn;ei lete him doun,</L>
<L>&amp; bouweld him alle hote, &amp; brent &thorn;am in &thorn;e fire,</L>
<L>His hede &thorn;an of smote, suilk was William hire;</L>
<L>&amp; for he had mayntend &thorn;e werre at his myght,</L>
<L>On lordschip lended &thorn;ore he had no right,
<PB REF="00000558.tif" N="330"></L>
<L>&amp; stroied &thorn;ore he knewe, in fele stede sers</L>
<L>His body &thorn;ei hewe on foure quarters,</L>
<L>To hang in foure tounes, to mene of his maners</L>
<L>In stedo of Gonfaynounes, &amp; of his baners.</L>
<L>&para; At London is his heued, his quarters ere leued, in Scot|land spred,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cowe de Waleys.</NOTE></L>
<L>To wirschip &thorn;er iles, &amp; lere of his wiles, how wele &thorn;at he sped.</L>
<L>It is not to drede, traytour salle spede, als he is wor&thorn;i,</L>
<L>His lif salle he tyne, &amp; die &thorn;orgh pyne, withouten merci.</L>
<L>&thorn;us may men here, a ladde forto lere, to biggen in pays;</L>
<L>It fallis in his i&yogh;e, &thorn;at hewes ouer hie, with &thorn;e Walays.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>OF William haf &yogh;e herd, how his endyng was,<NOTE PLACE="marg">DeRoberto Rege Scot|torum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now of kyng Roberd to telle &yogh;ow his trespas.</L>
<L>Als Lenten tide com in, Cristen man's lauh,</L>
<L>He sent for Jon Comyn, &thorn;e lord of Badenauh;</L>
<L>To Dounfres suld he come, vnto &thorn;e Minours kirke,</L>
<L>A spekyng &thorn;er &thorn;ei nome, &thorn;e Comyn wild not wirke,</L>
<L>Ne do after &thorn;e sawe of Roberd &thorn;e Brus.</L>
<L>Away he gan him drawe, his conseil to refus,</L>
<L>Roberd with a knyue &thorn;e Comyn &thorn;er he smote,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh whilk wounde his lyue he lost, wele I wote.</L>
<L>He &yogh;ede to &thorn;e hie autere, &amp; stode &amp; rested him &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>Com Roberde's squiere, &amp; wonded him wele more,</L>
<L>For he wild not consent, to reise no folie,</L>
<L>Ne do als he ment, to gynne to mak partie,</L>
<L>Ageyn kyng Edward, Scotland to dereyne,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De occi|sione Jo|hannis Comyn.</NOTE></L>
<L>With werre &amp; batail hard, reue him his demeyne.
<PB REF="00000559.tif" N="331"></L>
<L>Sir Jon wild not so, &thorn;er for was he dede.</L>
<L>Bot Roberd wild do, &amp; o&thorn;er &thorn;at gaf him rede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he suld go to Scone, &amp; mak redy &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>&amp; whan it were alle bone, to tak &thorn;e dignite.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Et la gerlaunde i prist, qe Reis solait porter, En signe de seignorye a son en|coronner, E mayntenaunt apres par tut fist crier Citez, burgs &amp; villes, des Englays voyder. Euesqes deus estoy|ent primatz au [<I>vel</I> a] dubber Oue le abbe de Scone, qe puys lachata cher, [<I>vel</I> le chata chier,] Countes &amp; ba|rouns, chiualer, esquier, Du realme descoce estoynt [<I>vel</I> estoyent] conseyller, Jurez en eyde al Breus, par tere &amp; par mer, <I>&amp;c. MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e garland Roberd tok, &thorn;at whilom was &thorn;e right,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lond forto loke, in signe of kynge's myght.</L>
<L>Primatis bisshopes tuo &thorn;o with croice &amp; ryng,</L>
<L>&amp; an Abbot mo of Scone, &thorn;at dubbid &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>Erles, barons inowe mad him &thorn;er feaute,</L>
<L>With oth he did &thorn;am bowe, at his wille to be,</L>
<L>&amp; alle Inglis men did he woyde &thorn;e lond,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei mot fynde or ken in stede &thorn;er he &thorn;am fonde.</L>
<L>&para; Now gos &thorn;e Brus about, werre he &thorn;inkis to hold,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis &thorn;e katched out, to &thorn;e kyng &thorn;e told.</L>
<L>Edward &thorn;an he toke folk with his banere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle went of Penbroke, his name was Sir Eymere.</L>
<L>&amp; o&thorn;er men fulle gode, barons &amp; barons pere,</L>
<L>At tyme wele &thorn;ei stode, &amp; did &thorn;er deuere.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e date was a &thorn;ousand, &thorn;re hundred mo bi sex,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e werre of Scotland &thorn;orgh &thorn;e Brus eft wex.
<PB REF="00000560.tif" N="332"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;is &yogh;ere, als I told, at &thorn;e Whitsonen day,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De solem|pnitate festi Regis apud West|monaste|rium.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng his fest suld hold at Westmynstre fulle gay,</L>
<L>His sonne Edward &thorn;e prince, &amp; fiftene for his sake,</L>
<L>&thorn;re<NOTE PLACE="foot">Others say, that the whole number then knighted was, two hundred threescore and seven. See Dugdale's Baronage, Tom. I. p. 80. b.</NOTE> hundred of &thorn;e prouince, knyghtes wild he make.</L>
<L>It was &thorn;e kynges costage, for ilk a knyght was gest,</L>
<L>Also &thorn;ei mad mariage of som &thorn;at were &thorn;e best.</L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;ong erle of Warenne with grete nobley was &thorn;are,</L>
<L>A wif<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Dugdale observes</I> (loc. cit.) <I>that John E. of War|ren, having an offer made unto him by the King, in his Cham|ber at Westminster, in Parlia|ment, upon Munday next, be|fore the feast of S. Edward, King and Martyr, 33 Edw. I. of Joan, Daughter to Henry, Earl of Baar, gratefully accepted there|of (he being not then fully twenty one years of age) and took her to wife.</I></NOTE> &thorn;ei him bikenne, &thorn;e erle's douhter of Bare.</L>
<L>&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Le Count de Aroundel, saisie de ses feez, Il prist la damoisele, ki [<I>vel</I> qe] pere fu clamez Willam de Warenne, a dieu comaun|dcz, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> erle of Arundelle his londes lauht he &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&amp; toke a damyselle, William douhter of Warenne.</L>
<L>&yogh;ong Sir Hugh was &thorn;are, &thorn;e Spensere stoute &amp; gay,</L>
<L>Gilbert douhter of Clare wedded he &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>It is not to wene, bot certeynly to witen,</L>
<L>Joye inouh is sene, &thorn;er suilk a fest is smyten.</L>
<L>In alle Breteyn was nouht, si&thorn;en Criste was born,</L>
<L>A fest so noble wrouht aftere no biforn,</L>
<L>Out tak Carleon, &thorn;at was in Arthure tyme,</L>
<L>&thorn;are he bare &thorn;e coroune, &thorn;ereof &yogh;it men ryme.
<PB REF="00000561.tif" N="333"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THE prince after &thorn;e fest sone his leue toke,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Iter arri|puit versus Scociam.</NOTE></L>
<L>With jolif men of gest toward &thorn;e North he schoke,</L>
<L>To chace kyng Robyn, where he myght him fynde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at slouh &thorn;e gode Comyn, destroie him rote &amp; rynde.</L>
<L>His fader Edward, North mad his jorne,</L>
<L>Him toke a sekenes hard, at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lanercost <I>vulgo. Et sic MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE> Laynertost lay he.</L>
<L>Bot Jhesu &thorn;orgh his myght, blissed mot he be,</L>
<L>Reised him vp right, &amp; passed &thorn;at hage.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">Maintenaunt apres surdrent [<I>vel</I> sour|drount] les dolours As ab|bes, as euesques, as clers &amp; lays plusours De la tere de|scoce a [<I>vel</I> as] gentz souent periours, <I>MSS. Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;er after ros hard schoures in Scotlond of &thorn;e clergie,</L>
<L>Bisshops, abbotes, &amp; priours, &thorn;ei had misborn &thorn;am hie,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;at fals blode, &thorn;at often was forsuorn,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer in treuth stode, sen Jhesu Criste was born.</L>
<L>&para; Sire Eymere of Valence lay at Saynt Jon toun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Dominus Eymerus de Valen|cia apud Sanctum Johannem. Et de bello de Metfen.</NOTE></L>
<L>In his alience with many erle &amp; baroun.</L>
<L>Of Scotlond &thorn;e best were &thorn;an in his feith,</L>
<L>&thorn;er &thorn;ei gan alle rest, tille &thorn;ei herd o&thorn;er greith.</L>
<L>Sir Robert &thorn;e Brus sent to Sir Eymere,</L>
<L>&amp; bad he suld refus &thorn;at him had forsaken ilk a pantenerc.</L>
<L>&thorn;e traytours of hise &thorn;at him had forsaken</L>
<L>&thorn;ei suld to &thorn;e Jewise, whan &thorn;ei &thorn;e toun had taken.</L>
<L>&thorn;e to&thorn;er day on &thorn;e morn com &thorn;e Brus Roberd,</L>
<L>&thorn;e toun wist it beforn, &thorn;orgh spies &thorn;at &thorn;ei herd.</L>
<L>Sir Eymere wild haf gon out, Sir Ingram Vmfreyuile</L>
<L>Preid him forto lout, tille it were none &thorn;at while.</L>
<L>"If we now out wende, &amp; leue &thorn;e toun alone,</L>
<L>"&thorn;ei gete &thorn;e faired ende, &amp; we be slayn ilkone.
<PB REF="00000562.tif" N="334"></L>
<L>"Bot do crie &thorn;orgh &thorn;e toun, &thorn;at non for wele no wo,</L>
<L>"In<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Pro</I>, strete.</NOTE> stete walk vp &amp; doun bot to &thorn;er innes go.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e crie was cried, walkand was non sene,</L>
<L>Bot to innes hied, as &thorn;er no man had bene.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis perceyued wele, &thorn;ei durst not isshen oute,</L>
<L>It neghed nere metesel, &thorn;an ros vp alle &thorn;e route.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e hie midday went &thorn;e Scottis men,</L>
<L>Tuo myle was &thorn;er way, to &thorn;e castelle of Metfen.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ei to Metfen cam, &thorn;ei dight &thorn;am to &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>&thorn;an said Sir Ingram, "if we go now, we &thorn;am gete.</L>
<L>"Dight vs now ilk one, go we, God vs spede,</L>
<L>"Leue not &thorn;e toun alone, &thorn;e way I salle &yogh;ow lede.</L>
<L>&para; On Saynt Margarete day Sir Ingram &amp; Sir Eymere</L>
<L>Com on &thorn;am &thorn;er &thorn;ei lay alle dight to &thorn;e dynere.</L>
<L>&thorn;er vaumward was sone dight, our Inglis had mervaile,</L>
<L>&thorn;ei were so sone at &thorn;e fight, &amp; redy to assaile.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Inglis &thorn;orgh &thorn;am ran, &amp; had &thorn;e fairer side,</L>
<L>&thorn;e Scottis ilk a man, &thorn;e lordes durst not bide.</L>
<L>Here now a contreuore, &thorn;orgh Roberde's avis,</L>
<L>Abouen &thorn;er armore did serkis &amp; surplis.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ei fled on rowe, in lynen white as milke,</L>
<L>For non suld &thorn;am knowe, &thorn;er armes whilk were whilk.</L>
<L>Our men &thorn;at wild haf dede, bare &thorn;am forth fulle stoute,</L>
<L>Sir Eymer had no drede, he serchid &thorn;am alle oute.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e first comyng he slouh Sir Eymere stede</L>
<L>&thorn;at did Robert &thorn;e kyng, &amp; turned bak &amp; &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>Sir Eymer had inowe, &thorn;at horsid him ageyn,</L>
<L>Roberte's men &thorn;ei slowe, &thorn;e numbre vncerteyn.
<PB REF="00000563.tif" N="335"></L>
<L>&thorn;an bigan &thorn;e chace, &amp; drof &thorn;e kyng Robyn,</L>
<L>To reste had he no space, long to duelle &thorn;er in.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Freselle &thorn;er he fled, sone after was he fonden,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Capcio Sy|monis Fre|selle.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now taken he is &amp; led vnto &thorn;e toure of Lundon,</L>
<L>&thorn;er his dome he feyng als traytoure salle &yogh;e witen,</L>
<L>First drawen &amp; si&thorn;en heyng, &amp; his hede of smyten.</L>
<L>Allas! it was to mene, his vertuz &amp; his pruesse</L>
<L>So fele in him were sene, &thorn;at perist for falsnesse.</L>
<L>His hede vnto &thorn;e brigge to sette was it sent,</L>
<L>&thorn;e body lete &thorn;ei ligge, &amp; som &thorn;erof &thorn;ei brent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HERE now &thorn;e grete despite, &amp; &thorn;e vilenie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Capcio cleriScoci&aelig;, &amp; missi sunt ad Angli|am super hakeneis.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at to &thorn;er bak gan bite of Scotlond &thorn;e clergie.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Saynt Andrew, &amp; &thorn;e abbot of Scone,</L>
<L>&thorn;e bisshop of Glascow, &thorn;ise were taken sone.</L>
<L>Fettred on hakneis, to Inlond ere &thorn;ei sent,</L>
<L>On sere stedis it seis, to prison mad present.</L>
<L>Lewed men &amp; clerkis, &thorn;at did werre mayntene,</L>
<L>Als theues bere &thorn;ei merkis, hanged alle bidene.</L>
<L>Cristofore of Seton many man him sauh</L>
<L>Hanged for treson of Jon of Badenauh,</L>
<L>Hanged als &thorn;e Freselle, &amp; in &thorn;e same stede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erle of Ascetelle &thorn;ei bed &thorn;e same bede.</L>
<L>Saue he was not drawen, &thorn;at poynt was forgyuen.</L>
<L>Bot alle with schame slawen, &thorn;orgh treson &thorn;erto dryuen.</L>
<L>Allas! &thorn;at jentille blode com to so ille fyne,</L>
<L>&amp; alle for falsnes &yogh;ode to scheme's dede &amp; pyne.</L>
<L>&amp; wele I vnderstode, &thorn;at &thorn;e kyn&yogh; Robyn</L>
<L>Has dronken of &thorn;at blode &thorn;e drink of Dan Waryn.
<PB REF="00000564.tif" N="336"></L>
<L>Dan Waryn he les tounes &thorn;at he held,</L>
<L>With wrong he mad a res, &amp; misberyng of scheld.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en in to &thorn;e forest he &yogh;ede naked &amp; wode,</L>
<L>Als a wilde beste, ete of &thorn;e gres &thorn;at stode.</L>
<L>&thorn;us of Dan Waryn in his boke men rede,</L>
<L>God &yogh;yf &thorn;e kyng Robyn, &thorn;at alle his kynde so spede.</L>
<L>&para; Sir Robynet &thorn;e Brus he durst noure abide,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Roberto Brus, &amp; fuga circum circa fit.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei mad him restus, bot in more &amp; wod side.</L>
<L>Towhile he mad &thorn;is trayne, &amp; did vmwhile outrage,</L>
<L>Com Arthure of Bretayne, &amp; asked his heritage.</L>
<L>Holy Richemond schire he cleymed &thorn;at &thorn;orgh right,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De comite Britanni&aelig;.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kyng Edward our sire him ansuerd fulle light.</L>
<L>He had so light ansuere, &thorn;at Arthure toke his leue,</L>
<L>God schilde vs fro &thorn;e werre, &thorn;at non with o&thorn;er greue.</L>
<L>Whan Arthur was gon, &thorn;e kyng did alle a no&thorn;er,</L>
<L>He gaf it to Sir Jon, Sir Arthure's bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>Holdand of him in fe, als whilom was vsage,</L>
<L>Of Sir Edward fre, &amp; of alle his linage.</L>
<L>&thorn;e duke of Bretayn with fulle heuy chere</L>
<L>Passed ouere agayn, fulle light ansuere had here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOW of kyng Robyn salle I &yogh;it speke more,</L>
<L>&amp; his bro&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sire Thomas de Breus <I>for</I> Tomlyn, Thomas, <I>in the Fr.</I></NOTE> Tomlyn, Thomas als it wore,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De Thoma &amp; Alexan|dro, frati|bus Roberti Brus, &amp; capcione corum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; of Sir Alisandere, &thorn;at me rewes sore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at bo&thorn;e com in skandere for dedes &thorn;ei did &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>Of arte he had &thorn;e maistrie, he mad a coruen kyng</L>
<L>In Cantebrige to &thorn;e clergie, or his bro&thorn;er were kyng.
<PB REF="00000565.tif" N="337"></L>
<L>Si&thorn;en was neuer non of arte so &thorn;at sped,</L>
<L>Ne bifore bot on, &thorn;at in Cantebrigge red.</L>
<L>Robert mad his fest, for he was &thorn;ore &thorn;at tyme,</L>
<L>&amp; he sauh alle &thorn;e gest, &thorn;at wrote &amp; mad &thorn;is ryme.</L>
<L>Sir Alisander was hie dene of Glascow,</L>
<L>&amp; his bro&thorn;er Thomas &yogh;ed spiand ay bi throw,</L>
<L>Where our Inglis men ware not in clerke habite,</L>
<L>&amp; non wild he spare, bot destroied also tite.</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e kyng Robyn &thorn;ei &yogh;ede &thorn;e Inglis to spie,</L>
<L>Here now of &thorn;er fyn &thorn;am com for &thorn;at folie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A SERGEANT of Galweye, his name was Makedowel,</L>
<L>On Askwednesday, whan messe was don ilk del,</L>
<L>Sursante he &thorn;am mette, als &thorn;ei fro kirke cam,</L>
<L>&thorn;er way he &thorn;am withsette, smertly &thorn;ore &thorn;am nam.</L>
<L>He did &thorn;am fettre wele, streitly &amp; right hard,</L>
<L>&amp; sent &thorn;am to Carlele vnto kyng Edward.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng wele paied was, he sette justise of lawe,</L>
<L>Demed &thorn;e Brus Thomas bo&thorn;e to hang &amp; drawe,</L>
<L>Sir Alisander &thorn;e same, &amp; after &thorn;er hangyng,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e bi o name hede &thorn;am bad &thorn;e kyng.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e pape Boniface wrote in his sexte boke,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Nota bene.</NOTE></L>
<L>What clerke felle to haf grace, for what cas men him toke,</L>
<L>Whilk clerke, for what trespas, where men suld him saue,</L>
<L>&amp; where he taken was, what habite on suld haue,</L>
<L>&amp; if he were atteynt, als thef &thorn;orgh felonie,</L>
<L>Of suilk &thorn;e pape mas pleynt, &amp; writes to &thorn;e clergie;</L>
<L>&amp; if &thorn;e decretal ne were ordeynd for &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&thorn;e clerkes ouer alle ne rouht to do amys.
<PB REF="00000566.tif" N="338"></L>
<L>&thorn;e date a &thorn;ousand was, &thorn;re hundred &amp; seuen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">M<SUP>o</SUP>. CCC<SUP>o</SUP>. VII<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e clergie for &thorn;at cas held &thorn;am more in euen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AFTER &thorn;e Paske's wele &thorn;at &thorn;ise men were &thorn;us schent,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Parliamen|tum apud arlele.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng at Carlele held his parlement.</L>
<L>Fro Romc a Cardinalle &thorn;e pape &thorn;ider sent,</L>
<L>To wite &thorn;e sothe alle &thorn;e mariage long of ment.</L>
<L>If &thorn;e prince mot haue &thorn;e kynge's douhter of France,</L>
<L>&thorn;e acorde &amp; pes mot saue &thorn;orgh &thorn;at aliance,</L>
<L>&amp; at &thorn;e parlement was a grete spekyng,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e clergic it ment of holy kirke's &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Erles &amp; barons, ilkone it forsuore,</L>
<L>For what manere resons &yogh;it wot I no more,</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e last ende of &thorn;er grete counsaile,</L>
<L>To London suld &thorn;e sende men &thorn;at myght auaile,</L>
<L>To speke &amp; purueie whilk suld ouer &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>&thorn;e sothe to Philip seie, &amp; sette a certeynte</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at mariage, how &amp; whan suld be,</L>
<L>&amp; bate alle o&thorn;er outrage, for Gascoyn do feaute.</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e poyntes spoken &thorn;e parties bifore had said,</L>
<L>Neuer suld be broken on payne &thorn;er on was laid.</L>
<L>&amp; whan &thorn;e parties wold mak a finalle pes,</L>
<L>God grante it &thorn;am to hold &thorn;e conant &thorn;at &thorn;ei ches.</L>
<L>&para; &yogh;it gos kyng Robyn forth in his rioterie,<NOTE PLACE="marg">DeRoberto Brus, &amp; morte Jo|hannis Waleis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne com not &yogh;it his fyn to ende of his folie.</L>
<L>Bot Sir Jon de Waleis taken was in a pleyn,</L>
<L>&thorn;orgh spiyng of Norreis, men &thorn;at were certeyn,</L>
<L>Fettred on a hakeney, &amp; to London led,</L>
<L>To bring him sone on wey, &thorn;e justise &thorn;erto sped.
<PB REF="00000567.tif" N="339"></L>
<L>Als his dedes was, &thorn;er on &thorn;ei gaf &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>For som of his trespas first &thorn;ei did him drawe.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en for o&thorn;er theft, &thorn;ei hanged him men witen,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en lete him doun eft, &amp; his hede of snyten,</L>
<L>&amp; born to London brigge fulle hie with outheys,</L>
<L>Biside his bro&thorn;er to bigge William &thorn;e Waleys,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuer had pite of Inglis man no weys,</L>
<L>Bot brent toun &amp; citez, kirkes &amp; abbeys,</L>
<L>Chanon, monk &amp; frere alle passed &thorn;orgh his suerd,</L>
<L>Was no man so dere, to dede &thorn;ei &yogh;ede in ferd.</L>
<L>Blissed be &thorn;ou God, &thorn;at &thorn;ou in erth cam,</L>
<L>&thorn;i word is wele trod, I say it, bi William.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Exem|plum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;ou said, "with suerd &thorn;at smote, with suerd suld be smyten,"</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e Waleis it bote, &thorn;e vengeance &yogh;e may witen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A! Jhesu, fulle of myght, &thorn;at alle &thorn;e world salle deme,<NOTE PLACE="marg">De morte Regis Ed|wardi.</NOTE></L>
<L>May no man lyue so right, no so wele him &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>No so stalworth be, ne so douhti of dede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at has powere to fle &thorn;e dede &thorn;at is to drede.</L>
<L>Adam first gan synne, did &thorn;at God forbede,</L>
<L>Alle we were him inne, whan he serued &thorn;e dede.</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en he &amp; we alle com of him &amp; Eue,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Magni &amp; parvi, omnes &amp; singuli, reges &amp; principes, superbus &amp; humi|lis, proth dolor! mors in pr&aelig;dam rapit omnia sillaba qu&aelig;dam.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;orgh &thorn;e dede salle falle, be we neuer so leue.</L>
<L>&thorn;e hardy kyng Belyn &thorn;e cite of Rome wan,</L>
<L>&amp; si&thorn;en Constantyn &amp; Maximian.</L>
<L>Arthure wan alle France, slouh &thorn;e Emperour of Rome,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise of suerd ne lance douted dynt no dome.
<PB REF="00000568.tif" N="340"></L>
<L>&thorn;ise kynges men dred, &amp; alle &thorn;e world &thorn;am knewe,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;er grete boldehed, &thorn;e dede &yogh;it doun &thorn;am threwe.</L>
<L>Where ere `ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dele.</NOTE>  now alle &thorn;ise, where ere &thorn;ei bicomen,</L>
<L>&thorn;ise hardy men &amp; wise? &thorn;e dede has alle &thorn;am nomen.</L>
<L>Among alle &thorn;ise hardie may Edward our kyng</L>
<L>Be sette fulle solempnelie, &amp; mad of grete praisyng.</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;e dede of Arthure in Inlond was &thorn;er non,</L>
<L>&thorn;at so wele stode in stoure ageyn his foos ilkon.</L>
<L>&thorn;is was Edward, kyng Henry sonne &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>Ti&thorn;ing haf we hard, &thorn;e dede him doun has kast.</L>
<L>Now may men sing &amp; say, in romance &amp; ryme,</L>
<L>"Edward is now away, right has lorn his tyme.</L>
<L>"Sir Jon of Badenauh, who salle venge &thorn;i dede?</L>
<L>"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Edward le fiz Edward, Rey de la tenure, Ke tenuz est par vowe, le Rey Robin destrure, <I>Gall.</I></NOTE>&thorn;e prince is heire &thorn;orgh lauh, &thorn;at to &thorn;e coroun him bede.</L>
<L>"He has mad his vowe, to stroie &thorn;e kyng Robyn,</L>
<L>"&thorn;at in Dunfres slowe Sir Jon &thorn;e rede Comyn.</L>
<L>His dede whan it felle here, &thorn;e date I salle &yogh;ow neuen,</L>
<L>Of Criste a &thorn;ousand &yogh;ere, &thorn;re hundred &amp; seuen,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Moriebatur apud Burgh bi sandes.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e mone&thorn; of July euen &thorn;e seuend day.</L>
<L>Toward Scotlond to hie, at Burgh bi sandez he lay,</L>
<L>His tyme was no more sette here to regne in landes,</L>
<L>He died at a hamelette, men calle it Burgh bisandes.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e body &thorn;at nyght &thorn;er lay, &thorn;e soule at Criste's dome,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ostensa est pap&aelig; mors ejus eadem nocte per visionem.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e pape &thorn;e to&thorn;er day wist it in &thorn;e courte of Rome.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pape on &thorn;e morn bifor &thorn;e clergie cam,</L>
<L>&amp; teld &thorn;am biforn, &thorn;e floure of Cristendam
<PB REF="00000569.tif" N="341"></L>
<L>Was dede, &amp; lay on bere, Edward of Inglond.</L>
<L>He said with heuy chere in spirit he it fond.</L>
<L>Fiue &yogh;ere he gaf pardoun, of peyns to be fre,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for him with deuocioun said <I>pater &amp; aue.</I></L>
<L>To Waltham &thorn;ei him brouht, baronage &amp; &thorn;e clergie,</L>
<L>For monethes for him wrouht his seruise solempnelie.</L>
<L>&thorn;ei bawmid his body, tresore wild &thorn;ei non spare,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pouere &thorn;ei gaf party, his soule bettere to fare.</L>
<L>Four &amp; tuenty &yogh;ere, auht monethes &amp; fiue daies,</L>
<L>Noblie regned he here, bi profe &amp; gode assaies.</L>
<L>Fro Waltham beforsaid to Westmynster &thorn;ei him brouht,</L>
<L>Biside his fadere is laid in a toumbe wele wrouht.</L>
<L>Of marble is &thorn;e stone, &amp; purtreied &thorn;er he lies,</L>
<L>&thorn;e soule to God is gone, to &thorn;e joye of paradis, Amen.</L>
<L>&para; Now must I nede leue here, of Inglis forto write,</L>
<L>I had no more matere of kynges lif in scrite.</L>
<L>If I had haned more, blithly I wild haf writen,</L>
<L>What tyme I left &thorn;is lore, &thorn;e day is for to witen,</L>
<L>Idus &thorn;at is of May left I to write &thorn;is ryme,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>It should be</I> D.</NOTE>B letter &amp; Friday bi ix. &thorn;at &yogh;ere &yogh;ede prime.</L>
<TRAILER>The End of Langtoft's Chronicle.</TRAILER>
</LG>
